<head>      
<title> FIRM DENIES RESPONSIBILITY FOR ATROCITIES 
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
FIRM DENIES RESPONSIBILITY FOR ATROCITIES 
</h1></td>      
</table>      
Inter Press Service
   <br>  
                                October 31, 1996, Thursday<br>
    PARIS, Oct. 31<p> 
        The French oil company Total, facing criticism over its decision to 
     maintain
     investments in Burma despite the outcry over abuses committed by that 
     country's
     military regime, says its actions are legal and provide no immediate 
     direct benefit for the state.
     
        Criticisms by human rights advocates and international legal 
     experts were not
     fair said a spokesman for Total. "There is no international law 
     prohibiting
     foreign companies from working in Burma."
     
        Critics say the firm's project in Burma make it at least partly 
     responsible
     for the brutalities being committed against politicians and the 
     general
     population by the military regime. In a report released recently in 
     Paris, the
     International Federation of Human Rights Leagues (FIDH) said Total was 
     accountable for the abuses.  
     <p>
        Citing the company's gas project in southern Burma, FIDH accused 
     Total of
     extending moral, political and economic support to the State Law and 
     Order
     Restoration Council (SLORC) in Rangoon.
     
        But the Total spokesman said: "We are not engaging in politics. 
     Legally, we
     are not breaking any law. The situation is not the same as that of 
     Iraq against
     which there is an international embargo. Total is not present in 
     Iraq."
     
        He said at this stage the project in southern Burma represents an 
     investment
     and does not profit the Burmese authorities. "It is not bringing in 
     revenues for
     the authorities, and will not for a long time to come. In a few more 
     years, who
     knows who the authorities will be," the Total spokesman told IPS.
     <p>
        But Olivier Russbach, specialist on international law and director 
     of the
     International Law Research Center 90 said: "It is a false approach to 
     excuse
     one's behavior on the basis of what the international community 
     decides to do or
     not to do about the human rights violations committed by a country."
     
        He added: "It is not necessary at all to wait for what the U.N. 
     Security
     Council says or does not say about Burma. Total does have civil 
     responsibility
     for what is going on in Burma."
     
        According to Russbach, the silence of the U.N. Security Council is 
     not a
     measure of the gravity of acts of states. "There is no embargo against 
     Turkey or
     Russia, but that does not say anything about the crimes by Turkey or 
     Russia."
     <p>
        The military junta in Burma, which has changed its name to Myanmar, 
     is one of
     the most dictatorial regimes in the world, says the FIDH.
        It has jailed opponents, restricted political activity and 
     overturned the
     results of the last democratic elections and jailed its winner, Aung 
     San Suu Kyi
     of the National League For Democracy (NLD). Earlier this month, the 
     regime
     arrested pro-democracy campaigner U Kyi Maung.
     
        Its human rights record is recognized as "particularly terrifying," 
     or
     "sufficiently serious," the FIDH points out. They are attempting to 
     push the
     U.N. Human Rights Commission to appoint a special rapporteur for the 
     country.
     Burma's military has been condemned repeatedly by the U.N. General 
     Assembly and
     the International Labor Organization.
     <p>
        Begun in 1992 in a joint venture with the state-controlled Myanma 
     Oil and Gas
     Enterprise (MOGE), Total's project in Burma represents more than a 
     third of the
     foreign investments in that country.
     
        Estimated at $ 1.2 billion, the project will exploit the vast gas 
     reserves at
     Yadana. When completed some time in 1998, it would deliver some 525 
     million
     cubic feet of gas per day to Thailand, earning Rangoon yearly revenues 
     estimated
     at between $ 200 billion and $ 500 billion.
     
        "Human rights violations related to the project have been 
     confirmed: forced
     displacement of populations, forced labor, child labor, torture, rape 
     and
     extortion," charged the FIDH.
     
        Together with several other non-governmental organizations in 
     France and
     other countries, the FIDH has joined an international campaign to get 
     Total to
     freeze its activities in Burma and to allow an independent 
     investigation into
     various charges.
     <p>
        While human rights violations have been committed by members of the 
     Burmese
     army placed in charge of the security at the construction site, the 
     FIDH
     maintains that Total is not exonerated. And while it is unlikely that 
     Total has
     resorted directly to forced labor, it is nevertheless clear that it 
     tolerates
     and benefits from it.
     
        The abuses, says the FIDH, arise from the militarization of the 
     region
     through which the pipeline will pass. "A number of groups opposed to 
     the regime
     in Rangoon are active in the area. The regime and foreign investors 
     agree that
     the pacification of Burma is a necessary condition for contracts," the 
     organization states.
     
        As such, contracts with Burma specify that the regime must 
     guarantee the
     security of the site and the protection of Total employees, the FIDH 
     points out.
     SLORC has therefore sent several infantry battalions, or around 10,000 
     soldiers.
     
        Total would also be interested in seeing that the SLORC stays in 
     place, says
     the FIDH. Legislators elected in the nullified 1989 elections have 
     clearly
     indicated that as the "real representatives" of the Burmese people, 
     they do not
     recognize contracts passed with the SLORC. They have said that they 
     will not
     recognize contracts signed up with the junta if the civil government 
     comes to
     power.
     <p>
        Total has reaffirmed its commitment to respecting human rights 
     everywhere in
     the world and says it will never accept to use forced or child labor 
     on any
     project, in Burma or anywhere else. The project, it argues, will 
     contribute to
     the country's economic development, which will probably encourage 
     Burma "to
     improve relations with the rest of the world and promote social 
     change."
     
        Under these circumstances, FIDH says that investing in Burma, and
     particularly under the form of a joint venture with an enterprise 
     entirely
     controlled by the authorities, amounts to a gesture of moral and 
     political
     solidarity with the authorities.
     <p>
        "It is also an act of complicity. In signing a contract with the 
     junta, Total
     agreed to close its eyes to the massive, systematic and confirmed 
     violations of
     human rights," it charges.
     
        "There are actions that are apparently innocuous but are heavy with 
     moral
     meaning, and there are economic actions that have political 
     consequences.
     Whether one likes it or not, economic power these days means disposing 
     of
     political power," it argues.
     <p>
        Upbeat official assessments of the state of the Burmese economy 
     have recently
     been challenged by a report prepared by the U.S. Embassy in Rangoon 
     which cited
     soaring deficits, declining foreign investments, rising and 
     potentially
     unserviceable debt, rampant military spending and increased reliance 
     on income
     derived from drug trafficking.
     
        Since 1991, the Burmese regime claims it has attracted over $ 4.13 
     billion
     worth of foreign investments and in 1993 and 1994 recorded an average 
     gross
     domestic product (GDP) growth rate of 8.2 percent.
     
        But the 134-page U.S. embassy report said that although pledged 
     foreign
     investment is rising the actual inflows had fallen from 9.3 percent to 
     five
     percent of GDP between 1991 and 1994.
<br>Copyright 1996 Inter Press Service   

