<html>
<head>
<title> Big Oil's Gamble on a Pariah Regime
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>
<tr>
<td><h1>
Big Oil's Gamble on a Pariah Regime
</h1></td>
</table>

It was a foreign investor's worst nightmare.  During an "open for
business"  investment promotion meeting in May, Roger Truitt, president of
Arco Asia Inc., met with one of the ruling generals from Burma's brutal
military regime.  The next day, a photo of the two smiling men was
splashed on the front page of the government news-paper-just as the
generals touched off a firestorm of international protests by arbitrarily
arresting more than 250 supporters of the opposition National League for
Democracy.<p> 

But embarrassment goes with the territory these days for
Westerners doing business in Burma (or Myanmar, as the current crowd
renamed it seven years ago).  "Burma has become the South Africa of the
1990s," says Simon Billenness, senior analyst at Boston-based Franklin
Research & Development, which specializes in what it terms socially
responsible investments. Some half- dozen U.S. companies-among them Amoco,
Liz Claiborne, Levi Strauss, and Pepsico-have tried and quit the country,
turned off by both local corruption and pressure from customers back home.
Six U.S. cities have passed laws barring municipal contracts to companies
that deal with Burma.<p> 

Despite the rising heat, Arco and a hardy band of
international oil giants have so far vowed to press ahead with major
energy development projects. Unocal, the largest U.S. inves- tor in Burma,
owns 28% of the $1 billion Yadana offshore gas project-the French company
Total is the lead partner-a potentially lucrative venture that will export
to Thailand for hard currency. Says John Imle Jr., president of Unocal: 
"Geology and geography-not geopolitics-are our dictates."<p> 

Echoing that
line, Arco has also brushed aside a shareholder resolution calling on the
com- pany to quit Burma.  After all, it points out, it is following a
strict code of conduct that prohibits illegal payoffs, endangering
employees, and investing in places that Washington puts off-limits.<p>

The odds are growing, however, that Burma may soon join the ranks
of those off-limits countries.  The U.S. already denies the Burmese junta
access to World Bank loans.  Now critics want to put it right at the top
of Washington s list of outlaw regimes, along with Libya and Iraq, and
shut off private invest- ment by U.S. companies as well. Says Senator
Mitch McConnell, a conservative Republican from Kentucky who has attracted
bipartisan support for just such a bill: "There is no doubt that
investment by U.S. companies subsidizes a regime responsible for
outrageous abuses."<p>
<img align=left src=child.gif>
Though McConnell agrees with the notion that trade and investment
help moderate governments in China and Vietnam, Burma, he maintains, "is
quite different." For one thing, its military rulers have done nothing to
curb production of opium-their biggest cash crop and the source of 60% of
the heroin seized on U.S. streets.  Moreover, the Burmese generals are
suppressing a local democracy movement that won 82% of the seats in a free
parliamentary election in 1990 and was prevented from taking office. To
keep their grip on power, the generals'State Law and Order Restoration
Council (whose acronym in English is the sinister-sounding handle Slorc),
has relied upon arbitrary arrests, summary executions, rape, and forced
labor-abuses well-documented by Washington, the United Nations, and most
recently, by a film produced by the British network ITV, which showed
children being forced to help build a state railway that runs through the
region where Unocal and Total's pipeline is being laid.<p> 

So far,
including the big-ticket energy projects, Burma has managed to attract
only about $1 billion of investment, mainly from Southeast Asian nations. 
Such "constructive engagement," Burma's neighbors insist, is the best way
to encourage further reforms.  Imle of Unocal argues that even if his
company pulled out, another would take its place: "As Myanmar opens up its
economy to the West, it is time for us to lead by example.  It is not time
to slam the door shut."<p>

<img align=left src=suu_kyi.gif>
But can an open-door policy really civilize this rogue regime's
behavior?  Aung San Sun Kyi, leader of Burma's democratic forces and
winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, urges foreign companies to stay out of
Burma until Slorc's generals agree to share power.  Says she: "Anybody who
really knows what's going on with the Burmese economy wouldn't want to
invest here." One influential fellow who buys that line is billionaire
global investor George Soros.  Testifying before Congress last month, he
backed a ban on investment: "I would endorse any type of economic
sanctions only as a last resort.  But Burma is a case where desperate
measures are needed because the situation is so desperate."<p> 
- Louis Kraar<br> 
