<html>    
<head>      
<title> Indonesia sees Burma as prospective gas supplier
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
Indonesia sees Burma as prospective gas supplier
</h1></td>      
</table>      
Reuters World Service<br>
     
                            December 2, 1996<br> 
     
<b>Rangoon</b><p>
     
        Indonesia is negotiating with Burma's military government over the 
     prospect of buying natural gas from big offshore fields in the Bay of Mottama 
     in southern Burma, Indonesian diplomats said on Monday.
     
        The sources said any future Indonesian purchase of Burmese natural 
     gas would come under the framework of a memorandum of understanding (MOU) on 
     bilateral cooperation in the energy sector signed by the two countries in 
     mid-October.  They said an Indonesian delegation arrived in Rangoon recently to 
     negotiate with their Burmese counterparts following a visit in mid-October by 
     Indonesian Oil Minister Sudjana and Faisal Abda'oe, the chief of state oil 
     company Pertamina.
     <p>
        Burma is currently developing its Yadana and Yetagun offshore 
     fields. It will pipe natural gas from the fields onshore in 1998, mostly for export to 
     Thailand. Burma's energy ministry estimated that the Yadana field in the Bay 
     of Mottama contained about 5.7 trillion cubic feet of commercial reserves of 
     natural gas.<p>

        Indonesian diplomats said the recently-signed MOU covered bilateral
     cooperation in both upstream and downstream energy sectors.
It includes technical and human resource assistance that Jakarta 
     will provide
     to Burma in exploring new gas and petroleum resources and in 
     modernising its
     run-down oil refineries.
     
        They said Pertamina will likely send a few more delegations to 
     Rangoon to
     negotiate with Burmese officials in 1997.
     
        The sources did not exclude the possibility that Indonesia might 
     supply
     Burma with crude oil and refined products in the future, saying it 
     could come
     under bilateral talks.
  
