<head>      
<title> Japan to extend 4 bil. yen debt-relief grant to Myanmar 
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
Japan to extend 4 bil. yen debt-relief grant to Myanmar </h1></td>      
</table>      
<i>      Asian Economic News</i><br>
     
                                     December 2, 1996<br>
     
<b>YANGON</b>, Nov. 26 Kyodo<br>
     
        Japan and Myanmar have exchanged notes in Yangon for a Japanese 
     government
     debt-relief grant of 4 billion yen for the first half of fiscal 1996, 
     the
     Japanese Embassy here said Tuesday.
     
        Since Myanmar was declared a least developed developing country 
     (LDDC) in
     1987, Japan has extended debt-relief grants to cover interest and part 
     of
     capital with the intention of producing the same effect as canceling 
     the debt of
     an LDDC.   Myanmar owed Japan more than 400 billion yen when Japanese 
     loans were
     stopped in 1988.
     
        Japan extended a debt-relief grant of 3.6 billion yen in 1988, 3.5 
     billion
     yen in 1990, 3 billion yen in 1991, 4 billion yen in 1992, 6.2 billion 
     yen in
     1993, 12 billion yen in 1994, and 4 billion yen in 1995.
