<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<html>    
<head>      
<title> Agreement on gas field in Myanmar first for Japanese oil 
     company.
     Thai power outfits buy total output from offshore
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
Agreement on gas field in Myanmar first for Japanese oil 
     company<br>
     Thai power outfits buy total output from offshore
</h1></td>      
</table>      
     
                                    The Nikkei Weekly
<br>     
                                     November 4, 1996
     <p>
        Nippon Oil Co., Texaco Inc. of the U.S. and Premier Oil Plc of the 
     U.K. will
     start pumping natural gas from a field about 160km off the coast of 
     Myanmar from
     the fall of 1999.
     
        The consortium inked an agreement on Oct. 29 with the Myanmarese 
     and Thai
     governments to sell planned daily output of 30,000 barrels to Thai 
     electric-power companies through the Petroleum Authority of Thailand.
     
        The Texaco-led group will invest 50 yen billion (438.6 million 
     dollars) in
     the project to build plant and transport facilities. Texaco holds a 
     50%
     concession in the field, while Premier owns 30% and Nippon Oil has 
     20%. Premier
     obtained the rights to the Andaman Sea gas field; Texaco and Nippon 
     Oil joined
     the project in 1991.  
     <p>
        Officials from the companies predict the field has sufficient gas 
     reserves to
     support commercial drilling.
     
        This is the first natural-gas project in Myanmar to include a 
     Japanese oil
     refiner-wholesaler. The daily output will be equivalent to 3% of the 
     daily
     volume of liquefied natural gas imported by all Japanese 
     electric-power and
     city-gas companies. Thailand is increasing imports of gas to meet 
     surging
     electricity demand.
     <p>
        Field fits strategy
     <p>
        Nippon Oil has already invested 3 yen billion in the project 
     through Nippon
     Oil Exploration (Myanmar) Ltd., a joint venture shared with Japan 
     National Oil
     Corp.
     
        Under contract terms with the Myanmarese government, Nippon Oil's 
     proceeds
     will likely be less than its stake of 20%, industry sources said.
     
        Nippon Oil has rights to parts of gas fields in Texas and the Gulf 
     of Mexico,
     and produces between 8,000 and 9,000 barrels of natural gas each day. 
     The
     Myanmarese project is in line with the company's strategy to reinforce 
     supply of
     raw materials from its own operations.
     <p>
        Despite some political risks involved in development and 
     production, the
     project has stable buyers and is expected to contribute to Myanmar's 
     economy,
     Nippon Oil sources said.
     
        Despite growing criticism of its military government, foreign 
     companies are
     showing a strong interest in developing the country's natural 
     resources.
     <p>
        In late September, Myanmar's military junta arrested several 
     members of the
     National League for Democracy, a move that further strained its 
     relations with
     the U.S. and other countries. As a result, some foreign companies are 
     pulling
     out of the country.
     
        But companies from Europe, the U.S. and member countries of the 
     Association
     of Southeast Asian Nations are active in developing Myanmar's 
     natural-resources
     and tourism industry.
     
        From April through September, Myanmar approved foreign investments 
     of more
     than 1 billion dollars, up 150% from the same period last year.
          <p>
