<html>    
<head>      
<title> Boulder may aim boycott at Myanmar
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
Boulder may aim boycott at Myanmar
</h1></td>      
</table>      
<i>     The Denver Post</i><br>
     
                           December 3, 1996 <br>
     
     

      By Mary George, <i>Denver Post</i>  Staff Writer<p>
     
     
     BOULDER - AT&T, Ford and Federal Express would be among firms turned 
     away by
     Boulder if it boycotts companies doing business in Myanmar.
     
        Boulder Friends for a Democratic Burma, led by former Burmese 
     princess Inge
     Sargent, has asked the city council to consider the "selective 
     purchasing"
     ordinance.  The measure would prevent the city from buying goods or 
     services
     from companies that do business in Myanmar.
     <p>
        The military government of Myanmar, the Asian country formerly 
     known as
     Burma, is getting attention worldwide for its drug trade and its poor 
     human-rights record. The U.S. government estimates that 60 percent of 
     the heroin
     used in the United States comes from Myanmar.
     
        "For the sake of our city and our people, let's send them a 
     message," said
     Sargent, whose first husband, Shan Prince Sao Kya Seng, disappeared 
     after a 1962
     military coup and is presumed murdered. "Maybe others will follow us. 
     I do
     believe that we can motivate the nation, and that this nation can 
     motivate the
     world."
     <p>
        Boulder council members will take a preliminary vote on the 
     proposal tonight, then a second vote Dec. 17. Other companies that might have to be purged from the city's purchasing logs are Arco, Texaco, Unocal and ITT.  The law would affect an estimated $2 million in city business a year, said Benita Duran, assistant city manager.
     <p>
        The state of Massachusetts and eight other U.S. cities have such 
     laws. The cities are San Francisco, Berkeley, Oakland and Santa Monica, Calif.; 
     Ann Arbor,  Mich.; Madison, Wis., Takoma Park, Md., and Carbarro, N.C.
<hr>
