. <!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<html>    
<head>      
<title> Motorola's pullout from Burma clears way for big San Francisco contract
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
Motorola's pullout from Burma clears way for big San Francisco contract
</h1></td>      
</table>      

Motorola Inc. is in line to win a $ 40 million contract to provide 
     an emergency communication system for San Francisco because it is closing 
     its operations in Burma and coming into compliance with a city ban on 
     doing business with the country's repressive regime.
     <p>
        Although Motorola said yesterday that its Burma shutdown had 
     nothing to do with San Francisco's boycott, backers of the measure called the 
     decision a significant human rights victory. But others said Motorola now stands 
     to win the contract without competitive bidding -- at a potential cost of 
     millions in taxpayer dollars. 
     <p>
        ''There's been a growing national and international boycott against 
     doing business with Burma because of gross human rights violations there,'' 
     said Supervisor Tom Ammiano. ''Motorola can say they made the decision 
     because of business concerns, but if it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, 
     it's a duck.''
     <p>
        Motorola's decision is the latest turn in a twisting course that is 
     supposed to lead to a state-of-the- art communication system to serve San 
     Francisco's Fire Department, paramedics and Police Department.
     <p>
        The company, based in Schaumburg, Ill., won the contract 2 1/2 
     years ago without competitive bidding. City officials supervising the project 
     had said they already had some Motorola equipment and wanted Motorola to 
     provide the rest of the system.
     <p>
        But a year ago, a federal court ruled that the city could not award 
     the contract without taking bids from other companies.
     <p>
        Ericsson GE, part of an international conglomerate and one of 
     Motorola's biggest competitors worldwide, then submitted its bid on the project.  
     According to Supervisor Angela Alioto, it was $ 12 million to $ 14 million less 
     than Motorola's.
     <p>
        Then last spring, the supervisors passed the Burma measure. The 
     country's military leaders have been widely condemned for repressing a 
     pro-democracy movement and refusing to cede power to a democratically elected 
     government. 
<p>
        That measure made both Ericsson and Motorola ineligible for the
     communications project. Ericsson's Swedish parent company has had 
     multimillion dollar deals to provide phone system equipment in Burma. And Motorola 
     has had a small office there with one employee.
     <p>
        The decision to close that office and relocate the employee 
     apparently leaves Motorola once again as the sole bidder on the project. 
        But the controversy probably is not over.
     <p>
        ''Competitive bids keep prices down and services up,'' said Alioto.
     ''Awarding these contracts without bids is the biggest scam going in 
     this government. If you want money to clean the streets and help the 
     homeless, that's where you can find it.''
     <p>
        Alioto said she would press for further reviews of the 
     communication project. 
               <hr>
