http://server.soros.org:80/burma/sfmitsub.html 204.168.83.130 19970112144212 text/html 5991
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 12 Jan 1997 14:36:06 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<html>    
<head>      
<title> Conflict Over Hiring Mitsubishi to build San Francisco Airport 
</title>      
</head>      
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">      
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>      
<tr>      
<td><h1>      
Conflict Over Hiring Mitsubishi to build San Francisco Airport </h1></td>      
</table> 
<p>     
         Airport officials want to award a $ 137 million construction 
     contract to Mitsubishi, despite strong warnings by another city agency that San 
     Francisco's minority contracting goals will not be met and that the intended 
     subcontractors are not qualified to do the work.
     <p>
         Airport chief John Martin said Wednesday that he wanted Mitsubishi 
     Heavy Industries of America to build a "people mover" at San Francisco 
     International Airport. Mitsubishi's bid on the light-rail transit system is $ 19 
     million less than the second-lowest bidder, ADtranz of Pittsburg.
     <p>
         The fight for the contract has been fierce, with Mitsubishi 
     retaining high-powered attorney William Coblentz as a chief representative and 
     ADtranz retaining City Hall lobbying guru Don Solem and his firm. ADtranz has 
     gone so far as to hire a private investigator to check the credentials of the 
     subcontractors with which Mitsubishi plans to work.  
     <p>
         In addition, politics has come into play. Supervisor Tom Ammiano 
     is trying to block Mitsubishi's bid, contending that the company has ties to 
     Burma in violation of a city law he authored. The ordinance prohibits The City 
     from contracting with firms that do business in Burma, a Southeast Asian 
     nation whose
     military rulers routinely violate human rights, watchdog groups say.
     <p>
         Martin says the Burma ordinance does not apply to the people-mover 
     contract because the law exempts construction projects, a contention Ammiano is 
     fighting. The Airports Commission will consider the matter at a special 
     meeting tentatively scheduled for Dec. 23.
     <p>
         Martin's recommendation comes after the release of a scathing 
     report Nov. 21 by the San Francisco Human Rights Commission asking that Mitsubishi's 
     bid be shelved. The agency investigated Mitsubishi's bid to see whether it 
     complied with city goals that call for at least 12 percent of contracted work to be 
     done by local businesses owned by women and minorities. The commission keeps a 
     list of qualified businesses from which contractors are supposed to select.
     <p>
         The panel contends that the three subcontractors Mitsubishi picked 
     to meet the contracting goals come up short, and that Mitsubishi failed to 
     show that it had made a good-faith effort to find qualified outfits. Among its 
     findings: 
<ul>
       <li>  Woman-owned Aladdin Builders, assigned to supply and install 
     equipment for automated doors, "does not possess the expertise" to do the job and 
     will have to work under another subcontractor that does.
     
<li>Minority-owned B&F Concrete Contractors Inc., assigned to provide 
     finishing work, including doors, ceilings, hardware, walls, floor finishes and 
     painting, is "not certified by the Human Rights Commission as a supplier of such 
     material." In addition, the expected work is not the type "supplied by 
     the company in the normal course of its business."
     
<li>Minority-owned Metalset, assigned to perform steel fabrication and 
     to supply and install walkway, guidance and retention material, is not certified 
     as a supplier, "nor does it have adequate facilities to be a supplier of 
     such material."
     </ul>
     Not good enough, panel says, because B&F Concrete Contractors and Metalset are certified by the 
     Human Rights Commission to do some of the work, the panel gives Mitsubishi 
     partial credit toward meeting the minority- and female-owned contracting 
     goals. But the value adds up to only 10.5 percent of the total project, falling short 
     of the 12 percent recommended.
     <p>
         Meanwhile, ADtranz is raising questions about the legitimacy of 
     the subcontractors, and hired a private investigator to check them out. 
     The investigator, Montano and Associates, concluded that Metalset and B&F 
     Concrete Contractors were shell businesses, that their San Francisco offices 
     were seldom if ever used, and that their principal owners worked for other 
     companies. 
<p>
         Metalset President Ricardo Rosales called the allegations 
     nonsense, saying his business is legitimate. Representatives of B&F Concrete 
     Contractors could not be reached for comment.
     <p>
<center><h3>     Officials feud</h3></center>
     
         Adding further intrigue to the tangled people-mover contract is a
     disagreement between the airport's Martin and the Human Rights 
     Commission. Martin sent Human Rights Executive Director Marivic Bamba a pointed 
     letter last week in which he said he had a number of "concerns and questions" over 
     the panel's Mitsubishi report, which she wrote.
     <p>
         He declined to outline his concerns in the letter "so as not to 
     adversely impact litigation The City is facing or will face in the future." 
     However, he offered to direct the city attorney to review her report and present 
     findings to the Airport Commission.
     <p>
         Bamba could not be reached for comment.
     <p>
         Martin said Wednesday that he felt comfortable in recommending 
     Mitsubishi get the job. "They're the low bidder and qualified," he said.<p>
<hr>
