<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: Interfax 20Dec96 Armemnian Nuclear Safety Key  in EBRD Talks</title>
<h1>Interfax 20Dec96 Armemnian Nuclear Safety Key  in EBRD Talks</h1>
<i>ctroy@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 20 Dec 96 12:08:39 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#92">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#92">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#92">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#92">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0093.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 20DEC96 - LATEST ISSUE OF OPPOSITION NEWSPAPER CONFIS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0091.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 19DEC96 - TRIALS ON POST-ELECTION UNREST IN YEREVAN T"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     SAFETY OF ARMENIAN NUCLEAR PLANT KEY TOPIC IN TALKS WITH EBRD<br>
     <br>
                    YEREVAN, Dec  19 (Interfax)  - The safety of the <br>
     Armenian nuclear power  station has  been a  key subject  of the  <br>
     talks between Yerevan  and the  European Bank for Reconstruction and<br>
     Development (EBRD)  during the  past two years, Armenian Prime<br>
     Minister Armen  Sarkisian told  a Thursday  news conference in<br>
     Yerevan.<br>
        Under a 1993 agreement on a $57 million EBRD loan for the<br>
     construction of  the fifth section of the Razdan thermal power<br>
     station, the  nuclear plant should not have resumed operation.<br>
     Now Armenia has a chance "to overcome the clause by diplomatic<br>
     means," Sarkisian said.<br>
        The second  unit of  the nuclear  station resumed work in<br>
     1995 and  now the  international community  has  focussed  its<br>
     attention on  the safety  of the  facility.  "The  station  is<br>
     vitally important  for the  republic and we will do our utmost<br>
     to resolve the problem," the prime minister said.<br>
        He thinks  the task  is achievable  because "the  West is<br>
     ready to offer experts and funds for this purpose."<br>
     He said  that on  recommendations from the EBRD a council<br>
     for nuclear  energy including  foreign experts was formed this<br>
     year under the Armenian president.<br>
        Sarkisian said  the  EBRD  suspended  financing  for  the<br>
     expansion of the Razdan thermal station last year. A total $30<br>
     million out of the planned $57 million was disbursed.<br>
        He  said   a  mistake  in  evaluating  the  cost  of  the<br>
     construction was  among the  reasons for  the freezing  of the<br>
     project. Initially  it was planned to spend $80 million on the<br>
     project, $25  million of  which  should  have  come  from  the<br>
        Armenian government,  but in  the process  of construction  it<br>
     turned out  that the  funds were  insufficient,  the  official<br>
     said.<br>
        A total  $80 million more has to be found now to complete<br>
     the station,  the prime minister said. The Armenian government<br>
     intends to invite international financial institutions as well<br>
     as private investors to join the project.<br>
     During his  recent visit  to London,  Sarkisian suggested<br>
     repaying Armenia's  debt by  offering the  EBRD a stake in the<br>
     Razdan power plant.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
