<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI</title>
<h1>OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 96 11:39:24 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 19DEC96 - TRIALS ON POST-ELECTION UNREST IN YEREVAN T"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax, 12/12 NAGORNO-KARABAKH MAY OPT OUT OF PEACE TALKS"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RIGHTS IN CENTRAL ASIA. In <br>
     its annual survey of freedom and democracy worldwide, the U.S.-based <br>
     Freedom House identified Tajikistan and Turkmenistan as among the 17 <br>
     most repressive regimes in the world, RFE-RL reported on 18 December. <br>
     Uzbekistan, which last year also appeared in the worst category, <br>
     improved its record in 1996. Among the CIS countries, Armenia, <br>
     Georgia, Moldova, Russia, and Ukraine are rated "partly free;" and <br>
     Azerbaijan, Belarus, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, <br>
     and Uzbekistan are listed as "not free." Freedom House ratings are <br>
     based on a check- list of political rights and civil liberties, <br>
     including the degree of autonomy for minorities, the status of the <br>
     opposition, the nature of electoral laws, and the degree of freedom of <br>
     assembly and freedom of the media. -- Lowell Bezanis<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
