<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: Interfax, 12/12 NAGORNO-KARABAKH MAY OPT OUT OF PEACE TALKS</title>
<h1>Interfax, 12/12 NAGORNO-KARABAKH MAY OPT OUT OF PEACE TALKS</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 13 Dec 96 13:39:22 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#89">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#89">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#89">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#89">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0090.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0088.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 13DEC96 - ARMENIAN CHURCH HEAD MEETS WITH POPE"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
               NAGORNO-KARABAKH MAY OPT OUT OF PEACE TALKS WITH AZERBAIJAN<br>
     <br>
                    STEPANAKERT, Dec  12 (Interfax)  - The  parliament of the<br>
               self-proclaimed Nagorno-Karabakh  Republic has  questioned the<br>
               wisdom of participating in the Minsk peace process.<br>
                    It expressed  its regret Thursday over the failure of the<br>
               Organization for  Security and  Cooperation in Europe's summit<br>
               in Lisbon to denounce the Azerbaijani delegation's position on<br>
               the Karabakh-Azerbaijani conflict.<br>
                    The remarks  made by  the OSCE  chairman-in-office on the<br>
               principles underlying  the resolution  of the Karabakh problem<br>
               is "an  attempt at dictating the status of Nagorno-Karabakh in<br>
               total disregard  of the  people's right  to self-determination<br>
               and other OSCE principles," a parliament statement says.<br>
                    Every nation  has a  right to  freedom and  security,  it<br>
               says. "Our  people have  paid too  large a price for that, and<br>
               will never  agree to  become a  chit in  a big  oil game," the<br>
               statement says.<br>
                    The Karabakh  parliament called  on Baku  "to abandon the<br>
               policy of  annexation" and  start  bilateral  talks.  "We  are<br>
               convinced that this is the shortest and most constructive road<br>
               to accord  and peace between Nagorno-Karabakh and Azerbaijan,"<br>
               the document says.<br>
                    The Karabakh  parliament described  the statement made by<br>
               the  OSCE   chairman-in-office  as  a  biased  position  which<br>
               reflects only  Azerbaijani interests  and is inconsistent with<br>
               the essence of international cooperation.<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
