<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: OMRI - 12DEC96 - TURKEY ABANDONS PLANS TO OPEN BORDER WITH A</title>
<h1>OMRI - 12DEC96 - TURKEY ABANDONS PLANS TO OPEN BORDER WITH A</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 12 Dec 96 11:20:25 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 13DEC96 - ARMENIAN CHURCH HEAD MEETS WITH POPE"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 11DEC96 - THREE DASHNAK PARTY MEMBERS SENTENCED TO DE"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     TURKEY ABANDONS PLANS TO OPEN BORDER WITH ARMENIA. The Turkish Foreign <br>
     Ministry on 11 December announced that Turkey will not open its border <br>
     with Armenia unless the latter "takes steps" toward respecting <br>
     Azerbaijan's sovereignty over Nagorno-Karabakh and provides for a <br>
     withdrawal of Armenian forces from the "occupied Azerbaijani <br>
     territories," international agencies reported. The ministry statement <br>
     contradictsa an earlier announcement by Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller <br>
     that the border will be opened soon (see OMRI Daily Digest, 24 October <br>
     1996). The ministry might be reacting to Armenia's refusal to sign a <br>
     document that mentioned Nagorno-Karabakh as part of Azerbaijan at the <br>
     OSCE's recent summit in Lisbon. Turkey closed its border with Armenia <br>
     in early 1992 after accusing it of "military aggression" against <br>
     Azerbaijan. -- Emil Danielyan<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 13DEC96 - ARMENIAN CHURCH HEAD MEETS WITH POPE"</a>
