<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: CENASIAN  BATTALIN  MAY  BACK  KARABAKH PEACEKEEPING  EFFORT</title>
<h1>CENASIAN  BATTALIN  MAY  BACK  KARABAKH PEACEKEEPING  EFFORT</h1>
<i>arichter@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 12 Nov 96 18:09:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 13Nov96 - Nagorno-Karabakh Election Update"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 12Nov96 - Ter-Petrossyan Inaugurated Amid Controversy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 <br>
 CENTRAL  ASIAN  BATTALION  MAY  BACK  PEACEKEEPING  EFFORT  IN KARABAKH<br>
 <br>
 BAKU, Nov  12 (Interfax)  - Kyrgyz  Foreign Minister Roza<br>
 Otunbayeva  does   not  rule   out  the   possibility  of  the participation of <br>
 a Central Asian battalion in the peacekeeping operation in Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
 The Central  Asian states' forces might be represented in<br>
 the international peacekeeping contingent that is likely to be deployed in  the <br>
 conflict  zone after  Azerbaijan and  Armenia sign a peace agreement, she told <br>
 Interfax in Baku today.<br>
 If the parties concerned make this request, this question<br>
 may be  discussed by  the Interstate  Council of  the  Central Asian Union, <br>
 comprising Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.<br>
 The Central  Asian battalion  has this year taken part in<br>
 military exercises within NATO's Partnership for Peace program in Virginia, the <br>
 United States, she said.<br>
 Similar military  exercises, observed by foreign military<br>
 experts, including  NATO  representatives,  will  be  held  in Central Asia <br>
 next year, she said.<br>
 <br>
 (c) Interfax, 1996<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
