<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: 6 Nov 96 - Armenian Opposition Criticizes Constitutional Cou</title>
<h1>6 Nov 96 - Armenian Opposition Criticizes Constitutional Cou</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 07 Nov 96 11:36:09 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#59">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#59">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#59">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#59">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "7Nov96 - Armenia's New Prime Minister to Continue Econ. Refo"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0058.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "6 Nov 96 - More Karabakh Diplomacy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     ARMENIAN OPPOSITION CRITICIZES CONSTITUTIONAL COURT. Shavarsh <br>
     Kocharyan, the Constitutional Court representative of defeated <br>
     presidential candidate Vazgen Manukyan, said the court "violates the <br>
     principles of equality and transparency" in validating the 22 <br>
     September election results, Noyan Tapan reported on 5 November. The <br>
     opposition appealed to the court on 24 October, asking it to annul the <br>
     vote. Kocharyan claimed that numerous documented cases of <br>
     irregularities are not being addressed. According to him, Manukyan <br>
     asked the court to return property and documents from his campaign <br>
     headquarters seized by the Interior Ministry, but this was refused on <br>
     the grounds that the court "is not empowered to solve this problem." <br>
     Kocharyan said the Ministry's actions amount to a virtual suspension <br>
     of the party, which, according to Armenian law, only the <br>
     Constitutional Court has the right to decide. -- Emil Danielyan<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
