<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: OMRI--3 Oct 1996--OSCE CASTS DOUBTS ON ARMENIAN PRES. POLL</title>
<h1>OMRI--3 Oct 1996--OSCE CASTS DOUBTS ON ARMENIAN PRES. POLL</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 03 Oct 96 12:13:02 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#31">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#31">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#31">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#31">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--2 0CTOBER 1996--MANUKYAN ABJURES VIOLENCE"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--1 October 1996 -- TER-PETROSSYAN SOFTENS RHETORIC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
     <br>
     OSCE CASTS DOUBTS ON ARMENIAN PRESIDENTIAL POLL. The OSCE/ODIHR <br>
     mission issued a statement in Warsaw on 2 October noting "very serious <br>
     breaches of the election law" during last month's Armenian <br>
     presidential election, AFP and RFE/RL reported. The mission noted a <br>
     discrepancy of 21,000 between the number of ballots counted and the <br>
     number of votes cast; President Levon Ter-Petrossyan has claimed <br>
     victory by a margin of less than 22,000 votes. Central Electoral <br>
     Commission Chairman Khachatour Bezirjian rejected the OSCE claims on <br>
     the grounds that the organization's tallies of irregularities are "not <br>
     mathematically correct," according to AFP. Opposition presidential <br>
     candidate Vazgen Manukyan on 2 October called for a second round of <br>
     voting or a new election. -- Liz Fuller<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--2 0CTOBER 1996--MANUKYAN ABJURES VIOLENCE"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--1 October 1996 -- TER-PETROSSYAN SOFTENS RHETORIC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
