<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: OMRI--25 September 96--TER-PETROSSYAN LEADS IN ARMENIAN PRES</title>
<h1>OMRI--25 September 96--TER-PETROSSYAN LEADS IN ARMENIAN PRES</h1>
<i>tlankina@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 26 Sep 96 14:53:23 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#28">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#28">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#28">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#28">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0029.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--30 September 96--COMMISSION UPHOLDS TER-PETROSSYAN'S E"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0027.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--25 September 96--TER-PETROSSYAN LEADS IN ARMENIAN PRES"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     TER-PETROSSYAN LEADS IN ARMENIAN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION . . . According <br>
     to data released at midday on 24 September by the Central Electoral <br>
     Commission, incumbent Levon Ter-Petrossyan received 52.32% of the <br>
     votes cast in the 22 September presidential election, while his <br>
     principal challenger Vazgen Manukyan gained 40.73%, Noyan Tapan <br>
     reported. Voter turnout was given at 58.25%. In Yerevan, with returns <br>
     from one district still outstanding, Manukyan's share of the vote was <br>
     53% compared with 41% for Ter-Petrossyan. Simon Osborn, who <br>
     coordinated the OSCE/ODIHR election monitoring mission, told a news <br>
     conference on 24 September that the 89 foreign observers had noted <br>
     several flagrant violations, including the theft of ballot boxes in <br>
     one Yerevan precinct, but that these were not of a magnitude to cast <br>
     doubt on the overall results, Western agencies reported. -- Liz Fuller<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0029.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--30 September 96--COMMISSION UPHOLDS TER-PETROSSYAN'S E"</a>
