<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Armenia: OMRI--26 September 96--MANUKYAN ARRESTED</title>
<h1>OMRI--26 September 96--MANUKYAN ARRESTED</h1>
<i>tlankina@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 26 Sep 96 14:38:04 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--25 September 96--TER-PETROSSYAN LEADS IN ARMENIAN PRES"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI -- 26 September 96--OPPOSITION SUPPORTERS STORM ARMENIA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     MANUKYAN ARRESTED. Presidential spokesman Shahen Karamanukyan and <br>
     Interior Minister Vano Siradeghyan denounced the attack on the <br>
     parliament building as "an attempted fascist coup ordered by one of <br>
     the leaders of the National Democratic Union," Reuters and AFP <br>
     reported. ITAR-TASS quoted Siradeghyan as stating that three <br>
     organizers of the protest had been arrested; Prosecutor General <br>
     Artavazd Gevorkyan announced that the organizers would be charged with <br>
     attempting to stage a coup d'etat and the attempted murder of the <br>
     parliament speaker and his deputy, according to AFP. Speaking on state <br>
     television on the morning of 26 September, President Ter-Petrossyan <br>
     imposed a ban on all unsanctioned meetings and demonstrations. Early <br>
     the same day, riot police surrounded the presidential palace, which is <br>
     close to the parliament building, and tanks and armored personnel <br>
     carriers cordoned off Yerevan's main square and the nearby <br>
     headquarters of the NDU. On the morning of 26 September, the Armenian <br>
     parliament voted by an overwhelming majority to lift Manukyan's <br>
     immunity. He and several other opposition leaders were subsequently <br>
     arrested, Western agencies reported. -- Liz Fuller<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
