<title>Groong Network: From Russian nationalist "Zavtra" (Tomorrow)</title>
<h1>From Russian nationalist "Zavtra" (Tomorrow)</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 11 Jan 1997 11:21:15 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#334">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#334">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#334">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#334">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0335.html">David Davidian: "Turkish Press Review"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0333.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "From Russian nationalist "Zavtra" (Tomorrow)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
(I recommend to take some of the assertions of this newspaper with a grain<br>
of salt. Accuracy is not its forte.  And it is generally known for wrapping<br>
world affairs in grand theories of conspiracy. The conference on ivestments<br>
in Russia is not held secretely at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.<br>
The last day of the conference is tomorrow January 12. Some things though<br>
(Yeltsin's health etc.) they often get right. Cheers. AM.)  =20<br>
<p>
<p>
Zavtra No.1, January 1997 page 1<br>
<p>
   Unattributed 'field reports by the DEN =AEMDBO=AF=AEMDNM=AFsecurity=<br>
 service'<br>
<p>
  Sources in the medical circles report that on the night of 2-3 January a<br>
special team from the Kremlin hospital went to B. Yeltsin whose legs had<br>
suddenly begun swelling and who developed malfunctioning in the heart<br>
activity.  That served as a reason for the president's noshow at the<br>
children's [New Year's] celebration at the Kremlin with Yu. Luzhkov.<br>
Meanwhile, the leadership of the presidential staff entrusted the doctors to<br>
do their best to enable Yeltsin to meet with H. Kohl in Zavidovo.  To this<br>
end B. Yeltsin was transported by a special helicopter to his villa in<br>
Zavidovo, which now has a complete intensive care unit with state-of-the-art<br>
equipment that can enable the sick man to hold negotiations for up to two<br>
and a half hours....<br>
 According to sources in Bonn the main motive for H. Kohl's visit to Moscow<br>
is Bonn's intention to consolidate the positions of V. Chernomyrdin as prime<br>
minister in order to make sure that he "lasts" in this post until B.<br>
Yeltsin's natural demise.  Observations by German doctors who took part in<br>
the operation and in consultations were analyzed and presented by the BND to<br>
the federal chancellor.  According to them the physical demise of B. Yeltsin<br>
could come at any moment; it cannot be prevented by any medical means.  The<br>
president's maximum capacity period -- with a gradual worsening of health --<br>
is estimated at 15 months.  In this connection a group of German banks and<br>
leading energy corporations recommended that H. Kohl take to Moscow an offer<br>
of additional IMF loans against the pledge of Viktor Chernomyrdin's<br>
remaining in his post to overcome economic difficulties during the most<br>
crucial period in the first half of 1997.  This activism by H. Kohl,<br>
according to a source in Bonn, is related to the intention of German<br>
financial circles to prevent the advent of a purely U.S. creation (Chubays,<br>
Potanin, Yavlinskiy, and so forth) in the top position in the Russian<br>
Federation after Yeltsin's departure....<br>
 A number of sources in the inner circle of Russian Federation Defense<br>
Council Secretary Yu. Baturin report that pressure on the power ministries<br>
will soon be stepped up; a series of decisions are pending to revise the<br>
internal structure in the power departments.  These include the FSB,<br>
[Federal Security Service] the Internal Affairs Ministry, and the Defense<br>
Ministry.  The Baturin group believes that in late 1996 it achieved a<br>
historic breakthrough in modifying the command and control structure of the<br>
Defense Ministry, as well as its system of as a whole, in the face of<br>
counteraction by P. Grachev and some other generals.  At present chaos is<br>
growing within the Defense Ministry amid the introduction of a<br>
U.S.-patterned concept whereby the General Staff is to play a paramount=<br>
 role. =20<br>
 The general squabble that has emerged in the military conforms with the<br>
guidelines for the full surrender of positions to pro-Turkish forces in<br>
Chechnya and other Caucasus republics. =20<br>
 Baturin and the presidential staff are preparing an analogous attack on the<br>
Internal Affairs Ministry and the FSB.  It is planned to entrust leading<br>
positions in the power structures to those generals who were directly<br>
involved with the Chechen fighters and bankers of a pro-Chechen orientation.<br>
A leading role in the further "chaotization" of the Caucasus is assigned to<br>
the Russian Federation Security Council and I. Rybkin, who for a long period<br>
of time has maintained friendly relations with the Ingushetia Bank [BIN] (M.<br>
Gutseriyev is deputy Duma speaker and head of the BIN).<br>
 According to sources at the World Bank (USA) a series of large scale<br>
schemes are being elaborated in the V. Potantin entourage and the financial<br>
corporation Renaissance Capital, which is affiliated with Uneximbank,<br>
designed to restructure large enterprises in the Russian Federation with the<br>
subsequent sale of new stakes on the New York exchange, which will help to<br>
systematically transfer control of industry and property rights to its<br>
objects into the hands of major U.S. magnates.=20<br>
 The model here is the firm Vympelkom which was created by Academician V.<br>
Zimin, director of the Radio Scientific and Research Institute, who earlier<br>
worked for the FAPSI [Federal Government Communications and Information<br>
Agency] on a project to encode and decode secret radio frequencies.  Trading<br>
on his position, V. Zimin with a number of colleagues founded a firm to sell<br>
Bee-Line mobile phones, transferring to it the best telecommunication<br>
frequencies, and then with the assistance of Renaissance Capital prepared<br>
the placement of stocks on U.S. exchanges, where they were bought up by<br>
representatives of the G. Soros group.  It so happened that G. Soros has<br>
from the start been behind the activity of Renaissance Capital and<br>
Uneximbank in this sphere....<br>
 According to sources in New York's financial circles soon, possibly on 12<br>
to 22 January, Anatoliy Chubays, V. Potanin, Federal Bankruptcy<br>
Administration Director P. Mostovoy, Federal Securities Commission chief S.<br>
Vasilyev, and some other officials will arrive in the United States.  They<br>
will take part in a conference at Harvard University, the J. Kennedy School<br>
of Management, and the Harvard Institute for International Development<br>
(headed by the not-unknown G. Sachs).  Others will come unofficially, via<br>
clandestine channels.  In both instances closed meetings are scheduled with<br>
leading figures at the IMF, the World Bank, and Wall Street.  The central<br>
subject is related to the third stage of the redistribution of property in<br>
the Russian Federation and the CIS as part of the play on arrears and the<br>
transfer of property rights to Russia's key strategic enterprises into the<br>
hands of U.S. major financial groupings.  The main object of the dialogue on<br>
the pending multilevel scheme is RAO [Russian Joint Stock Company] Gazrpom;<br>
in 1997 it is planned to restructure it by giving access to RAO assets to<br>
Uneximbank, Obyedinennyy [United] Bank, and others, which will represent the<br>
interests of U.S. financial circles.  The present scheme of restructuring<br>
(proposed by Gazprom itself) is deemed unable to meet the interests of the<br>
U.S. financial establishment.  In the event of Gazprom's structures being<br>
wholly transferred to the regional level Potanin and Berezovskiy will be<br>
able to acquire controlling stakes in the extremely rich mining enterprises,<br>
including in the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous District, where they have long<br>
been actively sounding out local Duma deputies....<br>
 According to sources close to CIA analytical structures in Washington the<br>
main aim of the U.S. intelligence community in the next few months is the<br>
overthrow of S. Milosevic as well as the current regime in Sofia.  This will<br>
help to place these governments under control and cut the lines of Russia's<br>
potential influence in the Balkans as well as scuttle the implementation of<br>
the Caspian oil transportation route via the port of Burgas (Bulgaria) to<br>
Yugoslavia to Europe bypassing Turkey.  S. Milosevic and the Russian<br>
Federation should reap the fruit of their meek acceptance of the Dayton<br>
agreements.  The only way out for S. Milosevic is to rely on patriotic<br>
circles in Belgrade and in other parts of Serbia, just as it is for the<br>
socialist government in Bulgaria.  The indifference of the Russian special<br>
services and the Foreign Ministry stuns analysts in the United States and<br>
Europe....<br>
 According to reports from Ankara it is planned soon to create a<br>
coordinating center for liaison with Caucasus peoples and republics.<br>
Substantial intermediary functions are to be given to the political top of<br>
Azerbaijan, including President G. Aliyev's personal connections with R.<br>
Aushev, the leader of Ingushetia, via V. Alekperov, president of Russia's<br>
largest oil company Lukoil.  The latter, observers believe, is being<br>
increasingly assigned a major role in infringing Russian strategic oil<br>
interests in the Caucasus and in other regions.  Russia is given a<br>
negligible share of profit in any large oil project while V. Alekperov<br>
pushes through the Russian government such geographic routes for the<br>
pipelines whereby  the Russian Federation loses its strategic control of<br>
them....<br>
 U.S. special services held conferences to assess performance in 1996.<br>
Major debacles are linked with the failure of plans to eliminate A.<br>
Lukashenka in Minsk and foment a new military conflict in Tajikistan, and<br>
the collapse of the Talib offensive toward Turkmenistan's borders.  Another<br>
major flop has been the inability to scuttle the Russian-Chinese dialogue.<br>
In this sphere, it is planned to take pinpoint action to thwart economic<br>
projects (energy, the military industrial complex, aircraft building, and<br>
the nuclear industry).  Expansion of control over TV in the Russian<br>
Federation and in the CIS as a whole is considered to be the most impressive<br>
ideological success story.  It is planned to strengthen financial and other<br>
forms of interaction with the Russian TV leadership (Malashenko, Sagalayev,<br>
Kiselev, Lysenko, Svanidze, and others)....<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
