<title>Groong Network: ANC Eastern US appoints new director</title>
<h1>ANC Eastern US appoints new director</h1>
ANC Eastern US (<i>76443.1011@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>10 Jan 97 20:50:46 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#330">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#330">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#330">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#330">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0331.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 01/11/97"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0329.html">Noyan Tapan: "Noyan Tapan Bulletin 09/01/97"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Armenian National Committee<br>
of the Eastern United States<br>
80 Bigelow Avenue<br>
Watertown, Massachusetts 02172<br>
Tel: 617-923-1918<br>
Fax: 617-926-1750<br>
76443.1011@compuserve.com<br>
<p>
For Immediate Release<br>
1/7/97<br>
<p>
<p>
ANC appoints Grace Kehetian Kulegian executive director of Eastern US office<br>
<p>
WATERTOWN, MA--The Board of Directors of the Armenian National Committee of the<br>
Eastern United States (ANC ER) appointed Grace Kehetian Kulegian as its new<br>
executive director, effective January 1.<br>
	<br>
Kehetian Kulegian comes to the ANC ER office after almost five years with The<br>
Armenian Weekly as its Assistant Editor. Prior to that, she was was employed by<br>
the Beacon Communications newspaper group in Acton, MA, and the Massachusetts<br>
Institute of Technology, in Cambridge.<br>
<p>
"I am looking forward to working with the ANC in furthering the work of hai tahd<br>
and promoting issues of concern to the Armenian American community," said<br>
Kehetian Kulegian. "Working with the grassroots to promote hai tahd in the<br>
American political arena is exciting work, and I am especially looking forward<br>
to being part of that process."<br>
<p>
"We are enthusiastic about the new energy Kehetian Kulegian will bring to the<br>
diverse work of the ANC," said Harry Dederian, ANC ER chairman. "1997 will prove<br>
to be a challenging year, and we're confident Kehetian Kulegian's experience<br>
will benefit the ANC in meeting its challenges."<br>
<p>
Kehetian Kulegian is a member of the ARF Boston "Sardarabad" gomidehoutiun, the<br>
Armenian Relief Society Boston "Javo" chapter, and is a former member of the<br>
Detroit "Kopernik Tandourjian" AYF chapter. She is a member of the teaching<br>
staff of the St. Stephen's Armenian Church Sunday School in Watertown, where she<br>
resides with her husband, John, and their two sons, John Moushegh and Michael<br>
Kourken.<br>
<p>
###<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
