<!-- body="start" -->
	  NOYAN TAPAN DAILY INFORMATION BULLETIN<br>
                    FOR GROONG READERS<br>
                     January 09, 1997<br>
<p>
    -------------------------------------------------------<br>
                 (c) 1997, All Rights Reserved<br>
    Materials in this publication  may not be  reproduced in<br>
    any form  without  permission,  nor  may it  be sold or<br>
    otherwise transferred to a third party. <br>
<p>
     This is not the full daily information published by the<br>
     "Noyan Tapan" News Agency. The whole amount of our product <br>
     is on subscription basis.<br>
<p>
                Please direct all inquiries to:<br>
          Noyan Tapan Information &amp; Analytical Center<br>
                   E-mail: nt@nt.arminco.com<br>
          Tel &amp; Fax: (3742) 52-42-79, (3742) 56-19-05<br>
          URL: <a href="http://www.arminco.com/~nt1">http://www.arminco.com/~nt1</a><br>
   --------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
<p>
P O L I T I C A L   N E W S<br>
-------------------------------------------------     <br>
<p>
PREMIER STILL IN USA <br>
ON A WORKING VISIT<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 9 (Noyan Tapan). Armenia's Premier Armen<br>
Sargssian, who is now in Washington on a working visit, met<br>
Wednesday with Paul Gafney, vice-admiral of the US Naval<br>
Research Cemnter. Only three CIS republics have established good<br>
relations with the Naval Research Center and cooperate in the<br>
field of high technologies. Mr.Gafney accepted Premier's<br>
invitation to visit Armenia in order to get familiarized with<br>
our Republic's scientific potential.<br>
     In an interview to the "Washington Times" daily Armen<br>
Sargssian introduced Armenia's stance over the most important<br>
regional problems, in particular, development of cooperation in<br>
Caucasus, regional stability and peace, possible ways of<br>
economic cooperation between Armenia and her neighbors.<br>
     Armen Sargssian also introduced governmental programs aimed<br>
at developing Armenia's economic and social reforms. The goal of<br>
these reforms is to turn Armenia into a regional strategic<br>
state, creating strong sub-structures to ensure growth of<br>
economy and trade and encourage international investments.<br>
     During a short meeting with John Portyr, co-Chairman of the<br>
US Congress's committee for Armenia, the two underlined<br>
Armenia's importance in the establishment of democracy and<br>
market relations in the region. Premier presented Armenian<br>
government's internal policy, that is to solve all disputable<br>
problems with parties and political organizations through a<br>
dialogue.  According to him, the first stage of political<br>
discussions with opposition leaders have already started. <br>
     Premier also had a meeting with Chairman of the<br>
International Fund for Election Systems Richard Saudrith and<br>
introduced the development program for Armenia's democratic<br>
structures, especially mass media. The program suggests creation<br>
of favorable economic conditions for the present mass media and<br>
establishment of new ones.<br>
     During a meeting with representatives of Armenian colony<br>
that took place at the Armenian embassy to the USA, Premier<br>
spoke of programs aimed at strengthening economic stability,<br>
free market relations and involving international and internal<br>
investments. Armen Sargssian emphasized that Armenia's<br>
government is presently working out bills to stimulate<br>
privatization and investments in Armenia.<br>
     Speaking of Armenia-diaspora relations, Premier noted that<br>
the Armenian government encourages active relations between<br>
Armenia and diaspora. He specially emphasized the importance of<br>
unification of all links that unite Armenians all over the<br>
world. This is testified by the establishment of a special<br>
authority to deal with diaspora with the government.<br>
     Armen Sargssian is also supposed to meet with<br>
representatives of American business circles, in order to have a<br>
discussion over establishment of more close relations.  Premier<br>
will also meet with high ranking officials of White House and<br>
State Secretariat, a number of senators and congressmen. <br>
<p>
E C O N O M I C   N E W S<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
TIGRAN JRBASHIAN: ARMENIA <br>
CAN AFFORD SHARP INCREASE IN<br>
MONEY SUPPLY AND INFLATION<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 9 (Noyan Tapan). Armenia can afford sharp<br>
increase in the money supply (probably, up to 150 billion drams<br>
instead of current 50-60 billion drams) in order to promote<br>
economic growth, said Tigran Jrbashian, Director of the<br>
consulting company "Sed-Marsed."<br>
     In Jrbashian's opinion, one should not be afraid of a sharp<br>
increase in the inflation rate (up to 50% a year) either.<br>
According to him, the main thing is not to evade the inflation<br>
of demand, when "money works for consumption," and to make<br>
"money work for production" when money is spent on the work of<br>
enterprises. "Only in this case the reanimated industry will<br>
help overcome the dependence on international credits", said Mr.<br>
Jrbashian.<br>
     The head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)<br>
delegation in Armenia Tanos Katsabmas has stated that the<br>
allocation of the next ESAF credit tranche for 1997 may be<br>
delayed unless Armenia brings down the inflation rate in the<br>
budget and ensures tax assignments to the budget. A credit of<br>
$150 mln is designed for three years; Armenia received the first<br>
$50 mln in 1996.<br>
     One of the toughest conditions the IMF has set up for<br>
allocation of the credit is the stabilization of the dram rate.<br>
However, according to T.Jrbashian, the drop in dram's rate has<br>
been restrained by "barbarous methods" that are delays in<br>
payment of wages, pensions and fellowship.  Moreover, state<br>
enterprises were not even paid for state order supplies.<br>
     There appeared a chain of mutual non-payments on which<br>
sanctions imposed by the tax inspection lay as a heavy burden:<br>
on the one hand the government did not pay, on the other hand it<br>
demanded tax payments.<br>
     Jrbashian noted that economic growth under conditions of a<br>
transition period is known to be accompanied by inflation and<br>
devaluation. Such a growth proved to be impossible in Armenia<br>
because of the gap between the controlled dram rate and<br>
continuous growth of inflation. This gap has led to rise in<br>
prices of commodities in terms of dollar ( on the averrage,<br>
these prices have risen several times in Armenia over the last<br>
three years). Thus, excellent conditions have been created for<br>
getting super profits from import. At the same time such a<br>
situation played for the increase in cost price for export<br>
goods, making it impossible to compete both on the foreign and<br>
domestic markets.<br>
     Jrbashian noted that in response to the conditions on<br>
economic growth set by the IMF Armenia presented the figure of<br>
6%, which quite satisfied the IMF. However, as the Finance<br>
Minister noted, there had been no real economic growth in<br>
Armenia, and, therefore, this figure did not meet the reality.<br>
     In Jrbashian's opinion, the government may be denied IMF<br>
credit if it chooses the variant of an intensive economic<br>
growth. Such a policy proves its value in case of money supply<br>
control (and consequently inflation and devaluation) being aimed<br>
at concrete tasks, the main of which are the payment of state<br>
debts and state investments. <br>
<p>
H O M E   N E W S<br>
---------------------------------------------------------     <br>
   <br>
EXCISE STAMPS TO BE <br>
INSTALLED IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 9 (Noyan Tapan). Starting from the second<br>
quarter of this year Armenia will have excise stamps, Finance<br>
Minister Levon Barkhoudarian said.<br>
     There was announced a tender for preparation of excise<br>
stamps. It is expected that by the end of March the stamps will<br>
be issued.<br>
     Under a new version of the law "On excise tax", which<br>
started working on January 1, the excise tax is raised from the<br>
following goods:<br>
<p>
     Wine-vodka				125%<br>
<p>
     Beer				75%<br>
<p>
     Grape wines, wine raw material 	50%<br>
<p>
     Fish caviar			200%<br>
<p>
     Tobacco				50-100%<br>
<p>
     Jewelry goods			30%<br>
<p>
     Furs				25%<br>
<p>
     Cars				15%<br>
<p>
     Cut-glass and china		25%<br>
<p>
     Petrol				25%<br>
     <br>
WORLD HEALTH ORGANIZATION OPENED <br>
ITS SECOND OFFICE IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 9 (Noyan Tapan). Through the financial<br>
assistance of the World Health Organization (WHO) and the<br>
government of Norway an office of advisor to health ministers of<br>
Armenia and Georgia started recently working in Armenia. The<br>
basis for opening of the office was the quadrilateral agreement<br>
signed by WHO, government of Norway, health ministries of<br>
Georgia and Armenia within the framework of the program "Advisor<br>
for public health". Office Chief, Doc. Turalf Hassvold has been<br>
to Armenia since mid December to cover preliminary works on<br>
opening of the office.<br>
     Head of the WHO's office to Armenia Hrayr Aslanian said<br>
that the aim of the office is to assist health ministries of the<br>
two Transcaucasian states to work out a strategy of prospective<br>
health policy. According to him, WHO opened two offices in<br>
Armenia, however, they are registered at the foreign ministry as<br>
one mission.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
