<!-- body="start" -->
     &lt;Frontier&gt; November-December 1995, pp. 1-2<br>
     Copyright 1995, Kesten Institute, Oxford<br>
     <br>
     <br>
     "Full Circle"<br>
     <br>
     ******<br>
     Recent amendments to Azerbaijan's law on religion usher in a new era <br>
     of repression for western groups and give new powers to the leader of <br>
     the country's divided Islamic community writes Felix Corley<br>
     ******<br>
     <br>
     As elsewhere in the former Soviet Union, it seemed the end of the <br>
     Soviet period had ushered in an era of freedom of religion in <br>
     Azerbaijan too. Communist persecution came to an end, and a new <br>
     liberal law passed in 1992 guaranteed separation of religion and state <br>
     and banned state interference in religious affairs.  The only group <br>
     unable to take advantage of these new freedoms was the Armenian Church <br>
     in Azerbaijan, because of tensions fostered by the continuing conflict <br>
     over Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
     <br>
     The honeymoon period for religious groups is now over and political <br>
     control over religion appears to be making a comeback. Ironically, <br>
     Islam--the majority religion of the country--is now subjected to the <br>
     tightest controls.  The current government of President Heidar Aliyev <br>
     is suspicious of the inroads made by neighbouring Iran, and in <br>
     particular its promotion of Shia Islam, which is loyal to the Shia <br>
     authorities across the border.  An Iranian-sponsored network of Shia <br>
     mosques has sprung up, which is outside the control of the official <br>
     Muslim Board Led by Sheikh-ul-Islam Allahshukur Pashazade. <br>
     <br>
     After a long period of watching and waiting, the government finally <br>
     moved in May 1996 against the Islamic Party, a political body formed <br>
     in 1992 with close links to the Iranian embassy in Baku.  The National <br>
     Security Ministry arrested Akram Aliyev and other party leaders, <br>
     accusing them of spying on behalf of a foreign state. `The members of <br>
     the Islamic Party were dealing with everything but religion,' claimed <br>
     the Security Minster Namig Abbasov.<br>
     <br>
     The following month, the parliament (Milli Majlis) adopted amendment <br>
     to the 1992 law on religion.  One of the main provisions subordinated <br>
     all mosques to the Muslim Board, in an effort to stamp out pro-Iranian <br>
     fundamentalist mullahs. Pashazade had led a public campaign against <br>
     such mullahs, helped by the `competent authorities' (the National <br>
     Security Ministry), whose representatives have muttered darkly that <br>
     foreign religious education is being used as a cover for training in <br>
     espionage.  Other amendments bring religious publishing and <br>
     distribution under closer central control, as well as the selection <br>
     and dispatch of candidates to be trained abroad as mullahs. <br>
     <br>
     The consolidation of central control over mosques comes at a time of <br>
     upheaval within Azerbaijan's Muslim community.  Tension has been <br>
     running high between Pashazade and his former deputy, Haji Sabir <br>
     Hasanly, who was also the rector of the Caucasian Islamic University.  <br>
     After Hasanly accused Pashazade of links with the Ministry of National <br>
     Security, bribery and neglect of mosques, the Muslim Board relieved <br>
     Hasanly of is post for `slandering the Sheikh-ul-Islam, misuse of <br>
     religion and dividing the Muslim community'.  Hasanly retaliated by <br>
     threatening to take Pashazade to court.<br>
     <br>
     Despite the apparent power gained by Pashazade through the amendments <br>
     to the law on religion, and the removal of Hasanly, his basic position <br>
     is weak.  His support for separatists in his home region of Talysh in <br>
     southern Azerbaijan in 1993 has not been forgotten by the country's <br>
     political leadership.  He is also widely unpopular among practising <br>
     Muslims.  Hasanly, who can count on the support of President Aliyev's <br>
     New Azerbaijan Party, is still often tipped as a likely successor to <br>
     Pashazade.<br>
     <br>
     The amendments also affect religious groups other than Islam.  Under <br>
     the new provisions, it will no longer be possible to preach religions <br>
     alien to Azeri tradition or those which the government deems may lead <br>
     to divisions in society.  Foreigners will not be permitted to bring <br>
     religious propaganda into the country.  It remains to be seen how <br>
     these new elements in the law will be put into practice.<br>
     <br>
     Despite his success in promoting amendments to the law on religion, <br>
     Pashazade was still insisting in August that the law was no strong <br>
     enough to counter the activities of Christian `sects' and their <br>
     emissaries in Azerbaijan.  Experts at Baku's Islamic University claim <br>
     that more than 2,000 Azeri Muslims have been converted by such `sects' <br>
     in the past few months alone.  There are complaints that well-funded <br>
     Christian groups have been renting the best halls in Baku for <br>
     missionary purposes. Pashazade has called for the law to be tightened <br>
     further and for an increase in Islamic propaganda.<br>
     <br>
     Once such Christian group to have fallen foul of the law this year is <br>
     the World of Life Church, one of the largest Protestant communities in <br>
     the capital, whose 600 regular worshippers meet in the former KGB <br>
     building in central Baku. After two years of trying to gain official <br>
     status, the church was finally denied registration by the Ministry of <br>
     Justice in May on the grounds that some elements of its statute were <br>
     said to contradict the law on religion.<br>
     <br>
     One of the church's pastors, Aleksandr Neretin, complained that the <br>
     denial of registration was unfounded and represented religious <br>
     discrimination.  The church appealed against the decision, but the <br>
     appeal was turned down in June.  A spokesman for the Ministry of <br>
     Justice reaffirmed its view that the church's activity does not <br>
     conform with the law and cited the `negative attitude' towards the <br>
     church held by the Committee for Religion attached to the Council of <br>
     Ministers.<br>
     <br>
     The church is being backed by the Azerbaijan Committee for the Defence <br>
     of Legality and Human Rights, as well as the Helsinki Commission of <br>
     the US Congress.  However, the support of these bodies has so far <br>
     failed to secure the church's official recognition. <br>
     <br>
     [END]<br>
     <br>
     <br>
