        MODIFICATIONS IN CUSTOMS CODE OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 09, ARMENPRESS.<br>
Starting February 1, the new edition of the Customs Code of the<br>
Republic of Armenia will be put in action. The chapter 14, including <br>
16 articles, on customs rules, violations and liabilities  has been <br>
modified.<br>
According to the First Deputy-Director of the Customs Agency of the <br>
Republic of Armenia Grigor Melkumian, the modifications are made in<br>
consistent with the acting Constitution. If previously  customs officers <br>
levied the goods which became an object of  customs offense, from <br>
February on, according to the Constitution, the court will alienate <br>
property by means of levy. The customs service's administrative<br>
control will be in the forms of notifications and fines. The liabilities<br>
of <br>
the customs offence have been fortified: the articles 84-91 assume <br>
fines equal to 10, 20, 50, 100 and 200 times of the salary; the articles <br>
92-97 assume fines equal to 50 % and 100 % of the good which<br>
become an object of customs offence.<br>
The new edition does not make difference in citizens and officials as <br>
well. If formerly the article 92 defined the fine for citizens as equal to <br>
the minimum salary and for the officials as twice the minimum salary, <br>
according to the same article the fine is defined as 50 % worth of the <br>
cost of the good. <br>
Mr. Melkumian believes that these modifications will have positive <br>
and preventive effect  for reducing customs violations. At the same <br>
time it will be an income source for the budget.<br>
<p>
        NEW RATES OF FAMILY ALLOWANCE DEFINED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 09, ARMENPRESS.<br>
Starting January 1, 1997, the new rates of monthly family allowance<br>
for the children of the republic is defined. <br>
Monthly family allowance is given to all children under the age of 6,<br>
as well as to parentless children, to families having physically<br>
disabled children and 4 and more children, to single mothers. The<br>
allowance is given till the child is 17. The allowance is continued<br>
till 18 for the children studying at state registered institutes who<br>
do not receive grants. The children studying at the colleges with the<br>
period of study of 10 month are not considered in this category. The<br>
monthly allowance is 1380 Drams ($ 1= 420 Drams).  The mothers on<br>
partly paid work vacation will receive 1730 Drams till the child is 2.<br>
1730 Drams will also be given to single mothers who have children<br>
under 17 and children who study at state registered institutes do not<br>
receive grants till 18 (the children studying at the colleges with the<br>
period of study of 10 month are not considered in this category). The<br>
same will be applied to mothers who have unemployed status till the<br>
child is 2. The allowance for the birth of child is 4500 Drams.<br>
<p>
        BUDGET OF THIS YEAR TO TAKE RISK<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 09, ARMENPRESS.<br>
The state budget of this year is submitted to the co-session of the <br>
Committees of the National Assembly, on January 07. The Chairman of the<br>
Committee of Finance, Loan, Budgetary, and Economic Affairs Armen <br>
Eghiazarian thinks that it is early to make evaluations for the <br>
presented budget because the discussions have just started.<br>
The Head of the Central Bank Bagrat Asatrian stated that the Central <br>
Bank Council have highly evaluated the proposal. However, this<br>
budget has a risk of over-evaluating the amounts of some type of taxes<br>
and grants. Besides, Mr. Asatrian thinks that it is not necessary to<br>
define the maximum and minimum levels of inflation as 9.5 % and <br>
10.5 % in the Code on Budget. The maximum level defined as 10 %<br>
will be enough.<br>
<p>
        MEETING WITH ARF REPRESENTATIVES IN JUSTICE MINISTRY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 9, ARMENPRESS.<br>
On January 8, representatives of Armenian Justice Ministry met with<br>
the representatives of the supreme body of ARF (Armenian Revolutionary<br>
Federation). (On December 28, 1994 the operation of ARF was suspended<br>
by the Armenian President's order).<br>
During the meeting Mr. Alexanian, Armenian Minister of Justice, said<br>
that the Armenian Justice Ministry has no objections agains resuming<br>
the operation of ARF, provided Law of the Republic of Armenia is<br>
observed.<br>
According to the ARF representatives, the demand of the court verdict,<br>
is satisfied, they have made amendments in their By-Laws, but it is<br>
not acceptable for the Justice Ministry. The Justice Minister said,<br>
"The party may resume its activities only if it reconsiders the issue<br>
of foreign citizens' membership to their party as it is stated in the<br>
Armenian Law on "Non Governmental Political Organizations." The<br>
Minister also said that the Ministry cannot suggest any mechanisms for<br>
resuming the party's activities. According to the decision of the<br>
Supreme Court, Justice Ministry was to suggest mechanism for stopping<br>
the suspension, but after the 6 month period of suspension, the law<br>
is changed and making suggestion is forbidden by Article 5 of the<br>
Armenian Constitution. In conclusion, Mr. Alexanian said that the<br>
acting legislation makes it possible to eliminate the violations and<br>
now ARF may take that opportunity. In response, political<br>
representative of the supreme body of ARF Rouben Hakopian said that<br>
the reason for suspension are already eliminated by the convened<br>
meeting and by the amendments in the By-Laws.<br>
<p>
        NATIONAL ASSEMBLY DISCUSSES BUDGET OF 1997<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 9, ARMENPRESS.<br>
According to the established schedule of the National Assembly,<br>
discussions on budgetary issues started in the permanent committees of<br>
the National Assembly on January 8 and will last for a month, till the<br>
discussion of the law on "State Budget of the Republic of Armenia for<br>
1997" by the National Assembly.<br>
The document submitted by the Armenian Government, presents the<br>
economic policy of this year. The aim of the draft is to secure the<br>
stability of macroeconomics. Armenian Finance Minister Levon<br>
Barkhoudarian presented the state budget for 1997. The income is 113<br>
billion drams ($1=420), expenditure is 147 billion drams, and the<br>
deficite is 1.34 billion drams. The minimum and maximum annual<br>
inflation rates should be 9.5% and 10.5% correspondingly. The budget<br>
income was also presented. According to the Finance Minister, the<br>
increase in the income, as compared with the income of 1996, is<br>
expected to be 31.2%. In the submitted budget there is a considerable<br>
<p>
rise in tax incomes. Its specific gravity is 81 billion drams, which<br>
is by 32% more than it was in 1996.<br>
Such improvements are not due to the growth of taxes, but to improvements<br>
in taxation administration. 10 billion drams are planned to go to the<br>
state budget from the customs payments, which is 83% more than in<br>
1996. It is also planned to impose traffic tax.<br>
The total amount of non-tax income is expected to be 8.7 billion<br>
drams, 35.7% more than in 1996. The total amount of grants is expected<br>
to be 23 billion drams.<br>
Presenting the expenditure of the state budget, Mr. Barkhoudarian said<br>
that it will be 19% of Gross Interproduct. The calculation of the<br>
expenditure is based on the macroeconomic indeces predicted by<br>
socio-economic development program and predictions for the factors of<br>
increase in costs and rates.<br>
The deficite is planned to be covered by foreign and internal sources.<br>
The Central Bank of Armenia approved the bill of the law on "State<br>
Budget for 1997". Mr. Asatrian, the President of the Central Bank,<br>
also made some proposals which will be discussed by the Parliament.<br>
<p>
        IMPROVEMENTS IN SOCIAL CONDITION OF POPULATION AND ECONOMY TO<br>
        BE IN THE CENTER OF ARMENIAN PRESIDENT'S POLICY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN. JANUARY 9, ARMENPRESS.<br>
On January 8, press conference was held with Acting Press Secretary of<br>
the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon Zourabian. Mr.<br>
Zourabian spoke about the domestic problems of the Republic, foreign<br>
relations and the appointment of France as a Co-Chairman of OSCE<br>
(Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe) Minsk Group.<br>
According to the Acting Press Secretary, Armenia met the New Year in much<br>
better condition as compared with the last year. He said that the<br>
improvement of the social conditions of the population and of the<br>
economy will be in the center of the President's policy. The priority<br>
was given to the payment of salaries, pentions and subsidies to the<br>
employees of budgetary enterprises in time. According to him, the<br>
struggle against corruption could be effective only in case of<br>
substancial growth in the salaries of the officials. Mr. Zourabian<br>
said that the problems can be solved if order is established in tax<br>
collection. He reminded the meeting of the President with the<br>
directors of big enterprises, held on October 28, 1996, where relief<br>
was proposed as a way out for the enterprises. He also mentioned that<br>
as a result of undertaken measures, there have been substantial<br>
improvements in the budget. According to him, the taxation discipline<br>
will permanently be in the center of the President's attention and<br>
under his control.<br>
As for the appointment of France as a Co-Chairman of OSCE Minsk Group,<br>
Mr. Zourabian said that Armenia's position was positive for all three<br>
candidates: Germany, France and the United States.<br>
Later, Mr. Zourabian answered to the questions of the journalist. He<br>
introduced the President's schedule to those who were present.<br>
According to it, governmental session will be held on the coming<br>
Friday, on January 17, the President will head the Armenian<br>
delegation to the summit of CIS states, and in summer the President<br>
will have an official visit to Ukraine.<br>
The President's birthday is on January 9, and the journalists asked<br>
Mr. Zourabian to extend their congratulations to the President.<br>
