<p>
1. Rokhlin on Russian military (Interfax)<br>
2. US on Chechen elections (USIA)<br>
<p>
<p>
1. Defense Committee Head Pessimistic About Prospects for 1997  <br>
MOSCOW, Jan 2 (Interfax) --<br>
"Nothing good happened in 1996. Prospects for next year are<br>
no better," Chairman of the Russian Duma's Defense Committee<br>
Lev Rokhlin (the Our Home faction) told Interfax summing up<br>
the results of 1996. <br>
"The armed forces have broken up and the situation in<br>
the army is very serious," he said. <br>
The hopes for decent financing in 1997 have not been<br>
justified, he said. "The spending on defense envisaged in<br>
the state budget is even smaller than in 1996," he added. <br>
The 1997 budget, approved by the State Duma in a third<br>
reading on December 28, reserves 104.3 trillion rubles for<br>
defense which, to quote Rokhlin, is less than the actual<br>
defense-related spending in 1996. <br>
"Such a budget will cause the armed forces' further<br>
break-up," he said. <br>
"The armed forces poor performance in Chechnya attests<br>
to the ongoing disintegration of the army," Rokhlin said. <br>
He said prospects for next year were "very bad." <br>
<p>
<p>
2. From USIA<br>
January 6, 1997<br>
TEXT: STATE DEPT. ON UPCOMING CHECHNYA ELECTIONS<br>
(Election represents step toward democracy) <br>
<p>
Washington -- The scheduled January 27 Chechnya elections are an<br>
important part of the reconciliation process and "could constitute<br>
another step toward establishing democratic institutions and<br>
legitimate government in Chechnya," said U.S. State Department<br>
spokesman Nicholas Burns.<br>
<p>
Burns said the OSCE (Organization for Security and Cooperation in<br>
Europe) can play a "constructive role" in improving the quality of the<br>
elections. The United States has pledged $60,000 to the OSCE's Chechen<br>
election assistance fund.<br>
<p>
The following is the text of the January 6 Burns' statement.<br>
<p>
The United States welcomes continuing progress in preparing for<br>
elections in Chechnya, scheduled for January 27. These elections are<br>
an important part of the process of reconciliation and could<br>
constitute another step toward establishing democratic institutions<br>
and legitimate government in Chechnya. The United States welcomes<br>
recent statements of support for the electoral process by senior<br>
Chechen and Russian officials.<br>
<p>
We believe that the OSCE can play a constructive role in improving the<br>
quality of these elections and we have pledged sixty thousand dollars<br>
to the OSCE's Chechen election assistance fund.<br>
<p>
We have been encouraged by the generous support that other OSCE<br>
participating states have contributed to this purpose.<br>
<p>
We attach paramount importance to the safety of all foreign assistance<br>
workers in Chechnya and will continue to follow closely the security<br>
situation there. We note that Chechnya remains an area of instability.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
