<!-- body="start" -->
        NEZAVISIMAIA GAZETA: No.02 01/10/97<br>
<p>
TURKEY IS BUYING MISSILES<br>
<p>
By Alexander Reutov<br>
<p>
Confrontation<br>
<p>
Defense News, an American magazine, has reported recently that Turkey<br>
intends to purchase 18 Hawk missile systems of the ground-to-air class in<br>
Belgium and the Netherlands. France is said to be a go-between in this deal.<br>
This information was confirmed by an official spokesman of the Ministry of<br>
National Defense of Belgium who stated that such negotiations were indeed<br>
under way. Moreover, he opined that negotiations would be completed in the<br>
next couple of weeks.<br>
<p>
American Hawk class missiles were delivered to some NATO countries until<br>
recently. Now these countries need to get rid of them as they no longer meet<br>
modern standards. Turkey's intentions to purchase anti-aircraft systems was<br>
rather timely. The cost of the deal is estimated at $150 million. The cost<br>
includes expenses on modernization of the systems by a French company<br>
Thomson. The obsolete systems will require modernization of means of<br>
electronic security and targeting. It is planned that 10 systems each with 3<br>
missile launching capacity equipped with radars will be sold Belgium, and<br>
the remaining eight by the Netherlands. Turkey will be paying through a<br>
credit provided by France.<br>
<p>
It is noteworthy that this information is disclosed now that Ankara is<br>
making decisive protests against Russian-Cypriot deal on AA S-300 PMU-1<br>
systems. The Turkish leadership thinks that it is an offensive weapon and<br>
presents threat to the security of Turkey. According to Minister of Defense<br>
of Turkey Turhan Tayan (AM:transliterated from Russian) S-300 will enable<br>
armed forces of Cyprus to destroy targets on the southern shore of Turkey.<br>
He also stated that Ankara may be forced to repeat the scenario of 1974 when<br>
the Turkish army occupied the northern part of Cyprus. Now he is speaking<br>
about the southern part of the island populated by Greeks.             <br>
<p>
Situation in that part of the world is rather heated. Russia played a role<br>
in that by providing Cyprus with several dozens of modern tanks T-80U and<br>
armored personnel carriers BMP-3 which, according to the Cypriot leadership,<br>
are deployed to deter the 30 thousand strong Turkish expeditionary corps in<br>
the northern part of the island. Nonetheless it is difficult to imagine that<br>
the sides will end up in another military clash. Senior NATO brothers will<br>
do everything in their power to prevent the confrontation of Turkey and<br>
Greece, two NATO member countries. Last year Athens and Ankara were on the<br>
verge of a head on clash for a small uninhabited island which both countries<br>
claim to be theirs.  Then too passions were running high in both capitals,<br>
but the clash was prevented due to the pressure on them by NATO partners. (end) <br>
(Translated by AM)   <br>
<p>
<p>
"The most common form of human stupidity is <br>
forgetting what one is trying to do." <br>
<p>
Friedrich Nietzsche<br>
