<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE<br>
<p>
1/10/97<br>
<p>
<p>
1. FOREIGN MINISTER MEETS WITH ARF LEADERSHIP<br>
2. AZERI PARTIES OPPOSE HIGH AUTONOMY OFFER<br>
3. PRIME MINISTER MEETS WITH LEGISLATORS ON CAPITOL HILL<br>
4. ALL-ARMENIAN GAMES PLANNED FOR FALL<br>
5. US WARNS TURKEY AGAINST ATTACKING CYPRUS<br>
6. LETTER TO THE EDITOR<br>
7. KEY TO HIEROGLYPHICS DISCOVERED<br>
8. HYDROELECTRIC PLANT PRIVATIZATION POSTPONED<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
1. FOREIGN MINISTER MEETS WITH ARF LEADERSHIP<br>
ATHENS-The Armenian Revolutionary Federation leadership of <br>
Greece met with Armenias Foreign Minister, Alexander <br>
Arzoumanian, who was in Athens on an official visit this <br>
week.<br>
	Thursdays meeting, at the request of Arzoumanian, <br>
discussed the current political situation in Armenia, as <br>
well as issues concerning the Armenian community of Greece.<br>
	Armenias Ambassador to Greece, Armand Kirakossian, also <br>
attended the meeting.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. AZERI PARTIES OPPOSE HIGH AUTONOMY OFFER<br>
BAKU (Lragir, Armenpress)-Most of the political parties <br>
acting in Azerbaijan complained against the proposal of the <br>
Azeri government to provide a status of "high autonomy" to <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
	Representatives of the parties said that the provision of <br>
a "high autonomy" status is contradictory to the <br>
Constitution of Azerbaijan and to international law.<br>
	According to Article 7 of the Azeri Constitution, <br>
Azerbaijan is a unified country, they said, adding that <br>
providing "high autonomy" would mean switching from a <br>
unified to a federative state.<br>
	No other territory, apart from Nakhichevan, could have <br>
autonomy in Azerbaijan, they said, citing their <br>
constitution.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. PRIME MINISTER MEETS WITH LEGISLATORS ON CAPITOL HILL<br>
WASHINGTON-Armenias Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian had a <br>
series of meeting on Capitol Hill on Wednesday, the second <br>
day of his working visit to the United States.<br>
	He met with Senators Mitch McConnell and John Kerry, <br>
Congressmen Joseph Kennedy, Jim McGovern, George <br>
Radanovich, Co-Chairman of the Congressional Caucus on <br>
Armenian Issues Frank Pallone and Congresswoman Nancy <br>
Pelosi.<br>
	Prime Minister Sarkissian introduced the Armenian <br>
governments platform to the representatives of the US <br>
legislature, outlining a number of priority areas in full <br>
democracy building, economic development, privatization and <br>
investment processes, national stability and regional <br>
cooperation.<br>
	Speaking about the necessity of strengthening <br>
democracy and market economy, Sarkissian gave a brief <br>
account on what steps the government has taken during the <br>
first two months of his tenure as prime minister.<br>
	Sarkissian also emphasized the importance of fair <br>
resolution of the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict for the future <br>
development of the entire region.<br>
	Earlier that morning, Sarkissian met with ExIm Bank <br>
chairman Martin Kamark and director, Dr. Rita Rodriguez. <br>
The ExIm Bank promotes American business both domestically <br>
and internationally.<br>
	Sarkissian presented his governments priorities for <br>
this year, stressing the importance of conducting a policy <br>
of facilitating domestic investments, as well as creating a <br>
favorable infrastructure for large-scale investment.<br>
	Expressing their readiness to assist in accelerating <br>
private investments in Armenia, the ExIm Bank <br>
representatives underlined the importance of establishing <br>
legal framework and favorable conditions for the <br>
realization of financial programs in Armenia. An agreement <br>
with the bank is expected to be signed in the near future.<br>
	Accompanying the Prime Minister were Armenian Trade <br>
Minister Garnik Nanagulian, Armenias Ambassador to the US <br>
Rouben Shugarian and members of the Armenian embassies in <br>
Washington and London.<br>
	In addition to his meetings with the World Bank and <br>
the IMF, Sarkissian was scheduled to meet with members of <br>
the US business community to discuss avenues of closer <br>
cooperation. He was also expected to have meetings with <br>
White House and State Department officials.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. ALL-ARMENIAN GAMES PLANNED FOR FALL<br>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The All-Armenian Games, which will <br>
last from 7 to 10 days, are expected to be held in Yerevan <br>
in the fall, said Ashot Melik-Shakhnazarian, head of the <br>
International Organizations Department of the Armenian <br>
Foreign Ministry Thursday.<br>
	According to Melik-Shakhnazarian, Armenian athletes from <br>
forty-five countries will take part in the first <br>
competitions.<br>
	Arthur Gevorkian, head of the Sports Department of the <br>
Armenian Ministry of Culture, Youth and Sports Affairs, <br>
said the athletic facilities where the competitions are <br>
supposed to be held have already been selected.<br>
	He also noted that these facilities needed repairs. <br>
Chairman of Armenias Olympic Committee, Alexan Avetissian, <br>
said that the committee does not have sufficient funds to <br>
carry out the needed repairs, and therefore must rely on <br>
the government.<br>
	The games will included competitions in basketball, <br>
volleyball, tennis, table tennis and soccer. Women are <br>
expected to take part in only four of the five events.<br>
	Cultural events are also planned simulataneously with the <br>
games, to held once in four years.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. US WARNS TURKEY AGAINST ATTACKING CYPRUS<br>
WASHINGTON (Reuter)-The United States warned Turkey on <br>
Thursday against attacking Cyprus after reports that Ankara <br>
was seriously considering a military strike.<br>
	"This is no time for the Turkish government to be <br>
making wild and dramatic statements which will not be <br>
supported by any sensible member of the international <br>
community, State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told <br>
reporters.<br>
	"It would be completely out of bounds for Turkey to <br>
take this action, he added.<br>
	Turkish Defense Minister Turhan Tayan was reported to <br>
have warned on Wednesday that Turkey would attack Cyprus if <br>
it needed to protect the Turkish Cypriot community in the <br>
north of the Mediterranean island.<br>
	"What was needed in 1974 and what did we do? We will <br>
do the same again. If needed, we will strike, Tayan told <br>
the state-run TRT television channel in an interview.<br>
	Turkey has accused the Cypriot government of trying to <br>
change the balance of forces on the island by a deal <br>
announced over the weekend to buy Russian anti-aircraft <br>
missiles that could neutralize Turkish air superiority.<br>
	Burns, noting Tayans remarks, said: "We hope very <br>
much that this report...is incorrect. We hope it does not <br>
reflect in any way shape or form the views of the Turkish <br>
government.<br>
	"There can be no question that Turkey must respect the <br>
rules of the road here, which are no country, and <br>
specifically in this case Turkey, should threaten the use <br>
of military force against Cyprus; no country, specifically <br>
here Turkey, should undertake military force against <br>
Cyprus, he said.<br>
		In an unusually strong statement, Washington on <br>
Monday deplored Cyprus contract to buy the S-300 anti-<br>
aircraft missile system from Russia, saying it would <br>
introduce a destabilizing new military element and <br>
complicate peace moves.<br>
	But Burns stressed on Thursday that at this point only <br>
a contract has been signed and the system will not be <br>
deployed for at least 16 months. "Theres no reason for the <br>
Turkish government to run off and threaten anybody, he <br>
said.<br>
	He emphasized: "We need peace and stability in the <br>
eastern Mediterranean ... We need to try to convince the <br>
parties that we should re-energize the political talks on <br>
Cyprus.<br>
	Secretary of State-designate Madeleine Albright, in <br>
testimony presented to her Senate confirmation hearing <br>
Wednesday, said tensions and disputes between Turkey and <br>
Greece, two NATO allies, "affect European stability and our <br>
vital interests.<br>
	"Accordingly, we are prepared in this new year to play <br>
a heightened role in promoting a resolution in Cyprus but <br>
for any initiative to bear fruit, the parties must agree to <br>
steps that will reduce tensions and make direct <br>
negotiations possible, she said.<br>
The United States, gravely concerned about Cyprus plans to<br>
buy Russian anti-aircraft missiles, will renew this weekend <br>
efforts to reduce tensions between Greeks and Turks on the <br>
divided island.<br>
	Officials have said Carey Cavanaugh, a mid-level <br>
diplomat who heads the office of southern European Affairs, <br>
would visit Cyprus on Sunday and Monday, seeking to advance <br>
a political settlement there. He will also visit Greece and <br>
Turkey. <br>
	President Bill Clinton some time ago appointed a <br>
special envoy on Cyprus, Richard Beattie, and Burns was <br>
asked why Cavanaugh was going to the region, not Beattie. <br>
Burns said Cavanaugh had day-to-day responsibility for the <br>
region. Also, "you dont always need to have your special <br>
negotiators from Washington run out every time there is a <br>
problem. We do have very well-qualified American <br>
ambassadors in these three countries ... and we have great <br>
confidence in them, he said.<br>
	The Cypriot government said the missiles are <br>
defensive. The S-300 air defense system has a range of 150 <br>
km (90 miles) and can knock out aircraft and missiles in <br>
flight.<br>
	They dismissed the threats of a military strike by <br>
Turkey as nothing new. "For us the matter is over, <br>
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides told Reuters.<br>
	"We will not follow Turkey with polemic statements. <br>
We are focusing our attention to the political solution of <br>
the problem,  he said.<br>
	Earlier on Thursday the Greek government shrugged off <br>
similar but less explicit threats by Turkey.<br>
	Prime Minister Costas Simitis said Cypriot President <br>
Glafcos Clerides would be invited to Athens for talks on <br>
the issue this month but added there was no cause for <br>
concern that a new crisis would erupt between Greece and <br>
Turkey.<br>
	"There is nothing new in our region. Turkish <br>
aggression has been expressed for some time, he told <br>
reporters. "We would be playing Turkeys game if we showed <br>
particular worry over this and were swept into an <br>
atmosphere of crisis.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. LETTER TO THE EDITOR<br>
Dear Sirs:<br>
On January 3, 1997 the Armenian Assembly of American, <br>
through their staff member Arpi Vartanian, released an <br>
action alert regarding an article which appeared on the <br>
same day in The New York Times. That article, written by <br>
Michael Specter, was entitled "Drift to Dictatorship Clouds <br>
Armenias Happiness." Ostensibly, Ms. Vartanians action <br>
alert was a call to arms for Armenian-Americans to <br>
protest the papers revelation that democracy is faltering <br>
badly in the Republic of Armenia.<br>
	I find the Assemblys adoption of "Anti-Defamation <br>
Alert" in their release to be particularly offensive. It <br>
plays on the fears of well-intentioned Armenians, cloaking <br>
what is nothing but a poorly-reasoned political position <br>
paper under the language of anti-racism. If the Assembly is <br>
going to stick to their position as the de facto lobbying <br>
arm of the Ter-Petrosyan government, they can at least do <br>
the Diaspora in the US and their own credibility a favor <br>
and save the use of "anti-defamation" for slander that is <br>
worthy of community response. A balanced New York Times <br>
article that levels criticism at the side they support is <br>
not worth crying persecution over and only cheapens <br>
legitimate concerns about how Armenia and Armenians are <br>
portrayed in the US media.<br>
	However, I really hope that the Assembly wrote this <br>
out of naivete. I hope it was just sub-par work, a Friday <br>
afternoon rush job that got hastily approved for release. <br>
Because if this level of deception now represents what the <br>
Assembly plans to foist on the community as an "authority" <br>
and as "leaders," this is a cause for real concern. I dont <br>
think we deserve this.<br>
	But I do close with a caveat. I dont appreciate The <br>
New York Times coverage of Armenian issues over the past <br>
15 years, which is as long as I have read the paper. I have <br>
found them biased. With this in mind, I sincerely regret <br>
that the current government in Armenia has strayed so far <br>
that the Times is able to criticize Armenias leadership <br>
through balanced coverage rather than by careful editorial <br>
policy. While I think the Times article was very good, and <br>
some of the best recent writing in the American press on <br>
affairs in Armenia, I hope that we continue to watch their <br>
reporting carefully so that we dont get a false sense of <br>
security from its current honesty.<br>
	Sincerely,<br>
	Aram Adishian<br>
	New York, NY<br>
<p>
<p>
7. KEY TO HIEROGLYPHICS DISCOVERED<br>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenian scientists have discovered <br>
the key to decipher the hieroglyphics of the Urartu Kingdom <br>
in Van, the National Academy of Sciences of Armenia <br>
announced Friday.<br>
	Under the supervision of the academys vice-chairman <br>
Gagik Sargsian, a post-graduate student of the Armenian <br>
Oriental Studies Institute Artak Movsessian surveyed a <br>
writing system, which included 200 signs. The signs were <br>
written from right to left and up and down. The system also <br>
included auxillary signs and figures.<br>
	The key was said to have been discovered after thorough <br>
scrutiny of the Urartu hieroglyphics and cuneiform. <br>
Armenian scientists have managed to decode 33 signs, <br>
including three names-Ishpani, Menua and Inouan.<br>
	According to the scientists, there are grounds to <br>
make a presumption that inhabitants of the area of <br>
Biayna-Urartu-were writing in classical Armenian.<br>
<p>
<p>
8.HYDROELECTRIC PLANT PRIVATIZATION POSTPONED<br>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The privatization of eight small <br>
hydroelectric plants in Areni, Yeghegnadzor, Azatek, <br>
Ijevan, Arium, Meghri, Martuni, Giumri, which was planned <br>
to be carried out this month has been postponed until <br>
March, sources close to the Energy Ministry reported.<br>
	Seven other stations, including Voghji-2, Voghji-3, <br>
are also slated for privatization.<br>
	The 15 plants together are said to produce only 30 <br>
megaWatts of energy.<br>
<p>
