<title>Groong Network: Albright on Section 907</title>
<h1>Albright on Section 907</h1>
<i>elaine@aaainc.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 10 Jan 97 15:43:04 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#315">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#315">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#315">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#315">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0316.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Cyprus"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0314.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (January 10)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Armenian Assembly of America<br>
122 C Street, NW  Suite 350<br>
Washington, DC  20001<br>
tel. (202) 393-3434<br>
<p>
<p>
PRESS RELEASE<br>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE      <br>
     January 10, 1997   <br>
     <br>
     CONTACT:  Elaine Merguerian<br>
     <br>
                <br>
     ALBRIGHT CALLS FOR LIFTING OF SECTION 907<br>
     <br>
     WASHINGTON, D.C. _ In her testimony before the Senate Foreign <br>
     Relations Committee, January 8, Secretary of State-designate Madeleine <br>
     Albright called for the lifting of the prohibition on <br>
     government-to-government aid to Azerbaijan, known as Section 907 of <br>
     the Freedom Support Act.  Below are her comments on this subject made <br>
     at her confirmation hearing:<br>
     "Another dispute tangled by history and geography concerns Armenia, <br>
     Azerbaijan and the status of Nagorno Karabagh.  The good news here is <br>
     that the cease-fire has now held for more than two years.  The bad <br>
     news is that progress under the O.S.C.E.'s Minsk process has been <br>
     agonizingly slow.  We have very substantial economic, political and <br>
     humanitarian interests in this region, and are prepared to play a more <br>
     visible role in helping to arrange a settlement.  One step that <br>
     Congress could take to increase our influence would be to lift <br>
     restrictions on nonmilitary assistance to Azerbaijan, while <br>
     maintaining support for our generous aid program in Armenia."<br>
     <br>
        Armenian Assembly of America Executive Director Ross Vartian <br>
     reacted to the statement:  "The prohibition on non-military <br>
     government-to-government aid to Azerbaijan is a principled response to <br>
     that country's illegal, six-year blockade of Armenia and Nagorno <br>
     Karabagh.  We are deeply distressed that the Clinton administration <br>
     has once again called for the lifting of Section 907, while failing to <br>
     address the serious humanitarian needs of Armenians in Nagorno <br>
     Karabagh.  We hope the administration responds to a January 7 <br>
     community-wide request to meet with the president, to discuss how U.S. <br>
     impartiality can be restored in negotiations to peacefully resolve the <br>
     Karabagh conflict."                The Armenian Assembly is a <br>
     nationwide nonprofit organization which promotes public understanding <br>
     and awareness of Armenian issues.<br>
     X   X   X <br>
     NR#97-001<br>
     <br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
