----------------  J U D I C I A L   N E W S ---------------------<br>
<p>
ARMENIA TO TAKE MEASURES TO <br>
CANCEL DEATH PUNISHMENT<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 8 (Noyan Tapan). At a recent meeting in<br>
Yerevan between Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrossian and<br>
deputy of Swiss parliament, head of Swiss delegation to the<br>
Council of Europe Ernst Muleman the two mainly discussed the<br>
problem of Armenia's affiliation to the Council of Europe.<br>
Mr.Muleman said that in the near future two delegations will<br>
visit Armenia to find out whether Armenia's legislation meets<br>
Council of Europe's requirements, presidential spokesman Levon<br>
Zourabian said at a Wednesday briefing. Armenian President<br>
voiced willingness to reconsider all those normative acts that<br>
does not meet the requirements of the Council of Europe.<br>
     According to Levon Zourabian, as for the death punishment<br>
Levon Ter-Petrossian informed the guest that "since the time<br>
when democratic forces came to power no capital punishment has<br>
been executed". It was noted that the Armenian Constitution<br>
envisages cancellation of the death punishment and "in the near<br>
future the process of adoption of a relevant decision will be<br>
initiated".<br>
     Presidential spokesman noted that Armenia attaches much<br>
importance to the integration to the european structures, as<br>
well as involvement of the neighboring newly-born states into<br>
these structures. According to him, that will create new<br>
responsibilities and mutual obligations to promote the<br>
development of cooperation and democracy in the Caucasus and<br>
strengthen the stability.<br>
     "We are confident that affiliation to the Council of Europe<br>
will become an additional stimulus for Armenia to develop into a<br>
democratic and lawful state, and will help to raise the level of<br>
human rights protection and development of democratic<br>
establishments", Levon Zourabian said.<br>
<p>
<p>
------------- P O L I T I C A L   N E W S -----------------<br>
     <br>
ARMENIA WAS POSITIVE TOWARD EVERY <br>
CANDIDATE RUNNING FOR THE POST <br>
OF OSCE MINSK GROUP CO-CHAIRMAN<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 8 (Noyan Tapan). Armenia had a positive<br>
stance toward candidacies of Germany, France and USA running for<br>
the post of OSCE Minsk Group co-Chairman, Presidential Spokesman<br>
Levon Zourabian said at a briefing on Wednesday.<br>
     As was reported, OSCE managing Chairman, Swiss Foreign<br>
Minister Flavio Conti took a decision to appoint France<br>
co-Chairman of the OSCE Minsk Group.<br>
     "Generally, Armenia would agree to any state, except Turkey<br>
which cannot be impartial", Levon Zourabian said.<br>
<p>
ARA SAHAKIAN SAYS THAT ARMENIAN <br>
ALL NATIONAL MOVEMENT SHOULD GO <br>
ON PLAYING THE BALANCING ROLE<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 8 (Noyan Tapan). "From the political point<br>
of view the past year was remarkable by three events:<br>
presidential election, formation of the new government and local<br>
self-government election. And Armenian All National Movement<br>
(AANM) was in the center of these three events, as well as in<br>
the course of the past several years", Deputy Parliament Speaker<br>
Ara Sahakian said at an extended session of the state council.<br>
According to him, "the past year was also marked by dramatic<br>
events that found their climax in a violent act against National<br>
Assembly on September 25".<br>
     Ara Sahakian says that opposition does not want to obey the<br>
laws. "What is the difference between us and them. The basic<br>
difference is that we, having discussions, taking decisions<br>
assume the responsibility for our people and republic. And they<br>
again choose the streets to calm their political ambitions and<br>
drive our political struggle to the streets. It is natural that<br>
the streets dictate street methods of struggle, hence, a<br>
relevant counteraction", Ara Sahakian said.<br>
     "Those destructive steps that are taken by the opposition<br>
(or a part of it), as well as unlawful steps and their<br>
consequences make us to go on playing the balancing role", he<br>
said.<br>
<p>
LACK OF LEGAL MECHANISM IMPEDES <br>
REOPENING OF DASHNAK PARTY<br>
IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 8 (Noyan Tapan). Armenia's Justice<br>
Minister Marat Alexanian said that documents which had been<br>
submitted to the Ministry by the Dashnak Party's Supreme<br>
Authority are not sufficient to lift the ban on activities of<br>
the Party in Armenia. "We do not oppose the reopening of the<br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation -- Dashnaktsutiun in Armenia,<br>
if this is done within the law in effect," Alexanian said<br>
Tuesday after a meeting with representatives of the Dashnak<br>
Party's Supreme Authority. <br>
     Supreme Authority's political representative Rouben<br>
Hakobian said that Party's representatives had repeatedly<br>
applied to the Ministry of Justice in hopes of receiving<br>
explanations of how to lift the ban on Party's activities in<br>
Armenia. "However, we were only told what should not be done,<br>
and nobody explained us what we should do," he stressed. Up to<br>
present the Ministry of Justice has not officially responded to<br>
Supreme Authority's August 11 1996 letter related to resumption<br>
of Party's activities in Armenia.<br>
     The major opposition party, ARF-Dashnaktsutiun, was banned<br>
in Armenia for six months on orders of the Supreme Court of<br>
Armenia. The main reason of outlawing the Party was that the<br>
Party's Ruling Authority included foreign citizens.  In six<br>
months the Ministry of Justice again appealed to the Supreme<br>
Court, requesting to extend the ban for next six months.<br>
However, the Court rejected the suit.<br>
     The meeting of the Armenian Justice Minister with<br>
representatives of Dashnak Party's Supreme Authority was held in<br>
camera. Minister told journalists that "the agreement has been<br>
broken" and a half-and-hour-long meeting was held without<br>
participation of mass media representatives.<br>
<p>
<p>
--------------- E C O N O M I C  N E W S -------------------<br>
<p>
BUDGET REVENUES TO INCREASE BY <br>
31% UNDER REVISED DRAFT <br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 8 (Noyan Tapan). Under the amended draft<br>
budget for 1997 budget revenues should increase by 31% as<br>
compared with last year, while expenditures are supposed to<br>
increase by 22%, Armenia's Finance Minister Levon Barkhudarian<br>
announced.<br>
     Presenting the draft budget at a joint session of National<br>
Assembly's committees, Mr Barkhudarian reported that the budget<br>
deficit would not change, thus totaling 34 billion drams<br>
(approx. $75,500,000). Taking into consideration the expected 6%<br>
growth of GDP, the budget deficit will make up 4.4% of the GDP. <br>
     The first draft budget submitted in November to the<br>
National Assembly envisaged the growth of revenues by 40%, which<br>
then was described by the Central Bank as unrealistic. <br>
     Mr Barkhudarian said that according to preliminary<br>
assessments the revenue collection was completed at 96%-97% in<br>
1996. Inflation rate totalled 8.7% instead of projected 14%. The<br>
inflation rate projected for 1997 will be within 9.5%-10.5%.<br>
     The priority of budget financing will be given to the<br>
social sector (28% growth). Average salary is planned to be<br>
raised by 30%. <br>
     According to the Minister, the growth of budget revenues<br>
will be mainly ensured thanks to increase in tax assignments.<br>
For this purpose it is planned to move a number of amendments<br>
into Armenia's tax legislation. <br>
     The discussion of the draft budget in National Assembly's<br>
committees will be continued until late January. It is planned<br>
to present the draft budget at the plenary session of the<br>
Parliament on 3 February.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
