<title>Groong Network: NeGa: Primakov's diplomacy reviewed</title>
<h1>NeGa: Primakov's diplomacy reviewed</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 9 Jan 1997 10:17:28 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#307">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#307">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#307">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#307">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0308.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (January 9)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0306.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "MK: We shall always find a Cyprus to put against their NATO"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nezavisimaya Gazeta 9 January 1997 page 1<br>
<p>
   Report by Dmitriy Gornostayev:  "The First Year of Primakov's<br>
   Diplomacy Has Passed Without Breakdowns or Breakthroughs.  Has a<br>
   New Foreign Policy Evolved in Russia?"<br>
<p>
  A year ago, when the first foreign minister of the Russian<br>
  Federation was finally kicked out of Smolenskaya Square, [ministry<br>
  headquarters] many posed this question:  Will the parting with the<br>
  Kozyrev course in foreign policy be just as long as the eviction of<br>
  Andrey Kozyrev himself from the Foreign Ministry?<br>
 Practically nobody disagreed with that the course had to be changed: <br>
 Its pro-western, especially pro-U.S. orientation, which brought<br>
 certain dividends in the first years of the new Russian statehood,<br>
 eventually resulted in a series of debacles by Moscow diplomacy in<br>
 many parts of the world and many spheres of international activity.<br>
 The president's choice fell on Yevgeniy Primakov, who was head of the<br>
 Foreign Intelligence Service [SVR] at the time.  First commentaries<br>
 after the appointment predicted a speedy U-turn in Russia's foreign<br>
 policy, "a strengthening of imperial ambitions," and a deterioration<br>
 of relations between Moscow and the West. A year later it can be said<br>
 that these forecasts have been fulfilled, but not entirely.  There<br>
 has certainly been no 180 degree turn -- maybe a 90 degree one at<br>
 best, and Primakov did it quietly, without giving western politicians<br>
 cause to accuse him of a confrontational mood.  Moreover, during this<br>
 year he has clearly shown that he will not -- at least that he does<br>
 not intend -- to go beyond these 90 degrees. The refusal of<br>
 passionate love with the West manifested itself immediately at the<br>
 protocol level:  The new minister made his first foreign trips to CIS<br>
 republics, and it was not until February that he held negotiations<br>
 with U.S. State Secretary Warren Christopher.  Generally speaking,<br>
 the relations between the heads of the two countries' diplomatic<br>
 departments are fairly indicative, largely reflecting the state of<br>
 things in the Russian-U.S. dialogue. Instead of the old "friend<br>
 Andrey" and "friend Warren" they use only "Mr." and address each<br>
 other by family name.  According to U.S. diplomats it has become far<br>
 more difficult to conduct negotiations:  The Russians have toughened<br>
 their positions, and on some issues they can even be described as<br>
 intransigent.  At the same time Primakov continuously stresses that<br>
 Russia does not wish to relapse into the confrontation of the Cold<br>
 War era.  Naturally, these words are pure rhetoric, but even so, they<br>
 need to be pronounced, and quite often too.  Such tactics gradually<br>
 -- very, very gradually -- began to produce results.  True,<br>
 oftentimes belated results.  A good case in point is the dialogue on<br>
 the issue of NATO expansion.  The tough and sharply negative position<br>
 on the expansion of the North Atlantic alliance has after all played<br>
 its role, and the final document of the recent OSCE summit did not<br>
 include a U.S. proposed passage on the role of NATO as the crux of<br>
 European security.  It is also noteworthy that after numerous<br>
 negotiations the bloc -- thus far in word only -- is talking about<br>
 the possibility of giving Russia guarantees of the nondeployment of<br>
 nuclear weapons on the territory of newly admitted member states. <br>
 True, these guarantees are not worth a cent today, and after the<br>
 admission of the Czech Republic, Poland, and Hungary to the alliance<br>
 they can turn into pure  fiction.  The most terrible thing, however,<br>
 is that we talk about all these achievements by Russian diplomats<br>
 knowing that in half a year, in Madrid, three or maybe four East<br>
 European countries will receive official invitations to join NATO. So<br>
 the joy over the shifts in the relations with the North Atlantic<br>
 alliance can be compared only to the joy of a team hopelessly losing<br>
 a match and repulsing a series of attacks at its gate minutes before<br>
 the end of the match. On the other hand, there is an opinion abroad<br>
 that the game will end not in July at the Madrid NATO summit, but<br>
 only in 1999, when the expansion actually goes ahead.  Until then,<br>
 Foreign Ministry  leaders assure, there is still time to find a<br>
 solution to the problem of alliance enlargement.  Possibly Yevgeniy<br>
 Primakov has a couple of unexpected options up his sleeve.  But even<br>
 if he uses the most crafty one, he will find it extremely difficult<br>
 to conduct the dialogue with NATO.  What matters here is not at all<br>
 Primakov, but the legacy that he inherited from his predecessor. This<br>
 legacy is unenviable.  Weak positions not only in relations with the<br>
 West, but also in the Balkans, the Middle East, and the Asian Pacific<br>
 region.  Serbs, Muslims, and Croats are reconciled by a U.S.<br>
 diplomat; peace agreements on Bosnia are signed in Dayton and Paris;<br>
 a Palestinian-Israeli peace declaration is signed in Washington; and<br>
 a nuclear reactor for the North Koreans is built not by their former<br>
 allies, the Russians, but by their perennial enemies, the Americans.<br>
 Primakov assumed the post of foreign minister under extremely<br>
 difficult conditions.  Apart from the purely political difficulties<br>
 there were also huge personnel problems:  The central apparat of the<br>
 Foreign Ministry was not in a battle-ready condition, and was<br>
 inefficient in dealing with the task of foreign policy coordination. <br>
 Personnel turnover in the Foreign Ministry was very high while the<br>
 diplomats' salaries very low.  To sum up, diplomacy was degrading.<br>
 And this affected the new minister's performance. A year ago Primakov<br>
 began to lead foreign policy from the crisis.  What has he achieved?<br>
 Perhaps the main achievement of Yevgeniy Primakov is that during the<br>
 past year he has not made new mistakes and managed to retain the good<br>
 that remained before his advent.  To be sure, such an appraisal of<br>
 performance will not flatter not only a minister but any ordinary<br>
 person.  And still this is the first thing that jumps to the eye, if<br>
 we talk in general terms.  Yet if we go into details, Primakov's year<br>
 has left a mixed impression.<br>
   Liabilities [subhead]<br>
 1.  Inability to comprehensively resolve the problem of boosting<br>
 integration within the CIS.  Intensifying centrifugal trends within<br>
 the Commonwealth. 2.  An evident worsening of relations with Ukraine<br>
 -- the main target of Russian foreign policy in the post-Soviet<br>
 region.  It is drifting further away toward the West, and utterances<br>
 can already be heard about Ukraine's possible NATO membership,<br>
 something that no one could even think of a year ago. 3.  A weakening<br>
 of contacts and understanding with Georgia. 4.  Differences with<br>
 Kazakhstan and Azerbaijan on a number of economic matters, in<br>
 particular, over the problem of Caspian oil. 5.  The weakening of<br>
 [Russian] influence on Moldova and the withdrawal of troops from the<br>
 Dniester Region (the latter, of course, might be assessed in a<br>
 variety of ways, but it has negatively affected Russian positions in<br>
 South East Europe). 6.  The loss of former positions in Tajikistan<br>
 after the signing of inter-Tajik accords (see also assets). 7.  An<br>
 increase in Turkey's economic, ideological, and information expansion<br>
 to the regions of southern Russia and the Turkic republics of the<br>
 CIS. 8.  The impotence of Russian diplomacy in the question of<br>
 liberating Russian pilots from Afghan captivity (if the Foreign<br>
 Ministry was involved in their escape, it would be no sin to admit<br>
 that). 9.  The impossibility of stopping NATO expansion. 10. The<br>
 inadequate level of work in the parliament.  The treaties on START<br>
 II, chemical weapons, biological weapons, and a number of other<br>
 international documents have not been ratified up to this day.  The<br>
 Foreign Ministry is largely responsible for that. 11. Increasing<br>
 shrinkage in [Russian] influence on the Balkans and the Near East.<br>
 One can foresee objections:  Much of what is listed above can be<br>
 attributed to objective difficulties that do not depend on diplomats'<br>
 professional qualities.  Yes, that is true.  But the leadership of<br>
 the ministry is called upon precisely in order to overcome these same<br>
 difficulties.  By the way, it succeeded in so doing in a number of<br>
 areas. Assets [subhead] 1.  The level of foreign policy coordination<br>
 has increased substantially.  Primakov is one of the few cabinet<br>
 members who has direct access to President Yeltsin since his stint as<br>
 Foreign Intelligence Service [SVR] director.  For this reason he<br>
 carries greater clout with members of the Russian leadership who are<br>
 involved in foreign policy matters one way or another, including<br>
 secretaries of the Security Council and the Defense Council; the<br>
 ministers of defense and foreign economic relations; directors of the<br>
 SVR, Federal Security Service [FSB], and Federal Border Service<br>
 [FPS]; as well as parliamentarians.  It has all contributed to better<br>
 foreign policy collaboration between the branches of power and<br>
 various agencies. 2.  The personnel situation has improved.  The<br>
 ministry is no longer plagued by the hectic personnel turnover that<br>
 was characteristic of it under Kozyrev.  Perhaps, the Foreign<br>
 Ministry's only subdivision where this problem has not yet been<br>
 resolved is the disarmament department. The reason for numerous<br>
 staffers' reluctance to stay -- and graduates's unwillingness to<br>
 apply for jobs at the Russian Foreign Ministry -- has remained<br>
 unchanged; the problem is low pay. Among personnel policy<br>
 achievements one should point out the fact that Primakov has<br>
 effectively refrained from reshuffling the ministry's top echelon,<br>
 limiting himself to several changes, such as "deputy<br>
 minister-ambassador" or "department director-deputy minister," which<br>
 is commonplace in diplomatic practice.  This made it possible not to<br>
 break the former pattern of operation, but simply to adjust it. <br>
 Access-the-board personnel changes would have undoubtedly had a<br>
 negative impact on the operation of the foreign policy agency. 3. <br>
 The signing of a treaty with Belarus, which, even though Russia has<br>
 not yet got any specific benefits from it, has become the only<br>
 example of translating into life integrationist trends within the<br>
 CIS.  The Union of Four -- Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, and<br>
 Kyrgyzstan -- is an even more amorphous entity, which, perhaps, does<br>
 not deserve to be ranked among successes of Russian diplomacy in the<br>
 CIS. 4.  An improvement in relations with China.  This is a fairly<br>
 important achievement of both the Foreign Ministry and personally<br>
 Yevgeniy Primakov.  Boris Yeltsin's visit to the PRC in April of last<br>
 year, the arrival of State Council Premier Li Peng in Moscow, the<br>
 creation of a permanent commission at the level of chiefs of<br>
 government, increasingly vibrant military-technical cooperation,<br>
 preparations for a Russian-Chinese summit in Moscow, which is<br>
 expected to yield serious results in terms of bilateral and<br>
 international relations -- it can all fully justifiably be called an<br>
 accomplishment of Russian diplomacy. 5.  The signing of inter-Tajik<br>
 accords in Moscow.  The Russian foreign policy agency should<br>
 undoubtedly be given credit for that. 6.  Some successes, albeit<br>
 small, in the dialogue with NATO, which might in the future help<br>
 Russia obtain more advantageous terms in its relations with the<br>
 alliance, even in its new lineup.  Unfortunately, there have been<br>
 much more setbacks than achievements in this area, which has been<br>
 mentioned above.  Yet it is essential to follow up on the results<br>
 achieved, insisting on the signing of a full-scale and detailed<br>
 treaty between Russia and NATO, which would lay down the principles<br>
 of the two sides' special relationship, including legally binding<br>
 guarantees to each other.  To all appearances, the current leadership<br>
 of the Russian Foreign Ministry intends to proceed in approximately<br>
 the same vein.  Yet it is also possible that Primakov has more<br>
 far-reaching plans.  All the more so because the solution to the<br>
 problem of relations with the North Atlantic Alliance -- judging by<br>
 Yeltsin's recent talks with Kohl and also the Kremlin meeting on<br>
 NATO-related matters -- will become Russia's priority during this<br>
 year and, possibly, for the remainder of this century. 7.  Progress<br>
 in the settlement of border disputes with the Baltic states,<br>
 particularly, with Lithuania. 8.  Reaching agreement with the United<br>
 States on one of the ABM Treaty's components -- low-speed means. 9. <br>
 Active efforts to compel the UN Security Council to lift sanctions<br>
 from Yugoslavia and to partially lift the embargo on Iraq's oil<br>
 sales. 10. The dismantlement of ideological stereotypes in foreign<br>
 policy is one of Primakov's accomplishments.  Now, as it should be,<br>
 you can no longer hear from the foreign minister during his visits<br>
 abroad harsh critical words about both left-wing or right-wing<br>
 opposition.  Such words as "the reds and the browns" or<br>
 "fascism-mongering," which used to be hurled at deputies of the<br>
 parliament of one's own country, have disappeared from the vocabulary<br>
 of Russian diplomacy.  It will be recalled that Primakov said at his<br>
 first news conference as Russia's new foreign minister:  "I do not<br>
 want to be a weathercock."  Ideological winds might blow in various<br>
 directions, but national interests stand over and above any idea,<br>
 whether democratic, Communist, or matriarchal for that matter. * * *<br>
 At the moment Yevgeniy Primakov is probably the best possible,<br>
 although not the ideal figure at the post of foreign minister.  He<br>
 is, without doubt, an experienced man, who is well known and<br>
 respected on the international circuit.  He belongs to a group of<br>
 unsinkable ministers who have no fears lest they should be dismissed.<br>
  He has personal contact with the president.  It is considered bad<br>
 manners among members of the political elite to criticize him.  He<br>
 suits virtually everyone, but... It is just this absence of criticism<br>
 and control -- within reasonable limits, of course -- that could play<br>
 a nasty trick on him.  Minor mistakes that go unnoticed at the<br>
 beginning tend to end up as blunders.  Thank God, last year was not<br>
 marked by failures of Russian diplomacy or its chief.  But,<br>
 unfortunately, no serious breakthroughs were achieved either. <br>
 Weighing setbacks against successes, the latter turn out to be less<br>
 numerous. This year will be very difficult for Russian diplomacy. <br>
 Primakov has so far only managed to hold up the slide of Russia's<br>
 foreign policy indicators.  Now his objective is to ensure their<br>
 growth.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
