<title>Groong Network: MK: We shall always find a Cyprus to put against their NATO</title>
<h1>MK: We shall always find a Cyprus to put against their NATO</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 9 Jan 1997 09:47:24 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#306">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#306">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#306">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#306">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0307.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "NeGa: Primakov's diplomacy reviewed"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0305.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "NeGa: It will be safer on Cyprus"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Moskovskiy Komsomolets 9 January 1997 page 1<br>
<p>
   Report by Yulia Kalinina:  "We Shall Always Find a Cyprus To Put<br>
   Against Their NATO"<br>
<p>
  The scandal that has developed around the decision of "Greek" Cyprus<br>
  to buy Russian S-300 surface to air missiles can be regarded as<br>
  nothing short of a "worldwide" recognition.  The West thus sings<br>
  praise to Russian arms traders.<br>
 The righteous wrath over the prospect that the SAM complexes will<br>
 necessarily disturb the balance of forces in Cyprus means that our<br>
 weapons have not only gained a good and firm foothold on the world<br>
 arms market, but have also gradually turned into a real threat for<br>
 the western arms market, including the U.S. market. The fact is that<br>
 the current contract with Cyprus is not the first in the history of<br>
 Russian-Cypriot trade relations.  Approximately a year ago<br>
 Rosvooruzheniye [state company for the export and import of arms and<br>
 military equipment] sold to the island a substantial amount of armor,<br>
 including BMP-3 armored vehicles and T-80U tanks.  The Americans<br>
 missed the contract, but when they woke up, it was too late:  They<br>
 failed to prevent the appearance of Russian armor on Cyprus.  As a<br>
 result the military attache of the U.S. Embassy had to leave Cyprus: <br>
 The appropriate services apparently deemed his slip unpardonable. As<br>
 concerns the latest "SAM" contract, our western competitors learned<br>
 about it in good time and immediately tried to scuttle it.  In<br>
 mid-December Cyprus was visited by British Foreign Secretary Rifkind,<br>
 who thoroughly tried to persuade the government to give up the deal. <br>
 In late December Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Chiller came to<br>
 Moscow.  She tried to work on the Russian side but to no avail<br>
 either.  All the efforts proved futile, and on 4 January the<br>
 multi-million contract for the delivery of S-300's was signed. True,<br>
 not everything has yet been lost for the Americans because before the<br>
 contract takes effect it is to be confirmed by a session of the<br>
 Cypriot parliament.  It is quite possible that such a strong pressure<br>
 will be exerted on the lawmakers that they will give in, respond to<br>
 the appeals "not to disturb the balance of forces," and the contract<br>
 will not be ratified. Rosvooruzheniye, whose hyperactivity brought<br>
 about the entire scandal, refuses to comment on it because "the whole<br>
 story from a purely commercial turned into a purely political one." <br>
 The only thing that we managed to learn from company experts is that<br>
 U.S. Patriot complexes (analogues of our S-300's) are obviously<br>
 inferior to the Russian systems on many characteristics, and if the<br>
 Americans do not stop the realization of the contract now, soon our<br>
 SAM complexes will naturally begin to squeeze U.S. products from the<br>
 "Mediterranean" market.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
