<title>Groong Network: NeGa: It will be safer on Cyprus</title>
<h1>NeGa: It will be safer on Cyprus</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 9 Jan 1997 09:44:52 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#305">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#305">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#305">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#305">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0306.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "MK: We shall always find a Cyprus to put against their NATO"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0304.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 01/09/97"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nezavisimaya Gazeta 9 January 1997 page 1<br>
<p>
   Report by Igor Korotchenko:  "It Will Be Safer on Cyprus"<br>
<p>
  Turkey's demarche is not going to change Moscow's principled<br>
  approach to expanding military-technical cooperation between Russia<br>
  and Cyprus, NG was advised at the Rosvooruzheniye state company.  As<br>
  we know, a contract signed in Nicosia 4 January 1997 calls for the<br>
  delivery to Cyprus a batch of mobile S-300 PMU-1 antiaircraft<br>
  missile systems which has sparked Ankara's extremely negative<br>
  reaction.  The S-300 PMU-1 is capable of effectively engaging<br>
  high-speed aerodynamic and ballistic targets up to 100 and 40<br>
  kilometers away and at corresponding altitudes of between 50 meters<br>
  to 25 kilometers.  It takes not more than five minutes to deploy the<br>
  antiaircraft missile system.<br>
 The Rosvooruzheniye state company delivered to Cyprus earlier T-80U<br>
 tanks and BMP-3 infantry fighting vehicles.  Nicosia has signed the<br>
 C-300 PMU-1 contract despite unprecedented pressure from major<br>
 Western countries.  For example, the island was visited for this<br>
 purpose by a British government delegation led by Secretary of State<br>
 for Foreign Affairs Malcolm Rifkind in December 1996.  The United<br>
 States military attache accredited in Cyprus was relieved of his<br>
 position by the Pentagon for ineffective work to prevent the signing<br>
 of this contract.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
