<title>Groong Network: Fast Growing Tree Project in Armenia</title>
<h1>Fast Growing Tree Project in Armenia</h1>
Areg Gharabegian (<i>Areg_Gharabegian@parsons.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 8 Jan 97 13:07:50 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#298">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#298">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#298">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#298">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0299.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 1/8/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0297.html">Richard Giragosian: "TransCaucasus: A Chronology, January 1997 (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     PLANTING  FAST  GROWING  TREES  IN  ARMENIA<br>
     By Areg Gharabegian<br>
     <br>
     The purpose of this project is to grow US developed hybrid fast <br>
     growing trees in Armenia and bring tree genetics improvement expertise <br>
     to the Armenian Academy of Science, Institute of Botany's plantation <br>
     forestry program.  In addition, to develop a source for biomass to <br>
     energy in Armenia and use fast growing hybrid trees for reforestation.<br>
     <br>
     About 10,000 hybrid US and Canadian trees have been already planted in <br>
     Armenia during last three years.  This project is financed by the <br>
     Armenian Engineers and Scientists of America (AESA) and managed by the <br>
     Institute of Botany of the Armenian Academy of Science.  These <br>
     plantations were established to evaluate the best species for <br>
     different locations in Armenia.  Some of the species have shown very <br>
     promising growth.  As of September 1995, which was the end of the 1995 <br>
     growing season, some of the species that were planted in April of 1994 <br>
     had grown by as much as 3 meters 10 centimeters.  As of September 1996 <br>
     these trees where as high as 6 meters.  AESA arranged for the visits <br>
     of three US specialists to Armenia in October 1994 and June 1995 to <br>
     evaluate the potential of the fast growing trees for biomass to <br>
     energy, reforestation, and erosion control purpose.<br>
     <br>
     Government of Armenia has allocated 200 hectares in Ararat Valley for <br>
     planting fast growing hybrid trees.  Planting at this site will start <br>
     spring of 1997.  The purpose of this plantation is to create a <br>
     foundation for developing the tools needed to accomplish necessary <br>
     basic research in developing new fast-growing trees using US hybrids <br>
     which are suitable for Armenia.  During the first two years of this <br>
     project approximately 40,000 trees will be planted on 30 hectares of <br>
     land each year.<br>
     <br>
     The eventual goal is to develop a profitable tree production system <br>
     which can be deployed in the saline and alkaline degraded soils of the <br>
     Ararat Valley in Armenia which are not suitable for agricultural use.  <br>
     As part of this project advanced US forest tree genetics technology <br>
     will be utilized to accelerate tree production systems in some of the <br>
     saline parts of Ararat Valley.  Several tree types have shown very <br>
     encouraging growth rates in alkaline soil which presently is not used <br>
     for agricultural purposes.  If large scale short rotation plantations <br>
     were started in parts of Ararat Valley which has saline soil using the <br>
     selected hybrid trees, it is anticipated that after four or five <br>
     rotation periods (approximately 35 years), some of the alkaline areas <br>
     could be used for selected agricultural purposes.  As a result of this <br>
     project, portions of the Ararat Valley will be covered by trees which <br>
     will have positive environmental impacts.  In addition, these <br>
     plantations could be used in the future as a source for biomass to <br>
     energy production.<br>
     <br>
     Fast growing hybrid trees could also be ideal choice for reforestation <br>
     of the destroyed forest areas.  Reforestation is an urgent issue in <br>
     Armenia.  The near total loss of imported fossil fuel has resulted in <br>
     wide-spread deforestation from 1991 to 1995.  Results of tests <br>
     conducted during last years have reviled that the hybrid poplars will <br>
     grow at least three to four time faster than the native poplars.  <br>
     These hybrid trees can become large mature trees in no more than ten <br>
     years.  Figure 3 shows growth of these hybrid trees in one year.<br>
     The Armenian National Academy of Science headed by Mr. Fadey <br>
     Sarkissian, former Prime Minister has personally agreed to make this <br>
     project work.  As the former Prime Minister of Armenia, his contacts <br>
     and influence will go far in making the project happen.  The Armenian <br>
     principle investigator is Dr. Ashot Charchouglian, director of the <br>
     Institute of Botany of the Academy of Science, which is the Armenian <br>
     center for biological research.  A key participant of this project is <br>
     Dr. Baikar Khourshoudian, the father of Armenian forestry, who has <br>
     exceptional knowledge of tree plantation.<br>
     <br>
     AESA presently is conducting a fund raising to purchase and ship <br>
     40,000 hybrid poplar tree cuttings to Armenia.  Interested parties can <br>
     contact AESA at 818/547-3372, 111 N. Jackson Street, Suite 103, <br>
     Glendale, California  91206 or Areg Gharabegian at 818/440-6047, <br>
     e-mail:AREG_GHARABEGIAN@PARSONS.COM.<br>
     <br>
     Note - The Armenian Engineers and Scientists of America (AESA) is a <br>
     non profit 501(c)(3) US organization dedicated to bring cooperation <br>
     and to share professional knowledge among engineers and scientists in <br>
     the US and Armenia.<br>
