Subject: TransCaucasus: A Chronology, January 1997 (fwd)<br>
<p>
The following is the latest version of the monthly publication,<br>
"TransCaucasus: A Chronology."  This issue covers events in the region for<br>
the month of December, 1996.<br>
  For more information or to be added to the email distribution list,<br>
please contact the author, Richard Giragosian. The "TransCaucasus: A<br>
Chronology" is now entering its sixth year of monthly publication.<br>
<p>
Richard Giragosian<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
email: giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
                        TransCaucasus<br>
                        A Chronology<br>
                       (E-Mail Version)*<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
Vol. VI                  January, 1997                         No.1<br>
<p>
<p>
The TransCaucasus: A Chronology is a chronological summary of the<br>
significant social, economic, and political events in the lower<br>
Caucasus, as reported by local and international media and selected<br>
sources in the region.  Full acknowledgement should be given to all<br>
material quoted from or based on this publication.<br>
<p>
Compiled and written by Richard Giragosian (giragosi@essential.org)<br>
Edited and designed by Christopher Hekimian<br>
<p>
ISSN 1078-3113<br>
<p>
A Publication Of The Armenian National Committee of America<br>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
Republic of<br>
Armenia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
29,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than Maryland<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan (east) 566 km<br>
Nakhichevan (south) 221 km<br>
Georgia 164 km<br>
Iran 35 km<br>
Turkey 268 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
3.6 million<br>
68% urban<br>
110.5 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
93.3% Armenian<br>
1.5% Russian<br>
1.7% Kurdish<br>
3.5% Assyrian, Greek, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Levon Ter Petrosian, President; Hrant Bagratian, Prime<br>
Minister; Vahan Papazian, Foreign Minister.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Armenia re-established its independence on September<br>
23, 1991, after more than 70 years of Soviet rule.  The first<br>
Armenian Republic was established on May 28, 1918.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Armenia joined the CIS in March 1992 and<br>
CIS Defense Treaty in May 1992.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A constitution was adopted by national referendum on<br>
July 5, 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Elections were held for Parliament July 5, 1995 and for<br>
President September 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to<br>
Armenia is Ambassador Peter Tomsen. The Armenian representative to<br>
the United States is Ambassador Rouben Shugarian.  The Armenian<br>
representative to the United Nations is Ambassador Alexander<br>
Arzoumanian.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
ARMENIA - Human Rights Watch World Report 1997<br>
<p>
The government's crackdown on the political opposition in September<br>
1996 cast a pall on human rights.  Given the 1995 ban on the<br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF), Armenia's largest<br>
opposition party, and fraudulent 1995 parliamentary elections, the<br>
1996 crackdown accentuated the government's intolerance of any real<br>
political opposition.  This crushing of opposition forces bore out<br>
Defense Minister Vazgen Sarkissian's September 25 warning that<br>
"After [the September 25] events, even if they win 100 percent of<br>
the votes, neither the Army nor the National Security and Interior<br>
Ministry would recognize such political leaders."<br>
<p>
In April, the Ministry of Justice attempted to close Azg, the<br>
Ramkavar party daily, claiming that it needed to re-register under<br>
the auspices of the diaspora Ramkavar party, which is pro-Ter-<br>
Petrosian.<br>
<p>
The Ministry of Justice refused to register the Committee for the<br>
Defense of Political Prisoners, basing its decision on its view<br>
that since there were no political prisoners in Armenia, such an<br>
organization was unnecessary.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 December: A delegation of Armenian government officials led by<br>
parliamentary chairman Babken Ararktsian meet with Chinese<br>
parliamentary chairman Qiao Shi and other officials in Beijing. <br>
The meetings review bilateral relations and discuss the expansion<br>
of governmental cooperation in science, education and commerce. <br>
The relations between the two countries have steadily grown since<br>
China first extended diplomatic recognition in 1991.<br>
<p>
4 December: The Armenian government reveals plans to import 1.1<br>
billion cubic meters of natural gas in 1997 under the terms of the<br>
state social and economic developmental program recently ratified<br>
by the parliament.  The state plan also envisions utilizing foreign<br>
expertise to modernize the country's natural gas transport system. <br>
Armenian natural gas transport and supply facilities have remained<br>
idled since their closure in 1992 as a result of the full economic<br>
and transport blockade by Azerbaijan.  The Armenian government is<br>
also planning to privatize its state gas concern, Armgazprom, with<br>
assistance from the European Union.<br>
<p>
5 December: Armenian interior ministry police detain several<br>
leading members of the opposition National Progress party for<br>
questioning.  Although the incident remains unexplained, the<br>
detention is apparently the latest example of the government's<br>
campaign to intimidate and impede the country's political<br>
opposition parties.<br>
<p>
8 December: President Levon Ter Petrosian and National Security<br>
Minister Serge Sarkisian meet in Yerevan with Russian Border Troops<br>
Commander, General Andrei Nikolayev, to discuss the status of<br>
Russian military personnel in Armenia.  The border troops,<br>
stationed along the Armenian-Turkish border, are chronically short<br>
of adequate food supplies, as well as fuel and spare parts for<br>
their equipment.  The Russian troop presence is based on the terms<br>
of a 1992 renewable bilateral accord whereby both countries finance<br>
the troops' deployment and operational needs.<br>
<p>
9-10 December: Newly appointed Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian,<br>
during a visit to the United Kingdom, meets with several leading<br>
European companies to promote greater foreign investment in<br>
Armenia.  The prime minister also meets with several British<br>
government officials and parliamentarians.<br>
<p>
10 December: The Armenian Supreme Court issues sentences in the<br>
"Dro" trial, condemning three defendants to death on charges of<br>
terrorism, drug trafficking and crimes against the state.  The<br>
three defendants are Armen Munjoyan, Arsen Artsrouni and Armen<br>
Grigorian.  The Court also sentences the remaining eight defendants<br>
to terms ranging from three to fifteen years imprisonment and<br>
orders the state confiscation of all the defendants' property.  The<br>
defendants included Artavazd Manoukian who died while in custody<br>
<i>&gt;from internal hemorrhaging and lack of medical attention.  ARF</i><br>
leader and defendant, Hrant Markarian, was found guilty of<br>
possessing multiple passports and an unregistered firearm, but was<br>
not found to have any connection to the "Dro" group, thus<br>
exonerating the ARF.  The prosecution had claimed that Markarian's<br>
participation with "Dro" proved the ARF's involvement as well.<br>
<p>
10 December: On his first formal visit to Moscow, newly appointed<br>
Armenian Foreign Minister Alexander Arzoumanian meets with Russian<br>
Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov.  The meeting reviews the<br>
conflicting positions regarding Nagorno Karabagh during the recent<br>
summit of the organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe<br>
(OSCE).  Although Moscow remains committed to guaranteeing the<br>
territorial integrity of Azerbaijan and providing a limited<br>
concession of autonomy for Nagorno Karabagh within Azerbaijan<br>
proper, the foreign minister promised to continue the constructive<br>
dialogue with all sides in their mediation attempt.<br>
<p>
10 December: The representative of the World Bank to Armenia,<br>
Vahram Nersissiants, announces that the multilateral lending<br>
organization is preparing to extend a new loans to the country. <br>
The World Bank assistance, providing credits for the development of<br>
Armenia's legislative and educational sectors, would bring the<br>
total level of World Bank aid to approximately $500 million.<br>
<p>
11 December: In response to the death sentences imposed the day<br>
before on three defendants in the "Dro" trial, the human rights<br>
organization Amnesty International issues a statement demanding<br>
that Armenian President Levon Ter Petrosian immediately commute the<br>
sentences.  The year long trial has been the centerpiece of the<br>
government's campaign against the country's largest opposition<br>
party, the Armenian revolutionary Federation (ARF), and the course<br>
of the trial has been marked by several legal irregularities and<br>
the sporadic violation of the civil liberties of the defendants.<br>
<p>
11 December: In a reflection of the growing level of corruption in<br>
the reforming economies of the former Soviet Union, Armenian<br>
officials announce that some 200 state tax inspectors have been<br>
dismissed amid charges of abuse of power and bribery.  There have<br>
been serious incidents of state corruption, including within the<br>
ranks of the police and law enforcement structures and among<br>
customs and tax inspectors in Armenia.<br>
<p>
11 December: The Turkish foreign ministry announces that Turkey<br>
will no longer open its border with Armenia as earlier promised by<br>
Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller.  The statement adds that the<br>
border will remain closed until Armenia "respects Azerbaijan's<br>
territorial integrity" and until the withdrawal of Nagorno Karabagh<br>
forces from the occupied areas of Azerbaijan proper.  The Armenian-<br>
Turkish border has been closed since 1992 in an effort to exert<br>
strategic economic pressure over the fragile Armenian economy.<br>
<p>
11 December: The head of the Armenian Church, Supreme Patriarch and<br>
Catholicos of All Armenians Garegin I, meets with Pope John Paul II<br>
at the Vatican.  The Pope states that he hopes the Armenian<br>
Apostolic Church will eventually reunite with the Roman Catholic<br>
Church.  The Armenian church split from Rome during the 5th<br>
century.<br>
<p>
13 December: Armenia's new Prime Minister Armen Sarkisian holds a<br>
meeting with representatives of the banned opposition Armenian<br>
Revolutionary Federation (ARF).  The meeting reviews the prime<br>
minister's plan for the coming year and discusses the importance of<br>
involving all political parties and groups in a constructive<br>
attempt to resolve the country's tense internal political crisis. <br>
<p>
13 December: The Korean electronics company Samsung opens its first<br>
store in Armenia, adding to its presence in the former Soviet<br>
Union.  Samsung maintains distribution outlets and stores in<br>
Russia, Ukraine and Kazakhstan. The company is also reportedly<br>
considering opening three other stores in Armenia.<br>
<p>
16 December: An official of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)<br>
announces that the Armenian government must make corrections to its<br>
economic program.  Specifically, the IMF criticizes the Ter<br>
Petrosian government's plan to allow a rise in inflation from this<br>
year's level of 10 percent to an annual rate of 14 percent for<br>
1997.  The country's fragile commercial banking sector is also<br>
cited as a systemic flaw, calling for immediate attention and for<br>
mergers and closures of some banking institutions.  The IMF also<br>
expresses concern over the government's failure to meet spending<br>
reduction targets set this year and its continued granting of state<br>
credit to the central bank beyond previously agreed upon limits.<br>
<p>
18 December: According to a new report issued by the U.S.<br>
organization Freedom House, Armenia is categorized as being only<br>
"partly free" by virtue of repression of the country's opposition<br>
political parties and their press and the less than democratic<br>
nature of the country's recent parliamentary and presidential<br>
elections.  The report, issued annually, is a world survey of<br>
governments and their patterns of democracy and governance as well<br>
as a review of each country's state of civil and political<br>
liberties.<br>
<p>
20 December: A recently formed U.S.-Armenian joint geological and<br>
prospecting company announces plans to drill three wells outside of<br>
Yerevan and conduct a seismic study of the region over the next<br>
five years.  The U.S. partner in the venture plans to invest some<br>
$10 million for the exploration and will launch oil production if<br>
any significant reserves are discovered.  Based on earlier surveys<br>
done by the Portuguese Parteko company and the British firm SPT,<br>
Armenia is expected to hold reserves of nearly 35 million tons of<br>
crude oil and 80 billion cubic meters of natural gas.  Any energy<br>
reserves found would be beneficial to the Armenian economy which is<br>
stalled by the paralyzing effects of the blockade of the country<br>
imposed five years ago by neighboring Turkey and Azerbaijan and due<br>
to the country's over 90 percent dependence on imports for its<br>
energy needs.<br>
<p>
