<p>
Republic of Georgia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
69,700 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than S. Carolina<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia 164 km<br>
Azerbaijan 322 km<br>
Russia 723 km<br>
Turkey 252 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
<p>
5.57 million<br>
56% urban<br>
78 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
69% Georgian<br>
9% Armenian<br>
6% Russian<br>
6% Ajarian<br>
5% Azerbaijani<br>
3% Ossetian<br>
2% Abkhazian<br>
<p>
Georgia includes the autonomous republics of Abkhazia and Ajaria<br>
and the South Ossetian Autonomous Region.<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Eduard Shevardnadze, President; Irakli Menagrashvili,<br>
Foreign Minister, Nickol Lekishvili, Secretary of State, Zurab<br>
Zhvania, Parliamentary Chairman.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Georgia established its independence on April 9,<br>
1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  The Georgian government joined the CIS on<br>
October 23, 1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was adopted in August, 1995,<br>
which reinstates a presidential form of government and provides for<br>
a strong executive branch and a unicameral 235-seat parliament.  A<br>
constitutional court was also created.  The constitution, however,<br>
does not address the status of Abkhazia, Ossetia or Ajaria.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Presidential and parliamentary elections were last held<br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to<br>
Georgia is Ambassador Kent Brown. The Georgian representative to<br>
the United States, as well as Canada and Mexico, is Ambassador Tedo<br>
Japaridze.  The Georgian representative to the United Nations is<br>
Ambassador Peter Chkiedze.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
GEORGIA - Human Rights Watch World Report 1997<br>
<p>
Human rights progress in Georgia stagnated in 1996.  Abuses<br>
persisted, especially torture and other forms of mistreatment in<br>
detention, arbitrary detention, appalling prison conditions, use of<br>
the death sentence, corruption of law enforcement officials and the<br>
judiciary, and harassment of some political dissidents. <br>
The year got off to a mixed start.  Monitors from the Organization<br>
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) termed the November<br>
5, 1995, parliamentary and presidential elections and the November<br>
19, 1995 , parliamentary run-offs "relatively open;" the<br>
assessments of the British Helsinki Group and others were generally<br>
less positive.<br>
Press freedom was widely enjoyed, although self-censorship remained<br>
a problem, particularly in the government media.  The September<br>
adoption of a law on state secrets that restricts some freedom of<br>
the media, and the de facto closure of independent TV channel<br>
Rustavi-2 on July 17, apparently for political reasons, raised some<br>
concern over the state of the independent media.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
8 December: The Georgian defense ministry announces the dismissal<br>
of the commander of the Georgian Navy, Rear Admiral Aleksandr<br>
Javakhishvili.  The Georgian naval forces have been undergoing<br>
recent modernization efforts and have moved swiftly in the last two<br>
months to exert a more assertive role in patrolling the waters off<br>
the strategic Georgian port facilities along the Black Sea coast.<br>
<p>
8 December: In a clash with Georgian forces, three Abkhazian<br>
officers are killed and two others are wounded in the Gali border<br>
district.  The Abkhazian government reacts by criticizing the<br>
Russian military peacekeepers stationed in the border region for<br>
their inability to prevent the attack.  The clash is reportedly the<br>
latest in a series of attacks seen as a new military offensive by<br>
the newly formed units of ethnic Georgian within Abkhazia.  The<br>
Abkhazian leadership has accused the Georgian security forces of<br>
having trained and armed theses units.<br>
<p>
9 December: The Ajarian parliament issues a statement protesting<br>
the Georgian refusal to authorize the creation of a free economic<br>
zone for the port city of Batumi.  The Georgian government has been<br>
reluctant to allow such a move, fearing that the economic zone<br>
would "encourage separatism" within the Ajarian Autonomous<br>
Republic.<br>
<p>
10 December: President Eduard Shevardnadze announces a formal<br>
moratorium on capital punishment.  Coinciding with International<br>
Human Rights Day, the announcement further states that the<br>
government will propose amendments to the penal code prohibiting<br>
the death sentence for high treason and other crimes, with the sole<br>
exception of premeditated murder with aggravating circumstances.<br>
<p>
10 December: During the course of a meeting with visiting Russian<br>
Duma chairman Gennady Seleznev, Shevardnadze and State Minister<br>
Niko Lekishvili protest the Russian government's trade restrictions<br>
on Georgian fruit and vegetables, wine and tea products.  The<br>
Georgian government has recently complained of the serious lack of<br>
market access for Georgian exports, citing the decline in bilateral<br>
trade.  Georgia is currently only the seventh leading trading<br>
partner with the Russian Federation.<br>
<p>
11 December: Chairman Seleznev, meets with Georgian officials<br>
during his participation in the summit of the Parliamentary<br>
Assembly of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation in Tbilisi.  The<br>
Russian official, in an address to the Georgian parliament, states<br>
that the Russian ratification of the pending bilateral accord on<br>
cooperation and political relations depends on the Georgian<br>
ratification of an agreement on the stationing of Russian troops in<br>
the country and other concessions by Tbilisi.  In protest to the<br>
statements, the Georgian opposition National Democratic<br>
parliamentary bloc walks out on the session.  The Russian official<br>
also states that Moscow would like to open a consulate in Batumi<br>
"to safeguard the interests of the 30,000 ethnic Russian community<br>
in Ajaria."<br>
<p>
14 December: Opposition National Democrats parliamentary bloc<br>
leader, Beso Djugeli, calls for the impeachment of Georgian Defense<br>
Minister Vardiko Nadibaidze for his "destruction of the country's<br>
military-industrial complex."  The defense minister has come under<br>
fire lately in the wake of his dismissal of Georgia's Navy<br>
commander.<br>
<p>
15-16 December: Tensions between Georgia and Russia escalate<br>
following the seizure of a Ukrainian ship by Russian naval forces<br>
near the Georgian Black Sea port of Batumi.  Georgia's<br>
parliamentary defense and security commission chairman Revaz Adamia<br>
and border troops commander, Major General Valeri Chkeidze, condemn<br>
the action by the Russian military as a threat to Georgian<br>
sovereignty and warn that it undermines prospects for the<br>
ratification of the 1994 bilateral Russian-Georgian border treaty. <br>
Further complicating the situation, Russian border troops have also<br>
sealed the Russian border with South Ossetia seriously disrupting<br>
commerce and trade.<br>
<p>
17 December: Ajarian parliamentary chairman Aslan Abashidze issues<br>
a communique announcing that Ajarian security forces have secured<br>
the administrative border with Georgia.  The statement explains the<br>
move as an attempt to control the transit of armed groups through<br>
Ajaria into Abkhazia.  The border area has been used by several<br>
armed Georgian groups to enter Abkhazia and despite numerous<br>
complaints to Tbilisi by the Ajarian leadership, these groups have<br>
also targeted Ajarian civilians in the area.<br>
<p>
___________________________________________________________________<br>
