Republic of Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
81,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Maine<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia (West) 566 km<br>
Armenia (southwest) 221 km<br>
Georgia 332 km<br>
Iran (south) 432 km<br>
Iran (southwest) 179 km<br>
Russia 284 km<br>
Turkey 9 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
7.3 million<br>
54% urban<br>
89 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
71% Azerbaijani<br>
11% Talish<br>
6% Russian<br>
4% Lezgi<br>
3% Daghestani<br>
3% Kurdish<br>
2% Avar<br>
<p>
The autonomous republic of Nakhichevan (pop. 350,000; 5,500 sq. km)<br>
as placed under Azerbaijani administration in 1921.<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Geidar Aliyev, President; Artur Rasizade, Prime<br>
Minister; Hasan Hasanov, Foreign Minister; Shamshaddin Khanbabayev,<br>
Premier of Nakhichevan.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Azerbaijan established its independence on August<br>
30, 1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Azerbaijan joined the CIS on September 24,<br>
1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was passed by referendum in<br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections: Parliamentary elections for a new 125-seat legislature<br>
were held November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to<br>
Azerbaijan is Ambassador Richard Kauzlarich.  The Azerbaijani<br>
representative to the United States is Ambassador Hafiz Pashayev. <br>
The Azerbaijani representative to the United Nations is Eldar<br>
Guliyev.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
AZERBAIJAN - Human Rights Watch World Report 1997<br>
<p>
The treason trials of President Heydar Aliyev's personal enemies,<br>
brutal treatment in detention, and continued repression of free<br>
speech stood in grim contrast to the Azerbaijan government's<br>
efforts to join international human rights institutions in 1996. <br>
Continued ill treatment in detention demonstrated how far<br>
Azerbaijan has to go in order to conform with Council of Europe<br>
standards and with the Convention Against Torture and Other Cruel<br>
Inhuman and Degrading Treatment or Punishment, which was ratified<br>
by the Azerbaijani parliament on May 31, 1996.<br>
The government continued to stifle political speech.  Government<br>
censors routinely refused to allow publication of issues of<br>
opposition newspapers that contained articles criticizing Aliyev. <br>
The Ministry of Justice repeatedly refused to register the<br>
Committee for Human Rights and Democracy, citing, among other<br>
things , the organization's failure to provide copies of the<br>
founder's passports, which is not among registration rules.  The<br>
government continued to deny the ICRC access to pre-trial<br>
detainees, but granted unhindered access to prisoners of war.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 December: An official of the Organization for Security and<br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Tibor Lakatti, is attacked during a<br>
tour of the militarized zone separating Azerbaijani and Nagorno<br>
Karabagh forces near Agdam. Azerbaijani security officials blame<br>
Nagorno Karabagh units for provoking the incident due to the<br>
"difficulty in distinguishing peacekeepers from Nagorno Karabagh<br>
forces."  Such attacks have occurred in the past, for example, when<br>
Azerbaijani forces fired upon a OSCE delegation touring the zone<br>
last April.<br>
<p>
3 December: The international human rights organization Helsinki<br>
Watch sends a letter to Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliyev<br>
protesting the Azerbaijani government's handling of the criminal<br>
case against former Defense Minister Rakhim Gaziyev.  The former<br>
defense minister, charged with crimes against the state in the<br>
military losses to Nagorno Karabagh forces during the May 1992<br>
defeats in Shushi and Lachin, has been denied visits by relatives<br>
and has been held in isolation without access to his lawyer beyond<br>
an initial meeting.  Gaziyev served as the defense minister under<br>
the government of Azerbaijani Popular Front leader Abulfez<br>
Elchibey, ousted from power in a coup d'etat.  Following the coming<br>
to power by Aliyev in June 1993, Gaziyev fled to Russia but was<br>
extradited to Baku in April 1996 after repeated Azerbaijani<br>
demands.  <br>
<p>
4 December: Speaking at a Baku press conference, Azerbaijani<br>
economic policy advisor Vakhid Akhundov announces that Azerbaijan<br>
plans on shipping 800,000 tons of crude oil through the Baku-<br>
Grozny-Novorossiisk pipeline.  The Azerbaijani official states that<br>
the state oil company SOCAR expects profits of $100 million from<br>
these early exports, estimated to be ready for shipment sometime<br>
next summer.  Azerbaijani officials also reveal that the country<br>
currently produces nine million tons of oil annually and is<br>
planning on annual exports of 1.5-2 million tons.<br>
<p>
5 December: The Azerbaijani ministry of communications announces a<br>
new $43 million project to upgrade the country's aging<br>
telecommunications sector.  The project involves the Azerbaijani<br>
state telecommunications firm with investment by Swedish and<br>
Turkish companies.  To date, the country's telecommunications<br>
sector enjoys significant Israeli and Turkish investment as well as<br>
assistance in its modernization from the European Union's TACIS aid<br>
program.<br>
<p>
5 December: Representatives of the country's main independent media<br>
issue a statement protesting the Azerbaijani government's decision<br>
to revoke the press credentials of the parliamentary correspondent<br>
for the opposition Azeri Popular Front's newspaper "Azadlyg."  The<br>
Aliyev government has a record of continued repression and<br>
censorship of the country's media.<br>
<p>
7 December: Azerbaijani foreign ministry officials announce that<br>
they have requested that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization<br>
(NATO) stage a seminar in Baku to examine issues related to<br>
pipeline security and environmental protection.  Azerbaijani state<br>
oil company SOCAR officials have added that the country's<br>
ministries of defense, interior and national security are seeking<br>
European Union assistance in the formulation of a security policy<br>
to effectively guarantee the safety of the pipelines planned to<br>
export Azerbaijan's significant energy reserves from the Caspian<br>
Sea.<br>
<p>
10 December: Azerbaijani security forces arrest a former special<br>
interior ministry forces (OPON) commander, Yelcin Amiraslanov, on<br>
charges of complicity in the March 1995 armed uprising seeking the<br>
overthrow of the Aliyev government.  To date, some nineteen coup<br>
participants have been arrested.  The March 1995 uprising consisted<br>
of members of the elite OMON branch of the interior ministry and<br>
was brutally defeated by regular army troops.  The elite units were<br>
then dissolved by President Aliyev and replaced by a restructured<br>
division, now known as OPON, and returned to direct control by the<br>
interior ministry.  This latest arrest follows a recent arrest of<br>
the leaders of another coup attempt directed against the Aliyev<br>
regime.  The so-called "Generals' coup," was led by three high<br>
ranking Azerbaijani military generals and involved the former aides<br>
to ousted Prime Minister Surat Guseynov and former Azerbaijani<br>
Communist Party boss and president Ayaz Mutalibov.<br>
<p>
12 December: The Azerbaijani parliament formally approves the<br>
country's 1997 budget.  The $758 million budget includes a $163<br>
million deficit, an increase from last year's budget deficit of<br>
$117 million.  The Azeri economic and finance ministries announce<br>
that the deficit will be financed from the signing bonuses paid to<br>
Azerbaijan by Western oil companies involved in energy deals in the<br>
country.  The government also forecasts a two percent rise in the<br>
Azerbaijani Gross Domestic Product (GDP).  In terms of state<br>
spending, education accounts for the largest amount, followed by<br>
military expenditures and social security and health care.<br>
<p>
14 December: In the fourth international contract between<br>
Azerbaijan and a consortium of Western oil companies anxious to<br>
develop the energy fields of the Caspian Sea, representatives sign<br>
a new deal to explore and develop the offshore Ashrafi and Dan<br>
Uluzu oil fields.  This new contract consists of a consortium of<br>
Western companies including the U.S. firm Amoco with a thirty<br>
percent share, an alliance of California-based UNOCAL with 25.5<br>
percent and the Saudi Arabian firm Delta with 4.5 percent, the<br>
Japanese oil company Itochu with twenty percent, and the<br>
Azerbaijani state oil concern SOCAR with the remaining twenty<br>
percent.  This $2 billion deal focuses on the exploitation of the<br>
two fields which hold an estimated 150 million tons of oil and 50<br>
billion cubic meters of natural gas reserves.  The project plans on<br>
yielding its first commercial exports by the year 2003 and a peak<br>
of seven million tons of crude oil annually by 2007.  This fourth<br>
international contract is the first one to exclude Russian<br>
participation and brings the total amount of foreign investment in<br>
the Azerbaijani energy sector to $13 billion.  This project also<br>
stipulates a bonus payment of $75 million from each of the<br>
consortium members to the Azerbaijani government.  The deal must be<br>
subject to parliamentary approval, however. <br>
<p>
16 December: Ukraine, Georgia and Azerbaijan formally mark the<br>
opening of a new Black Sea ferry link between Odessa and Poti.. <br>
The new transport link is an element of a "Euro-Asian Transport<br>
Corridor" plan calling for the formation of a new regional<br>
infrastructure and transport network connecting all countries in<br>
the region.  The ferry link is vital to Ukraine due to its large<br>
dependence on energy imports from Russia.  Georgia and Azerbaijan<br>
hope to utilize the transit link in the export of oil from offshore<br>
Azerbaijani reserves in the Caspian Sea.  Additional elements of<br>
the regional plan include the construction a new railway line from<br>
Azerbaijan through Georgia, a new $300 million project to construct<br>
a 40 million ton-capacity oil terminal facility at the Ukrainian<br>
port of Pivdenny near Odessa, and the completion of the<br>
modernization of the oil terminal at Batumi on the Georgian Black<br>
Sea coast.<br>
<p>
17 December: Meeting in Moscow with Chechen government official<br>
Eduard Khachukaev, Terry Adams, the chairman of the Azerbaijan<br>
International Oil Company (AIOC), the operational arm of the<br>
consortium of Azerbaijani and Western oil companies involved in the<br>
multi-billion dollar project to develop the offshore energy<br>
reserves of the Caspian Sea, discusses the issue of transporting<br>
oil from Azerbaijan through the pipeline transiting Chechenya.  The<br>
Chechen government is now seeking a share of transit tariffs and<br>
fees from the use of the Baku-Chechenya-Tikhoretsk-Novorossiisk<br>
pipeline.  The use of the this so-called "northern route" pipeline<br>
for transporting Azerbaijani oil is essential to the viability of<br>
the multi-billion oil deal and is strongly advocated by Russia. <br>
Recently, Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin met with the<br>
interim Chechen government led by Prime Minister Aslan Maskhadov to<br>
negotiate the secure use of the pipeline.<br>
<p>
20 December: The U.S. oil company Mobil announces a new plan to<br>
develop the Oguz oil and natural gas deposits in the Caspian Sea. <br>
The offshore reserves are estimated to contain 40 million tons of<br>
crude oil and 20 billion cubic meters of natural gas.  Negotiations<br>
on the details of the project are underway between Mobil and the<br>
Azerbaijani state oil company SOCAR.  Both the Russians and the<br>
Iranians are interested in gaining a share in this project.<br>
<p>
21 December: The operational arm of the 12-nation consortium of<br>
international oil companies formed to develop and exploit three<br>
offshore oil fields in the Caspian Sea, the Azerbaijan<br>
International Operating Company (AIOC), announces the completion of<br>
initial drilling in the offshore Azeri and Chirag fields.  The<br>
drilling of the fields by a Western firm marks the first direct<br>
Western involvement in Azerbaijan's energy sector since the<br>
beginning of the century.  Early production from the fields are<br>
expected to be ready for export sometime in early 1997 and will<br>
most likely be recovered from the nearby Guneshli field.<br>
<p>
__________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
4,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Delaware<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
150,000<br>
31 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
95% Armenian<br>
5% Assyrian, Greek,<br>
Kurdish, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Robert Kocharian, President (elected December 22,<br>
1994);  Leonard Petrossian, Prime Minister;  Arkady Gukasyan,<br>
Foreign Minister;  Samvel Babayan, Defense Minister.<br>
<p>
Independence:  The Republic of Nagorno Karabagh was established on<br>
September 2, 1991 and declared its independence on January 6, 1992.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Nagorno Karabagh is not a member of the<br>
CIS.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  The Parliament, which approved a temporary<br>
constitution in June 1992, had been working on drafting a<br>
constitution for the republic.  This task will now be assumed by<br>
the new parliament.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Parliamentary elections were held April 30, 1995 for a<br>
new 33-seat parliament.  Presidential elections are scheduled for<br>
November 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  Nagorno Karabagh's representative to<br>
the United States is Ardem Haroutunian.  Varoujan Krikorian is the<br>
representative of Nagorno Karabagh to the European Community and<br>
the European Parliament.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 December: As the international summit of the Organization for<br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) looms, Azerbaijani<br>
officials begin pressuring Armenian government figures to soften<br>
the Armenian diplomatic position regarding the Nagorno Karabagh<br>
conflict.  Azerbaijan promises Armenia a share in the revenue from<br>
the multi-billion dollar oil deals underway between Baku and<br>
Western oil companies.<br>
<p>
2-3 December: A summit of the member states of the Organization for<br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) convenes in Lisbon to<br>
review the international security group's structure, charter and<br>
agenda of diverse conflict mediation and preventive diplomacy.  The<br>
54-nation OSCE summit places the Nagorno Karabagh conflict high on<br>
its agenda in accordance with its long standing attempt at<br>
mediation over the past several years.  A preliminary mediation<br>
effort is launched by a working group of eleven OSCE nations led by<br>
Finland and Russia preceding the full summit with talks between<br>
Armenian and Azerbaijani officials failing to reach any significant<br>
accord.  The summit's handling of the Nagorno Karabagh conflict<br>
remains deadlocked over Azerbaijan's adamant demand for full<br>
recognition and endorsement of its territorial integrity despite<br>
the Armenian call for a guarantee of the right of self-<br>
determination for Nagorno Karabagh.  The Karabagh position regards<br>
its need for effective security guarantees and the articulation of<br>
its legal and diplomatic status as its priorities.  To date,<br>
Azerbaijan has conceded to offer Nagorno Karabagh a "high degree of<br>
autonomy" within Azerbaijan proper, contingent on the return of the<br>
occupied areas of Azerbaijan currently held by Karabagh forces and<br>
the return of the Azerbaijani refugees to those areas.  <br>
<p>
3 December: The Nagorno Karabagh Central Electoral Commission<br>
announces the final results of the November 24th election in which<br>
President Robert Kocharian was reelected to the presidency. <br>
According to the official final results, Kocharian garnered 88.9<br>
percent of the vote, followed by Boris Aroushanian with 7.05<br>
percent and Hrand Melkoumian with four percent.  Total voter<br>
turnout reached 70,058, or 80 percent of the eligible electorate.<br>
<p>
5 December: The Nagorno Karabagh ministry of health appeals for<br>
medical personnel due to the critical shortage of doctors and other<br>
medical staff in the republic.  According to the ministry, many<br>
qualified medical specialists are serving in the defense forces and<br>
that the shortfall of doctors is not being met by the small number<br>
of trained doctors coming to Nagorno Karabagh from Armenia.<br>
<p>
7 December: Recently reelected Nagorno Karabagh President Robert<br>
Kocharian announces that he is retaining Prime Minister Leonard<br>
Petrosian.  The prime minister is now empowered to form his new<br>
government within the next ten days.  The new government is<br>
reportedly adding new emphasis on the need for introducing more<br>
comprehensive systemic economic reforms and the challenges posed by<br>
the republic's unemployed and pensioners.<br>
<p>
10 December: The Nagorno Karabagh foreign ministry and parliament<br>
issue statements sharply critical of the recent summit of the<br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in<br>
Lisbon.  The statements threaten a review of Nagorno Karabagh's<br>
participation in the OSCE-brokered mediation attempt in light of<br>
the summit's acceptance of the Azerbaijani position regarding the<br>
Nagorno Karabagh conflict.  The Nagorno Karabagh position<br>
specifically faults the OSCE's endorsement of the principle of<br>
territorial integrity over the right of self-determination.  This<br>
conflict of principles is the fundamental diplomatic dispute<br>
deadlocking the mediation of the Karabagh question. <br>
<p>
10 December: Nagorno Karabagh President Robert Kocharian arrives in<br>
France leading a delegation of government officials and ministers. <br>
President Kocharian meets with French Senator Rene Rouquet, the<br>
head of the French Assembly's France-Armenia friendship group.  The<br>
French parliamentarian, speaking at a community gathering with the<br>
Karabagh delegation, commends the will of the Karabagh population<br>
in seeking their independence from Azerbaijan and recognizes the<br>
right of self-determination of Nagorno Karabagh.<br>
<p>
12 December: Arriving in Stepanakert on a working visit,<br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)<br>
representative Anjey Kasprchik meets with Nagorno Karabagh<br>
officials to review the situation in the region and to discuss<br>
further mediation efforts by the international security group in<br>
the wake of the recent summit in Lisbon.  The meetings also discuss<br>
the security needs of the Karabagh population.<br>
<p>
25 December: The Russian co-chairman of the OSCE Minsk group for<br>
Nagorno Karabagh Yuri Yukalov meets with Nagorno Karabagh officials<br>
in Stepanakert during a visit to the region.  The OSCE official<br>
also met with the Azerbaijani president and some Armenian officials<br>
earlier in the trip.  During the meetings, the OSCE representative<br>
favored continuing the mediation talks aimed at reaching a<br>
settlement of the Karabagh conflict.  In a statement made at the<br>
OSCE summit meeting in Lisbon, the current OSCE chairman, Swiss<br>
Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti, adhered to a strict set of<br>
principles to settle the Karabagh conflict.  These principles<br>
consisted of the recognition of Azerbaijan's territorial integrity<br>
by the international community, the granting of autonomy to Nagorno<br>
Karabagh and the guarantee of the security of the Nagorno Karabagh<br>
population.<br>
<p>
29 December: By the terms of a presidential decree, President<br>
Kocharian announces the new members of the Nagorno Karabagh<br>
cabinet.  Gerard Poghossian is appointed deputy prime minister;<br>
Minister of Health Care, Julia Logorian; Minister of Foreign<br>
Affairs, Arkady Ghoukasian; Minister of Agriculture, Valery<br>
Alexanian; Minister of Economy and Finance, Spartak Tevossian;<br>
Minister of Education and Science, Hamlet Assatrian; Minister of<br>
Internal Affairs, Garen Babayan; Minister of Construction, Edward<br>
Shahramanian; Minister of Defense, Samvel Babayan; Minister of<br>
Social Security, Serge Aroushanian; Minister of Justice, Yuri<br>
Hayrapetian; and Head of the Department for Statistics, State<br>
Register and Analysis, Oleg Yessayan.<br>
<p>
___________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
<p>
The source for the Human Rights Watch World Report 1997 in the<br>
Caucasus profile is the:<br>
Human Rights Watch, World Report 1997, Events of 1996<br>
<p>
