                CLAIMS FOR FORCED LEVY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 8, ARMENPRESS.<br>
The official taxation bodies of the Republic of Armenia have claimed for<br>
forced levy against certain companies which failed to perform the <br>
taxation responsibilities. The number of the companies reaches 162, <br>
including "Tosp", "Anush",  "Doghagorts", "Sirius",<br>
"Hastotcashinakan", "Avtobernich", "Haitskhakhot", "Yerevan<br>
Factory of Canned Goods", "Zangu" and others. The amount is<br>
9799547.0 thousand Drams (1$=420 Drams).<br>
<p>
                CLAIMS FOR BANKRUPTCY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 8, ARMENPRESS.<br>
The taxation bodies of the Republic of Armenia have claimed certain<br>
companies bankrupt which failed to perform the taxation <br>
responsibilities, including "Masis", "Haygorg", "Vanadzor Knitted<br>
Fabric Mill", "Haitrchnardshin" and others. Claims of bankruptcy are<br>
made against 28 companies, with the amount of 2009688.0 thousand <br>
Drams ($1=420 Drams).<br>
<p>
        GOVERNMENT ATTACHES GREAT IMPORTANCE TO INCOME GOT FROM TAXATION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 8, ARMENPRESS.<br>
The amount of fiscal debts in the Republic, according to the data of<br>
November 1, 1996, is 19.2 billion drams ($1=420 drams). The list of<br>
those avoiding fiscal liabilities, include governmental, as well as non<br>
governmental enterprises. 168 plaints on levy of the property and 29<br>
plaints on bankruptcy of enterprises have been submitted to People's<br>
courts, and 48 actions have been brought against the directors of the<br>
enterprises. Following the meeting with the Ministers of the Republic<br>
of Armenia, organized by the Armenian President on the procedure of<br>
paying off the debts, during November and December, 1996, 13.1 and 8.6<br>
billion drams have been paid to state budget correspondingly.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIAN PRIME MINISTER'S MEETINGS IN WASHINGTON<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 8, ARMENPRESS.<br>
The Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia Armen Sarkissian, who was in<br>
Washington to negotiate with World Bank and International Monetary<br>
Fund, met with leaders of International Financial Corporation and with<br>
Director of Exlm Bank Dr. Rita Rodrigess on January 7. During the<br>
meetings, the Armenian Prime Minister introduced the<br>
socio-economic situation of Armenia and the programs of the<br>
Government connected with privatization processes, foreign investments,<br>
improvements in banking and taxation systems. Mr. Sarkissian pointed<br>
out that the Armenian Government is working out a new program for<br>
socio-economic development of the Republic.<br>
On January 8, meetings are scheduled with senator John Kerri and<br>
editorial council of Washington Post.<br>
On the same day, the Armenian Assembly will organize a diner in honor<br>
of the Armenian Prime Minister.<br>
<p>
        4,000 PEOPLE SICK WITH ALCOHOLISM REGISTERED IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 8, ARMENPRESS.<br>
Today more than 4,000 people are registered in Armenia as chronic<br>
alcoholics, and unfortunately this number grows each year. According<br>
to Director of Republican Narcological Center Seda Djamalian, the main<br>
reason for this is the difficult social situation in which the<br>
population lives. Ms. Jamalian thinks that the Government should work<br>
out an antialcoholic program, take under its control the production of<br>
drinks, as well as their import to the Republic.<br>
Around 60 patients are undergoing a course of treatment in<br>
narcological center of Yerevan. According to the observations of the<br>
experts only 20% of those undergone treatment gives up drinking<br>
forever.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
