---------- S C I E N T I F I C   N E W S -----------<br>
<p>
1996 WAS A TURNING-POINT FOR ARMENIAN <br>
SCIENCE, NAS PRESIDENT SAYS<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 7 (Noyan Tapan). The year of 1996 was a<br>
turning-point in the work of the National Academy of Sciences,<br>
NAS President Fadey Sargssian said at a recent news conference<br>
in Yerevan.<br>
     He pointed out to some priorities in Armenia's science<br>
which are mainly related to energy, ecology, history,<br>
archaeology, geology, defense industries, seismic-resistant<br>
construction, etc. <br>
     Armenia has intensified its scientific relations with<br>
Russia and other CIS-member countries. For instance, a joint<br>
scientific center for parasitology founded on the basis of the<br>
Armenian Zoology Institute and Russian Institute for<br>
Parasitology started to operate in 1996. Another joint<br>
scientific center set up on the basis of the Armenian and<br>
Russian Biochemistry Institutes will start to operate soon.<br>
     The Armenian Academy of Sciences has also established ties<br>
with major scientific establishments of the USA, United Kingdom,<br>
France, Iran and China. Surveys for mineral resources as well as<br>
research aimed at creating new cheap compositional materials are<br>
being conducted within the framework of various joint scientific<br>
projects. A project on transmission of medical consultations via<br>
video system has been worked out jointly with the US Public<br>
Health Institute. Also a project on cultivation of quick-growing<br>
poplars is being implemented in association with the California<br>
University. The Academy also signed an agreement with Hungarian<br>
party on exchange of scientists.<br>
     Last year Armenian scientists participated in a number of<br>
international scientific conferences. In Armenia NAS organized<br>
13 sceintific forums with participation of foreign scientists.<br>
     Fadey Sargssian said that the intensive development of<br>
international ties helped to maintain not only scientific<br>
potential but also ensured the development of scientific trends<br>
which are of paramount importance for the Republic and for which<br>
separate funds have been earmarked. Sarkissian noted that the<br>
presidential decree on the National Academy of Sciences issued<br>
in 1993 had been actually realized in a new provision on<br>
providing funds to the Academy. Under the new provision NAS will<br>
be financed through special funds, which include basic financing<br>
and grants earmarked under implementation of concrete projects. <br>
     "We'll do everything so as to maintain and even multiply<br>
the achievements of the Armenian science," President of NAS<br>
said.<br>
<p>
-------------- H O M E   N E W S -------------------<br>
<p>
JAN QEZHUN: "OUR RELATIONS <br>
WILL HAVE PROGRESS"<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 7 (Noyan Tapan). In 1996 the relations<br>
between China and Armenia were marked by a number of very<br>
important events, that are first of all the mutual visits of top<br>
officials of the two countries. In April Deputy State Council's<br>
Premier, Foreign Minister of China Xiang Xicheng paid a visit to<br>
Armenia. Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrossian and Parliament<br>
Speaker Babken Ararktsian visited China. The same year Armenia<br>
opened an embassy in China.<br>
     Below is an interview with Ambassador of China to Armenia<br>
Jan Qezhun, in which he expressed his opinion about the<br>
development of relations between the two states.<br>
<p>
     Q. How can you characterize the relations between China and<br>
Armenia? What does Armenia mean for China?<br>
     A. People's Republic of China was among the first states to<br>
recognize Armenia's independence and established diplomatic<br>
relations with it on April 6, 1992. China's only wish is to<br>
contribute to the stability and peace in the whole<br>
Transcaucasian region to ensure its progress and prosperity.<br>
China pursues independent policy of development of relations<br>
with all countries. There are no political discords between<br>
China and Armenia. China backs Armenia's efforts aimed at<br>
protecting its sovereignty and independence. We are glad to see<br>
Armenia as our strategic partner and are ready to cooperate with<br>
her in solving international problems on the level of the<br>
biggest international organizations, such as UN. This was<br>
contributed by President Levon Ter-Petrossian's visit to China<br>
last May, during which Mr.Ter-Petrossian confirmed that Armenia<br>
would never recognize other Chinese state but only the People's<br>
Republic of China.<br>
<p>
     Q. What are the agreements that were and that will be<br>
signed between our two states?<br>
     A. Armenia and China concluded agreements on cooperation in<br>
practically all spheres of trade, economy, science and culture. <br>
     During a visit to China in 1992 Vice President and Premier<br>
Gagik Haroutiunian signed a number of governmental agreements:<br>
on extension and mutual protection of investments, in field of<br>
science and technique, culture, health care, tourism etc. There<br>
was also signed an agreement under which China was to give<br>
Armenia $4-million credit that has been already fulfilled by<br>
China.<br>
     During a visit by President Levon Ter-Petrossian, he and<br>
Chinese leader Xiang Xeming signed a communigue which set a base<br>
for further relations. They also concluded agreements on mutual<br>
evasion of double taxation, on cooperation in banking sphere and<br>
aviatransport.<br>
     For the years of 1997-1998 there have been signed protocols<br>
on concrete plans of cooperations in field of culture and<br>
tourism.<br>
<p>
     Q. Is your country going to invest in Armenia or open joint<br>
ventures? Do you see a chance to cooperate in developing new<br>
technologies?<br>
     A. Economic cooperations between China and Armenia have<br>
ancient traditions. Our countries were linked by the Great Silk<br>
Route. We have a high potential to develop trade-economic<br>
relations. The major obstacle to develop trade is the<br>
transportation problems. More favorable is the situation with<br>
the establishment of joint ventures that is encouraged by the<br>
Chinese government.<br>
     Upon improvement of the legislative base there can be<br>
expected growth of China's investments in Armenia.<br>
     In conclusion Mr. Qezhun said: "I am an optimist and I am<br>
confident that thanks to joint efforts our relations will have a<br>
progress and majority of problems will be solved in the near<br>
future.<br>
<p>
 ------------- J U D I C I A L   N E W S ------------------<br>
     <br>
MEETING WITH REPRESENTATIVES OF <br>
ARFD SUPREME AUTHORITY TO ARMENIA <br>
IS TO TAKE PLACE ON JANUARY 8 <br>
AT JUSTICE MINISTRY<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 7 (Noyan Tapan). Justice Minister Marat<br>
Alexanian met Tuesday with Rouben Hakobian, political<br>
representative of the ARFD Supreme Authority to Armenia. On the<br>
initiative of the Justice Ministry the meeting was attended by<br>
Directors of the "Armenpress" and "Noyan Tapan" news agencies<br>
Tigran Hakobian and Tigran Haroutiunian.<br>
     After a short discussion and taking into account the<br>
importance of the matter and mass media's interest toward it, it<br>
was decided to postpone the meeting till January 8 so that to<br>
ensure the presence of mass media representatives.<br>
     According to an agreement reached, there will be discussed<br>
problems connected with reanimation of ARFD activity in Armenia.<br>
     The meeting is to start at midday.<br>
<p>
NDU LEADER CONGRATULATES <br>
DEFENDANTS<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, January 7 (Noyan Tapan). Leader of the<br>
National-Democratic Union Vazgen Manoukian congratulated Vahan<br>
Hovhanessian accused in connection with the 31 case on occasion<br>
of the New Year and Christmas.<br>
     "I would like to wish you and all our friends in custody a<br>
Happy New Year and Merry Christmas. I wish that the year of 1997<br>
be the year of freedom for you and our people. Despite their<br>
tragic nature last year's events showed that we have a wonderful<br>
people (the opinion of our leaders that the population is<br>
disappointed and broken down did not prove to be true) and<br>
nothing should be spared for the sake of our people. Be strong,"<br>
the message reads. <br>
     NDU Board member Vladimir Hakhverdian reported that<br>
Manoukian addressed congratulatory messages to other defendants,<br>
accused in connection with the case of 31, as well as to those<br>
arrested in connection with September 25 events and those<br>
convicted in connection with the Dro case.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
