<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [01-07-97]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [01-07-97]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>07 Jan 97 19:06:09 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#284">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#284">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#284">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#284">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0285.html">Peter A. Tatian: "Eurasia Foundation request"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0283.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 1/7/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE<br>
<p>
1/07/97<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
1. JUSTICE MINISTER MEETS WITH ARF REP.<br>
2. MANOUKIAN SENDS GREETINGS TO POLITICAL PRISONERS<br>
3. "TRIAL OF 31" TO RESUME NEXT WEEK<br>
4. PRELACY HOSTS ANNUAL CHRISTMAS DINNER<br>
5. CLASS ACTION SUIT AGAINST LIBARIDIAN TO CONTINUE IN <br>
ARMENIAN COURTS<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
1.JUSTICE MINISTER MEETS WITH ARF REP.<br>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Justice Minister Marat Alexanian met <br>
with political representative of the Armenian Revolutionary <br>
Federation Executive Council of Armenia Rouben Hakobian <br>
Monday, and was expected to hold a second meeting on <br>
Tuesday.<br>
	At the request of the Justice Ministry, the meeting was <br>
attended by directors of the "Armenpress" and "Noyan Tapan" <br>
news agencies, Tigran Hakobian and Tigran Haroutiunian, <br>
respectively.<br>
	After a short discussion, the meeting adjourned early to <br>
allow more time for other representatives of the mass media <br>
to be present.<br>
	Tuesdays meeting was expected to focus on the issue of <br>
reinstating the ARF in Armenia.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
2.MANOUKIAN SENDS GREETINGS TO POLITICAL PRISONERS<br>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-National Democratic Union leader <br>
Vazgen Manoukian sent holiday greetings to ARF leader and <br>
defendant in the so-called "Trial of 31" Vahan Hovanessian <br>
and his co-defendants, as well as to the defendants in the <br>
so-called "Dro" case and those arrested following the Sept. <br>
25 post-election crackdown in Armenia, Vova Hakhverdian of <br>
the NDU reported.<br>
	"I would like to wish you and all our friends in <br>
custody a Happy New Year and Merry Christmas. I wish that <br>
1997 will be the year of freedom for you and our people. <br>
Last years events showed that we have a wonderful <br>
people-the opinion of our leaders that the population is <br>
disappointed and broken down did not prove to be true-and <br>
nothing should be spared for the sake of our people," <br>
Manoukian said in his message.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. "TRIAL OF 31" TO RESUME NEXT WEEK<br>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)--Monday's regularly scheduled court <br>
session for the so-called "Trial of 31" was cancelled due to <br>
the illness of a member of the judicial board, Nina <br>
Hakopian.<br>
	The next session will be held on Jan. 13.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. PRELACY HOSTS ANNUAL CHRISTMAS DINNER<br>
MONTEBELLO-The Western Prelacy of the Armenian Apostolic <br>
Church hosted its annual traditional Christmas dinner on <br>
Monday, January 6 in Montebellos Bagramian Hall, with more <br>
than 650 people in attendance.<br>
	Following a formal procession into the hall by Prelate <br>
Moushegh Mardirossian and members of the clergy representing <br>
the various prelacy churches in the Southland, Master of <br>
Ceremonies, Rev. Vicken Vassilian of Holy Martyrs Church in <br>
Encino asked the eldest guest at each table to dip the relic <br>
in red wine and pass it to the others on the table.<br>
	The benediction was said by Arch. Smpad Lapajian.<br>
	The evenings cultural program included a performance of <br>
traditional Christmas carols by the St. Marys Church Choir, <br>
poetry recitation by Meline Kelenjian and solo performances <br>
by Ara Ghazarian, Anoush Ghazarian and Rima Garabedian.<br>
	Prelate Mardirossian read a special New Years and <br>
Christmas message sent by His Holiness Aram I of the Holy <br>
See of Cilicia, then on behalf of the Prelacys Executive <br>
and Religious Councils and the Ladies Auxiliary, welcomed <br>
the gathering and praised benefactors John and Astghig <br>
Bedrossian, Walter and Clara Kerian and Richard and Tina <br>
Carolan for their continued generosity, especially for their <br>
recent donations to the Prelacy during the holiday season.<br>
	In his Christmas message, the Prelate said that the <br>
holidays are the time to make good on promises by taking <br>
steps to incorporate them in our daily lives.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. CLASS ACTION SUIT AGAINST LIBARIDIAN TO CONTINUE IN <br>
ARMENIAN COURTS<br>
NEW YORK-On December 19, 1996, the plaintiffs in the class-<br>
action suit against Armenian Presidential Advisor Gerard <br>
Libaridian sought to withdraw their case from the United <br>
States federal district court in order to attempt to pursue <br>
their cases in Armenian courts, according to a statement <br>
issued by the Center for Economic and Social Rights, a non-<br>
profit human rights group based in New York.<br>
	The suit charged Libaridian with legal responsibility for <br>
his role in the violent government crackdown against <br>
ordinary citizens and various members of opposition <br>
political parties and their families and neighbors, <br>
following the September 21, 1996 presidential election in <br>
Armenia, which was judged by election observers to be <br>
neither fair nor free.<br>
	The plaintiffs sought remedy for the injuries they <br>
suffered during the crackdown, when government forces <br>
rounded up more than 175 men and women, including members of <br>
the National Assembly, subjected them to beatings, torture <br>
and interrogation, and kept them captive in jails and <br>
isolation wards around the country for extended periods of <br>
time.<br>
	Many were held for over two weeks and suffered <br>
severe injuries requiring hospitalization. During <br>
their imprisonment, they had no contact with their <br>
families, and were not allowed access to counsel. At <br>
the same time, the government attacked a number of <br>
opposition political party offices, destroying or <br>
confiscating all of the parties records, equipment <br>
and property.<br>
	Sarah Leah Whitson, CESRs general counsel and an adviser <br>
on the case, commented: "The plaintiffs in this case are <br>
exceedingly brave, and have a sincere hope that they can <br>
move their country back on a democratic path. They are <br>
taking an enormous risk by choosing to pursue their cases in <br>
Armenian courts, where they have virtually no assurance that <br>
they will receive a fair trial. By bringing their cases in <br>
Armenia, they are giving the courts there another <br>
opportunity for redemption as an independent judicial body <br>
committed to protecting the rights of Armenias citizens and <br>
to seeing that justice is done."<br>
	"We will stand behind the plaintiffs in this case with <br>
every resource at our disposal. We will continue to provide <br>
them with legal assistance on questions of international law <br>
and to coordinate our efforts with local human rights groups <br>
in Armenia," she said. <br>
	Roger Normand, executive director of CESR, said: "We <br>
believe that several of the cases primary objectives have <br>
been achieved.  This case has sent a strong message to the <br>
government of Armenia that those responsible for violating <br>
international law and abusing the rights of other citizens <br>
can be held personally liable and brought to justice even in <br>
courts outside their country."<br>
	"The international community is watching the Armenian <br>
government very closely; we know the government knows that," <br>
he added.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Please send your comments and questions to Asbarez-on-line <br>
at the above E-mail address. We also encourage suggestions <br>
on improving our on-line services.<br>
