<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 10/21/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 10/21/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 7 Jan 97 1:17:04 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#275">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#275">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#275">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#275">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0276.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 1/6/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0274.html">Vachik Hacopian: "Avedis Tevanian leads Mac OS development team"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	+&gt; UN observers hostage in Tajikistan  <br>
	+&gt; Ratings agency downgrades Turkish debt  <br>
	+&gt; Iranian, Turkish presidents go on tour  <br>
	+&gt; Iran said to offer Syria-Turkey mediation  <br>
                               ======<br>
 UN observers hostage in Tajikistan<br>
	Seven foreign U.N. military observers and a number of<br>
ethnic Tajiks are being held hostage after gunmen abducted the<br>
group on a road east of the Tajikistan capital of Dushanbe. A<br>
source at the U.N. mission in the Central Asian nation says the<br>
attackers are militants loyal to a warlord who has vacillated<br>
between support for the opposition and the government. The<br>
source says the gunmen are demanding that they and their fellow<br>
militants be allowed to move freely from their base in<br>
Afghanistan to Tajikistan. They also want opposition forces to<br>
free the brother of their commander, Rizvon Sadirov. Among the<br>
hostages are two Bulgarians, an Austrian, a Dane, a Jordanian, a<br>
Ukrainian and a Uruguayan. Two Tajik U.N. workers and several<br>
members of a government- opposition peace commission are also<br>
being held. U.N. observers have been in Tajikistan since 1994<br>
monitoring an ineffective cease-fire between the government and<br>
opposition forces. Tajik opposition leader Said Abdullo Nuri and<br>
President Emomali Rakhmonov are now in Moscow.  They are<br>
scheduled to meet Saturday to try to agree on a plan to end<br>
years of conflict in the former Soviet republic.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Ratings agency downgrades Turkish debt<br>
	The European credit rating agency IBCA Friday downgraded<br>
long-term foreign currency ratings for about $50 billion of<br>
Turkey's foreign debt, citing "economic mismanagement and a<br>
lack of political will." IBCA said its rating for Turkey's<br>
senior and unsecured debt was reduced from BB minus to B plus,<br>
but a short-term B rating for debts up to a year remained<br>
unchanged. The London-based agency's officials were not<br>
available to comment on the ratings move, which was seen by<br>
financial experts as a setback to Islamist Prime Minister<br>
Necmettin Erbakan's coalition government in Ankara. IBCA said it<br>
still saw "many" strengths in the Turkish private<br>
sector. "However, these attributes continue to be undermined by<br>
economic mismanagement and a lack of political will to tackle<br>
public sector reforms," it added. It said that Erbakan, who<br>
formed a government after the collapse of a center-right<br>
coalition last year, "has not done nearly enough to arrest"<br>
the drift in Turkey. "Serious macro-economic imbalances have<br>
continued to develop: inflation, the fiscal deficit and the<br>
current account deficit all now rival or exceed the levels<br>
prevailing at the time of the last crisis in 1993-94." IBCA<br>
warned that unless Erbakan accepted structural reforms he ran<br>
the risk of becoming ensnared in a domestic debt trap.  "Turkey<br>
cannot afford a repetition of 1994 when it was shut out of<br>
international bond markets," said the agency.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Iranian, Turkish presidents go on tour<br>
	The presidents of Iran and Turkey flew together Friday<br>
to a Kurdish- dominated province in southeastern Turkey, Turkish<br>
officials said. The solidarity tour on the second day of Iranian<br>
President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani's four days in Turkey was<br>
unmistakable in its symbolism: Turkey has been fighting since<br>
1984 with Kurdish insurgents trying to carve an independent<br>
Kurdistan out of Turkey's southeast. At least 21, 000 people<br>
have been killed and many more wounded in Turkey's<br>
insurgency. Iran, which has a province called Kurdistan, also<br>
fights Kurdish separatists and opposes an independent Kurdish<br>
state that could include regions of Iran, Iraq, Syria and<br>
Turkey. Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, who made the unusual<br>
gesture Thursday of meeting Rafsanjani at the Ankara airport<br>
Thursday, accompanied the Iranian leader to Turkey's Anatolian<br>
province of Sanliurfa. The presidents were scheduled to tour the<br>
Southeast Anatolian Development Project, made up of 19<br>
hydroelectric plants and 22 dams along the Euphrates and Tigris<br>
rivers. The irrigation project also produces 130 billion<br>
kilowatts of electricity.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Iran said to offer Syria-Turkey mediation<br>
	Iran has offered to mediate between Syria and Turkey in<br>
a bid to improve their strained ties, Turkish sources said<br>
Friday. There was no word on whether either country has accepted<br>
the offer. Iran was calling on Syria to stop aiding Turkey's<br>
Kurdish rebels, in return for Turkey's taking a more hostile<br>
stand against Israel, the Damascus-based sources told United<br>
Press International. Turkey has a military cooperation accord<br>
with Israel. Syria has denied aiding Kurdish insurgents trying<br>
to carve an independent Kurdistan out of southeastern Turkey and<br>
has jailed some Turkish separatists. The sources said such<br>
mediation would result in a "unified stand by the three<br>
countries" with regard to regional developments , particularly<br>
with regard to Israel. Iran wants to contain the Kurdish issue<br>
within "a tripartite framework," the sources said.  Turkey,<br>
Iran, Iraq and Syria all have large Kurdish regions and their<br>
governments oppose an independent Kurdistan. Iranian President<br>
Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani made his mediation offer at the<br>
start of his visit to Turkey this week, the sources said.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
