<!-- body="start" -->
from: MacWeek OnLine, DECEMBER 23, 1996<br>
<p>
Priority One for new Apple OS boss: Shipping<br>
<p>
By Clifford Colby (clifford_colby@zd.com)<br>
and David Morgenstern (david_morgenstern@zd.com)<br>
<p>
Avedis Tevanian has just been handed the reins for the future modern Mac OS.<br>
<p>
Apple last week tapped the former NeXT Software Inc. vice president of<br>
engineering to lead a team of NeXT and Apple engineers in producing the<br>
successor to System 7.x. In a conversation today with MacWEEK, Tevanian<br>
said, "My overriding goal is to get our team and their team working<br>
together as one team moving forward."<br>
<p>
According to Tevanian, the working model of the forthcoming OS will be<br>
NeXTstep, with Apple technologies grafted on where they make sense. Hoping<br>
to avoid pitfalls that plagued Copland, the new OS meister said a primary<br>
concern will be to get the OS out the door.<br>
<p>
"We are focused on shipping product," Tevanian said. The new OS chief said<br>
Apple will now take a "pragmatic approach" to system software and add only<br>
features that can be accomplished in several months. "[NeXTstep elements]<br>
will not change unless there's added value."<br>
<p>
Initially, the forthcoming Mac OS will have most of the look and feel of<br>
its NeXTstep parent, with some minor changes, Tevanian said. The two user<br>
interface teams will then, "do the right thing and make it easy for<br>
existing users of Mac machines," he said.<br>
<p>
While NeXTstep is multithreaded, it does not support symmetrical<br>
multiprocessing. Tevanian said this feature will be finished in "a short<br>
number of months."<br>
<p>
According to Tevanian, NeXT built a machine with a pair of PowerPC 601<br>
processors several years ago, with a version of NeXTstep tuned for it. The<br>
company never shipped the hardware or software.<br>
<p>
After the company got out of the hardware business in 1993, the design was<br>
used by Mountain View, Calif.-based FirePower Systems Inc., which last year<br>
was bought by Motorola Inc.'s Computer Group.<br>
<p>
Although he would not give specifics, Tevanian hopes to ship versions of<br>
the NeXT-Mac OS to developers and customers by the end of 1997.<br>
<p>
-----------<br>
