<title>Groong Network: Foreign Policy: Winter 1996/7, Russia &amp; the New Transcaucasus</title>
<h1>Foreign Policy: Winter 1996/7, Russia &amp; the New Transcaucasus</h1>
David Davidian (<i>dbd@urartu.sdpa.org</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 5 Jan 1997 14:04:02 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#272">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#272">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#272">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#272">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0273.html">Horizon/Giro Manoyan: "Armenian premier leaves for Washington"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0271.html">ANCA-DC: "ANC Renews Call for Princeton to Remove Lowry"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
From: _Foreign Policy_, Winter 1996/1997, pages 141-159<br>
<p>
           _Eurasia Letter: Russia and the New Transcaucasus_<br>
<p>
                          by David E. Mark<br>
<p>
---------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
DAVID E. MARK, a retired career U.S. Foreign Service officer with the<br>
rank of ambassador, served one year in 1994-95 in Tbilisi, Georgia, as <br>
a member and later as deputy chief of the OSCE mission to Georgia. He<br>
now teaches occasional classes in international affairs at New York <br>
University.<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
	The transformation in December 1991 of the 15 constituent republics <br>
of the former Soviet Union into 15 sovereign states produced three newly <br>
independent countries in the Transcaucasus -- Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Georgia. <br>
Over the past five years, the three countries have experienced political and <br>
economic turmoil.  Indeed, the first two bloodily battled each other from 1988 <br>
to mid 1994 over the still unsettled fate of the "autonomous region" of<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh within Azerbaijan, whose predominantly Armenian population <br>
wishes to become part of Armenia. Georgia has experienced episodes of civil <br>
war, as well as the de facto "secession" of two ethnic minority territories-<br>
Abkhazia and South Ossetia-both of which are wedged up against the southern<br>
side of the towering Caucasus mountain range. On the northern<br>
slopes, inside the Russian Federation, there has been much<br>
discontent_but only in Chechnya has military action erupted.<br>
<p>
	In addition to providing humanitarian aid to impoverished popu-<br>
lations and to about 1.3 million refugees in the Transcaucasus, the<br>
international community has sought to restore a degree of political<br>
stability, based on the principles of territorial integrity and the de jure<br>
authority of the recognized states (Azerbaijan and Georgia). More<br>
concretely, the United Nations has established a military observer<br>
force in Abkhazia and led international negotiations to settle that<br>
dispute. The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe<br>
(OSCE) has a large mission in Tbilisi to focus on Georgia's problems,<br>
and, early in 1995, it fielded a smaller "assistance group" in Chech-<br>
nya to facilitate contacts there among all sides. The OSCE has strug<br>
gled over several years with the various parties in Nagorno-Karabakh<br>
to work out an accord on the framework of a political settlement,<br>
which would then perhaps enable the OSCE to deploy its first-ever<br>
peacekeeping force in a crisis area. The September 1995 creation of<br>
a second OSCE mission in "neutral" Tbilisi was supposed to facilitate<br>
these efforts.<br>
<p>
	While these innately handicapped multinational organizations<br>
have attempted their good works in the region, there has been only<br>
modest effort by individual governments, other than Russia's, to ex-<br>
ert political influence beyond whatever arises from humanitarian aid,<br>
support for economic reform, cultural relations, and the occasional<br>
review of the foregoing conflictive issues in the UN. Security Coun-<br>
cil. To be sure, Turkish commercial activity has been considerable in<br>
Georgia and Azerbaijan, and diaspora support for Armenia -- espe-<br>
cially from groups in the United States and France -- has been criti-<br>
cal to that nation's survival. Petroleum reserves in and around the<br>
Caspian Sea have lately drawn substantial investment commitments<br>
from the transnational oil industry. This development has increased<br>
worldwide interest in Azerbaijan's fate, but not much external<br>
political engagement. Even the participation of Georgia's embryonic<br>
military and Armenia's and Azerbaijan's slightly more developed<br>
armed forces in the NATO-sponsored "Partnership for Peace" has<br>
tended to be limited, pro forma, considerate of skeptical Russian at<br>
titudes, and constrained by the determination of NATO member states<br>
to avoid overextension into the former USSR.<br>
<p>
	Almost by default, the preeminent political-military player in the<br>
Transcaucasus has been Russia itself. Despite the Chechnya embar-<br>
rassment, Russia's territorial base in the Caucasus (north of the<br>
mountains) and its varied involvements in the Transcaucasus are<br>
grounded on the availability of innumerable levers of influence and<br>
pressure, including Russia's sheer size, its relative power, and its close<br>
and dominant connections with the neighboring region over the last<br>
two centuries. These links have been much more intimate than those<br>
in Central Asia (even allowing for Russian military involvement in<br>
Taiikistan) and reflect the proximity of the Transcaucasus to other<br>
major regional actors in western Asia and Eastern Europe. Given this<br>
background, the nonpartisan observer of the local scene might ask<br>
several questions:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Are Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Georgia capable of becoming more</i><br>
  than formally independent and sovereign?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Does Moscow feel the urge to recreate a dominant hegemony in</i><br>
  the region_both bilaterally and through the Commonwealth of<br>
  Independent States (CIS)?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Does Russian behavior in the Transcaucasus provide clues to its</i><br>
  future global security policies toward the West and neighboring<br>
  states? <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Do Western states, especially NATO member states, have much in-</i><br>
  centive to resist current patterns of political evolution in the<br>
  Transcaucasus?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Should or can international organizations do more to bolster the</i><br>
  viability of the three Transcaucasian states?<br>
<p>
	The answers to these questions will help interested governments<br>
to judge underlying Russian motivations, policies, and practices to<br>
ward other former Soviet republics.<br>
<p>
A VIEW FROM MOSCOW<br>
<p>
	Since 1991 an array of differing opinions has been voiced in Rus-<br>
sia about its future relations with the West and about Russia's<br>
role in the 21st century. These opinions reflect divergent visions<br>
of the country's destiny. Nevertheless, there is considerable agreement<br>
among all groupings that Russia should retain at least the Trans-<br>
caucasus within an effective sphere of influence, if not within some<br>
even more demanding and constrictive relationship.<br>
<p>
	Almost all Russians seem to have the visceral feeling that the<br>
Transcaucasus is, and ought to remain, politically inseparable from<br>
Russia. This belief reflects its presence within the domains of czars<br>
and commissars for the past 115 to 200 years, and the connection is<br>
seen as no less normal and natural than the continuing incorpora-<br>
tion of the (north) Caucasus in the Russian Federation. There has<br>
been a substantial influx of ethnic Russians into the northern Cau-<br>
casus since it became pacified almost 150 years ago. Russians now<br>
make up 20 to 25 per cent of the overall population. The remainder<br>
consists of peoples of other ethnic groups -- mostly from the distinct<br>
Caucasian language family, but with a mixture of ancient Turkic and<br>
Persian elements. Only one group, the Ossetians, is Christian (Or-<br>
thodox); the others are partially, or almost fully, secularized Muslims.<br>
However, all of the latter remember a history of resistance to Russ-<br>
ian rule in the first half of the 19th century (which the Chechens<br>
have lately renewed) and have enough residual grievances to cause<br>
Moscow concern about their susceptibility to transnational Islamic<br>
movements. Russia must also worry about the influence of Caucasian<br>
unrest on the stability of the neighboring Russian populated territo-<br>
ries of Krasnodar and Stavropol.<br>
<p>
	This widespread Russian apprehension spills over into contem-<br>
plation of the contiguous Transcaucasus. The Armenians and Geor<br>
gians -- both Christians -- speak distinct and unique languages, and<br>
the Azeris use a cousin of Turkish; but all three peoples have become<br>
partly Russified over the years. Moscow has not forgotten Turkish<br>
and, to a lesser extent, Persian territorial ambitions in the Trans-<br>
caucasus in the 17th and 18th centuries, as well as Turkish-Russian<br>
(and Turkish Soviet) tensions in the 19th and 20th centuries. Turkey<br>
today is viewed as both a rival in the region and a surrogate for NATO.<br>
<p>
	There is also a widely prevalent belief among Russians that none<br>
of the three Transcaucasian states will prove viable entirely on its<br>
own. Armenia is viewed as a landlocked and psychologically isolated<br>
enclave subject to Turkish, Iranian, and Azeri pressures; the new Re-<br>
public of Azerbaijan incorporates only perhaps one quarter of the<br>
Azeri people -- the rest of whom live under Iran's fundamentalist ls-<br>
lamic regime; and Georgia is thought to be too politically and eth-<br>
nically fragile. Although Muslim Turkey is constitutionally secular,<br>
most Russian officials involved in these questions believe it is prone<br>
to a relapse into politicized lslamism over the next decade or two.<br>
Russians thus foresee potential threats to their security in the cur-<br>
rent configuration of the Transcaucasus and its southern neighbors.<br>
lt is no wonder then that the old Soviet military command there has<br>
stayed on -- legitimated by treaties with Tbilisi and Yerevan -- with<br>
the barely changed name of the "Russian Group of Forces in the<br>
Transcaucasus." The generals' vision of regional stability and their<br>
support of the status quo ante seem to be shared by their diplomatic<br>
colleagues.<br>
<p>
SEPARATISM IN THE THREE REPUBL1CS<br>
<p>
In South Ossetia, Abkhazia, and Nagorno Karabakh -- the three<br>
most turbulent zones of the Transcaucasus -- secessionist adminis-<br>
trations have assumed de facto authority behind ceasefire lines set<br>
under agreements brokered by Russian authorities in 1992 and<br>
1994. In Abkhazia and South Ossetia (both within Georgia), Russian<br>
peacekeeping forces ensure physical separation between ex combat-<br>
ants. In Nagorno Karabakh, where there are no peacekeepers, the<br>
OSCE is trying to arrange for their introduction under its auspices once<br>
the outline of a peace settlement has been determined. Everyone<br>
hopes that Azerbaijan, which has been rebuilding its still very weak<br>
armed forces, will not be tempted to restart combat in an effort to re-<br>
store the territorial status quo ante against Armenia. On the other<br>
hand, perpetuation of the three ceasefires tends progressively to con-<br>
solidate and normalize the de facto existence of the secessionist<br>
regimes. In between these extremes, the three countries are trying to<br>
achieve an economic and political revival within boundaries recon-<br>
figured by war.<br>
<p>
	All three secessionist zones are outgrowths of Soviet era nation-<br>
ality policies in the Transcaucasus. While the USSR existed, Western<br>
observers generally decried nationality policies as a sham that, under<br>
the guise of recognizing the diverse cultural traditions and political<br>
ambitions of the scores of ethnic groups within Soviet frontiers, in<br>
fact allowed Moscow to use "divide and rule" tactics to impose uni-<br>
form totalitarian policies and Russification on all citizens. The situ-<br>
ation in the Caucasus Transcaucasus region essentially confirms this<br>
evaluation by providing examples of how arbitrary Soviet decisions<br>
since the 1920s have complicated the problems of peaceful cohabi-<br>
tation and contiguous development among the diverse ethnic groups<br>
that are now unexpectedly living in four independent states.<br>
<p>
	_Armenia_. Manipulative Soviet nationality policies over many<br>
years especially facilitated today's Armenian-Azerbaijani confronta-<br>
tion. Under decrees from Moscow, the Armenians in Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh were left in an autonomous region within Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
Meanwhile, the Azeris in the nearby enclave of Nakhichevan, which<br>
looks on the map as if it should have been part of Armenia, were in<br>
fact also integrated into Azerbaijan, although they were separated<br>
from it by Armenian territory. (Over the following decades, almost<br>
all of the 40 per cent of Nakhichevan's population that had been Ar-<br>
menian emigrated.) Once central authority began to loosen under<br>
Mikhail Gorbachev in the late 1980s, the Armenians saw a chance<br>
to rectify what they perceived to be the Soviet wrong of the 1920s.<br>
In 1988, supported by materiel and manpower from authorities in<br>
Yerevan and backed energetically by emigre communities in the<br>
United States and Western Europe, local Armenian forces in<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh began their progressively expanding military ac-<br>
tion to abolish Azerbaijan's authority in that territory. In the inter-<br>
vening years, the victors have not only attained this political goal but<br>
have, in the process, expanded Nagorno Karabakh's borders far into<br>
Azerbaijan proper -- creating up to 1 million Azeri refugees. Indeed,<br>
since the ceasefire in 1994, the insurgents have been successfully re-<br>
building Nagorno-Karabakh's economy. The region is now virtually<br>
a part of Armenia and includes a new highway over the seven-mile<br>
formerly Azerbaijani "Lachin Strip," which once separated Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh from Armenia. Soviet and subsequently Russian military<br>
equipment, supplies, training, and advice -- nominally covert, but<br>
barely disguised -- have been crucial to the Armenians' success over<br>
the last eight years. This history, in turn, has enhanced both Arme-<br>
nia's ever greater reliance on Russia and Azerbaijan's animosity to-<br>
ward Moscow, on which it ironically also still depends.<br>
<p>
	Under these circumstances, some normalization of Armenian<br>
political and economic life has started. President Levon Ter Pet-<br>
rosyan's political machine, though backed by somewhat oppressive<br>
security ministries and nourished by gross corruption and favoritism<br>
to economic "in-groups" and local mafias, has begun to relax con-<br>
trols on political expression. Despite a Soviet-era statist mentality,<br>
the mid 1995 parliamentary elections were more or less procedurally<br>
fair on election day, although access to the ballot by independent<br>
candidates was closely controlled, and a major opposition party was<br>
disenfranchised. Ballot fraud in Ter-Petrosyan's reelection in Sep-<br>
tember 1996 was apparently at least as serious. The Turkish blockade<br>
of Armenia continues, but transport links through Georgia and Iran<br>
have been upgraded, and growing Armenian confidence in geopolit-<br>
ical security has led to greater entrepreneurship and economic sta-<br>
bilization.<br>
<p>
	_Azerbaijan_. Since 1988, Soviet and then Russian policy toward<br>
Armenia has clearly been favorable. The same cannot be said of<br>
Moscow's relations with Azerbaijan or Georgia. Both have had more<br>
complicated domestic political experiences than Armenia, and var-<br>
ious events have provoked not only shifts in Russian policies, but also<br>
divergent and contradictory operational guidelines from military ele-<br>
ements, the civilian bureaucracy, and Boris Yeltsin's presidency. Un-<br>
doubtedly influenced by the battles in Nagorno-Karabakh, Azeris<br>
have exhibited greater nationalism and a more conscious demand for<br>
real independence. These stirrings are fostered by strengthened<br>
political ties to Turkey and growing commercial links with both Iran<br>
and Turkey. In 1990, riots against Russians living in the capital<br>
(Baku) were followed by the evacuation of all but one of the Russian<br>
military bases in 1992 and by the election of a populist (and moder-<br>
ately Islamist) regime soon thereafter. That regime, however, was<br>
overthrown in mid-1993 by Geidar Aliyev, a former Soviet Politburo<br>
member turned nationalist, who had the backing of local Commu-<br>
nist era elites_and perhaps the Kremlin as well.<br>
<p>
                &lt;&lt;Almost by default, the preeminent political-<br>
                  militaly player in the Transcaucasus has been<br>
                  Russia itself.&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
	Moscow's long-term concerns over the ultimate interrelationship<br>
between Azerbaijan and Turkey, and over that between Azerbaijan<br>
and the numerous Azeris inside Iran, have lately been supplemented<br>
by anxieties over oil. Moscow fears the birth of a world-class petro<br>
leum complex in the Caspian Sea region, free of its influence, and is<br>
determined to hamper any such independent evolution. Moscow at<br>
first exercised blatant political muscle to try to halt the export of Az-<br>
eri oil via any route that bypasses Russia -- specifically by a pipeline<br>
through Georgia and Turkey -- but has had to relent, due to blockage<br>
of its own route through Chechnya. Transnational oil firms, caught<br>
up in these politics, have authorized two pipelines -- one through<br>
Russia and the other through Georgia. The former option is, as noted,<br>
being delayed, while the latter is in the feasibility study stage.<br>
<p>
	Russia has placed further pressure on Baku by restricting the traf-<br>
fic of goods between it and Azerbaijan (along the Daghestan-<br>
Caspian Sea road and rail routes) on the pretext of heightened Russ-<br>
ian security needs arising from the nearby Chechnyan conflict.<br>
Meanwhile, in the interminable negotiations on a political settle-<br>
ment framework and on the establishment of an OSCE peacekeeping<br>
force around Nagorno-Karabakh, the Russians have retained control<br>
over any arrangements by holding a veto wielding cochairmanship of<br>
the main political negotiating body. Recognizing Russia's key influ-<br>
ence in this situation, and in anticipation of President Bill Clinton's<br>
April 1996 visit to Russia, the United States approached Moscow in<br>
March to try to work out an overall deal on both Nagorno Karabakh<br>
and the oil pipeline issues, but the initiative ended inconclusively.<br>
<p>
	The Azerbaijani economy is poverty stricken and will likely re-<br>
main so until the flow of oil money begins some time in the future.<br>
Of the small and declining earnings from petroleum facilities left over<br>
from Soviet days, much is dedicated to rebuilding the shattered armed<br>
forces. There has been little structural reform or private entrepre-<br>
neurship, and basic needs are met largely through European Union<br>
(EU), Iranian, and Turkish assistance. Meanwhile, even though the<br>
November 1995 parliamentary elections that "confirmed" President<br>
Aliyev's regime were only questionably fair, there can be no doubt<br>
about his current authoritarian mastery of national politics. Unlike<br>
in Georgia and Armenia, no Russian frontier troops are present in<br>
Azerbaijan -- but it is still a member state of the CIS.<br>
<p>
	_Georgia_. Just as Soviet nationality policy on Nagorno-Karabakh<br>
created mutual Azeri and Armenian dependency on Moscow, its<br>
treatment of ethnic minorities in Georgia produced the same result<br>
vis-a-vis the regime in Tbilisi. A South Ossetian Autonomous Re-<br>
gion was set up in the early 1920s within Georgia, across the Cauca-<br>
sus mountains from the Federative Republic of North Ossetia-Ala-<br>
nia within the Russian Federation, where the great bulk of ethnic<br>
Ossetians live. This region's existence ensured constant friction<br>
within Georgia that could at any time require Soviet arbitration and<br>
thus allow Moscow's manipulation.<br>
<p>
	In the 1980s, a mountain highway tunnel was built between the<br>
two Ossetias, ostensibly for military reasons. However, by facilitating<br>
year round contacts and greater closeness among all Ossetians (in-<br>
cluding the 125,000 who then lived in Georgia proper, plus the 75,000<br>
in the autonomous region itself), the tunnel increased the opportu<br>
nities for Ossetian nationalist agitation in the south. When the ex-<br>
treme nationalist Zviad Gamsakhurdia came to power in 1990, his<br>
government responded to South Ossetian agitation for broader au-<br>
tonomy by abolishing the autonomous region altogether. In response,<br>
the South Ossetians proclaimed their independence from Georgia<br>
and received armed support in 1991 and 1992 from North Ossetia --<br>
through the mountain highway tunnel. Their insurgent regime has<br>
been in de facto control of the area since 1992, though Moscow has<br>
rejected its pleas for incorporation into the Russian Federation and<br>
has intermittently generated strong pressures for its return to Geor-<br>
gian jurisdiction -- so far without result. However, Georgian President<br>
Eduard Shevardnadze and South Ossetian leader Ludvig Chibirov<br>
met in August 1996 in Vladikavkaz and agreed to future talks on sta-<br>
tus problems and interrelationships.<br>
<p>
	Abkhazia is another region that threatens Georgian integrity. Lo-<br>
cated along the northwestern section of Georgia's Black Sea coast,<br>
the predominantly Christian Abkhaz -- a linguistically Caucasian<br>
ethnic group -- became an ever smaller minority in their own land<br>
during Soviet times; by 1989, the Abkhaz made up only 18 per cent<br>
of the region's 540,000 people. Through conscious Soviet resettle<br>
ment policies in the 1940s and 1950s, which Tbilisi supported, the<br>
Georgian share of the population grew to 46 per cent, while Russian<br>
and Armenian communities accounted for most of the remaining 36<br>
per cent. Thus, even though Abkhazia had the status of an au-<br>
tonomous republic within Georgia, many in the Abkhaz minority felt<br>
that they had little cultural or political independence from Tbilisi's<br>
decrees_except when Moscow could be induced to intervene.<br>
<p>
	Gamsakhurdia's heavy-handed nationalistic approach in Georgia<br>
sharpened tensions from 1989 on and gave new legitimacy to a pre-<br>
viously semiquiescent Abkhaz nationalist movement, whose leaders<br>
were fighting for enhanced Abkhaz statutory privileges and eventual<br>
independence from Georgia. In 1991, a political crisis was averted by<br>
Tbilisi's concessions to the militant Abkhaz on election arrangements<br>
for the territory's legislature. Tensions again came to a head in Au-<br>
gust 1992, when Georgian troops entered the territory to fight rebels<br>
in Georgia's own civil war. Almost 14 months of battles ensued be<br>
tween intermittent ceasefires. In September 1993, Abkhaz fighters<br>
supplied largely with equipment and manpower from within Russia<br>
itself -- much of it from government sources but some from north<br>
Caucasian mercenaries_bloodily drove out Georgian forces, along<br>
with 230,000 Georgian refugees.<br>
<p>
	The 1992-93 civil war in Georgia was the result of Gamsakhur-<br>
dia's January 1992 ouster from Tbilisi by a Moscow-backed faction,<br>
which two months later invited former Soviet foreign minister (and<br>
former Georgian Communist Party chief) Shevardnadze to take<br>
power. Gamsakhurdia and his followers took over a western zone of<br>
Georgia (Mingrelia) bordering Abkhazia. Then, when Georgia's army<br>
collapsed in Abkhazia in September 1993 (as a result of major Russ-<br>
ian assistance to the Abkhaz), Gamsakhurdia's forces began a drive<br>
eastward from Mingrelia into Georgia's heartland. Shevardnadze was<br>
forced to turn to Moscow for help. Moscow responded favorably but,<br>
in return, required that Georgia become a member of the CIS -- some-<br>
thing that Moscow (but almost no Georgians) had long wanted.<br>
Once Russia intervened, Gamsakhurdia's men began a rapid retreat,<br>
and he almost certainly committed suicide in Chechnya around<br>
Christmas 1993.<br>
<p>
	The net effect of these 1993 events was to reinvigorate Russia's<br>
dominant influence in Georgia. Russia has remained the arbiter of<br>
the Abkhaz and South Ossetian insurrections, but it has no longer<br>
needed those issues as levers to pressure Shevardnadze. In mid-1995,<br>
Russia announced its full political support for the reintegration of the<br>
two secessionist regimes into Georgia with self-rule status. Although<br>
the 1995 initiative fell apart after Russia failed to exert real muscle<br>
to meet its proclaimed goal, Shevardnadze had no option but to stick<br>
with Moscow. As a result, Russia can use Georgia as a point of lever-<br>
age to exert influence over the entire Transcaucasus. Through Geor-<br>
gia's port of Batumi, oil and other supplies could be delivered to Ar-<br>
menia. And, via Armenia and direct Russian economic and transport<br>
levers, pressure could be kept on Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
	In this situation, Moscow was able to limit severely Georgia's<br>
room for geopolitical maneuver and to gain predominant influence<br>
over Georgia's security organs. Russia began slowly to recreate a mod-<br>
est Georgian army from the ground up and, in the process, placed<br>
many Russian (formerly Soviet) officers with Georgian ethnic con-<br>
nections into top positions. Similarly intimate links were reinforced<br>
between the two state security (intelligence) establishments. Russia<br>
and Georgia also signed the treaty, mentioned earlier, that legalized<br>
the presence of some 15,000 Russian troops on Georgian soil and ap-<br>
proved an agreement that grants Russian frontier troops lengthy con-<br>
trol over Georgia's border with Turkey and along the Black Sea.<br>
Moreover, Georgia's overall foreign policy orientation was coordi-<br>
nated at periodic CIS summits.<br>
<p>
	Behind the "protection" of these Russian security arrangements,<br>
Shevardnadze was free to restore Georgia as a functioning state and<br>
society. Moscow provided modest amounts of economic assistance<br>
and facilitated the reestablishment of select Soviet-era economic<br>
links between the two countries. Furthermore, Russia did not object<br>
to a host of bilateral economic agreements that Georgia signed with<br>
Western countries and international organizations, including the<br>
World Bank, the International Monetary Fund, the European Bank<br>
for Reconstruction and Development, the U.N. Development Pro<br>
gram, and the EU. Consequently, considerable economic stabiliza-<br>
tion has taken hold, but Georgia is still far from experiencing a full<br>
economic revival. Shevardnadze has tried to encourage private en-<br>
trepreneurship, but he recognizes that this will occur on a significant<br>
scale only when the economy has been substantially freed from the<br>
tight grip of criminal elements and a corrupt officialdom.<br>
<p>
	Shevardnadze has shown great political skill in weakening his op-<br>
ponents. By mid-1995, he had capitalized on gross errors by various<br>
mafia leaders to break up their groups and had begun to establish a<br>
hierarchy of regional officials loyal to him. This stronger position en-<br>
abled him in August 1995 to induce more than two-thirds of the once<br>
hopelessly fractious Parliament into a "give and take" process of ne-<br>
gotiating a new constitution. The approved charter establishes a pow-<br>
erful presidency; a U.S.-style separation of legislative, executive, and<br>
judicial powers; a full bill of rights; and a constitutional court. On<br>
November 5, 1995, Shevardnadze received almost three-quarters of<br>
the votes in the presidential election, while his parliamentary allies,<br>
under voting arrangements judged fair and honest, gained a func-<br>
tional majority in a legislature that had been reduced to only three<br>
parties. It is fair to say that Shevardnadze's commitment to the even-<br>
tual building of a democratic society in Georgia stands in substantial<br>
contrast with the authoritarian political propensities of the other two<br>
Transcaucasian regimes, especially the one in Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
INTERNATIONAL INVOLVEMENT<br>
<p>
Although the major powers of Europe, Asia, and North Amer-<br>
ica are intensely interested in the fate of the former Soviet<br>
Union as a whole --and of Russia and Ukraine in particular --<br>
the Transcaucasus does not draw much foreign policy focus, even<br>
though the U.N. and the OSCE are fitfully involved there. Indeed, the<br>
Transcaucasus has been largely ignored by the West for the last 300<br>
years, except for brief spurts of attention during the Crimean War<br>
(1853-56) and during the First and Second World Wars. Even then,<br>
the Transcaucasus was viewed only in the context of much broader in-<br>
ternational competition involving the fates of the Balkans, Iran,<br>
Turkey, and the Middle East, as well as of the British-Russian rivalry<br>
in South-Central Asia. Today, developments in the Transcaucasus--<br>
though of considerable strategic and psychological importance to Rus-<br>
sia, Turkey, Iran, and perhaps Ukraine -- are hardly likely to elicit<br>
much activism from distant powers that can barely bring themselves<br>
to address the instabilities of the former Yugoslavia and North Korea.<br>
<p>
	This semi-indifference is in marked contrast with Russia's giant<br>
role in the Transcaucasus. The rest of the world has not yet sought<br>
any effective counterweight but has merely issued modest advisories<br>
and admonitions on how to end bloodshed and reinforce the inde-<br>
pendence of the three new states. Implicit in this approach is a mod-<br>
icum of Western concern over preventing either the de facto or the<br>
de jure reincorporation of the Transcaucasus into Russia, lest this be<br>
the start of an effort to reconstitute the USSR as a whole in some non-<br>
Soviet guise.<br>
<p>
	Russia's actual motivations on future geopolitical arrangements<br>
are not yet clear. Some politicians accept the demise of the USSR;<br>
others seek that empire's resurrection in a new form. Foreign Minis-<br>
ter Yevgeny Primakov urges greater Russian leadership in the other<br>
new republics, without indicating his eventual aims. In any case, the<br>
sheer mechanics of reinventing the USSR would be daunting, given<br>
the international climate, Russia's weakness, and the formal institu-<br>
tionalization of the new states. Besides, an interim collaborative<br>
mechanism -- the CIS -- is already available to Moscow, and it requires<br>
no immediate definition of its ultimate shape.<br>
<p>
	_The CIS_. The conventional Western wisdom has been that the<br>
CIS is an ineffectual mechanism devised in haste in December 1991<br>
to soften the impact of the Soviet collapse. This view is true enough<br>
historically, but it does not take into account that the Russian gov-<br>
ernment has since made a major effort to breathe substance into the<br>
organization. Thus, the CIS now has a formal institutional framework<br>
that allows Moscow to seek to consolidate its regional preeminence<br>
without challenging accepted international legal norms.<br>
<p>
	All of the non-Baltic former republics are now members of the<br>
CIS, albeit with varying degrees of enthusiasm. Concurrently, Moscow<br>
maintains a network of special contacts with its former republics. For-<br>
mally, there are two or three CIS summit sessions each year at which<br>
regional themes are discussed and backroom deals are negotiated.<br>
Similar assemblages occur regularly at ministerial levels in every field<br>
of policy and administration. At these meetings, set agendas are ad-<br>
dressed, and many bilateral and multilateral accords are signed --<br>
even though implementation is spotty, and some Russian initiatives,<br>
such as a mutual security treaty, have not yet gained approval. She-<br>
vardnadze himself used the January 1996 summit to gain overall CIS<br>
backing for a reassertion of Georgian authority over the two seces-<br>
sionist regions and for a partial blockade around Abkhazia, though<br>
realization of these efforts will again depend on Moscow's own fol-<br>
low-through (which has been erratic).<br>
<p>
	Cynical observers, who note the lack of formal institutional ma-<br>
chinery for enforcement, the weakness of administrative implemen-<br>
tation, and the partial marginalization of the weak CIS coordinating<br>
secretariat, doubt that the CIS will permit Moscow to assert effective<br>
control over the former republics. Yet this view fails to grasp the dy-<br>
namics of the growing Russian governmental commitment to, and ac-<br>
tivism in, the CIS. A large Ministry for Cooperation with the States<br>
Participating in the CIS is heavily involved with all the ex-union re-<br>
publics and coordinates nondiplomatic interministerial contacts<br>
among them, as well as between the former republics and the de-<br>
centralized entities of the Russian Federation, such as (autonomous)<br>
republics and oblasts (large regions). The Ministry of Foreign Affairs<br>
has active new divisions that radiate outward to the newly indepen-<br>
dent states and that generally oversee bilateral commissions dealing<br>
with those states. Defense Ministry ties are also significant to most<br>
CIS mernbers. A ministry for Nationalities and Regional Affairs is sup-<br>
posed to operate only within the Russian Federation but, in fact, is<br>
active as well in addressing ethnic questions in the other new re-<br>
publics (the "near abroad"). The presidential staff attempts overall<br>
coordination of these efforts, but the presidency's clout is reduced by<br>
its own inefficiencies and by Yeltsin's many distractions, as well as by<br>
the absence of a national political consensus on foreign and domes-<br>
tic policy options.<br>
<p>
	In this light, the long term results of Russia's institutional thrusts,<br>
both unilaterally and through the CIS, toward the former Soviet re-<br>
publics remain uncertain. Nonetheless, the potential for Moscow's<br>
leverage is clear: If Russia recovers its power and wishes to pursue<br>
hegemonic aspirations, it may do so.<br>
<p>
	_The United Nations_. Since the U.N. has not been a key organi-<br>
zation for dealing with most consequences of the USSR's collapse, it<br>
has also shied away from playing a conspicuous geopolitical role in<br>
the Transcaucasus (although the Security Council has undertaken<br>
periodic discussions of trouble spots and has given its blessing to the<br>
OSCE'S involvement). The only instance of direct U.N. activity has<br>
been in Abkhazia, where the U.N. deployed a modest observer mis-<br>
sion early in 1993 when the war between the Georgians and the Abk-<br>
haz separatists was still undecided. Following Georgia's defeat, an ef-<br>
fort was made to expand the mission into a peacekeeping force, but<br>
member nations failed to agree on such a U.N. mandate. After Rus-<br>
sia established its own force in June 1994, the U.N. observer mission<br>
was enlarged to become a military group of 136 officers charged with<br>
monitoring the situation and observing Russian peacekeeping activ-<br>
ities. An agreement brokered by Russia in April 1994 between Geor-<br>
gians and Abkhaz had already provided for U.N. sponsorship of in-<br>
ternational negotiations among the parties to reach a peaceful<br>
settlement, and those talks began in August 1994 and continued into<br>
1996. The Abkhaz regime has insisted upon both its own sovereignty<br>
and its coequal international status with Georgia, however, and this<br>
point has prevented any significant progress. This impasse makes<br>
continued reauthorizations of the U.N. military observer mission in<br>
Abkhazia uncertain, but threats by Georgian militants to resort again<br>
to the use of armed force are not very credible.<br>
<p>
	All parties are aware that, in the case of Abkhazia, as in all other<br>
Transcaucasian disputes, the real determinant of peace (other than<br>
the outcome of a possible renewal of hostilities) will be the degree<br>
and nature of Moscow's policy intervention. Only Moscow possesses<br>
the means to generate real pressures on the combatants. As events in<br>
1995 showed, though, even Moscow's pressure will be ineffectual un-<br>
less it is constant, coherent, and intense enough to convince all sides<br>
of Russia's determination to impose a solution. To date, Moscow has<br>
not given believable evidence of its level of commitment to early res-<br>
olution in any of the three Transcaucasian battle zones (Abkhazia,<br>
South Ossetia, and Nagorno Karabakh); it has only probed with half<br>
measures, which, as internal Russian divisions and the course of the<br>
war in Chechnya imply, may be all that Moscow is currently capable<br>
of contributing. Thus, all secessions remain unresolved, and cynical<br>
observers will maintain that this confusion coincidentally serves Rus-<br>
sia by increasing the dependence of all other players on Moscow.<br>
<p>
	_The OSCE_. The OSCE is still feeling its way as an active regional<br>
security organization in Europe that has as members all European<br>
states, all former Soviet republics, the United States, and Canada.<br>
Nonetheless, through decisions in its Permanent Council in Vienna,<br>
diplomatic activity by its member states, and its two field missions for<br>
Georgia and Nagorno Karabakh (both of which are headquartered<br>
in Tbilisi), the OSCE has had an active role in seeking to mediate con-<br>
flicts in the Transcaucasus.<br>
<p>
                 &lt;&lt;Georgia's Shevardnadze has shown great<br>
                   political skill in weakening his opponents.&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
	The OSCE mission has been entrenched in Georgia since Decem-<br>
ber 1992. Its periodically renewed and general mandate calls for the<br>
promotion of human rights, democratization, and an end to the two<br>
secessionist regimes. Through members who are military officers, it<br>
also monitors the Russian led peacekeeping operation in South Os-<br>
setia. It has excellent access to all Georgian governmental and par-<br>
liamentary institutions from the chief of state on down, close links<br>
with the Russian embassy, and broad relations with the rest of the<br>
diplomatic corps. It consults with all major political groups, the me-<br>
dia, and academia, and it has significant grassroots links. OSCE mem-<br>
bers travel almost daily to the secessionist area of South Ossetia and<br>
monthly to Abkhazia. In both places, mission members have estab-<br>
lished repeated contacts with leading figures and keep in touch with<br>
the influential authorities of the Federative Republic of North Osse-<br>
tia-Alania within Russia.<br>
<p>
	The chief of mission (a position that has been held of late by a<br>
succession of very able German ambassadors) regularly exercises his<br>
wide latitude for initiatives under the mandate. Besides his work in<br>
Georgia, he travels regularly to Moscow for consultations and is a<br>
member of the four party Joint Control Commission for South Os-<br>
setia. The OSCE also participates in the already noted sporadic,<br>
United Nations-led, international negotiating sessions regarding the<br>
Abkhazian conundrum.<br>
<p>
	All of the foregoing involvements have given the mission con-<br>
siderable scope for imaginative approaches to the myriad issues in-<br>
volving Georgia. Certainly it has facilitated contacts among the dis-<br>
putants in South Ossetia and put human rights abuses in Abkhazia<br>
on the international agenda. The mission has also become an ac-<br>
cepted participant in all relevant bilateral and multilateral diplomatic<br>
efforts, though Russia remains the only player able to alter the con-<br>
text and thrust of the negotiations. The mission can be useful in a<br>
carefully delineated role, but it is hardly independently decisive,<br>
since, barring maximum Russian pressure, the secessionist regimes<br>
have no inclination to self destruct by agreeing to subordinate them<br>
selves to Georgian sovereignty.<br>
<p>
	The OSCE mission on Nagorno-Karabakh has yet to find a firm<br>
role in addressing that conflict, because the main action continues<br>
to revolve around multilateral diplomacy at OSCE headquarters in Vi<br>
enna and in major capitals, rather than on the ground in Armenia<br>
and Azerbaijan. Still, the mission has been able to improve contacts<br>
with ofhcials of the three regimes involved (Azerbaijan, Armenia,<br>
and Armenian insurgents in Nagorno-Karabakh).<br>
<p>
TRANSCAUCASIAN FUTURES<br>
<p>
As long as Russia maintains sufficient internal cohesion, it will<br>
be able to dominate the Transcaucasus politically and militar-<br>
ily. The three Transcaucasian states will probably preserve<br>
their formal sovereignty, develop a panoply of domestic policies, and<br>
carry on a broad range of international relationships, with one another<br>
and with the West. However, a Shevardnadze initiative on February<br>
28, 1996, to go further by forging closer collaboration among the three<br>
and, collectively, with neighboring Iran, Russia, and Turkey, is now<br>
quiescent in the face of local antagonisms, the great weight of Russia,<br>
and the lack of any counterweight from currently weak Iran and<br>
Turkey. Yet, on June 3, 1996, Yeltsin was able to convene in the Russ-<br>
ian city of Kislovodsk the three Transcaucasian chiefs of state and the<br>
heads of all (north) Caucasian political entities within the Russian<br>
Federation (without the participation of Iran and Turkey) to empha-<br>
size implicitly Russia's de facto hegemony and, explicitly, its large<br>
"peacekeeping role." They will not form a collaborative entity for re-<br>
gional selfSassertion, however, nor do they have the potential indi-<br>
vidually to resist Russia's de facto hegemony, which is exercised bilat-<br>
erally and through the CIS.<br>
<p>
	Whereas Georgian leaders in 1992 were saying bravely to foreign<br>
diplomats that they were willing to cooperate with Moscow on the<br>
basis of mutual respect to realize reasonable and shared objectives,<br>
their current line is quite different. Now they accept that their coun-<br>
try is largely subject to Russian geopolitical decisions. They merely<br>
hope that wise Russian leadership will recognize that Moscow's long<br>
run interests will be better served by a "loyal" Georgia that has been<br>
treated respectfully than by an embittered Georgia that has been<br>
forced to kowtow to Russian demands.<br>
<p>
	Armenia is in the same situation, though perhaps more willingly<br>
and enthusiastically than Georgia. This attitude stems from Arme-<br>
nia's historical hope for Christian Russia's protective embrace and<br>
from its need to overcome its partial isolation in a region of Muslim<br>
states. Moreover, as a country with military problems, it needs the<br>
backing of the large Russian armed forces (however disrupted the lat-<br>
ter may now be).<br>
<p>
	Azerbaijan seems not yet to have reached this conclusion about<br>
links to Russia, perhaps because it is still exploring the benefits of<br>
ties with Iran and Turkey. But Azerbaijan will very likely end up in a<br>
position similar to its neighbors because it is too weak by itself to re-<br>
sist Russian economic and commercial leverage (especially on petro-<br>
leum development). It cannot afford to depend on Iran, which has<br>
its own hegemonic aspirations regarding Azeris; and Turkey, though<br>
politically supportive, is not powerful enough to be decisive.<br>
<p>
	The conclusion that there are no local or external forces able to<br>
galvanize Transcaucasian stability, self-assertiveness, and collabora-<br>
tion flows from the geopolitical stance taken by the major Western<br>
powers. While they may have their own preferences for the region's<br>
evolution, Western states have not publicly identified any vital in<br>
terests there. Hence, no state has felt strongly enough about this mat-<br>
ter to make it an issue in its own relations with Moscow as part of an<br>
effort to keep Moscow from reestablishing its sphere of influence in<br>
the Transcaucasus. Indeed, judging by the West's conciliatory and<br>
compromising approach to Moscow in 1995 regarding an Azeri deal<br>
that would bring oil from the Caspian Sea area via a pipeline through<br>
Russia, the West seems to be accepting such a Russian sphere. Thus,<br>
given the lack of indigenous strength and the West's vacillation, the<br>
future of the Transcaucasus will depend essentially on which politi-<br>
cians become Russia's leaders in the next years and on which poli-<br>
cies they adopt toward the "near and far abroad."<br>
<p>
	A relatively hegemonic Russian approach to the Transcaucasus<br>
need not be interpreted in the West as the harbinger of a confronta-<br>
tional external policy in Moscow toward the West or of a desire to<br>
reconstitute the USSR in a new guise. There is simply too much his-<br>
torical baggage in the Transcaucasus for Moscow to refrain from vig-<br>
orous involvement in the region. In Russia's mindset, instability in<br>
the Transcaucasus, combined with troubles in its own Caucasus, im-<br>
pels the Kremlin to be particularly assertive along the former USSR'S<br>
borders with Iran and Turkey. The U.N. and the OSCE can have use<br>
ful but only limited functions in a region where a local big power<br>
moves instinctively to predominate.<br>
<p>
	America has tried, along with the EU, to implement a policy that<br>
would increase the stability of each regime in the Transcaucasus and<br>
of the region as a whole, without challenging Russia's evident para-<br>
mountcy and without undertaking policy commitments of its own.<br>
This policy seems eminently correct in the interim. What the United<br>
States should do if Moscow ever asserted a much more intensive<br>
sphere of influence would have to be determined on the basis of the<br>
overall U.S. and European stakes in the relationship with Moscow<br>
rather than strictly on the merits of the particular situation in the<br>
Transcaucasus. The realities of international politics may well mean<br>
that the three Transcaucasian states never attain the "justice" that<br>
their peoples objectively deserve, which is just the fate that has be<br>
fallen Kurds, Bosnians, and many other nationalities.<br>
<p>
-----------------------------------+---------------------------------------<br>
David Davidian dbd@urartu.sdpa.org | "It is necessary that not one Armenian<br>
Center for Regional Studies        | survive this annihilation." Dr. Nazim Bey,<br>
<i>                                   | Secretary, Young Turk Party. From: _Turk </i><br>
<i>                                   | inkilabinin ic yuzu_, Mevlanzade Rifat</i><br>
