<title>Groong Network: Items from  Itar-Tass domestic news digest of January 3: 4.</title>
<h1>Items from  Itar-Tass domestic news digest of January 3: 4.</h1>
Horizon/Giro Manoyan (<i>72263.1572@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 3 Jan 97 12:26:14 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#268">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#268">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#268">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#268">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0269.html">arpi@aaainc.org: "Items from  Itar-Tass domestic news digest of January 3: 4."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0267.html">Horizon/Giro Manoyan: "Drift to Dictatorship Clouds Armenia's Happiness"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
		 Itar-Tass domestic news digest of January 3: 4.<br>
<p>
OTC  1/3/97 11:17 AM  <br>
<p>
         BAKU, January 3 (Itar-Tass) - The filling of an export oil pipeline,<br>
intended for the pumping of oil from Baku to Novorossiisk, began on the  first<br>
days of the new year in the capital of Azerbaijan, Sayad Ibragimov,  First Vice<br>
President of the State Oil Company of Azerbaijan (SOCAR),  told Tass today. <br>
   According to Ibragimov, ten days are given to conducting that important<br>
operation, which will precede the beginning of the transportation of  Azeri oil<br>
to the world market across the Russian territory. In order to  create the needed<br>
pressure in the oil pipeline at the 255-kilometre-long  section connecting Baku<br>
and the Azeri border with Daghestan (a total  length of the pipeline is 1,411<br>
kilometres), it is necessary to pump  into it 60,000 to 70,000 tonnes of oil,<br>
Ibragimov said. Oil  transportation, planned for February and March, will amount<br>
to 30,000  and 40,000 tonnes respectively. An order for that has already been<br>
received by the Transneft company of Russia. It will handle the  transportation<br>
of Azeri oil to Novorossiisk, where it will be loaded to  tankers and exported<br>
to other countries. <br>
   The Azeri International Operation Company (AIOC) developing the Caspian<br>
off-shore oil fields is also satisfied with the pace of putting into  operation<br>
of the Baku-Novorossiisk export oil pipeline, intended mostly  for the<br>
transportation of early oil from the Caspian oil fields of  Azerbaijan. It is<br>
planned to start oil production at those oil fields  late in August, this year.<br>
Its president Terry Adams gave an interview  to the Zerkalo newspaper on the New<br>
Year eve, in which he said that he  was very much pleased with the results,<br>
achieved so quickly after the  signing of a contract on the development of three<br>
Azeri oil fields on  September 20, 1994. Foreign shareholders of AIOC, including<br>
the Russian  LUKoil company, are proud of the results achieved. According to<br>
Adams,  the speeding up of the implementation of the programme of early oil<br>
production resulted in the increase of the company's allocations for  that<br>
purpose from 600 million to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, which makes  about one<br>
sixth of total investments in the project. <br>
   rom/ezh <br>
    Copyright 1997   <br>
<p>
   V L A D I K A V K A Z -- The Transcaucasian highway is being cleared of<br>
snow. All transit passengers have been evacuated by helicopter to  Vladikavkaz,<br>
North Ossetian Minister for Emergency Situations Nikolai  Makoyev told<br>
Itar-Tass. Several dozens of trucks remain on the highway.  The truck drivers<br>
refused to leave, and were given warn clothing, food  and medicines. The North<br>
Ossetian Ministry for Emergency Situations is  closely watching developments on<br>
the highway, which connects the  Caucasus with southern Russia. A week ago<br>
snowslides blocked the highway  in several places and locked in over 300 transit<br>
passengers, who were  heading for Vladikavkaz and Transcaucasia, and 120 buses,<br>
cars and  trucks near the Rokskiy tunnel. <br>
   yur/ <br>
    Copyright 1997<br>
