<p>
<p>
NEWS RELEASE, December 23, 1996<br>
<p>
VICTIMS OF ARMENIAN GOVERNMENT'S<br>
HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES TO PURSUE DOMESTIC REMEDIES<br>
<p>
EMERGENCY OBJECTIVES ACHIEVED, CASE AGAINST<br>
PRESIDENTIAL ADVISER LIBARIDIAN TO BE REMOVED<br>
<i>&gt;FROM U.S. COURTS TO ARMENIA</i><br>
<p>
INTERNATIONAL HUMAN RIGHTS GROUPS TO MAINTAIN<br>
VIGILANT WATCH ON GOVERNMENT'S CONDUCT<br>
<p>
	On December 19, 1996, the plaintiffs in the class-action suit against <br>
the Republic of Armenia's Senior Presidential Adviser Gerard Libaridian sought <br>
to withdraw their case from the United States federal district court in order <br>
to attempt to pursue their cases in Armenian courts.  The suit charged <br>
Libaridian with legal responsibility for his role in the violent government <br>
crackdown against ordinary citizens and various members of opposition <br>
political parties and their families and neighbors, following the September <br>
21, 1996 presidential election in Armenia, which was judged by election <br>
observers to be neither fair nor free.  The plaintiffs sought remedy for the <br>
injuries they suffered during the crackdown, when government forces rounded up <br>
more than 175 men and women, including members of the National Assembly, <br>
subjected them to beatings, torture and interrogation, and kept them captive <br>
in jails and isolation wards around the country for extended periods of time.  <br>
Many were held for over two weeks and suffered severe injuries requiring <br>
hospitalization.  During their imprisonment, they had no contact with their <br>
families, and were not allowed access to counsel.  At the same time, the <br>
government attacked a number of opposition political party offices, destroying <br>
or confiscating all of the parties' records, equipment and property.  <br>
<p>
	With little hope for remedy in Armenia, victims of these human rights <br>
violations, with the assistance of the Center for Economic and Social Rights <br>
(CESR), a non-profit human rights group based in New York, sought to pursue <br>
their case in the United States against Libaridian, alleged in the complaint <br>
to be one of the principal architects of the crackdown, for his violations <br>
under international law. The case attracted a great deal of media attention <br>
both in Armenia and internationally.<br>
<p>
	Since the suit was filed on October 5, 1996, most of those detained <br>
have been released, and only 17 persons remain in custody.  In addition, the <br>
government has allowed two of the political parties that were closed down by <br>
the government, the National Democratic Union and the National Union for <br>
Self-Determination, to reopen their offices.  <br>
<p>
	In these circumstances, and as an expression of hope and good faith in <br>
the widely discredited Armenian courts, several of the victims, including the <br>
named plaintiffs in the U.S. action, decided to withdraw their case in the <br>
United States in favor of initiating proceedings in Armenia against those <br>
government officials responsible for the violations of their human rights.  <br>
<p>
	Sarah Leah Whitson, CESR's general counsel and an adviser on the case, <br>
comments:  "The plaintiffs in this case are exceedingly brave, and have a <br>
sincere hope that they can move their country back on a democratic path. They <br>
are taking an enormous risk by choosing to pursue their cases in Armenian <br>
courts, where they have virtually no assurance that they will receive a fair <br>
trial.  By bringing their cases in Armenia, they are giving the courts there <br>
another opportunity for redemption as an independent judicial body committed <br>
to protecting the rights of Armenia's citizens and to seeing that justice is <br>
done."<br>
<p>
	"We will stand behind the plaintiffs in this case with every resource <br>
at our disposal.  We will continue to provide them with legal assistance on <br>
questions of international law and to coordinate our efforts with local human <br>
rights groups in Armenia.  We also pledge to follow the proceedings closely, <br>
and immediately inform the international community of any attempts by the <br>
government to deny these people a fair procedure for vindicating their rights. <br>
 We hope that the Armenian government acts wisely this time to show the <br>
international community that it can in fact respect the rules of democracy and <br>
freedom."<br>
<p>
	Roger Normand, executive director of CESR, states: "We believe that <br>
several of the case's primary objectives have been achieved.  This case has <br>
sent a strong message to the government of Armenia that those responsible for <br>
violating international law and abusing the rights of other citizens can be <br>
held personally liable and brought to justice even in courts outside their <br>
country.  The international community is watching the Armenian government very <br>
closely; we know the government knows that.  Most of the opposition members <br>
who were detained in violation of international law have been released, and <br>
the headquarters of the NDU and NSDU have been permitted to reopen.  We want <br>
to encourage that sort of progress."<br>
<p>
	Adds Ms. Whitson, "The courageous men and women who brought this suit <br>
in the United States have set an example to the people in Armenia in seeking <br>
to speak out and hold their government accountable.  We want the people of <br>
Armenia to know that human rights groups and ordinary people all around the <br>
world will support their struggle to build a democratic state in Armenia."<br>
<p>
	For further information, please contact the following:<br>
<p>
	Sarah Leah Whitson, Esq. (212) 225-2794, fax (212) 225-3999, e-mail <br>
swhitson@cgsh.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
