GOOD EVENING,<br>
ARMEPRESS NEWS AGENCY OFFERS YOU THE FIRST ISSUE OF THE<br>
JANUARY 3, 1997, NEWS BULLETIN.<br>
RESPONSIBLE FOR THE ISSUE - MARINE GEVORKIAN<br>
<p>
                A R M E N P R E S S   B U L L E T I N<br>
<p>
<p>
                ARMENIAN PRESIDENT'S NEW YEAR MESSAGE<br>
<p>
"1997 TO BE A YEAR OF IMPROVEMENTS IN ECONOMIC LIFE, PARTIAL<br>
RELIEF OF SOCIAL SITUATION, ESTABLISHMENT OF ORDER AND<br>
LEGALITY"<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
On this festive occasion, I would like to make several necessary<br>
comments that may help to correctly perceive the reality and<br>
contribute to the realization of the ideas aimed to improve the<br>
reality. Lately, attempts are being made to create a frame of mind<br>
that the Presidential elections resulted in a split in our nation. In<br>
case of judging so, we should refuse from democracy, since the<br>
democratic states are to hold presidential and parliamentary elections<br>
each four-five years to find out the people's priorities. In case of<br>
judging so, we should also consider all the democratic states as<br>
split since during the elections the votes are divided between<br>
40-60 percents. So we should feel very confident that during the<br>
elections the votes of the people are approximately divided equally.<br>
For democratic states it is both natural and necessary, and by no<br>
means it can mean a split of the nation. The elections pass away,<br>
passions calm down, and the nation goes back to its ordinary way of<br>
life till the next elections, and so on.<br>
On the occasion of New Year, I do not find it needless to repeat my<br>
decisive statement on realizing all the programs aimed to improve<br>
the moral and legal atmosphere of the state, the policy of<br>
appointing officials, to launch a campaign against the corruption and<br>
administrative illegalities, to establish discipline in taxation.<br>
The new Government begins its activity by stimulating production, by<br>
involving foreign investments, and with serious intentions to develop the<br>
foreign trade. In this respect, I would like to tell you that in the<br>
first half of 1997, one or two international organizations crediting<br>
small and middle businesses, will start their activities here. We are<br>
also taking steps to provide also the big business with circulating<br>
assets.<br>
We look at the year 1997 as a year of improvements in the economic life<br>
of the Republic, a year of partial relief of the social situation of the<br>
population, and also a year of establishment of order and legality.<br>
If we also add the overcoming of the blockade, the necessity of<br>
opposing<br>
the international pressure on the issue of Artsakh, we may imagine<br>
what efforts will be required from the authorities, as well as from<br>
the people to provide the ordinary development of our country. As<br>
difficult it may seem, but I consider it a solvable problem, provided<br>
that we can ensure solidarity of our people and stability inside the<br>
country, for which I promise to put all my efforts.<br>
And now I want to express my best wishes to our people and wish them<br>
peace, happiness and prosperity.<br>
Happy New Year!<br>
<p>
         US FEDERAL JUDGE GRANTS REQUEST TO WITHDRAW LAWSUIT<br>
AGAINST LIBARIDIAN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, JANUARY 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
On December 20, 1996, United States District Judge Michael B. Mukasey<br>
of the Southern District Court of New York granted plaintiffs' motion<br>
to withdraw their complaint against Jirair Libaridian before the case<br>
could even be heard by the Judge. This brought to an abrupt end a<br>
lawsuit which was started against the Senior Advisor to President<br>
Levon Ter-Petrossian of Armenia last October with much noise and<br>
vindictiveness.<br>
In early October, Jennifer Green, plaintiffs' attorney of record,<br>
supported by two attorneys from the Center for Economic and Social<br>
Rights of New York, Sarah Leah Whitson and Michael Herman, had filed<br>
a<br>
civil action lawsuit in New York Federal Court, accusing Libaridian of<br>
"designing, planning, implementing and directing" a two-year terror<br>
campaign against the opposition in Armenia, culminating in alleged<br>
violations of human rights on September 25. The lawsuit, initiated on<br>
October 4, was launched with a full-scale media campaign, including but<br>
not limited to newspapers as well as the Internet, with vicious<br>
personal attacks on Libaridian.<br>
"The attorneys who brought the lawsuit had no choice but to withdraw<br>
the case; they must be quite embarrassed," said an expert close to the<br>
lawsuit. "The lawsuit was frivolous, had no merits, and had<br>
political and personal motivations, rather than any concern for human<br>
rights or democracy. Besides, it was done unprofessionally and in a<br>
manner that reflected viciousness and a political agenda," she added.<br>
The class action suit was initially brought in the name of Aramazd<br>
Zakarian, a citizen of Armenia and a member of Parliament. In<br>
November, Jean-Marie Atamian, an attorney with the prestigious<br>
international law firm of Mayer, Brown &amp; plant representing<br>
Libaridian, filed with the Court a memorandum of law asking the Court<br>
to dismiss the case on a number of jurisdictional and other grounds.<br>
The alleged acts of human rights violations were not deemed worthy of<br>
a response.<br>
Among the papers filed by Attorney Atamian in support of Libaridian's<br>
dismissal motion was an affidavit by Aramazd Zakarian, where Zakarian<br>
stated that he had never authorized the lawsuit. In his affidavit,<br>
Zakarian also expressed his outrage at the behavior of the attorneys<br>
in New York, for having proceeded with the lawsuit without his<br>
permission.<br>
Indeed, such irresponsible and unprofessional conduct by plaintiff's<br>
counsel continued unabated until they finally realized that they had<br>
no choice but to withdraw their meritless action. For example,<br>
Attorney Atamian and Attorney Green had been scheduled to appear<br>
before the Court on November 20 for the first time for a scheduling<br>
hearing. But Green failed to appear in Court without any notice to<br>
either the Court or opposing counsel. This outrageous behavior prompted<br>
the Court to issue an order which set a new hearing date on December 3<br>
and threatened to impose sanctions should plaintiff's attorney fail<br>
to appear a second time. Incredibly, Ms. Green again failed to appear<br>
before the Court on December 3. At the same time, rather than withdraw<br>
the case, Green and her associates proceeded to file an equally<br>
baseless "amended" lawsuit in the name of 13 new plaintiffs that<br>
included opposition figures Davit Vardanian, Shavarsh Kotcharian,<br>
Seyran Avakian, Filaret Berigian, Vova Hakhverdian, Gagik Mkrtchian,<br>
Karine Stepanian and others of Armenia.<br>
A new Court hearing was scheduled for December 23. However, Green<br>
and<br>
her associates once again failed to appear in Court. Instead, they<br>
filed papers to have their own case dismissed against Libaridian. One<br>
of the reasons given by Green was that at least some of the new<br>
plaintiffs in whose name the lawsuit now stood had refused to<br>
acknowledge the case and stated that they did not want their names<br>
associated with the case.<br>
The Judge immediately granted Green's request to withdraw the case,<br>
on December 20, 1996.<br>
Most observers consider the lawsuit a personal attack against<br>
Libaridian, who is a Diaspora Armenian and has held several key<br>
positions in the foreign policy area since he started working in<br>
Armenia in 1991 and has little to do with domestic politics. Some<br>
observers think the attack against Libaridian was part of the<br>
campaign launched internationally against President Ter-Petrossian to<br>
weaken Armenia's position before the OSCE Lisbon Summit. Libaridian<br>
has been one of the chief negotiators for Armenia in the<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh conflict and the personal representative of President<br>
Ter-Petrossian in the direct dialogue with Azerbaijan.<br>
Observers have also characterized the lawsuit as "frivolous," "lacking<br>
in substance," "abusive of the American legal system," and "a vicious<br>
attack that was seen as possible in the poisonous atmosphere created<br>
in the Diaspora against President Ter-Petrossian and his policies."<br>
Indeed, neither the original complaint nor the "amended" complaint<br>
contained a single factual allegation, much less any evidence, to<br>
support plaintiffs' irresponsible contention that Libaridian was in<br>
any way  involved in domestic affairs or in the alleged events.<br>
Observers have also noted that the pattern of behavior by the group<br>
backing the lawsuit is a form of manipulation of Armenian citizens,<br>
who are not entirely knowledgeable in the American legal system, by<br>
outsiders who misrepresented their actions in pursuit of personal and<br>
political gain.<br>
U.S. legal observers believe that Green and her associates have<br>
violated the legal code of conduct and are subject to Rule 11<br>
sanctions applicable in such cases where attorneys file a lawsuit<br>
without the clear and explicit consent of a plaintiff or plaintiffs<br>
whose names are listed in the lawsuit.<br>
Libaridian has refused to comment on the case. But an associate to the<br>
Senior Advisor believes that Libaridian does not hold any animosity<br>
against the citizens of Armenia, whom he believes were manipulated by<br>
forces outside Armenia. The associate also expressed doubts whether<br>
those who launched the vicious lawsuit against Libaridian were indeed<br>
concerned with democracy or human rights in Armenia or elsewhere.<br>
"Libaridian will probably not take any action against anyone," stated<br>
the associate, "he has more important things to do in life. But if<br>
these attorneys and those backing them have any civility or integrity<br>
they would issue a public apology to Libaridian for the disruption<br>
they have caused in his work, his personal life and the life of his<br>
family."<br>
<p>
        NEW YEAR GREETINGS OF CATHOLICOS OF ALL ARMENIANS<br>
<p>
  JANUARY 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
  On the occasion of New Year, Catholicos of All Armenians Garegin I<br>
<p>
  greeted all the heads of the Armenian Apostolic Sees: the Catholicos<br>
  of the Armenian Church in Cilicia, the Patriarchs of Jerusalem and<br>
  Istanbul, the heads of all the Dioceses in Armenia and abroad. He<br>
  called upon unification for encouraging and making fruitful the<br>
  Armenian Apostolic Church, the celebration of the 1700th anniversary<br>
  of which we have already started and will continue till 2001.<br>
  In his greetings the Catholicos expressed his best wishes to President  <br>
  of Armenia Levon Ter-Petrossian, to the three branches of authority:<br>
  the legislative, executive and judicial, to the Armenian army, the<br>
  people of Karabakh, the whole Armenian people.<br>
  The Catholicos said that this year, like any other year, we will<br>
  start with the behest of Jesus Christ's birthday. "Christ's name is<br>
  Emmanuel. Emmanuel means 'God stay with us,' let us stay with God,"<br>
  the Catholicos concluded.<br>
<p>
              CHANGES IN LAW ON EXCISE TAX<br>
<p>
   YEREVAN, JANUARY 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
   From January 1, 1997, the law on making changes in the law on<br>
   "Excise Tax" came into force. In an interview with an Armenpress<br>
   correspondent, First Deputy of the Chief of Tax Inspection Dadayan<br>
   said that according to the new law, tires and carpets are taken out<br>
   from the list of the goods to be taxed, they will be considered as<br>
   goods of necessity, besides, taxes on some goods are raised: wine<br>
   and vodka by 125%, sprawn by 200%, cigarette by 100%. The new<br>
   law states that for the goods imported to Armenia the object for<br>
   taxation is the importing cost of the good without the value added<br>
   taxes. According to Dadayan, because of the rise of excise tax on<br>
   wine and vodka, the costs of these products may temporarily go up.<br>
<p>
                     YEAR BEGAN WITHOUT SHOOTINGS<br>
<p>
    YEREVAN, JANUARY 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
    According to the press center of the Armenian Defense Ministry, on<br>
    the New Year night and during the next two days, there have not<br>
    been registered any violations of cease-fire on the Armenian-Azeri<br>
    border.<br>
<p>
                    ARMENIAN PRESIDENT SIGNED LAWS<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, JANUARY 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
     On December 30, 1996, Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrossian<br>
     signed laws passed by the Armenian National Assembly on<br>
     "ratifying the annual report on the state budget of the Republic<br>
     of Armenia for 1995," "program for 1995 about privatization and<br>
     denationalization of state enterprises and incomplete<br>
     constructions in the Republic of Armenia," "on making changes in<br>
     the decision of the National Assembly and in the 'program for<br>
     1996-97 about privatization and denationalization of state<br>
     enterprises and incomplete constructions in the Republic of<br>
     Armenia'."<br>
<p>
     YOU HAVE RECEIVED 6 MESSAGES.<br>
     THANK YOU FOR CHOOSING ARMENPRESS.<br>
     HAPPY NEW YEAR!<br>
