<title>Groong Network: VOA/Nagorno Karabakh</title>
<h1>VOA/Nagorno Karabakh</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 1 Jan 1997 15:41:00 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#255">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#255">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#255">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#255">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0256.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 1/2/97"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0254.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "!! IMPORTANT GROONG NOTE !!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DATE=12/31/96<br>
TYPE=YEAREND REPORT<br>
NUMBER=5-35350<br>
TITLE=96: NAGORNO-KARABAKH<br>
BYLINE=HASAN JAVADI<br>
DATELINE=WASHINGTON<br>
CONTENT=<br>
VOICED AT: <br>
<p>
INTRO:  THE CONFLICT IN NAGORNO-KARABAKH, ONE OF THE LONGEST AND <br>
BLOODIEST IN THE CAUCASUS, REMAINED UNRESOLVED IN I996.  THE <br>
ENCLAVE, POPULATED MOSTLY BY ETHNIC ARMENIANS, HAS BEEN FIGHTING <br>
FOR INDEPENDENCE FROM AZERBAIJAN SINCE 1988.  THOUGH A CEASEFIRE <br>
HAS BEEN IN EFFECT SINCE MAY 1994, NO POLITICAL SETTLEMENT IS IN <br>
SIGHT.  V-O-A'S HASAN JAVADI LOOKS INTO THE DISPUTE IN THE YEAR <br>
THAT JUST ENDED.<br>
<p>
TEXT:  ALTHOUGH THERE WAS  NO  BREAKTHROUGH IN THE <br>
NAGORNO-KARABAKH CONFLICT, THREE IMPORTANT EVENTS HAPPENED: <br>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS IN NAGORNO-KARABAKH, SOME RELAXATION IN <br>
U-S AID TO AZERBAIJAN AND MORE INVOLVEMENT BY EUROPEAN NATIONS TO<br>
RESOLVE THE CONFLICT.<br>
<p>
NAGORNO-KARABAKH'S DECISION TO HOLD PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS NEAR <br>
THE END OF 1996 (NOVEMBER 24) BROUGHT CRITICISM, NOT ONLY FROM  <br>
AZERBAIJAN, WHICH CONSIDERS THE ENCLAVE PART OF ITS TERRITORY, <br>
BUT ALSO FROM RUSSIA.  A STATEMENT ISSUED BY THE RUSSIAN FOREIGN <br>
MINISTRY SAID THAT THIS DECISION RAN COUNTER TO INTERNATIONAL <br>
EFFORTS TO SECURE A LASTING PEACE SETTLEMENT FOR THE REGION. <br>
HOWEVER, THE  ELECTIONS TOOK PLACE AS SCHEDULED, AND ROBERT <br>
KOCHARIAN WAS ELECTED PRESIDENT OF NAGORNO-KARABAKH.<br>
<p>
ROBERT BARYLSKI OF SOUTH FLORIDA UNIVERSITY, AN EXPERT ON THE <br>
CAUCASUS, SAYS BOTH SIDES IN THE CONFLICT HAVE OBLIGATIONS.  HE <br>
SAYS THAT WHILE THE STATE SHOULD RESPECT THE TERRITORIAL <br>
INTEGRITY AND HUMAN RIGHTS OF THE ETHNIC MINORITIES, MINORITIES <br>
HAVE CORRESPONDING OBLIGATIONS:<br>
<p>
                         BARYLSKI ACT// <br>
<p>
         ETHNIC MINORITIES ALSO HAVE RESPONSIBILITIES TO  RESPECT<br>
         THE TERRITORIAL INTEGRITY OF THE STATE WITHIN WHICH THEY<br>
         RESIDE. UNLESS THE MINORITIES RESPECT THE STATE IN WHICH<br>
         THEY LIVE, IT BECOMES IMPOSSIBLE IN THE GREATER CASPIAN <br>
         REGION TO EXPECT POLITICAL STABILITY IN ANY COUNTRY.<br>
<p>
                            END ACT//<br>
<p>
IN NOVEMBER, U-S DEPUTY SECRETARY OF STATE STROBE TALBOT AND <br>
SANDY BERGER, ANOTHER TOP OFFICIAL IN THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION,<br>
TRAVELED TO THE REGION TO TALK WITH SENIOR GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS, <br>
PARTICULARLY IN ARMENIA AND AZERBAIJAN, ABOUT REACHING PEACE IN <br>
THE REGION.  THEY ALSO DISCUSSED ISSUES RELATING TO DEVELOPING <br>
ENERGY SOURCES IN AND AROUND THE CASPIAN SEA.   <br>
<p>
 /// OPT /// ON JUNE 6, PRESIDENT BORIS YELTSIN HELD A REGIONAL <br>
SUMMIT IN THE SOUTHERN RUSSIAN CITY OF KOSLOVODSK.  IT WAS THE <br>
FIRST SUMMIT IN REGION SINCE THE BREAKUP OF THE SOVIET UNION.    <br>
YELTSIN AND HIS COUNTERPARTS FROM ARMENIA, AZERBAIJAN AND GEORGIA<br>
SIGNED A DECLARATION OF MUTUAL COOPERATION IN SETTLING  REGIONAL <br>
CONFLICTS. BUT THIS, LIKE MANY EARLIER ATTEMPTS, HAS NOT PRODUCED<br>
ANY RESULTS. /// END OPT.// <br>
<p>
SOME COUNTRIES IN THE REGION HAVE BENEFITTED MORE FROM OUTSIDE <br>
AID THAN OTHERS. THOUGH A U-S AID BILL FOR THE FORMER SOVIET <br>
STATES -- THE "FREEDOM SUPPORT ACT" -- ALLOWED AID TO ALL FORMER <br>
SOVIET STATES,  ONE OF ITS SECTIONS (907A) BANNED ALL <br>
GOVERNMENT-TO- GOVERNMENT AID TO AZERBAIJAN.  SINCE 1992, <br>
AZERBAIJAN HAS RECEIVED 92 MILLION DOLLARS THROUGH <br>
NON-GOVERNMENTAL ORGANIZATIONS,  WHILE THE GOVERNMENT OF ARMENIA <br>
HAS RECEIVED 625 MILLION DOLLARS OF DIRECT AID FROM THE UNITED <br>
STATES.<br>
<p>
IN JUNE 1996 A BILL WAS INTRODUCED IN THE U-S CONGRESS THAT  <br>
SOMEWHAT MODIFIED THE LANGUAGE OF THE 907 BILL, AND ALLOWED  THE <br>
USE OF AZERI GOVERNMENT FACILITIES TO STORE AID MATERIALS.  BUT <br>
THE BILL ALSO SPECIFIED THAT FOR EVERY SEVEN DOLLARS IN U-S AID <br>
TO AZERBAIJAN IN 1997, ONE DOLLAR MUST GO TO NAGORNO-KARABAKH. <br>
THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION CRITICIZED THIS PROPOSAL, SAYING THAT <br>
IT "INJECTED  DAMAGING POLITICAL LANGUAGE" INTO THE ATTEMPT TO <br>
ENHANCE THE U-S GOVERNMENT'S ABILITY TO PROVIDE HUMANITARIAN <br>
ASSISTANCE TO NEEDY INDIVIDUALS IN AZERBAIJAN.  ULTIMATELY THE <br>
BILL DID NOT PASS, BUT THE LANGUAGE OF THE ORIGINAL BILL WAS <br>
ALTERED. IT NOW GIVES THE U-S GOVERNMENT SLIGHTLY MORE LATITUDE <br>
IN ITS ABILITY TO DELIVER HUMANITARIAN AID.<br>
<p>
THE O-S-C-E (ORGANIZATION FOR SECURITY AND COOPERATION IN EUROPE)<br>
SENT SEVERAL DELEGATIONS TO ARMENIA AND AZERBAIJAN IN AN EFFORT <br>
TO WORK OUT A RESOLUTION OF THE CONFLICT. THESE EFFORTS <br>
CULMINATED IN THE O-S-C-E LISBON CONFERENCE.  BUT THE CONFERENCE <br>
DEADLOCKED IN A DISPUTE OVER THE WORDING OF ITS FINAL STATEMENT. <br>
<p>
ARMENIA REFUSED TO AGREE TO LANGUAGE STATING THAT <br>
NAGORNO-KARABAKH IS PART OF AZERBAIJAN.  AND PRESIDENT HEYDAR <br>
ALIYEV OF AZERBAIJAN THREATENED TO BLOCK THE WHOLE DOCUMENT IF <br>
THE LANGUAGE ABOUT NAGORNO-KARABAKH BEING PART OF AZERBAIJAN <br>
WASN'T INCLUDED IN A FINAL STATEMENT.  SINCE A SUMMIT DECLARATION<br>
HAD TO BE UNANIMOUSLY APPROVED, THE AZERBAIJAN PRESIDENT'S <br>
OPPOSITION MEANT THAT NO FINAL STATEMENT WOULD BE ISSUED.  AT THE<br>
LAST MINUTE, MR. ALIYEV AGREED TO A COMPROMISE THAT REMOVED THE <br>
LANGUAGE, BUT HAD IT INCLUDED IN A SEPARATE DOCUMENT. HE ALSO <br>
RECEIVED A STRONG STATEMENT OF SUPPORT FROM THE EUROPEAN UNION.<br>
<p>
IN RECENT YEARS AN ECONOMIC FACTOR HAS BEEN ADDED TO THE <br>
SITUATION. WESTERN OIL COMPANIES HAVE INVESTED MILLIONS OF <br>
DOLLARS IN THE OIL FIELDS OF AZERBAIJAN, AND THEY ARE KEENLY <br>
INTERESTED IN A SETTLEMENT OF THE CONFLICT SO THAT THEIR OIL <br>
PIPELINES TO THE BLACK SEA WILL BE SAFE FROM ATTACK. <br>
<p>
WHILE THERE ARE MANY FORCES INTERESTED IN BRINGING PIECE TO THE <br>
REGION, LITTLE HAS CHANGED IN THE LIVES OF MORE THAN  ONE   <br>
MILLION AZERI REFUGEES WHO HAVE FLED THE FIGHTING. THEY LIVE <br>
UNDER VERY DIFFICULT CONDITIONS IN BAKU AND IN VARIOUS CAMPS <br>
AROUND THE COUNTRY.<br>
<p>
NEB/HJ/KL<br>
<p>
31-Dec-96 5:10 PM EST (2210 UTC)<br>
NNNN<br>
<p>
Source: Voice of America<br>
.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
