<p>
<p>
            ------------- POLITICS ------------
<p>
CC RESOLUTION REGARDING ELECTION RESULTS ADOPTED BY
MAJORITY OF VOTES
     YEREVAN, November  26   (Noyan  Tapan). "This was the first
attempt  to  raise a  dispute   between  the  opposition and the
authorities  onto  a   civilized   level,"   Chairman   of   the
Constitutional Court (CC) of Armenia Gagik Haroutiunian  said at
a Monday news conference.
     Haroutiunian said that the Constitutional Court had  chosen
the right way -- a search for a final decision  through thorough
scritiny and analysis of all available documents.
     Haroutiunian  reported  that the  Constitutional Court  had
charged  lawenforcement    agencies   to   institute    criminal
proceedings in connection with a number of violations and  carry
out a probe into those cases. Haroutiunian was  astonished  over
the fact   that  a  person who  had   stolen a ballot box from a
polling station was sentenced to 10  days  in  jail.  Meanwhile,
according to him, that was a serious crime.
     CC Chairman said that the law on the  Constitutional  Court
of the Republic  of Armenia bans publicising the results of  the
discussions.  He only said  that  the resolution  was adopted by
the majority of votes. Constitutional Court  Chairman noted that
under  the  legislation in  effect, protocols of closed  meeting
were immediately sealed and sent to  state  archives.  "Pethaps,
in some years they will be accessible,  and everybody will  have
an opportunity to know what had happened," he said.
     Haroutiunian said  it   was  not right   to  form electoral
commission by   party  representation principle, since, he said,
the commissions should be made up  of professionals, whose  work
must be supervised.
     Haroutiunian highly appreciated a worthy  behavior  of  the
aggrieved party representatives at  the Court.  He  said that it
thanks to  them  that  the  proceedings  were held  on  a really
civilized level. "Our  country  needs opposition as we have  the
Parliament,  Government   and   the  Constitutional  Court,"  CC
Chairman said.
<p>
<p>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION IN KARABAKH AROUSED AZERBAIJAN'S
ANGER
     YEREVAN,  November 26   (Noyan Tapan).  The   November   24
presidential election  in  the   Nagorno-Karabakh Republic  were
held, despite statements from  a  number of countries that  they
will not recognize the election results.
     On the   same  day   rallies,   protesting   the   Karabakh
presidential   election  were    staged   in  Azerbaijan.    The
Instanbul-based  Armenian  "Marmara"  daily  reports  that Azeri
Culture Minister Polad Bul-Bul ogly said, addressing  a rally in
Baku,  that  the  elections  in Karabakh  were   nothing but  "a
politcal irritator". He said that  Azerbaijan  was  against  any
bloodshed, but,  if   necessary, they were ready  to  shed their
blood to liberate the occupied Azeri territories.
<p>
<p>
            --------------- ECONOMY ----------------
<p>
<p>
ECONOMIC REVIEW (NOVEMBER 17-24)
<p>
     YEREVAN, November 26 (Noyan Tapan).
<p>
     NATIONAL CURRENCY
     Dollar rate did not practically  change for the  week.  The
average cost of 1 USD decreased by 1 point and was equal to  434
drams during   the week.  At   the  same  time, the  margin (the
difference between sale and purchase prices) is still very  low.
Maximal sale  price   (433 drams against 1  dollar) dropped by 2
points, and minimal purchase price (436  drams) decreased by the
same two points.
     In principle, the  margin size is to  a certain  extent  an
indicator of the health of the national currency. The higher  is
the margin, the more alarming is  the  condition  of  the  given
currency, and vice versa. In our case, drop of the  margin  from
10 drams (2.5%  of the  dollar)  in  early November to  3  drams
(0.7%)  is a sign  of  healthening,  though  its causes are  not
clear.  The Government  did   not take  any efficient  steps  to
protect dram from devaluation , and did  not even  make a formal
statement on it. The Central Bank did only  one  thing:  for the
first time during  two months it  took part  in  tradings at the
Yerevan and Giumri Stock Exchange and purchased a rather  modest
sum of 200,000 dollars.
     But this   circumstance  could  never able  to  relax   the
tension on currency market. Here, we  have  probably  the result
of other factors: restraint from  emission, the  fact  that  the
government used only those sums that are  in circulation, delays
in pension and salary payments, and hence,  low consumer  demand
and  relatively  stable consumer prices.  Anyway,  it should  be
noted that it is not only the dollar rate that  affects consumer
prices, but  also consumer  prices cause changes  in the  dollar
rate.
     Exchange  rate  at the Moscow  Interbank Currency  Exchange
was 5,489 ruble on November 22.
<p>
     CONSUMER BUDGET
     By  the end   of  the  week the  cost  of   the living wage
consumer budget   was  12,900  drams (29.6 dollars). The cost of
the overalkl budget constituted 19,800 drams (45.5 dollars).
     So, the cost of the consumer budget dropped by  200  drams,
and 0.5 dollars.
<p>
     CONSUMER PRICES
     NT-16  index calculated   of  16 staple   food products was
equal  to 1,000,  i.e.  general level of consumer prices  had no
relation to changes in dollar rate and remained unchanged.
<p>
     INVESTMENT ACTIVITY
     Following the "Hrant"  index,  the investment  activity was
9.55 during the week.
<p>
     TREASURY BILLS MARKET
     "Sed  Marced"  index of   profitability of   treasury bills
constituted 0.3996, which is  456 points  lower  if  compared to
the previous   week. The profitability  was 39.96%. According to
President of   the Sed   Marced Firm  Tigran  Jerbashian,   such
decrease  is  conditioned by  the fact that  2,000,000,000-worth
treasury  bills were   used  up by  foreign  investors  two week
before.
<p>
<p>
            ------------- KARABAKH NEWS -----------
<p>
<p>
KARABAKH DISAPPOINTED WITH HELSINKI NEGOTIATIONS, FM SAYS
     YEREVAN, November 26 (Noyan Tapan).  "We  are  disappointed
with the results of this round of negotiations  on  the Karabakh
conflict", Karabakh Foreign Minister Arkady  Ghoukassian said at
a Nov. 26 news conference.
     He  noted that results  of  a  half-and-a-year  work of the
OSCE  Minsk  group  and  principles  of  the conflict settlement
worked out by the Armenian party were left out  of  the  account
at  the   Helsinki    negotiations.   Ghoukassian  said    that,
unfortunately, at the last moment  representatives of Azerbaijan
refused  to participate  in   the work,   insisting   that   the
negotiations  must be  held from the initial position,  i.e. the
principle of territorial integrity of Azerbaijan.
     Ghoukassian  said  that  the Nagorno-Karabakh  Republic did
not consider   itself to  be   a  part  of Azerbaijan,   and any
decision must proceed from this position.  "We  are  against any
attempts to   predetermine the  results   of  the  negotiations.
Respecting the  territorial  integrity,   Karabakh is  ready  to
discuss this issue only after both  contending sides  hold equal
initial positions at the  negotiations  and the Nagorno-Karabakh
Republic  is  viewed as   a subject  of the  international law,"
Karabakh's FM said. He described  statements by  the Azeri  side
as statements of the  lost party which  demands  capitulation of
its enemy. "If Azerbaijan really viewed Nagorno Karabakh  as its
integral part, it would have  decided this  problem  by  itself,
without turning to international organizations," he noted.
     According to Ghoukassian, Azerbaijan intends  to kick up  a
row at   the  forthcoming  OSCE summit   in Lisbon.  He   voiced
confidence  that if  Azerbaijan  insists  that  the  territorial
integrity be a basic principle of the  conflict settlement, then
Armenia will have to use its right to veto.
     He stressed  that  the  issue of  territorial  integirty is
directly connected with the problem of  Karabakh's  status. "The
fact  that the  Nagorno-Karabakh  Republic  is   independent  is
obvious  and the status of  Karabakh  must be  a  result  of the
negotiations,  and not   a starting   point  for   the  latter,"
Ghoukassian said.
     He emphasized   that  the presidential  election in Nagorno
Karabakh proved that the Karabakh people trusts its leadership.
     Ghoukassian said that the internal political  situation  in
Armenia had played a certain part in toughening of  position  of
Azerbaijan. However, he voiced confidence that  this  would  not
influence the positions of Karabakh and Armenia.
<p>
CONFLICTING SIDES FAIL TO AGREE A COMMON DOCUMENT
     YEREVAN, November  26  (Noyan   Tapan).  No document  to be
submitted at   the forthcoming OSCE summit in  Lisbon  has  been
adopted  at a recent  round of talks  over the Karabakh conflict
held in Helsinki. The positions of the parties  to  the conflict
remained unchanged,   President elect   of the  Nagorno-Karabakh
Republic Robert   Kocharian  said   at  a  news   conference  in
Stepanakert. He noted that no document had  been  adopted during
Libaridian-Guluzade meeting as well.
     Kocharian noted that there  is  still a  chance to  agree a
common  document  in  Vienna, a   document,  which  will then be
presented at   the  Lisbon summit.  But   he was skeptical about
that. He  said Azerbaijan  would stick  to its  position  as  it
hoped to   submit  its  own  document at   the   Lisbon  summit.
According to   Kocharian, the   Azeri side   will be pushing for
territorial integirty of Azerbaijan. Azerbaijan counts  that the
document will be supported by all countries-participants of  the
cummit, and if Armenia  uses its rights to  veto  and  does  not
vote for  that  document, it will have  to  confront with  other
OSCE-member  countries.  Azerbaijan   believes  that  this  will
seriously affect Armenia's international image.
     "This is the major  position on  which  Azerbaijan  stakes.
Taking  this    position  Azerbaijan  torpedoes  any  compromise
decision which  might   be  achieved before the Lisbon  summit,"
Kocharian said.
<p>
<p>
           -------- CRIMINAL AND JUDICIAL --------
<p>
MANVEL EGHIAZARIAN REFUSES TO ATTEND HEARINGS ON CASE OF 31
     YEREVAN, November 26 (Noyan Tapan). At a  Nov.  25  hearing
on the case of 31  Manvel  Eghiazarian's nephew Gagik Vanian did
not plead guilty to committing an attempt on policeman's life.
     Vanian  confirmed testimonies  that  he   had  given during
preliminary  probe.   He   said  that  on  the  day  of   arrest
Eghiazarian's house was encircled  by  armed people in masks and
heavy  military  vehicles (Vanian said the house  was surrounded
by tanks).  Armed  people burst  into the yard of the house  and
opened  fire.  Eghiazarian was   crying out: "Don't shoot, there
are small children at the house." Vanian said  he  was  not with
Eghiazarian   and  could   not    remember   precisely   whether
Eghiazarian returned fire or not. Vanian  said he  did not  know
whether the  assailants   were agents   of  the   lawenforcement
bodies.
     Vanian said that out of the arms  seized at his  apartment,
only 15 cartridges really belonged to him. He said he  kept them
as a memory about the Karabakh war. He said he did not  know how
the rest of the arms appeared at his apartment. As to arms  that
had been found at Eghiazarian's, Vanian  said  that  "Manvel has
always kept   arms at  home  and   even   much  more   than  the
lawenforcement agents have found."
     Manvel   Eghiazarian  said  that   he  refuses  to   attend
hearings, whereas   his  wife Mariam Khzyrjian will not  come to
the court as a witness.
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
