ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/31/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
EDITOR'S NOTE: Our next posting of articles from the combined January 2-<br>
3 issue, will appear on Thursday, Jan. 2, 1997. We wish our readers a <br>
happy and safe New Year.<br>
<p>
<p>
1. LEBED UNVEILS NEW RUSSIAN PARTY<br>
2. IRANIAN VICE-PRESIDENT CONCLUDES ARMENIA VISIT<br>
3. GANGSTERS USED FOR MISSIONS ABROAD<br>
4. ARMENIAN ORPHANS DIE OF POISON GAS<br>
5. RUSSIA AND ARMENIA SIGN TAX AGREEMENT<br>
6. OSCE MINSK GROUP CO-CHAIRMAN ARRIVES IN BAKU<br>
7. FORMER PRIME MINISTER BEGINS NEW PROJECTS<br>
8. DEPUTY MINISTER OF EDUCATION AND SCIENCE RESIGNED<br>
9. ARMENIA SUPPLIES CANNED FOOD TO THE US<br>
10. ARMEN NAZARIAN SELECTED BEST ATHLETE OF ARMENIA<br>
<p>
<p>
1. LEBED UNVEILS NEW RUSSIAN PARTY<br>
<p>
GOLITSYNO, Russia (Reuter)-Russias controversial former security chief <br>
and would-be president, Alexander Lebed, said on Friday he was launching <br>
a political "third force," which he hopes will one day propel him into <br>
the Kremlin.<br>
	The gravel-voiced former paratroop general, sacked by President Boris <br>
Yeltsin in October for insubordination, said his new party already had <br>
substantial financial backing an would aim to forge a broad alliance <br>
among diverse social groups.<br>
	"We will seek the support of small and medium-sized businesses, big <br>
private industry, the armed forces, the military-industrial complex, the <br>
intelligentsia," Lebed told a news conference at the village of <br>
Golitsyno, outside Moscow.<br>
	He said some banks, companies and wealthy individuals had offered to <br>
fund his organization, which he named the Russian National-Republican <br>
Party.<br>
	Lebed, 46, said the RNRP would draw support from both the left and <br>
right of Russias fractured political spectrum but added it would take <br>
several months to draw up an official program.<br>
	"We must become an alternative to both the communists and the present <br>
democratic apparatchiks," said the charismatic, pug-nosed Lebed, <br>
referring to the opposition and Yeltsins Kremlin administration.<br>
	His new party is closely linked to the "Honor and Motherland <br>
Movement," whose conference in Golitsyno on Friday provided the stage <br>
for Lebeds announcement.<br>
	Lebed, shunned by Russias rulers since being fired as secretary of <br>
the policy-making Security Council, needs to build a strong political <br>
base if he is ever to realize his ambition of succeeding Yeltsin in the <br>
Kremlin.<br>
In an interview published on Friday in the Nezavisimaya Gazeta daily<br>
Lebed said Yeltsin was still a sick man and should resign. The 65-year-<br>
old president returned to the Kremlin on Monday after a heart bypass <br>
operation on November 5.<br>
	Yeltsin says he now feels well and is again in full control of the <br>
vast country, but Lebed told reporters the next few months <br>
<p>
<p>
2. IRANIAN VICE-PRESIDENT CONCLUDES ARMENIA VISIT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Combined Sources)-Irans First Vice-President Hasan Habibi <br>
conluded his four-day visit to Armenia Saturday, after signing a number <br>
of cooperation agreements expanding Iran-Armenia bilateral relations.<br>
	Ter-Petrosyan characterized relations between the two countries as <br>
having undergone "qualitative changes" during a joint press conference <br>
held on Saturday prior to Habibis departure.<br>
	In his address before the National Assembly last Thursday, Habibi <br>
expressed satisfaction with the existing bilateral relations.<br>
	"If until recently Armenia-Iran relations were exclusively focused <br>
on trade, now they are acquiring a nature of economic cooperation," Ter-<br>
Petrosyan said.<br>
	Six bilateral memoranda and protocols on mutual understanding and <br>
cooperation in the communications, energy and industrial sectors, as <br>
well as taxation, were signed between the neighboring countries. A <br>
separate memorandum dealing with the problem of raising funds for the <br>
construction of the Iran-Armenia gas pipeline was also signed with the <br>
hope of encouraging Iranian investments in Armenia.<br>
	Ter-Petrosyan highly praised Irans policies in the region, <br>
describing them as "balanced." According to him, although Iran does not <br>
formally participate in the negotiation on the settlement of the <br>
Karabakh conflict, its (Irans) balanced relations with all countries of <br>
the region are in themselves factors of stability in the region.<br>
	"All countries of the region should have a chance to act and <br>
develop freely," Habibi said.<br>
	Habibi expressed hope that the Caucasus would be stable and <br>
peaceful in order to benefit economic development of the individual <br>
countries.<br>
	Vice-President Habibi arrived in Yerevan on Dec. 25 and met with <br>
high-level government officials, as well as addressed Armenias National <br>
Assembly.<br>
	During his meeting with Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian, Habibi <br>
said that time had come to tap the "untapped reservoir" in Iran-Armenia <br>
relations.<br>
	It was announced that the Armenian-Iranian joint committee for <br>
economic cooperation would hold its regular session in March 1997 in <br>
Tehran. The committee was created in 1994. Armenias Prime Minister <br>
Armen Sarkissian is expected to attend the meeting in Tehran.<br>
	In addition, Ter-Petrosyan is scheduled to visit Iran in May 1997 <br>
at the invitation of Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. GANGSTERS USED FOR MISSIONS ABROAD<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-A scandal over Turkeys alleged use of gangsters as <br>
political hitmen deepened on Friday after official testimony that a drug <br>
smuggler wanted for murder had carried out missions abroad for the <br>
security establishment.<br>
	Former interior ministry adviser Korkut Eken told a parliamentary <br>
inquiry that far-right mobster Abdullah Catli had worked with security <br>
officials for years, parliamentary sources said.<br>
	"He said he knew Catli and that (the gangster) had worked for the <br>
state, even before 1980, a source close to the commission of inquiry <br>
told Reuters.<br>
	A top intelligence officer told the same inquiry on Thursday that <br>
Turkeys intelligence service MIT had cooperated with Catli in <br>
unspecified foreign ventures in the 1980s, the source said.<br>
	It was the strongest confirmation of media and opposition reports <br>
that leading officials were closely linked to underworld figures in the <br>
past. The reports say the links may still exist.<br>
	Catli is central to a scandal that erupted on November 3 when he died <br>
in a traffic accident as a passenger in a car also carrying a senior <br>
policeman and a parliament member from Foreign Minister Tansu Cillers <br>
True Path Party.<br>
	The interior minister, also from Cillers party, quit last month amid <br>
accusations that Turkish officials used gangsters into the 1990s to kill <br>
Kurdish rebel sympathizers and business rivals in exchange for ignoring <br>
gangland drug smuggling and money laundering.<br>
	Ciller told members of a crack police unit not to be demoralized by <br>
accusations that some of its members were embroiled in illegal killings <br>
and the drugs trade.<br>
	"There have been unjustified attacks against you recently. I know how <br>
much that has saddened you, Ciller said in an address to a police <br>
academy near Ankara.<br>
	"Keep your heads up high, said Ciller, dressed in a camouflage <br>
special forces jacket. Three members of the unit have been suspended for <br>
allegedly cooperating with Catli in the July murder of Turkeys top <br>
casino owner in a drug money quarrel.<br>
	The Islamist-led coalition government of Prime Minister Necmettin <br>
Erbakan has shown few signs of cracking in the face of media reports <br>
that Cillers businessman husband and several members of her party are <br>
close to the mob.<br>
	Pro-Islam backbench parliamentarians are uneasy about a speech last <br>
month by conservative Ciller in which she indirectly praised Catli as a <br>
patriot.<br>
	Catli, a member of the extreme-right Grey Wolves movement, was wanted <br>
for the killing of seven Turkish leftists in 1978.<br>
	Parliamentary sources confirmed reports in several dailies that the <br>
head of Turkish intelligences anti-terror unit, Mehmet Eymur, testified <br>
on Thursday that the intelligence service had worked with Catli.<br>
	"He told the commission that the state used Abdullah Catli abroad <br>
from 1983, Islamist deputy Mehmet Elkatmis, who chairs the <br>
parliamentary inquiry, told the ATV television station. He did not <br>
specify what tasks Catli may have carried out.<br>
	Catli spent time in jail in France and Switzerland for drug smuggling <br>
in the 1980s. A forged version of a type of passport given only to <br>
leading officials was found on his body after the car crash.<br>
	The Turkish media have said Catli was involved in carrying out a <br>
number of anti-Armenian terrorist acts.<br>
	Eymur told the commission the intelligence service cut its relation <br>
with Catli when it became aware of his drug dealings.<br>
	"We gave him up and national police headquarters took him and began <br>
to use him, Hurriyet newspaper quoted Eymur as saying. The inquiry is <br>
closed to the press but there have been frequent leaks.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. ARMENIAN ORPHANS DIE OF POISON GAS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg/Noyan Tapan)-Eight mentally retarded and disabled children <br>
died as a result of inhaling poisonous coal gas. Four children and a <br>
nurse are recovering  in  the  Erebouni  medical center.<br>
	Noyan Tapan had previously reported that the children had died due <br>
to burns sustained from fire. <br>
<p>
<p>
5. RUSSIA AND ARMENIA SIGN TAX AGREEMENT<br>
<p>
MOSCOW (Itar-Tass)-Armenian Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian and his <br>
Russian counterpart Viktor Chernomyrdin signed an intergovernmental <br>
agreement Saturday to avoid double taxation on incomes and property.<br>
	Chernomyrdin noted that he and Sarkissian had reached a mutual <br>
understanding on all questions.<br>
	The Russian Prime Minister expressed hope that the sides to the <br>
conflict in Nagorno-Karabakh would arrive at an early solution next <br>
year.<br>
	He told reporters that relations between the two nations[Russia and <br>
Armenia] "have been built long ago, and there were and should not be any <br>
differences between our peoples."<br>
	Prime Minister Sarkissian expressed hope that 1997 "can be decisive <br>
in strengthening relations between Armenia and Russia." Sarkissian <br>
echoed Chernomyrdins sentiments on the long-standing relations between <br>
the two nations and added, "We in Armenia regard them [the relations] as <br>
strategic."<br>
	Sarkissian pledged that as prime minister, he would do his best to <br>
further strengthen relations with Russia.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. OSCE MINSK GROUP CO-CHAIRMAN ARRIVES IN BAKU<br>
<p>
BAKU (Itar-Tass)-Russian co-chairman of the Organization for Security <br>
and Cooperation in Europe Minsk Group, Yuri Yukalov, met with Azeri <br>
President Gaidar Aliyev on Saturday, following his brief stay in <br>
Armenia.<br>
	Yukalov also visited the Nagorno-Karabakh capital, Stepanakert, and <br>
met with President Robert Kocharian prior to his arrival in the Azeri <br>
capital Baku.<br>
	Yukalov stressed the importance of continuing efforts to reach an <br>
agreement in the coming year.<br>
	In a statement made at the OSCE summit meeting in Lisbon, current <br>
OSCEchairman-in-office, Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti gave an <br>
account of the major principles in the settlement of the Karabakh <br>
conflict-to recognize Azerbaijans territorial integrity by the <br>
international community, to grant a status of autonomy to Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh and to ensure the security of the population.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. FORMER PRIME MINISTER BEGINS NEW PROJECTS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Respublica Armenia, Lragir)-The former Prime  Minister  of  <br>
Armenia,  Hrant  Bagratian, has written the first chapter of his book on <br>
Armenias society.<br>
	According to Armenpress, the first chapters of the book  are ready <br>
to publication. According to the author, the main theme  of the book is <br>
a "discussion about Marxism".  It  touches  upon  the reasons of the <br>
fall of the Soviet  Union,  public-historical problems, historical <br>
evolution of private ownership, problems  of Western  and  Asian  <br>
politics and many other subjects. The  book   considers the historical <br>
experience of the Armenian statehood, economic  policy of the country, <br>
national ideology, and national values.<br>
	In addition, Bagratian has reportedly signed a contract with the <br>
International Monetary Fund to head its projects in Russia and Ukraine.<br>
	Bagratian is expected to leave for  Russia on Wednesday to get <br>
acquainted with the situations in the two Commonwealth of Independent <br>
States countries.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. DEPUTY MINISTER OF EDUCATION AND SCIENCE RESIGNED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg/Noyan Tapan)-The Deputy  Minister  of Education and <br>
Science, Haroutyun Karapetian, has sent a letter of resignation to the <br>
Armenian Prime Minister. <br>
disagreements with the current Minister Artashes Petrossian,  who is <br>
willing to eliminate the principle of theme financing, used in Armenia <br>
in the  recent  years,  and  return  to  the  centralized financing <br>
principle, used during the soviet period. <br>
		With theme financing, heads of the  approved  themes  decide <br>
how to use the money  allocated  to  their  scientific theme. <br>
Centralized financing means are distributed by the heads of scientific <br>
institutions.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. ARMENIA SUPPLIES CANNED FOOD TO THE US<br>
<p>
NOYEMBERIAN (Azg/Fact)-The  Ayroum factory of canned foods has already <br>
supplied $20,000 in goods to the US earlier this year.<br>
	In addition to the foreign orders, the factory now  produces <br>
tomato paste, peach and apple jams, as well as raw materials  for the <br>
production of alcohol. <br>
<p>
<p>
10. ARMEN NAZARIAN SELECTED BEST ATHLETE OF ARMENIA<br>
<p>
	YEREVAN (Haytani Hanrapetutyun)-The  Executive Committee of the <br>
Armenian  National Olympics decided in its recent session that the best <br>
Armenian athlete in 1996 was Olympic champion free-style wrestler Armen <br>
Nazarian. Nazarian and  his  trainer  will receive monetary prizes of <br>
$4,000 and $1,000 respectively. 	Karapetian has reportedly resigned <br>
due to <br>
