<!-- body="start" -->
IRAN NEWS (28.12.96)<br>
RESENDED BY NORAIR HAKOPIAN,<br>
COMPUTER ASSISTANT of IRI EMBASSY<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
# President Rafsanjani Congratulates Christians<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------ <br>
<p>
IRAN NEWS NATIONAL DESK TEHRAN - President Hojjatoleslam<br>
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani on Wednesday congratulated world Christians<br>
and especially Iran's Christian community on Christmas. President<br>
Rafsanjani, in his message, hoped that Christians, all over the world would<br>
collaborate with followers of other religions and "breathe a new life into the<br>
body of the Christian communities and open a new chapter for the Christian<br>
world". He also said that he considered a good sign this year the falling of<br>
the Christmas Eve on the birthday anniversary of Hazrat Mahdi (A.S.) the<br>
Twelfth Imam (now in occultation) of the Prophet of Islam Mohammad's<br>
(S) infallible Household which was celebrated Thursday, IRNA reported. <br>
<p>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------ <br>
<p>
# Habibi Meets Armenian Craftsmen, Traders, Industrialists<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------ <br>
<p>
BY OUR CORRESPONDENT YEREVAN, ARMENIA - Iran's First<br>
Vice-President Hassan Habibi met and conferred with a number of<br>
Armenian industrialists, traders and craftsmen here on Thursday. <br>
Habibi told the Armenians that the fledgling cooperation between <br>
Iran and Armenia stemmed from traditional, historical and cultural<br>
ties of the two countries. He said that the volume of technical and<br>
industrial cooperation between the two countries, especially within <br>
the framework of Tehran-Yerevan Joint Economic Commission, <br>
was favorably growing. He added that Iran was ready to offer<br>
technical and industrial know-how to Armenian craftsmen in<br>
any area that they might be interested. He referred to the Iranian <br>
and Armenian legislation bodies' support for conclusion of bilateral<br>
industrial,trade and economic agreements. Habibi hoped that the<br>
two countries would be capable of taking steps in order to expand<br>
bilateral relations and cooperation by utilizing such a "strong <br>
backbone." Habibi said that solving banking and customs problems <br>
faced by the two parties would pave the ground for an increase in <br>
the volume of mutual transactions. He added that preparing the <br>
ground for joint investments and activating each other's private <br>
sectors could be effective in realizing such an important goal.<br>
Meanwhile, the head of Armenian Craftsmen and Producers'<br>
Association said that members of the association would visit <br>
Iran in future to explore ways of expanding mutual technical <br>
and industrial cooperation. Habibi also inspected the<br>
Armenian tire manufacturing and chemical plant in the suburbs<br>
of Yerevan on Thursday. The Iranian first-vice president arrived <br>
here on Wednesday heading a high-ranking politico-economic<br>
delegation. <br>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------ <br>
<p>
# Habibi Inaugurates Iranology Center in Yerevan<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
BY PARISA ALINIA YEREVAN, ARMENIA - Iran's First Vice <br>
President Hassan Habibi on Thursday inaugurated the Iranology<br>
Center of Caucasia.<br>
He also addressed a two-day seminar on Iranology in the Caucasus.<br>
"The Islamic Republic of Iran supports the scientific and research <br>
activities carried out by the center and by those professors and <br>
scholars who are conducting research studies on issues related<br>
to Iran," he said in his inaugural address.<br>
"From the sociological point of view, the main problem with<br>
contemporary Iranology in Europe stems from the fact that it looks<br>
 at phenomena from outside rather than from within." The first vice <br>
president said the study of the Persian language would serve as <br>
an important and fundamental factor in Iranology debates and studies. <br>
He said the Persian language has been used either as a native <br>
and main language or it has been the language of science, <br>
literature and culture throughout the history after Islam not only <br>
in Iran but also in Central Asia, the Caucasus, Turkey, part of<br>
Eastern Europe, the Indian Subcontinent, Mesopotamia and <br>
even in the Far East. <br>
 "Throughout its majestic and great history, Iran has followed<br>
humanitarian culture, love and kindness," Professor Garnic Asatourian,<br>
head of the center and head of the Iranology Department at the Oriental<br>
Institute of Armenian Science Academy said at the ceremony.<br>
 The Armenian minister of culture on his part said at the ceremony that <br>
the Persian language and literature has played a significant role in the <br>
establishment and evolution of human civilization. <br>
"Armenia is for expansion of its cooperation with Iran in the fields of<br>
culture and arts," he stressed. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
