<title>Groong Network: Armenia home to 300,000 refugees (second article in Montreal Gazette)</title>
<h1>Armenia home to 300,000 refugees (second article in Montreal Gazette)</h1>
Giro Manoyan (<i>72263.1572@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 30 Dec 96 13:48:19 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#239">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#239">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#239">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#239">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0240.html">Giro Manoyan: "Wind of gale force damages Armenian regions."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0238.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 12/30/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
NOTE: The following article, along with yesterday's article and photos by the<br>
author, is posted at the &lt; <a href="http://www.armen-info.com/hol">http://www.armen-info.com/hol</a> &gt; site.  The third and<br>
last article in this series will also be posted at the same site.<br>
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
-----------------<br>
<p>
Armenia home to 300,000 refugees<br>
<p>
Joe Fiorito, Special to the Gazette <br>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
SECOND OF A THREE-PART SERIES<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, Armenia - Maria Avakian is a senior citizen. She lives on a pension of<br>
$8 a month. She can't buy much more than bread, but she's luckier than most<br>
Armenian refugees. <br>
<p>
She has her own house. <br>
<p>
Avakian just moved into a cinder-block cottage, one of 70 built this year for<br>
refugees of Nagorno-Karabakh's war of independence from Azerbaijan. The cottages<br>
are a product of German foreign aid; 70 more are planned for 1997. <br>
<p>
Many more are needed.<br>
<p>
Armenia has 300,000 refugees.<br>
<p>
Avakian's cottage has one room. There is no running water. Her husband has taken<br>
the bucket and gone for his daily walk to a tap a kilometre away. But at least<br>
it's a place they can call home.<br>
<p>
The Avakians had a house once before, on a plot of land with apple and lemon<br>
trees in Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan. They were forced to flee in 1988, when<br>
radical Azeris went on a rampage, killing 68 Armenians; it was the third such<br>
riot in Azerbaijan that year, following Nagorno-Karabakh's declaration of intent<br>
to secede from Azerbaijan and join Armenia.<br>
<p>
The war is quiet now, but scars remain. <br>
<p>
"The Azeris beat my neighbors and cut them with knives," says Maria Avakian. She<br>
draws a finger, not across but up the length of her wrist; it leaves a white<br>
mark on her skin. Then she offers her visitors glasses of sweet tea; she has<br>
little else but tea.<br>
<p>
<p>
And the view from her front porch - this is, after all, the high Caucasus - a<br>
thin, blue sky with white clouds; those colors, repeated in the mountains rising<br>
in the distance.<br>
<p>
Raya Pogosova doesn't have the luxury of the long view. She is a social worker<br>
who works with refugees, and a refugee herself. Her own grandparents were killed<br>
in front of her in Baku.<br>
<p>
She shrugs as if that's normal and leads me next to a complex of mobile homes,<br>
set up for the Armenians who fled the village of Getashen, Azerbaijan. They live<br>
now in a cluster of mobile homes known as Getashen Camp. <br>
<p>
The mobile homes are Russian-made, rusty and leaky, more like tin cans tipped on<br>
their sides, outfitted with woodstoves and windows. <br>
<p>
Siran Baghramian, 66, was roughed up and deported from Getashen in 1988. Her<br>
husband, Shaliko Maroutian, was a foreman on a collective farm; he had a price<br>
on his head. He escaped on foot and walked for a week through the mountains at<br>
night until he reached safety.<br>
<p>
Today they own a few pots, a few dishes, the clothes on their backs. They do<br>
what they can to eke out their pensions. They keep a few chickens for eggs.<br>
Shaliko dug a garden in the yellow dirt outside their front door.<br>
<p>
Like other refugees, they are allowed 100 litres of kerosene each winter for<br>
heat, but they have to borrow the money to buy it, and most of the heat goes out<br>
the window; the trailer is poorly insulated. How cold does it get? "If you would<br>
spend a night here, you would know," says Siran, sharply. <br>
<p>
What can you tell me about Getashen? Siran begins to cry. She says, "Why do you<br>
have to remind me of that?" Shaliko comforts her.<br>
<p>
The government of Armenia can't provide much comfort for its war refugees; it<br>
wasn't able to cope after the earthquake of 1988, when the disaster made half a<br>
million people homeless.<br>
<p>
The country's a mess, badly polluted and falling apart from years of Soviet<br>
neglect. Its industries are out of date, it has few natural resources.<br>
<p>
Six hundred thousand citizens have left Armenia in the past five years, fed up<br>
with the lack of work, exhausted by the cost of Armenia's continuing support for<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh, weary of the hardships of a Turkish-Azerbaijani blockade.<br>
<p>
Of the 3.5 million Armenians who remain, roughly one in nine is a refugee.<br>
Unemployment is high. The average wage is a bit less than $60 a month; this in a<br>
country where a day's worth of bread is 35c, a kilo of apples costs $4.50, and<br>
gasoline costs what it does in Montreal.<br>
<p>
Armenia has electricity - the nuclear reactor knocked out by the earthquake is<br>
back on line - but few people can afford to pay for power, and there are still<br>
frequent brownouts. <br>
<p>
Yerevan looks dark and grim at night; there are no neon signs. That's not to say<br>
there is no night life. One evening, I watched half a dozen toughs in a downtown<br>
restaurant laughing loudly, locking arms and spending more on one round of<br>
drinks than Maria Avakian spends in a month on bread. <br>
<p>
The young men were muscle for hire. <br>
<p>
They rotated deferentially around their leader, a hard case in a tailored suit<br>
and a freshly laundered shirt. He wore jewelled rings on his hands, and a fat<br>
gold chain around his neck. <br>
<p>
The hired muscle froze when their boss took a moment to fix the foreigner with a<br>
stare so quiet and cold it silenced the room.<br>
<p>
"Who's the guy in the blue suit?" I asked my companions when we'd left and I<br>
felt safe. "Don't worry about him," they said. "We had guys like him under<br>
Stalin. We took care of them before, we'll take care of them again."<br>
<p>
They didn't sound certain.<br>
<p>
The road to capitalism and democracy, like every other road in this country, is<br>
a bumpy ride; last September's election in Armenia was rigged.<br>
<p>
Canada's Minister of Foreign Affairs, Lloyd Axworthy, expressed deep concern<br>
over the results, and called for a full-scale assessment. The government of<br>
Armenia replied that it was open to working toward democratization. <br>
<p>
Translation? Canada: You can't do that. Armenia: Don't call us, we'll call you.<br>
It may be too late for any calls.<br>
<p>
Vazken Manougian, the man some claim is the country's rightful president, was<br>
forced into hiding after the election. While underground, he received word that<br>
if he'd agree to permanent exile, 20 members of an outlawed faction of his party<br>
would be freed from jail. <br>
<p>
Manougian refused. <br>
<p>
He emerged after five days of seclusion, confident that the world was watching.<br>
The world is not watching very hard; three of those jailed were recently<br>
condemned to death for alleged terrorist activity. <br>
<p>
Those sentences are being appealed. No one has been put to death in Armenia in<br>
the last five years. It could be worse. At least there are courts in which to<br>
launch appeals.<br>
<p>
According to Manougian, Armenia has fallen into the hands of three clans, a kind<br>
of post-Soviet Mafia with a structure based on kinship, muscle and threats<br>
passed along by thugs in blue suits.<br>
<p>
The clans are reputed to have direct connections to the banks and the copper<br>
industry; clans control small and medium business, and have purchased privatized<br>
industries at bargain-basement prices.<br>
<p>
There is a street in downtown Yerevan where old women sell paper cones of<br>
walnuts and pumpkin seeds to earn the equivalent of a few pennies, a primitive<br>
capitalism illegal under communism. <br>
<p>
Thugs in blue suits profit from the sale of nuts and seeds.<br>
<p>
Economic relations with Canada are minimal; bilateral trade between Canada and<br>
Armenia amounts to less than $1 million a year. According to sources at the<br>
Armenian embassy in Ottawa, "We have very little to offer you, and we cannot<br>
afford to buy Canadian goods, which are expensive." <br>
<p>
As a result, Ottawa has little clout in this part of the world. There are only<br>
80,000 Armenians in Canada, nearly half of them in Montreal.<br>
<p>
Although Canada contributes nearly $10 million in developmental and aid money to<br>
Armenia, that's a negligible amount given the scope of the problems. <br>
<p>
And the emergence of the clans in Armenia may be the major reason why it's<br>
difficult to rebuild the country with investment money from abroad: diaspora<br>
Armenians are reluctant to underwrite musclemen and profiteers.<br>
<p>
It's not that there isn't money available. <br>
<p>
Armenians have typically done well for themselves abroad. Armenians in the<br>
United States donated $11 million to rebuild the road from Armenia to<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh. Armenians in Montreal and Toronto are paying for a $1-million<br>
waterline to supply Karabakh's capital, Stepanakert.<br>
<p>
Kevork Tscharshafdjian, a Toronto businessman who lives half the year in<br>
Yerevan, estimates that as much as $50 million a month comes into Armenia, most<br>
of it in the form of direct donations to families from overseas relatives.<br>
<p>
That figure may be high, but there's no way of knowing for sure. The government<br>
can barely keep track of the number of people who live in Armenia, let alone how<br>
much they receive in the form of private donations.<br>
<p>
If thugs like the man in the blue suit dream of carving up the country, if<br>
refugees like Siran Baghramian dream of a warm bath, and if immigrants dream of<br>
returning home, then the citizens of Armenia dream of an end to the blockade.<br>
<p>
And the resumption of what Hrant Khatchaturian says is Armenia's traditional<br>
role in the region. Khatchaturian, a leading member of Armenia's Union of<br>
Constitutional Rights, says his country should be "an east-west link in the<br>
Caucasus between Turkey and Azerbaijan, and a north-south link between Georgia<br>
and Iran."<br>
<p>
Armenia may be a broker, but Azerbaijan has all the wealth; enormous off-shore<br>
reserves, estimated at more than a billion barrels of oil, and 65 billion cubic<br>
yards of gas, lie offshore in the Caspian Sea.<br>
<p>
Two development deals, worth a total of $3.5 billion U.S., were signed last<br>
month. "Sometimes I think the region would be better off without oil, which is<br>
the source of many conflicts," says member of parliament Rupig Hagopian. <br>
<p>
"The political equation here will change because of oil."<br>
<p>
These latest deals will certainly increase Azerbaijan's political and diplomatic<br>
weight and its military capability, if it so chooses; bad news for the economic<br>
recovery of Armenia, and bad news for the sovereignty of Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
<p>
"That's why international recognition is necessary for us," says Dr. Zori<br>
Balayan, a representative of the government of Nagorno-Karabakh. Now based in<br>
Yerevan, Balayan is one of the original leaders of the Karabakh Movement for<br>
independence, which ignited this region eight years ago. <br>
<p>
Balayan knows he bears a heavy burden, but "diplomatic recognition is our<br>
guarantee of peace." Unfortunately for him, Armenia's current political troubles<br>
are hindering his cause. <br>
<p>
There is a small Canadian irony hidden in the troubles here. While would-be<br>
president Manougian was holed up underground in the aftermath of the election,<br>
his office was sealed and his files removed. <br>
<p>
Hanging on his office wall was a framed copy of the Canadian Charter of Rights<br>
and Freedoms; the charter disappeared along with the files. <br>
<p>
Manougian was eventually allowed to return to his office. He found everything<br>
had been put back. Everything, that is, except the charter. He smiles. "Human<br>
rights are a dangerous thing here." <br>
<p>
At the end of the day, social worker Raya Pogosova attends to the human rights<br>
of two more refugees: Svetlana Perieva and her daughter Gaya share one small<br>
room, barely big enough for two cots, a cupboard and a refrigerator. <br>
<p>
Gaya, 19, has dark hair, big eyes and psychological problems; she and her mother<br>
were beaten before they were deported from Azerbaijan. Gaya smiles readily, but<br>
she is restless and has difficulty looking anyone in the eye. <br>
<p>
Svetlana, 40, is a sewing-machine operator; there is no work for her. She and<br>
her daughter rarely go out. There is no danger of anyone coming to pound on<br>
their door in the middle of the night, and they have nothing of value to<br>
protect.<br>
<p>
But they are afraid to leave their room.<br>
<p>
TOMORROW: The bitter legacy of izgnaniya, the drive to hunt down and expel the<br>
Armenians from Azerbaijan and the parallel effort to rid Armenia of Azeris.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
