<title>Groong Network: Armenia to keep Nagorno-Karabakh region peaceful</title>
<h1>Armenia to keep Nagorno-Karabakh region peaceful</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 29 Dec 1996 16:50:36 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#235">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#235">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#235">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#235">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0236.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "Wind of gale force damages Armenian regions."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0234.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/30/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 MOSCOW (Dec. 28) XINHUA - Armenian President Levon Ter-Peterosyan <br>
said his country should do its best to keep the Nogorno-Karabakh region <br>
peaceful and stable, Itar-Tass news agency reported today. <br>
   Ter-Peterosyan made the remarks at a joint press conference held with <br>
Iran's First Vice-President Hassan Ebrahim Habibi. <br>
   Azerbaijan and Armenia reached a ceasefire agreement in May, 1994 after <br>
six years of war triggered by the announcement of independence of the <br>
Nogorno-Karabakh region, whose population is mainly Armenian ethnics. <br>
   Habibi said that he hopes the Caucasian Region will keep stable and <br>
peaceful to benefit the development of economies of the countries <br>
there. <br>
   Habibi arrived in Yerevan, capital of Armenia, on December 25 for his <br>
four-day visit to Armenia. <br>
   During his visit, the two countries signed a mutual understanding <br>
memorandum, and agreements of cooperation on energy, industry, <br>
communication and trade. <br>
   Habibi will visit Tajikistan on December 29 after ending his trip to <br>
Armenia.  Enditem <br>
   29/12/96 03:20 GMT <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
