<title>Groong Network: Artcile in the Montreal Gazette</title>
<h1>Artcile in the Montreal Gazette</h1>
Horizon Online (<i>72263.1572@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 28 Dec 96 23:42:23 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#233">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#233">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#233">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#233">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0234.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/30/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0232.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "OSCE Minsk group co-chairman to meet Azerbaijani ..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The following article appeared in today's (Dec. 28) The Gazette daily of<br>
Montreal, on page 1 and page 11. The article, the accompanying shorter articles<br>
and photos by the author will be posted at the    &lt;<br>
<a href="http://www.armen-info.com/hol">http://www.armen-info.com/hol</a> &gt; site by 6:00 EST, today.<br>
<p>
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
-------------------<br>
Bloody road to ballot box<br>
<p>
Nagorno-Karabakh's struggle for freedom<br>
<p>
Joe Fiorito, Special to the Gazette <br>
<p>
FIRST OF A THREE-PART SERIES<br>
<p>
Stepanakert, Nagorno-Karabakh - Nora Babayan pushed her way through a crowd of<br>
foreign observers, brushed aside a photographer, and slipped a piece of paper<br>
through a slit in a plywood box. The world did not sit up and take notice, but<br>
it was big news for Babayan. <br>
<p>
She's never voted for a president before. <br>
<p>
Getting to the ballot box has been a bloody struggle for her and the rest of the<br>
Armenians of Nagorno-Karabakh, who are in the middle of a war of independence<br>
<i>&gt;from surrounding Azerbaijan. </i><br>
<p>
Although no bullets are flying at the moment - it's been quiet for a couple of<br>
years now - the struggle is far from over, and the election put a strain on an<br>
uneasy peace; Azerbaijan considers Babayan's ballot illegal.<br>
<p>
In fact, no government in the world recognizes the little enclave as anything<br>
more than a part of Azerbaijan. But the people of Nagorno-Karabakh are bent on<br>
self-determination, and the election is part of their political strategy: act<br>
like a nation, and you'll<br>
be perceived as one. <br>
<p>
No matter how long it takes. <br>
<p>
Time is part of the problem. The people of Nagorno-Karabakh have had a<br>
succession of Turkish, Persian and Russian rulers throughout their history;<br>
they've survived as Armenians because they've made an art of semi-autonomy.<br>
<p>
There is an uncomfortable ethnic and religious cast to the dispute - Azeris are<br>
Muslim, Armenians are Christian, and power ebbs and flows between them like a<br>
pulse in the vein of history.<br>
<p>
Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh achieved independent union in 1918, but the Soviet<br>
Union took control of the region in 1920, and set the boundaries of Karabakh<br>
inside Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
It is a country of high peaks, harsh weather; its name is a pocket history of<br>
foreign rulers: "kara" is from the Persian, meaning fertile; "bakh," from the<br>
Turkish for garden. "Nagorno" is from the Russian, meaning mountainous.<br>
<p>
In 1988, excited by the possibility of perestroika, or Soviet restructuring, the<br>
people of Nagorno-Karabakh announced their intention to rejoin Armenia. <br>
<p>
All hell broke loose. <br>
<p>
Radical Azeris ran wild in Azerbaijan; in the cities of Sumgait, Kirovabad and<br>
Baku, women were raped, men beaten to death, families tossed out of their homes<br>
because they were Armenian. <br>
<p>
Hundreds died, thousands were injured. The brutality was fresh and familiar,<br>
reminding some of the genocide of 1915, when Turks killed 1.5 million Armenians;<br>
the Azeris are a Turkic people.<br>
<p>
The resulting war was short, nasty and brutish: 15,000 dead, an ugly little list<br>
of atrocities on both sides. There is a kind of quiet in the region for the<br>
moment; not war, but not quite peace. A deal to<br>
resolve the status of the region appears far off but the situation seems stable.<br>
Azerbaijan, for the moment, has accepted that it can't retake the area without<br>
great unrest in the region.<br>
<p>
According to the United Nations High Commission for Refugees, there are a<br>
million homeless on both sides; Azerbaijan claims a million all by itself.<br>
<p>
There are plenty of refugees, and there is also a sense of emptiness; 40,000<br>
Azeris once lived in Nagorno-Karabakh, and many more lived in Armenia; none<br>
remains today, just as no Armenians remain in Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
It will take a miracle to restore Nagorno-Karabakh to normal life. Archbishop<br>
Barkev Mardirossian knows all about miracles. At the height of the fighting, his<br>
house was destroyed by an Azeri rocket. <br>
<p>
He walked away without a scratch. <br>
<p>
These days, his life is much quieter; he prefers to watch his flock rebuild,<br>
rather than watch them destroy or be destroyed. <br>
<p>
"I had my special difficulties during the war," says Mardirossian. He is, after<br>
all, a man of the cloth, and the commandments of the church forbid killing; but<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh is Christian, and soldiers want communion. <br>
<p>
"I told our men that, in battle, they have the right to defend their wives,<br>
their land, their faith and their freedom. But they must not be cruel men or<br>
wild animals; they are soldiers, not killers."<br>
<p>
A fine distinction, and probably the same one made by Mardirossian's Muslim<br>
counterpart, Sheik Ul Islam Pasha Zade. In spite of that distinction - perhaps<br>
because of it - the two religious leaders<br>
have met frequently in Geneva, using the moral authority of their offices to<br>
bring about an exchange of hostages, and urging a peaceful settlement to the<br>
war. <br>
<p>
So far, so good.<br>
<p>
MATERIALS IN SHORT<br>
<p>
The people of Stepanakert are using the two-year lull in the war to rebuild as<br>
best they can, to sweep up the rubble and replant their gardens. <br>
<p>
Peace is nearly as much a struggle as war. Nagorno-Karabakh is subject to a<br>
Turkish-Azerbaijani blockade. Food, fuel and building materials are in short<br>
supply, and water is uncertain in most places, available only for a few hours in<br>
the morning and at night. <br>
<p>
Karabakh is getting some help from the Armenian diaspora:<br>
<p>
Montreal's Armenians are spending half a million dollars to build a water pipe<br>
around Stepanakert; the Armenians of Toronto have donated an equal amount to<br>
connect the pipe to a supply of fresh water.<br>
<p>
Nora Babayan's vote might have been illegal, but the election last month was the<br>
standard stuff of democracy. Electoral districts were mapped out, voters<br>
registered, independent scrutineers hired and trained. Out of a population of<br>
150,000, about 90,000 registered to vote. <br>
<p>
There were three candidates for president, each of whom were authorized $600 in<br>
expenses, and 300 litres of fuel for travel. Incumbent Robert Kocharian, with<br>
the advantage of office and a reputation as a hotshot military commander, was<br>
confident of victory. He declined the money and the fuel.<br>
<p>
There were few signs of a Western-style campaign. A single banner stretched<br>
across a downtown street in Stepanakert. On one side, "We're asking the<br>
international community for recognition;" on the other, "May the best man win."<br>
<p>
The election came off without a hitch. <br>
<p>
Mostly, that is; a few old people brought the passports of relatives and<br>
friends, expecting to cast proxy ballots; standard practice in Soviet days, but<br>
illegal now. Some people cast proxies anyway.<br>
<p>
Stepanakert is a small town. People know their neighbors here.<br>
<p>
None of the 38 international observers seemed concerned.<br>
<p>
CHURCH WAREHOUSE<br>
<p>
The day before the election, workmen were polishing a large metal cross that<br>
once adorned Mardirossian's cathedral, the Church of the Savior. <br>
<p>
Armenians have been Christian since 301 A.D., and this particular church has<br>
become a powerful political symbol: during the war, Azeri troops used it as a<br>
warehouse for Russian rockets; death stored in a church. <br>
<p>
The Azeris reckoned that Armenians would be reluctant to bomb their own holy<br>
place to bits. They were right. No bombs were used. Armenian troops retook the<br>
holy place by hand. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijani war planes bombed the church in retaliation. The roof and walls were<br>
damaged and the cross toppled, but the church was not destroyed. <br>
<p>
Four of his seven churches are battle-marked, yet Mardirossian refuses to<br>
describe this as a religious conflict. "There is a mosque in this town. I would<br>
not allow our soldiers to destroy it. This is not a religious war, it is a fight<br>
for territory and freedom." He describes the war this way for a reason. <br>
<p>
Religious struggles never end. <br>
<p>
This war isn't over yet. <br>
<p>
Off the coast of Azerbaijan, in the Caspian Sea, there is as much oil as all the<br>
reserves in the United States, including Alaska. Two new development deals worth<br>
a total of $3.5 billion U.S. were signed last month. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan's share will buy a lot of guns if it wants to continue to fight, but<br>
oil in itself is a diplomatic tool with a bigger bang than any gun.<br>
<p>
American interests are hoping a pipeline can be built across the Caucasus,<br>
through Nagorno-Karabakh to the Turkish Mediterranean; they hope to convince the<br>
Azeris that wealth has more virtues than warfare.<br>
<p>
The race is on. <br>
<p>
Robert Kocharian won the election handily. The next day, he celebrated victory<br>
with a cocktail party, a press reception and a visit to Archbishop<br>
Mardirossian's damaged church. He watched quietly as the giant cross was hoisted<br>
high in the air and replaced atop its spire.<br>
<p>
Then he prayed. <br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
- Tomorrow: Coping with the refugees in the capital of Armenia, and coping with<br>
the demands of a fledgling democracy in the former Soviet republic.<br>
