<title>Groong Network: VOA/Russia/Muslims</title>
<h1>VOA/Russia/Muslims</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 28 Dec 1996 06:35:59 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#231">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#231">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#231">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#231">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0232.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "OSCE Minsk group co-chairman to meet Azerbaijani ..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0230.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/28/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DATE=12/26/96<br>
TYPE=BACKGROUND REPORT<br>
NUMBER=5-35331<br>
TITLE=RUSSIA FACES ITS MUSLIMS <br>
BYLINE=MAXIM KNIAZKOV<br>
DATELINE=WASHINGTON<br>
CONTENT=<br>
VOICED AT: <br>
<p>
INTRO: A HUMILIATING DEFEAT AT THE HANDS OF MUSLIM SEPARATISTS IN<br>
CHECHNYA AND ADVANCES OF ISLAMIC REBELS IN RUSSIAN-BACKED <br>
TAJIKISTAN HAVE RAISED QUESTIONS ABOUT RUSSIA'S RELATIONS WITH <br>
ITS MUSLIM NEIGHBORS AND ITS OWN MUSLIM COMMUNITY.  V-O-A'S MAXIM<br>
KNIAZKOV EXAMINES WHETHER MOSCOW'S MILITARY FAILURES SIGNAL <br>
TROUBLE IN RUSSIA'S MUSLIM-POPULATED REGIONS. <br>
<p>
TEXT: ON THE FACE OF IT, THE WORST FEARS OF RUSSIAN NATIONALISTS <br>
SEEM TO BE COMING TRUE.  JUST A FEW MONTHS AFTER RUSSIA <br>
RELUCTANTLY AGREED TO WITHDRAW FROM BREAKAWAY CHECHNYA, ISLAMIC <br>
REBELS WENT ON THE OFFENSIVE IN RUSSIAN-BACKED TAJIKISTAN. <br>
<p>
THE 25-THOUSAND RUSSIAN SOLDIERS DEPLOYED IN THAT CENTRAL ASIAN <br>
STATE FOUND THEMSELVES UNDER FIRE FROM ISLAMIC FIGHTERS, NOW <br>
REPORTED TO BE LESS THAN 180 KILOMETERS FROM DUSHANBE, THE <br>
CAPITAL.  <br>
<p>
ALL THIS HAS PROMPTED MANY RUSSIANS TO CAST A WARY EYE ON MUSLIMS<br>
LIVING ALONG ITS BORDERS AND IN RUSSIA ITSELF.  BUT YAHYA <br>
SADOWSKI, AN EXPERT ON THE ISLAMIC WORLD WITH WASHINGTON'S <br>
BROOKINGS INSTITUTION, DOES  NOT  EXPECT THE RIPPLE EFFECT FROM <br>
CHECHNYA OR TAJIKISTAN TO BE FELT IN RUSSIA.  MR. SADOWSKI SAYS <br>
THAT IS BECAUSE RUSSIA'S MUSLIM COMMUNITY IS ANYTHING BUT UNITED.<br>
<p>
                // ACT ONE SADOWSKI // <br>
<p>
         THE CHECHEN EXPERIENCE IS VERY UNIQUE, HOWEVER. THIS <br>
         LEVEL OF MILITANCY, THIS HEIGHT OF PASSION AND DETAILED <br>
         MILITARY ORGANIZATION AND SO ON IS  NOT  LIKELY TO BE <br>
         FOUND AMONG MANY OTHER MUSLIM GROUPS OF THE FORMER <br>
         SOVIET UNION.  FOR EXAMPLE, IN THE NEARBY TERRITORY OF <br>
         DAGESTAN, A REGION THAT HISTORICALLY HAS BEEN TIGHTLY <br>
         LINKED TO CHECHNYA, THAT ACTUALLY PARTICIPATED WITH THE <br>
         CHECHENS IN THE RESISTANCE AGAINST RUSSIAN OCCUPATION IN<br>
         THE 19TH CENTURY, WE HAVE NOT SEEN ANYTHING LIKE THE <br>
         SAME SORT OF MILITANCY. <br>
<p>
                    // END ACT //  <br>
<p>
HOME TO MORE THAN 30 MUSLIM ETHNIC GROUPS, RUSSIA SAW AN UPSURGE <br>
OF AN ISLAMIC SELF-DETERMINATION MOVEMENT IN THE EARLY 1990'S.  <br>
THEN, IT ALL BUT SWEPT THE AUTONOMOUS REPUBLIC OF TATARSTAN, EAST<br>
OF MOSCOW.  ONLY THE SHOWERING OF THAT OIL-PRODUCING REGION WITH <br>
ECONOMIC BENEFITS HELPED THE KREMLIN KEEP EVENTS THERE FROM <br>
SPINNING OUT OF CONTROL. <br>
<p>
BUT SOME RUSSIAN POLITICIANS ASK THEMSELVES WHETHER THEY WILL SEE<br>
MORE UNREST NOW THAT CHECHNYA HAS LAID BARE RUSSIA'S MILITARY <br>
WEAKNESS.  MR. SADOWSKI BELIEVES THE TATARS AND OTHER MUSLIMS <br>
LIVING ALONG THE RIVER VOLGA ARE UNLIKELY TO FOLLOW IN THE <br>
FOOTSTEPS OF THE CHECHENS.  <br>
<p>
               // ACT TWO SADOWSKI // <br>
<p>
         THE VOLGA TATARS HAVE A MUCH MORE REFINED SENSE OF <br>
         IDENTITY AND A MUCH MORE URBANE STYLE OF POLITICS THAN <br>
         MANY OTHER GROUPS.  THEY MAY WISH FOR AUTONOMY FROM <br>
         RUSSIA, AND AN INCREASE OF LOCAL ECONOMIC BENEFITS AND <br>
         SO ON, EVERY BIT AS PASSIONATELY AS THE CHECHENS DO.  <br>
         BUT THEY ARE LIKELY TO ORGANIZE A PURSUIT OF THAT ALONG <br>
         VERY VERY DIFFERENT KIND OF LINES.  THESE ARE NOT PEOPLE<br>
         WHOSE FIRST REACTION IS TO TURN TO URBAN GUERRILLAS <br>
         WARFARE. <br>
<p>
                     // END ACT // <br>
<p>
BY CONTRAST, PATRICIA CARLEY, A CENTRAL ASIA ANALYST WITH THE U-S<br>
INSTITUTE OF PEACE, IS CAUTIOUS ABOUT PREDICTING A FUTURE COURSE <br>
OF EVENTS.  SHE SAYS A LOT WILL DEPEND ON WHETHER RUSSIA'S OWN <br>
DECLINE WILL CONTINUE, PROMPTING VARIOUS COMMUNITIES INSIDE THE <br>
COUNTRY TO LOOK MORE AGGRESSIVELY AFTER THEIR OWN INTERESTS. <br>
<p>
               // ACT THREE CARLEY // <br>
<p>
         THE DEFEAT IN CHECHNYA AND THE PROBLEMS IN TAJIKISTAN <br>
         DON'T HAVE MUCH TO DO WITH ISLAMIC REVIVAL.  I THINK <br>
         THEY HAVE A LOT TO DO WITH THE COLLAPSE OF THE SOVIET <br>
         UNION AND THE RUSSIAN MILITARY.  I THINK THEY HAVE A LOT<br>
         TO DO WITH THE RUSSIAN POPULATION BEING UNWILLING TO <br>
         SUSTAIN THE KIND OF INVOLVEMENT NECESSARY, FOR EXAMPLE, <br>
         IN TAJIKISTAN FOR RUSSIANS ACTUALLY TO DO ANYTHING.  IT <br>
         COULD HAVE EASILY BEEN A NON-MUSLIM AND NON-RUSSIAN <br>
         PEOPLE, WHO WERE FIGHTING AGAINST RUSSIAN COLONIZATION. <br>
<p>
                       // END ACT // <br>
<p>
MEANWHILE, WITH RUSSIAN TROOPS CONCLUDING THEIR PULLOUT FROM <br>
CHECHNYA, CHECHEN SEPARATIST REBELS ARE NOW SAID TO BE IN <br>
PRACTICALLY FULL CONTROL OF THEIR REPUBLIC.  IN TAJIKISTAN, A <br>
RECENTLY CONCLUDED CEASE-FIRE ACCORD IS ALLOWING ISLAMIC REBELS <br>
TO CONSOLIDATE THEIR GAINS.  (SIGNED)  <br>
<p>
NEB/MAX/KL<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
26-Dec-96 3:20 PM EST (2020 UTC)<br>
NNNN<br>
<p>
Source: Voice of America<br>
.<br>
