<title>Groong Network: Post-Communist Armenia</title>
<h1>Post-Communist Armenia</h1>
R.H. Lola Koundakjian (<i>rhk9@columbia.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 27 Dec 1996 14:46:29 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#228">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#228">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#228">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#228">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0229.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 12/27/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0227.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "1227aol.txt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The following appeared in The (Toronto) Globe and Mail on Sat. Dec. 21 in<br>
the "Focus &amp; Books" section. The title of the article is "The party is<br>
over" and concerns the political situation in the ex-Soviet republics. It<br>
was written by Geoffrey York, of the Globe's Moscow bureau, in Moscow. The<br>
article occupies 2/3 of the front page of the section of the paper and all<br>
of page 4, where it goes to small print for a survey republic-by-republic. <br>
The situation in Georgia is described as being somewhat better than<br>
Armenia; that in Azerbaijan worse. Here is what is said about Armenia.<br>
	"Armenia was once regarded as one of the best hopes for democracy<br>
in the former Soviet Union. Its President, Levon Ter-Petrosyan, was a<br>
scholar and former dissident who had spent time in jail in the Soviet era. <br>
But in recent years, Armenia has slid inexorably toward authoritarian<br>
rule. In 1994, the biggest and oldest opposition party was banned, and<br>
dozens of its members were arrested on questionable charges. More than a<br>
dozen newspapers were closed, journalists were beaten and several<br>
newspaper offices were fire-bombed. The first post-Soviet parliamentary<br>
election was held last year, but foreign observers said it was unfair. Ten<br>
parties were banned from participating, widespread fraud was reported and<br>
independent candidates were subjected to violence and intimidation. The<br>
electoral commissions were controlled by the ruling party. Only a few<br>
parties were permitted to campaign, and they were given virtually no<br>
access to state media. A new constitution gave sweeping powers to the<br>
president: He can dissolve parliament, appoint and dismiss the prime<br>
minister and appoint all judges and court members. <br>
	"This year, Mr. Ter-Petrosyan has further tightened his grip. He<br>
claimed victory in presidential elections in September, but observers said<br>
they witnessed "systematic fraud on a massive scale." Ballot boxes were<br>
stolen by the President's supporters, and groups of soldiers were ordered<br>
to vote for the President, they said. The observers said the<br>
irregularities were enough to cast doubt on the President's claim of<br>
victory. Moreover, they said, the opposition candidates had very little<br>
access to state television.<br>
	"After the election, opposition protests became violent and the<br>
government sent tanks into the streets. Dozens of opponents were arrested<br>
and several political parties shut down. Police broke into the offices of<br>
opposition parties, beating and arresting their members. The main<br>
opposition candidate went into hiding because he feared arrest."<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
