<title>Groong Network: 1227aol.txt</title>
<h1>1227aol.txt</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>27 Dec 96 14:37:15 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#227">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#227">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#227">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#227">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0228.html">R.H. Lola Koundakjian: "Post-Communist Armenia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0226.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Armenpress Homepage"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/27/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
EDITOR'S NOTE: THE FOLLOWING ARTICLES APPEARED IN THE DEC. 27-28 <br>
COMBINED ISSUE. OUR NEXT POSTING WILL BE ON MONDAY, DEC. 30.<br>
<p>
<p>
1. PRESIDENT KOCHARIAN APPROVES NEW KARABAKH CABINET<br>
2. IRANIAN VICE-PRESIDENT ARRIVES IN ARMENIA<br>
3. HURRICANES RIP THROUGH SYUNIK AND LORI PROVINCES<br>
4. MINSK GROUP CO-CHAIRMAN ARRIVES IN ARMENIA<br>
5. CONSTRUCTION OF CARGO TERMINAL BEGINS AT ZVARTONOTS AIRPORT<br>
6. HCA TO FECILITATE DIALOGUE IN TRANSCAUCASUS CONFLICTS<br>
7. NEW SUBWAY STATION TO SERVICE 20,000 PASSENGERS<br>
8. TEACHER RE-TRAINING PROGRAM COMPLETED<br>
9. TURKEY SUSPENDS SEVEN POLICE OFFICERS IN SECURITY SCANDAL<br>
10. IRAQI PAPER ASSAILS TURKEY OVER US FLIGHTS<br>
<p>
<p>
1. PRESIDENT KOCHARIAN APPROVES NEW KARABAKH CABINET<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Newly-elected Nagorno-Karabakh President <br>
Robert Kocharian signed a decree Wednesday, naming the new <br>
cabinet.<br>
	Gerard Poghossian was appointed deputy prime minister.<br>
	Kocharian, who won by overwhelming majority to become the <br>
mountainous republics first-ever publicly elected president made <br>
the following appointments:<br>
	Minister of Health Care, Julia Logorian; Minister of Foreign <br>
Affairs, Arkady Ghoukassian; Minister of Agriculture, Valery <br>
Alexanian; Minister of Economy and Finance, Spartak Tevossian; <br>
Minister of Education and Science, Hamlet Assatrian; Minister of <br>
Internal Affairs, Karen Babayan; Minister of Construction, Edward <br>
Shahramanian; Minister of Defense, Samvel Babayan; Minister of <br>
Social Security, Serge Aroushanian; Minister of Justice, Yuri <br>
Hayrapetian; and Head of the Department for Statistics, State <br>
Register and Analysis, Oleg Yessayan.<br>
	The National Security and Privatization and Investments <br>
ministers had yet to be named as of press<br>
<p>
<p>
2. IRANIAN VICE-PRESIDENT ARRIVES IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Combined Sources)-Iran intends to maintain good <br>
neighborly relations will all countries in the Transcaucasus, <br>
including Armenia, Iranian Vice-President Hasan Habibi said <br>
Thursday upon his arrival to Yerevan.<br>
	Habibi, who is on a four-day official visit, conveyed <br>
Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjanis message to Ter-<br>
Petrosyan, emphasizing the importance of strengthening bilateral <br>
relations with Armenia.<br>
	Ter-Petrosyan expressed satisfaction with Irans balanced <br>
policy in the region.<br>
	The meeting underlined the importance of settling the <br>
Karabakh conflict and establishing peace in the Caucasus, and also <br>
touched upon specific issues of cooperation between the two <br>
countries, including trade, economic, scientific and cultural <br>
ties.<br>
	In his address to the National Assembly, the Iranian vice-<br>
president pointed to the joint Iranian-Armenian economic committee <br>
created in 1994, the construction of a bridge across the Arax <br>
River on the Iran-Armenia border, regular flights between the two <br>
capitals, and other existing cultural and trade and economic <br>
relations as symbols of mutual cooperation and understanding <br>
between the two countries.<br>
	"Today, we are in the process of constructing an Iran-<br>
Armenia natural gas pipeline, fiber-optic telephone communication <br>
lines, an oil refinery in Armenia for Iranian oil, to be sold in <br>
Armenia, and a dam and a hydroelectric plant on the Arax River," <br>
Habibi said.<br>
	With regard to regional political issues, Habibi said, "The <br>
existing instability is adversely affecting the short- and long-<br>
term interests of the countries and the peoples of the region, <br>
their cultural and national progress and, ultimately, their <br>
independence."<br>
	Habibi ruled out the use of force as a solution to existing <br>
regional problems.<br>
	During his meeting with Armenian Prime Minister Armen <br>
Sarkissian, Habibi said that although many bilateral programs have <br>
been implemented, there still remains an untapped reservoir in <br>
Iran-Armenia relations.<br>
	Habibi is expected to meet with businessmen and other high-<br>
level government officials.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. HURRICANES RIP THROUGH SYUNIK AND LORI PROVINCES<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Lragir)-A hurricane ripped through Armenias Syunik <br>
province Wednesday, uplifting power poles in Goris, which resulted <br>
in a power outage in Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
	Several power transmission poles and transformers were also <br>
damaged in Kapan, resulting in a loss of power to the area. The <br>
roofs of several homes, a hospital and a school were blown off as <br>
well.<br>
	The hurricane also started fires in the Baghaberd, Zork, <br>
Shahoumian and Shinararneri districts. Telephone communication <br>
between some of the villages was interrupted.<br>
	According to preliminary information provided by the City <br>
Council of Kapan, $16 million in damage was caused by the <br>
hurricane.<br>
	Strong winds caused significant damage in the Lori province <br>
on Thursday.<br>
	Over thirty communities in Tashir and Stepanavan experienced <br>
power outages when one hundred power lines were destroyed.<br>
	The winds blew off roofs of buildings in the Ruminakan <br>
[Romanian] district of Stepanavan and Ani district of Tashir.<br>
	Special rescue teams have been formed to help clean up the <br>
damage.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. MINSK GROUP CO-CHAIRMAN ARRIVES IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Respublica Armenia)-Russian co-chairman of the <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe Minsk Group, <br>
Yuri Yukalov, arrived in Yerevan Thursday.<br>
	Yukalov met with Foreign Minister Alexander Arzoumanian that <br>
same day. They discussed the problems related in the Karabakh <br>
negotiations following the OSCE Lisbon summit, as well as further <br>
activities of the Minsk Group.<br>
	Yukalov was expected to travel to Stepanakert and Baku that <br>
same day to meet with the heads of government.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. CONSTRUCTION OF CARGO TERMINAL BEGINS AT ZVARTONOTS AIRPORT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg)-Construction of a cargo terminal at the Zvartnots <br>
airport of Yerevan began Wednesday. The construction is funded by <br>
the US-based Billharberd company at a cost of $15.4 million.<br>
	The deputy head of the office implementing the construction, <br>
Karen Mkhitarian, said that according to the contract signed with <br>
the Dutch Cargo Service Center company, the employees of the <br>
terminal will receive special training in the Netherlands.<br>
	Once the construction is completed, Cargo Service Center <br>
will operate the terminal for the first year.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. HCA TO FECILITATE DIALOGUE IN TRANSCAUCASUS CONFLICTS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The Helsinki Citizen Assembly has planned to <br>
organize a meeting for relatives of those killed or missing in <br>
action during the conflicts in Transcaucasia.<br>
	Head of HCA Transcaucasia Office, Marten Van Garten, <br>
reported that the meeting would only be the beginning of a major <br>
program by the HCA aimed at bringing the conflicting sides <br>
together.<br>
	Van Garten suggested that the Azeris visit the graves of <br>
those killed during the war. According to the Azeris, the Armenian <br>
cemeteries in Azerbaijan are being protected and sanctions are <br>
being imposed for the defamation of graves.<br>
	Van Garten said that the implementation of these projects <br>
depends on the initiatives of local groups. "We just want to help <br>
these initiatives as there are many examples of similar contacts <br>
which are very helpful for the development of the peacemaking <br>
process," he said.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. NEW SUBWAY STATION TO SERVICE 20,000 PASSENGERS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg, Noyan Tapan)-Operation of the tenth station of the <br>
Yerevan subway in Charbakh started Wednesday.<br>
	The new line connects the city center with the predominantly <br>
blue-collar district of 20,000 people.<br>
	Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian, who was on hand at the <br>
opening ceremony, said that the government will allocate funds for <br>
the extension of the subway and the completion of the Achapniak <br>
station.<br>
	The new line starts from the Shengavit station and is 1,600 <br>
meters long. The station will serve up to 20,000 passengers a day.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. TEACHER RE-TRAINING PROGRAM COMPLETED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg)-Armenias Ministry of Education and Science has <br>
completed their two-and-a-half-month-long qualification testing of <br>
the republics teachers.<br>
	Of the 717 teachers tested from nine different provinces of <br>
Armenia-Lori, Armavir, Gegharkounik, Shirak, Aragatzotn, Ararat, <br>
Vayots-Dzor, Kotayk and Yerevan-only 219 passed.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. TURKEY SUSPENDS SEVEN POLICE OFFICERS IN SECURITY SCANDAL<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-Turkish Interior Minister Meral Aksener has <br>
suspended seven police officers in a security scandal over alleged <br>
links between authorities and organized crime, the interior <br>
ministry said in a statement on Thursday.<br>
	The seven, from several units in central and southern <br>
Turkey, are being questioned over claims they deliberately made no <br>
effort to arrest gangster Mehmet Ozcan and that they aided and <br>
abetted convicted criminals.<br>
	The interior ministry had said in the statement that Ozcan <br>
was still at large, but later confirmed he was now in custody.<br>
	Main opposition leader Mesut Yilmaz met prosecutors at <br>
Istanbul state security court on Thursday. Party aides said he <br>
handed over documents connected with the scandal.<br>
	Media reports say the documents confirm the existence of a <br>
network of 120 people directed by senior policemen and involved in <br>
murder, extortion and drug smuggling.<br>
	The Radikal newspaper said on Wednesday that a criminal gang <br>
headed by Ozcan had at one time been led by Abdullah Catli, a late <br>
mobster at the center of the scandal.<br>
	Convicted heroin smuggler Catli, who had been wanted for <br>
murder for 18 years, died last month in a traffic accident in the <br>
same car as a senior policeman and a member of parliament.<br>
	The subsequent scandal led to the resignation of Akseners <br>
predecessor at the interior ministry and the suspension of <br>
Istanbul police chief Kemal Yazicioglu.<br>
	The media says security officials and politicians have <br>
turned a blind eye to underworld activities and used gangsters to <br>
kill political opponents and business rivals.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. IRAQI PAPER ASSAILS TURKEY OVER US FLIGHTS<br>
<p>
BAGHDAD (Reuter)-An official Iraqi newspaper condemned Turkey on <br>
Thursday for allowing the United States and Britain to extend <br>
their use of its airbases to patrol the skies of northern Iraq.<br>
	"The Turkish decision is not independent and nationalist... <br>
It smells of a conspiracy against Iraq, said al-Thawra, organ of <br>
the ruling Baath party.<br>
	Turkish parliamentarians voted on Wednesday to give Islamist <br>
Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakans government the power to <br>
authorize continued flights over northern Iraq after the mandate <br>
for the current operation, known as Provide Comfort, expires on <br>
December 31.<br>
	US, French and British planes have been shielding Iraqs <br>
Kurds from Baghdad since hundreds of thousands of Kurds fled to <br>
Turkey and Iran after a failed uprising at the end of the 1991 <br>
Gulf War.<br>
	Thawra said Turkey adopted the decision as a result of <br>
"American and British threats and pressure. Even bribes were given <br>
in order to influence the Turkish policy.<br>
	A Turkish foreign ministry official said on Wednesday that <br>
France had decided to withdraw its support for the force. "Turkey <br>
should have taken an independent decision like that of <br>
France...France took part in setting up the so-called Hammer <br>
Force (in 1991) and participated in its activities but it is no <br>
more convinced of its tasks, the Iraqi newspaper said.<br>
	The White House said it was confident that France would soon <br>
rejoin the operation.<br>
	Last week the Iraqi ruling partys newspaper warned Ankara <br>
that bilateral ties would be damaged if Turkey extended the <br>
operation which uses Incirlik in southern Turkey as its airbase. <br>
	Turkey has been a major outlet for Iraqi oil to world <br>
markets since Iraq resumed limited exports via pipeline under an <br>
oil-for-food deal with the United Nations this month. Iraq was <br>
barred from exporting oil under UN sanctions imposed for its <br>
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.<br>
<p>
