<title>Groong Network: Revised 'Some impressions from HH Karekin I's Press Conf.'</title>
<h1>Revised 'Some impressions from HH Karekin I's Press Conf.'</h1>
<i>mrw@arminco.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 27 Dec 1996 14:32:54 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#224">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#224">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#224">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#224">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0225.html">Areg Gharabegian: "Armenia/Powergen:  Privatization"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0223.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Two items of interest from the Russian press"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yerevan, Monday, 23. December, 1996, 23:39<br>
<p>
To Hayastan, Groong,<br>
<p>
Due to hurry, many errors occurred in my first edition of "Some <br>
impressions from HH Karekin I's press conference 23 Dec". Please <br>
accept that I re-send the whole message. To all I wish to express my<br>
deepest wish, or "genats", that you Armenian culture and <br>
faith may flourish as in the "voskedareroum", that you may develop<br>
a more and more offensive - not defensive and apologetic - <br>
self identity, and that, finally, through common efforts "spjurk" and <br>
"hajrenik" will act as two well coordinated hands, well placed on<br>
the one and the same gifted person.<br>
<p>
Greetings<br>
Rev. Michael Westh<br>
&lt;mrw@arminco.com&gt; <br>
Yerevan  <br>
<p>
////////////////////Original, corrected message begin//////////////<br>
<p>
Some impressions from HH Karekin I's press conference, held <br>
in Etchmiadzin 23 December 12.00 - 14.00. Based on notes <br>
taken down during the press conference. I do not intend to give a<br>
picture of the interview isolated from the themes that have been <br>
raised on this list already as well as those in the news from <br>
for instance Reuters Bureau claiming, that at "1500 year old <br>
disagreement has found its solution".<br>
<p>
Greetings<br>
Rev. Michael Westh<br>
&lt;mrw@arminco.com&gt; <br>
Yerevan  <br>
<p>
First HH gave a presentation of the aims and themes of his visit to <br>
Rome. <br>
<p>
1.  His Holiness, Karekin I's visit to Rome took place not as an <br>
isolated phenomenon. Other Churches were represented in Rome <br>
as well. Thus the Georgian, the Russian and the Romanian Churches.<br>
<p>
2.  One day was set aside for meetings held within the framework of the <br>
World Council of Churches (WCC). <br>
<p>
3.  HH, after a short presentation of the history of the "ecumenical" <br>
movement after 1945, gave much attention to the need for <br>
the strengthening of this movement at the entrance to the 3 millennium <br>
after Christ. The WCC meetings were dedicated to further unity, especially <br>
concerning the Churches" common prayer, theological reflection, and <br>
ministry to their respective peoples.<br>
<p>
4.  The fellowship between the existing Churches is a true and necessary <br>
sign and testimony to the world, that Christ dwells in his Church (as <br>
according to John's Gospel chapter 17, where Christ prays that the <br>
believers may be one as the Son is one with the Father).<br>
<p>
5. Such fellowship, however, is already in existence. It is given already<br>
<p>
in Christ to the Church Universal. It needs not be created or organized <br>
though man's effort. <br>
<p>
6.  The Armenian Church should continue being active within the <br>
Ecumenical movement. The Armenian Church is about to celebrate its 1700 <br>
anniversary. This should not take place as a special people's special <br>
event without any connection with the rest of the world. This <br>
anniversary concerns the Church Universal as well as the Armenian <br>
Church, since the heritage of the Armenian is not a special Armenian one,<br>
it testifies, however,  in its own special way to the faith common to the <br>
Oriental Orthodox Churches, the Catholic, the Orthodox (Greek and Russian) as well <br>
as the (mainline?) Protestant Churches.<br>
<p>
7.  One of the important themes for the meetings with the Pope - adding <br>
to the need for a deeper fellowship between the represented churches - was <br>
the fast growing need for a new moral or ethical code in all spheres of life. <br>
The societies worldwide are highly alienated from a firmly <br>
established moral code. This is not only the problem to the Church, nor <br>
to other religions, but it is a problem to mankind.<br>
<p>
8.  There was a high degree of mutual understanding in many areas of <br>
discussion, not least the question of the nature of Christ: The same <br>
Christ, who was born, suffered and was crucified, is also true God, God's <br>
Logos. Thus, the teachings of the Armenian Church, and its stance from <br>
after Chalcedon in 451 in no way were given up. On the contrary. The <br>
Armenian position was understood and recognized by the Pope as <br>
orthodox teaching. HH's book "The Council of Chalcedon and the <br>
Armenian Church" was known to the other participants. There was agreement, <br>
that different types of language and categories being use, as well as <br>
political and polemical elements, highly added to the schism after 451.<br>
<p>
9.  Pope John Paul II, head of 900.000 believers, listened carefully <br>
and understand and appreciated the Armenian cause as presented to him.<br>
Such a firsthand presentation of the life and witness of the Armenian Church<br>
was a necessary element of the meetings, and it was received in the most <br>
positive way. <br>
<p>
<p>
This part reflects HH's answers to some questions raised:<br>
<p>
10.  The head of the Roman Church held the position, that <br>
the natures of Christ are not to be conceived of as two separately <br>
acting wills in Christ, as did the Nestorian Churches. The Armenian <br>
Church is (no longer) understood as a "monophysitic". It was admitted, <br>
that such "termini" were attached to the "Oriental Orthodox  Churches" <br>
due to lack of understanding of their real positions. That time, <br>
unfortunately was the time for polemic between churches, now is the <br>
time for dialogue. This was, however, not rhetoric. Even history,<br>
HH stressed show positive examples hereof.<br>
<p>
11.  All Churches face similar challenges in their respective lands, <br>
therefore the need for fellowship in prayer, reflection and ministry. <br>
This is the "positive" imperative for seeking fellowship. Separation is not needed. <br>
<p>
12.  There is likewise a need for re-evangelizing Armenia, and speeding <br>
up the Church's activities. This need stems from the lack of freedom <br>
religion and speech during 70 years of communist dominion  and the <br>
present activity of some Churches and groups in Armenia, with no <br>
contact to the Armenian Church. However, the need for Christian <br>
instruction should not primarily be motivated negatively as a kind of <br>
"re-action". In stead it is time for "action". It is time for positively <br>
and actively live out and make flourish all which lies in Armenian <br>
Christianity and culture, contributing to the Church Universal as well<br>
as to the world.<br>
///////////////////////END/////////////////////////<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
