<title>Groong Network: Two items of interest from the Russian press</title>
<h1>Two items of interest from the Russian press</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 27 Dec 1996 12:55:44 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#223">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#223">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#223">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#223">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0224.html">mrw@arminco.com: "Revised 'Some impressions from HH Karekin I's Press Conf.'"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0222.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/26/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1. Chechen oil (NeGa)<br>
2. Elections in Chechnya (Segodnya) <br>
<p>
Nezavisimaya Gazeta 27 December 1996 page 3<br>
<p>
   Report by Igor Rotar:  "The Foundation of Independence or a Menace?<br>
Chechen Oil Is Both"<br>
<p>
  At the time when Chechnya was, at least formally, controlled by Russian<br>
troops, local oil was stolen on a grand scale.  In an interview, the former<br>
head of the South Oil Company, the sole monopolist in producing and refining<br>
Chechen oil, made no secret of the fact that the greater part of the<br>
republic's "black gold" is still being embezzled.<br>
   Time has demonstrated that it is more difficult to place Chechen oil<br>
under control than to stop the war.  The power in Chechnya has changed, but<br>
under the new masters oil is being siphoned off with no less intensity than<br>
under the federal authorities.  In independent Chechnya-Ichkeria, home-made<br>
gasoline is traded everywhere.  This is done in a amazingly simple way:<br>
Regular crude oil is put into a kind of moonshine still, and refined.  The<br>
quality of the resultant product is very low but quite passable if the car<br>
owner does not particularly spare his vehicle.  Underground oil companies<br>
with their own employees and the necessary equipment operate in the<br>
republic.  There is a clear-cut specialization in the underground oil<br>
business:  Some engage in oil production; others, in oil refining, and still<br>
others, in trading it.  Normally a criminal group seizes an oil hole; hired<br>
workers extract oil while an armed detachment guards the site.  Small<br>
private oil refineries that are located in practically all populated areas<br>
are also guarded.  True, the "privatization" of oil holes is not the only<br>
and, most important, not the main method of getting rich.  There are also<br>
more primitive methods.  Thus, for example, complete miniature plants are<br>
set up near the pipeline to illegally siphon off oil. <br>
   Initially the new authorities intended to establish a monopoly in the oil<br>
business.  President Yandarbiyev of Chechnya-Ichkeria even issued an edict<br>
on fighting the misappropriation of oil products.  This, however, was where<br>
the fight stopped.  "This edict is not being implemented.  Approximately<br>
3,000 tonnes of oil are produced in Chechnya every day.  The market price of<br>
our oil is approximately $80 per tonne.  That is to say, every day we are<br>
losing some $240,000!" Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov, the newly appointed<br>
president of the South Oil Company, which is now a state company of<br>
Chechnya-Ichkeria, told your correspondent.<br>
   It is indicative that the Chechen-Ichkerian authorities have none of<br>
their former optimism about stopping the misappropriation of oil.  Today<br>
Groznyy has returned to its usual tactics, blaming Moscow for its woes.  "In<br>
principle we could easily stop the stealing of oil and the illegal<br>
production of oil products.  But today the 'oil business' has become almost<br>
the main source of income for the majority of Chechen families.  Thus far<br>
Moscow has not disbursed even a kopeck of the promised compensation.  There<br>
are no employment opportunities in the republic, and so to many the oil<br>
trade has become possibly the only way of sustaining their families,"<br>
Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov said. <br>
   It was planned to conclude a treaty on the joint transportation of oil,<br>
based on an agreement between the Chechen and Russian premiers, which was<br>
signed in Moscow on 1 December.  Yet for unknown reasons the treaty was<br>
never signed.  Neither is it clear what share of profit from the oil transit<br>
Chechnya will retain.  "I believe that we should get approximately<br>
one-seventh to one-eight part of the profit:  This is just about the<br>
proportion of the pipeline stretch that passes across the Chechen<br>
territory," Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov believes.  This point of view, however,<br>
is not shared by Boris Pastukhov, first deputy foreign minister of the<br>
Russian Federation:  "It is not quite correct to assess the profit from the<br>
transportation of oil in relation to the length of the pipeline.   For<br>
instance, if a pumping station is located on a small stretch of a pipeline,<br>
the share of profit on this section sharply increases.  So, the question of<br>
what share of profit the Chechen authorities are entitled to calls for<br>
additional negotiations." <br>
   Yet in light of the mounting wave of crimes in Chechnya profit sharing is<br>
perceived as a purely abstract question. <br>
(end)<br>
<p>
Segodnya 27 December 1996 page 3<br>
<p>
   Report by Mariya Roshchina:  "No Single Candidate for Ichkerian President<br>
Could Be Found.  All Candidates, Excepting Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, Must Step<br>
Down From Their Posts"<br>
<p>
  Yesterday a meeting of the candidates for Chechen president was held in<br>
Groznyy.  Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, Aslan Maskhadov, Movladi Udugov, Shamil<br>
Basayev, and Akhmed Zakayev tried to reach an agreement on nominating one<br>
single candidate.  The meeting was attended by a mufti [Muslim cleric] so as<br>
to have every candidate -- should they decide to run for president on their<br>
own -- take an oath on the Koran that they would abide by the results of the<br>
27 January elections.  After the three-hour talks in the residence of<br>
President Yandarbiyev the candidates parted company, pledging to resume<br>
discussions on the subject next week, Mr. Udugov said.  Participants in the<br>
meeting, which was dubbed the "Meeting of Five," issued a joint appeal to<br>
the residents of the republic, reaffirming their unity and calling on the<br>
Chechens "to pay no heed to idle talk," in particular, about an alleged<br>
split in the Ichkerian leadership.  The appeal points out that regardless of<br>
how the problem of nominating a single candidate is resolved or what results<br>
the elections might yield, all the members of the "Group of Five" "will work<br>
as a single team" with the winner.<br>
   If no single candidate can be named, all the contenders, except for the<br>
incumbent president, will have to step down from their current posts.  The<br>
Chechen Central Electoral Commission demanded that yesterday, invoking the<br>
republic's electoral law.  Shaaman Akbulatov, press secretary of the Chechen<br>
Central Electoral Commission, explained that the republic's Constitution<br>
does not call for the president to resign during his election campaign.<br>
According to Shaaman Akbulatov, the other candidates, including Prime<br>
Minister Aslan Maskhadov, have already announced their readiness to resign<br>
from their posts.  Now these decisions are due to be formalized by<br>
presidential edict.<br>
   In the meantime, the nomination of candidates for the Chechen parliament<br>
continues.  In each of a total of 63 districts from 10 to 20 candidates have<br>
been fielded both by parties and individually.  Independent candidates must<br>
collect 300 signatures to be officially registered by the Central Electoral<br>
Commission.<br>
   Yet it seems that the hope that all Chechens, regardless of their place<br>
of residence, would be able to vote for the president and parliament of<br>
Chechnya are not destined to come true.  Ruslan Kutayev, minister for ties<br>
with CIS countries and Russia, said yesterday that polling stations would,<br>
in all likelihood, be opened only in Ingushetia and Dagestan.  In Dagestan,<br>
a polling station is due to be opened in the district center of Khasavyurt;<br>
and in Ingushetia, in the village of Sleptsovskaya.  The Chechens living in<br>
Moscow, Kazakhstan, Ukraine, or southern Russia will not be able to vote,<br>
Mr. Kutayev said, because of the shortage of funds.  Furthermore, it is<br>
believed in Groznyy that the Chechens who live outside Chechnya are<br>
"pro-Russian minded and will vote for the candidates who suit Moscow best."<br>
   Boris Berezovskiy, deputy secretary of the Russian Security Council,<br>
analyzing the candidates' views, concluded, however, that only the incumbent<br>
Chechen president, Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, would be dangerous for Russia.<br>
Aslan Maskhadov, Movladi Udugov, Shamil Basayev, and Akhmed Zakayev cannot<br>
imagine their republic outside Russia and without Russia, Boris Berezovskiy<br>
told the "Ekho Moskvy" radio station yesterday.  They all understand that<br>
the current goings-on in Chechnya amount to a complete lack of the rule of<br>
law, which can only be ended by legitimate elections.<br>
   Yet it is Chechnya's no-holds-barred developments that could call the<br>
legitimacy of the elections into question:  It is doubtful that Russian and<br>
international observers will go to Chechnya.  The Russian State Duma has<br>
already declined to send its observers.  The joint commission, operating on<br>
the basis of the Russian Security Council's authority, is due to dispatch<br>
its own observers to monitor elections in Chechnya, but no volunteers have<br>
yet showed up to go to the republic.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
