<title>Groong Network: Russian Defense Minister Is Looking for Adversaries</title>
<h1>Russian Defense Minister Is Looking for Adversaries</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 26 Dec 1996 14:29:55 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#221">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#221">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#221">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#221">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0222.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/26/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0220.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Armenpress homepage"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Kommersant-Daily 26 December 1996 page 1<br>
<p>
   Report by Aleksandr Korzhakov:  "The Defense Minister Is Looking for<br>
Adversaries"<br>
<p>
  Yesterday -- for the first time since the breakup of the Warsaw Pact --<br>
Russia, through its defense minister, attempted to pinpoint the countries<br>
that currently which pose military danger to the CIS, including Russia.  A<br>
danger that might evolve into an immediate military threat.  In other words,<br>
Igor Rodionov for the first time listed the so-called most likely<br>
adversaries of Moscow.  They include the United States, the NATO bloc,<br>
separately Turkey.  Next come Iran, Pakistan, Japan, and China.  A motley<br>
crew, to be sure.<br>
   Few could have suggested that Rodionov's report at the conference on the<br>
CIS strategic partnership could essentially turn into a conceptual summary<br>
of the Defense Ministry leadership's general vision of the political<br>
situation in the world.  But there you go, just yesterday, addressing<br>
delegations of the CIS countries' defense ministries, the head of the<br>
Russian Defense Ministry for the first time proposed a number of joint<br>
preventive measures to stave off possible military threats to the Commonwealth.<br>
   The assessment of the situation, as done by Rodionov, was fully<br>
traditional for the Russian military ministry:  First among countries that<br>
could potentially threaten not only Russia, but the entire CIS was the<br>
United States, which is striving toward an unrivaled world leadership.<br>
Naturally, next comes NATO.  In the minister's view, the alliance is just "a<br>
serious challenge to the present-day realities and a potential source of<br>
danger, which could evolve into a military threat."  The situation on the<br>
CIS' southern and southeastern borders is just as tense:  Due to the<br>
continuing buildup of offensive weapons and the desire of "certain regional<br>
centers of power" to expand their zones of influence by "diminishing the<br>
importance of the CIS states," Turkey, Iran, Pakistan, Japan, China, and a<br>
number of other countries -- that were not named by the minister --<br>
represent increasing military danger.<br>
   Curiously, "Rodionov's list" includes at least two countries with which<br>
Russia is linked by large-scale trade, economic, and military contacts.<br>
Whatever the defense minister might say about potential threats, he cannot<br>
deny that the continuing buildup of offensive weapons in Asia, which has<br>
caused the Defense Ministry's anxiety, occurs with Russia's most active<br>
involvement.  Moreover, with the involvement of the minister himself or his<br>
deputies (a signature of one of them is necessary for any contract on arms<br>
exports to be valid).  The inclusion of China -- the main importer of<br>
Russian weapons -- on the list of "the most likely adversaries" could bode<br>
serious troubles in store for Rodionov.  The reason is that the minister's<br>
utterances are unlikely to contribute to the success of Chinese Premier Li<br>
Peng's visit to Moscow, which is due to take place shortly.  This also<br>
applies to Iran, included by Rodionov on the "black list," although just a<br>
day earlier Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeniy Primakov returned from a<br>
Tehran visit, which was to have given a new boost to economic and political<br>
dialogue between Moscow and Tehran.  On the whole, the minister is out of<br>
step with the rest, to put it mildly.<br>
   Possibly, the minister just wanted to cite "live examples" to his CIS<br>
colleagues to show that in the emerging military-political situation all CIS<br>
members should do their utmost so as to retain the "sufficient" potential of<br>
the strategic nuclear forces and to rally around Russia for this purpose.<br>
At the same time, the Russian Strategic Nuclear Forces were portrayed as a<br>
joint nuclear shield for all the Commonwealth countries, which, as is well<br>
known, they are still not.  The minister also called for work to be stepped<br>
up to create a joint air defense system as well as the systems of<br>
intelligence and command and control for "coalition groups of forces."  The<br>
last are necessary in order to ensure collective security and will be<br>
created as soon as next year.  But given that the CIS countries, as the<br>
minister put it, took so long "to understand the evolution of strategic<br>
partnership and military-political integration," there can be no guarantees<br>
that the urgent measures to restore the strategic parity he enumerated will<br>
be realized any time soon at least within the continent's expanses.<br>
   Judging by yesterday's statement by Uzbekistani President Islam Karimov,<br>
however, it will rather be the other way around.  Speaking in Tashkent --<br>
yet unaware of Rodionov's report -- he flatly rejected any possibility of<br>
creating a military-political bloc within the CIS," including as a<br>
counterbalance to NATO expansion.  Other CIS countries are not rushing to<br>
hide under Russia's "military umbrella" either; furthermore, many of them<br>
pursue foreign policy that is, to put it mildly, not in line with that of<br>
Moscow.  Their foreign policy priorities feature many a country from<br>
"Rodionov's list," first  and foremost Turkey.  In short, as Leo Tolstoy<br>
used to say about novelist Leonid Andreyev:  "He is trying to scare me, but<br>
I don't feel frightened."<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
