<!-- name="mrw@arminco.com" -->
<!-- email="mrw@arminco.com" -->
<!-- subject="Some impressions from HH Karekin I's press conference 23 Dec" -->
<!-- id="199612260452.XAA16572@ararat.bu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Groong Network: Some impressions from HH Karekin I's press conference 23 Dec</title>
<h1>Some impressions from HH Karekin I's press conference 23 Dec</h1>
<i>mrw@arminco.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 25 Dec 1996 23:52:23 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#218">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#218">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#218">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#218">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0219.html">Shahe N. Sanentz: "JAAIP #5"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0217.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 25)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yerevan, Monday, 23. December, 1996, 23:39<br>
<p>
To Hayastan,<br>
<p>
Some impressions from HH Karekin I's press conference, held <br>
Etchmiadzin 23 December 12.00 - 14.00. This is bases on notes I have <br>
taken down during the press conference. I do not intend to give an <br>
picture of the interview isolated from the themes that have already been <br>
raised on this list and in the news from for instance Reuters Bureau, <br>
that has claimed, that at "1500 year old disagreement has found its <br>
solution".<br>
<p>
Greetings<br>
Rev. Michael Westh<br>
&lt;mrw@arminco.com&gt; <br>
Yerevan  <br>
<p>
First HH gave a presentation of the aims and themes of his visit to <br>
Rome. <br>
<p>
1.  The visit to Rome took place not as an isolated phenomenon. Other <br>
Churches were gathered in Rome as well. Thus the Georgian, <br>
Russian and Romanian Churches (maybe others)<br>
2.  One day was set aside for meetings held within the framework of the <br>
World Council of Churches (WCC). <br>
3.  HH then, after a short presentation of the history of the "ecumenical" <br>
movement after 1945, gave much attention to the need for <br>
strengthening this movement the entrance to the 3 millennium after <br>
Christ. The WWC meetings especially were dedicated further <br>
developments in the Churches" common _prayer_, _reflection_, and <br>
_ministry_ to their respective peoples.<br>
4.  True fellowship between churches is a true and necessary sign in the <br>
world, that Christ dwells here (as according to John's Gospel <br>
chapter 17).<br>
5.  However, such a fellowship is already in existence and given in <br>
Christ to the Church Universal. It is not to be created by man's <br>
effort, or organized. <br>
6.  The Armenian Church should be active within the Ecumenical <br>
movement. The Armenian Church is about to celebrate its 1700 <br>
anniversary. This should not take place as a special people's special <br>
event without any connection with the rest of the world. This <br>
anniversary concerns the Church Universal as well as the Armenian <br>
Church, since its heritage is not a special Armenian but testifies to <br>
the faith common to the Oriental Orthodox, the Catholic, the <br>
Orthodox (Greek and Russian) as well as (some) Protestant <br>
Churches.<br>
7.  One of the important themes for the meetings - adding to the need <br>
for a deeper fellowship between the represented churches - was the <br>
fast growing need for a new moral or ethical code in all aspects of <br>
life in a world, that is highly alienated from firmly established moral <br>
code. This is not only the problem of the Church, nor other religions <br>
but it is the problem of mankind.<br>
8.  There was a high degree of mutual understanding in many areas of <br>
discussion, not least the question of the nature of Christ: The same <br>
Christ, was born, suffered and was crucified, is also true God, Gods <br>
Logos. The teaching of the Armenian Church, and its stance from <br>
after Chalcedon in 451was not given up. On the contrary, the <br>
Armenian position was understood and recognized (by the Pope) as <br>
orthodox teaching. HH's book "The Council of Chalcedon and the <br>
Armenian Church" was known to the other participants. There was <br>
agreement, that different type of language and categories, as well as <br>
political  and polemical element highly added to the schism after 451<br>
9.  Pope John Paul II, the head of 900.000 believers listened carefully <br>
and understand the Armenian cause as presented to him by HH<br>
10.  The head of the Roman Church expressed the understanding, that <br>
the natures of Christ are not to be conceived of as two separately <br>
acting wills in Christ, as did the Nestorian Churches. The Armenian <br>
Church is not understood as a "monophysitic", and it was admitted, <br>
that this "terminus" was attached to the "Oriental Orthodox  <br>
Churches" without real understanding of their positions. Then was <br>
the time for polemic between churches, now is the time for dialogue.<br>
11.  All Churches face similar challenges in their respective lands, <br>
therefore the need for fellowship in prayer, reflection and ministry. <br>
Separation is not needed. <br>
12.  There is likewise a need for re-evangelizing Armenia, and speeding <br>
up the Church's activities. This need stems from the lack of freedom <br>
religion and speech during 70 years of communist dominion  and the <br>
present activity of some Churches and groups in Armenia, with no <br>
contact to the Armenian Church. However, the need for Christian <br>
instruction should not primarily be motivated negatively as a kind of <br>
"re-action". In stead it is time for "action".<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
