<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-24-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-24-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>24 Dec 96 19:32:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#214">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#214">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#214">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#214">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0215.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 24)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/24/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/24/1996<br>
<p>
EDITOR'S NOTE: Asbarez will be closed tomorrow for Christmas. Our <br>
next posting will be Thursday, December 26, 1996. Merry Christmas <br>
and have a safe holiday.<br>
<p>
<p>
1. FOREIGN MINISTRY ISSUES STATEMENT ON RECENT BLUNDER<br>
2. KAREKIN I DISCUSSES RECENT POPE MEETING<br>
3. RUSSIAN DEFENSE MINISTER VISITS BAKU<br>
4. WORLD BANK TO ALLOCATE NEW CREDITS TO ARMENIA<br>
5. OCALAN CALLS FOR DIALOGUE WITH TURKEY<br>
6. CIS COMMISSION CONSIDERS LAWS ON FIGHTING MAFIA<br>
7. EBRD APPROVES LOANS FOR AZERBAIJAN<br>
8. BLACK SEA YOUTH COMMISSION TO MEET<br>
9. GROUP WARNS OF MILITARY CONVERAGE<br>
10. US VOICES CONCERN OVER TURKISH-IRAN TIES<br>
<p>
<p>
1. FOREIGN MINISTRY ISSUES STATEMENT ON RECENT BLUNDER<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-At a recent environmental conference, head <br>
of the Armenian delegation, Minister of Ecology Souren Avetissian <br>
signed a joint statement issued at the conference, Armenias <br>
Foreign Ministry announced.<br>
	The second Conference of Ministers of Environmental <br>
Protection of Central Asia, Caucasus and Balkan States took place <br>
Dec. 16-18 in the Turkish capital of Istanbul.<br>
	A total of 13 delegations including delegations of the self-<br>
proclaimed Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus and the Republic of <br>
Macedonia-Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia-attended the <br>
conference.<br>
	According to the Foreign Ministry statement, "the Republic <br>
of Armenia proceeding from resolutions of the United Nations and <br>
other international organizations, recognizes the Former Yugoslav <br>
Republic of Macedonia only under its international name and voices <br>
hope that all issues related to the name of this state will be <br>
settled through peaceful negotiations mediated by the United <br>
Nations and mutual compromise."<br>
	"Our country remains faithful to its principle position <br>
which has been uttered for many times...the problem of Cyprus must <br>
be settled within the framework of relevant UN resolutions. The <br>
Republic of Armenia will not recognize any other government, but <br>
the legal leadership of Cyprus," the Foreign Ministry statement <br>
said.<br>
	In addition, "the Foreign Ministry of the Republic of <br>
Armenia informs that it did not entrust the Ministry of Ecology of <br>
the Republic of Armenia to sign any documents under which the <br>
self-proclaimed Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus put its <br>
signature."<br>
	"While encouraging regional cooperation in the field of <br>
environmental protection, the Foreign Ministry of the Republic of <br>
Armenia considers inadmissible any politicization of conferences <br>
dealing with this important problem," the statement concluded.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. KAREKIN I DISCUSSES RECENT POPE MEETING<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Having established a cooperation between the <br>
Catholic and the Armenian Apostolic Churches, the Armenian <br>
Apostolic Church does not discard religious controversies existing <br>
between the two Churches, Catholicos of All Armenians, Karekin I <br>
said, commenting on the joint declaration signed  the during his <br>
visit with Pope John Paul II at the Vatican.<br>
	"We still do not recognize the Chalcedon Council. However, <br>
the historically inherited controversies and dissensions should <br>
not be an impediment in the way of uniting  the two Churches, <br>
which at the same time does not mean becoming similar. The <br>
unification is Gods will," His Holiness said.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. RUSSIAN DEFENSE MINISTER VISITS BAKU<br>
<p>
BAKU (Azg)-Russian Defense Minister Igor Rodionov visited Baku on <br>
Monday to discuss military collaboration with Azerbaijan. Rodionov <br>
said that Russia will do its best to promote the development of <br>
friendly relations between the two countries.<br>
	Rodionov said that the negotiations will center on bilateral <br>
relations, particularly on collaboration in the defense sector. He <br>
said that several agreements have already been signed between <br>
Russia and Azerbaijan regarding defense, but the goal of the <br>
current visit was to more clearly define their details. Rodionov <br>
planned to discuss Russian use of the Gabeline radar station with <br>
Azeri President Gaidar Aliyev.<br>
	The Gabeline radar station was built in Azerbaijan as part <br>
of the Soviet Unions military/strategic monitoring system during <br>
the Cold War.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. WORLD BANK TO ALLOCATE NEW CREDITS TO ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The World Bank will allocate loans for six <br>
new programs of economic development for Armenia for the coming <br>
year, World Bank representative in Armenia, Vahram Nersissiants <br>
said.<br>
	During his visit to Armenia last week, Director of the World <br>
Banks Eastern Europe and Central Asia Section, Basil Kawalski, <br>
expressed the World Banks eagerness to continue and extend <br>
cooperation with Armenia.<br>
	Nersissiants said that Armenia would be given loans by the <br>
World Banks International Development Association from the so-<br>
called "window of free long-term loans." The loans are due for <br>
repayment in 35 years with a grace period of 10 years.<br>
	The World Bank has allocated loans for nine economic <br>
programs as well as earmarking a grant for a rehabilitation <br>
program for the ecology of Lake Sevan. According to Nersissiants, <br>
the total loans allocated to Armenia will total nearly <br>
$500,000,000.<br>
	One of the programs, Enterprise Development Credit Program, <br>
will be approved by the Council of the World Bank in the near <br>
future. The cost of the program is $16.75 million. Sums designated <br>
for other programs have not yet been specified.<br>
	Earthquake Rehabilitation Credit Program ($28,000,000) is <br>
expected soon. Nersissiants reported that restoration works in the <br>
earthquake area would continue due to the Municipal Social Sector <br>
Credit Program. This program provides for the restoration of <br>
housing and water supply systems both in the earthquake area and <br>
Yerevan.<br>
	In 1997, the World Bank will continue Structural Adjustment <br>
Credit Program. Besides, the World Bank is likely to allot loans <br>
under the program of formation of agricultural infrastructures. <br>
Also, Health Care and Education Reform Support Credit will be <br>
approved for Armenia next year.<br>
	Nersissiants reported that the negotiations were being held <br>
with the World Bank on allocation of "a grant for culture" which <br>
will be made for the National Opera and Ballet Theater of Armenia.<br>
	According to Nersissiants the World Bank rarely provides <br>
grants for culture, however, in former Soviet republics where <br>
culture is highly regarded, cultural reforms have acquired <br>
economic significance.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. OCALAN CALLS FOR DIALOGUE WITH TURKEY<br>
<p>
DIYABAKIR, Turkey (Reuter)-Kurdish leader Abdullah Ocalan renewed <br>
calls for a lasting solution to 12 years of conflict in southeast <br>
Turkey in a television interview broadcast on Monday.<br>
	"I want there to be a way for dialogue in 1997. Without <br>
putting forward any pre-conditions, I invite the Turkish state to <br>
a solution of the Kurdish problem by political means," the <br>
Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) chief said in the interview <br>
broadcast by Belgian-based Med-TV.<br>
	Ocalan said Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan had <br>
made various initiatives for dialogue with the rebels after he <br>
came to power in June, but that these had since been abandoned. <br>
	Turkish governments and the military have often refused <br>
direct negotiations with the PKK, which they regard as a terrorist <br>
group. A unilateral rebel cease-fire declared last year was <br>
ignored by Turkey.<br>
	Ocalan said the PKK was trying to find a party leader or <br>
government official with whom they could talk and repeated <br>
assurances that he had dropped demands for a separate Kurdish <br>
state on Turkish soil.<br>
	"I want the problem to be solved by political means, within <br>
Turkeys national borders," he said.<br>
	Ocalan, also known as "Apo," threatened more suicide <br>
bombings in Turkeys major cities if what he called the repression <br>
of the Kurdish people continued.<br>
	"This time we will send hundreds of Kurds into the big <br>
cities. Its not a difficult thing for a guerrilla with a bomb to <br>
get on a bus or a plane, or infiltrate into a crowded place," he <br>
said.<br>
	Ten people, mostly members of the security forces, were <br>
killed in two suicide bombings in Turkish cities at the end of <br>
October and 10 soldiers were killed by a human bomb in eastern <br>
Turkey in July.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. CIS COMMISSION CONSIDERS LAWS ON FIGHTING MAFIA<br>
<p>
BAKU (Itar-Tass)-The Commonwealth of Independent States Inter-<br>
Parliamentary Assemblys commission in charge of working out <br>
recommendations on fighting organized crime in member countries <br>
held a meeting in the Azeri capital of Baku on Saturday.<br>
	The meeting was attended by parliamentarians from nine of <br>
the 12 CIS states, including Russia.<br>
	Participants stressed that laws on fighting organized crime <br>
are necessitated by the current situation in post-Soviet republics <br>
which have been swept by crime and corruption.<br>
	They stressed that only joint efforts can stop organized <br>
crime. <br>
	The commission approved several laws aimed at improving <br>
investigative activities and providing better protection for <br>
victims, witnesses and other persons who help in investigations.<br>
	The participants also discussed laws on combating corruption <br>
and terrorism, and on the protection of law enforcement people.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. EBRD APPROVES LOANS FOR AZERBAIJAN<br>
<p>
LONDON (Itar-Tass)-The European Bank for Reconstruction and <br>
Development issued a $13.7 million loan to Azerbaijan on Monday to <br>
help improve its airline infrastructure.<br>
	The loan will be used to increase the capacity of <br>
Azerbaijans airports, modernize their air-traffic controls and <br>
improve the safety of air transportation.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. BLACK SEA YOUTH COMMISSION TO MEET<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-A meeting, initiated by the international <br>
organization "Young People" and the Helsinki Citizen Assembly has <br>
been planned between youth organization representatives of the <br>
Black Sea basin on the border of Ijevan-Kazakh.<br>
	HCA coordinator for the Caucasus, Marten Van Garten, said <br>
that the meeting must contribute to ties between youth <br>
organizations of Georgia, Armenia, Azerbaijan, as well as Balkan <br>
states, Ukraine, Moldova and Russia.<br>
	"This action is aimed at reconciling, developing the level <br>
of relations between citizens and establishing democracy," Van <br>
Garten said. According to him, this meeting may be viewed as a <br>
sort of a youth congress that speaks out on behalf of citizens.<br>
	He noted that the meeting can become a continuation of a <br>
symbolic corridor between Ijevan and Kazakh that was opened in <br>
December of 1992 at the meeting of mothers and wives of Armenian <br>
and Azeri prisoners of war.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. GROUP WARNS OF MILITARY CONVERAGE<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-A Turkish broadcasting watchdog body warned <br>
television channels on Tuesday about their reporting of the <br>
military in a widening security scandal.<br>
	"Media organs must fulfill their legal obligations... <br>
Broadcasting must respect constitutional principles and democratic <br>
rules," the Radio and Television Supreme Council said in a <br>
statement.<br>
	The council, which has the authority to temporarily halt <br>
television broadcasts, said it was examining reports "covering <br>
some unfounded allegations and statements about the Turkish armed <br>
forces."<br>
	The media last week reported rumors that the military might <br>
intervene to clear up a scandal over alleged ties between <br>
officials and far-right gangsters. The influential armed forces <br>
have denied the charges.<br>
	The scandal erupted in November after a senior policeman and <br>
a gangster died in an accident in the same car. A government <br>
deputy who heads a militia that fights Kurds was injured in the <br>
crash.<br>
	Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakans coalition government last <br>
month threatened to clamp down on press criticism of state <br>
officials but a planned draft law restricting the media has yet to <br>
be debated in parliament.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. US VOICES CONCERN OVER TURKISH-IRAN TIES<br>
<p>
WASHINGTON (Reuter)-The United States voiced concern Monday at <br>
NATO ally Turkeys decision to sign economic agreements with Iran <br>
last week in defiance of US calls to isolate Tehran.<br>
	"We remain concerned ... by all efforts to intensify <br>
cooperative relations with Iran until Tehran reforms its <br>
unacceptable international policies," State Department spokesman <br>
Glyn Davies said.<br>
	The United States accuses Iran of being the most active <br>
state sponsor of anti-Western terrorism. It also faults Tehran for <br>
opposing the Middle East process and allegedly seeking to acquire <br>
weapons of mass destruction.<br>
	"The Turkish government knows well our concerns, we <br>
communicate them to them frequently, and we will maintain an <br>
active dialogue with the government of Turkey," Davies told <br>
reporters at the departments daily briefing.<br>
	The agreements, designed to double trade between Turkey and <br>
Iran to $2 billion, were signed near the end of a four-day visit <br>
to Turkey last week by Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.<br>
	Turkey has repeatedly ignored US warning regarding relations <br>
with Iran and continues to develop ties with that nation.<br>
	Turkey also went against US wishes over the summer during an <br>
Iraqi attack on Kurdish settlements in Northern Iraq on the <br>
Turkish border.<br>
<p>
