Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Foreign Minister Primakov against foreign military presence in Persian<br>
Gulf <br>
2.  Government source defends possible arms sales to Iran <br>
3.  Armenian nuclear power plant to have another power unit <br>
4.  New criminal links to police unveiled in Turkish mafia scandal <br>
5.  Russian Defence Minister Visits Azerbaijan <br>
6.  Cooperation with Vatican Does Not Erase Identity-Catholicos <br>
7.  Accord on Russian-Azeri Military Cooperation Not Signed <br>
8.  Azerbaijan Upgrades Air Navigation System with EBRD Loan <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Foreign Minister Primakov against foreign military presence in<br>
Persian Gulf <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1534 gmt 22 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeniy Primakov has said that the Persian Gulf<br>
region should become "a zone of peace and stability" and devoid of foreign<br>
military presence. Speaking in Tehran after meeting his Iranian counterpart,<br>
he expressed support for Iran's desire to normalize its relations with the<br>
United Arab Emirates and other Gulf states. He said Iran should be a<br>
full-fledged member of the world community, and gave an assurance vc that the<br>
development of relations between Moscow and Tehran is not directed against<br>
the USA. Primakov also held an hour-long meeting with the Iranian president,<br>
with whom he discussed bilateral relations and President Yeltsin's health. <br>
<p>
Iranian president receives Primakov  (Text of report by Itar-Tass news<br>
agency)<br>
<p>
Itar-Tass correspondent Konstantin Kazeyev: President Ali Akbar<br>
Hashemi-Rafsanjani of Iran today received Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeniy<br>
Primakov, who is here on a two-day official visit. During hour-long talks the<br>
two men exchanged views on bilateral cooperation. <br>
<p>
The Russian foreign minister handed Hashemi-Rafsanjani a personal message<br>
from Russian President Boris Yeltsin. <br>
<p>
The president of the Islamic Republic of Iran inquired about Yeltsin' s<br>
health after the operation. He expressed satisfaction at the Russian leader's<br>
recovery. <br>
<p>
Yevgeniy Primakov also held talks with Ali Akbar Nateq-Nuri, the speaker of<br>
the Iranian parliament or Majlis today. <br>
<p>
Primakov speaks against foreign military presence in Persian Gulf <br>
<p>
Excerpt from report by Itar-Tass news agency <br>
<p>
Itar-Tass correspondent Konstantin Kazeyev: Mutual understanding between<br>
Russia and Iran is of vast importance for a peaceful settlement of the<br>
conflicts in Afghanistan, Tajikistan and region as a whole, Russian Foreign<br>
Minister Yevgeniy Primakov said after talks with his Iranian counterpart, Ali<br>
Akbar Velayati. <br>
<p>
At a news conference held in Tehran on Sunday night [22nd December], the<br>
ministers spoke about the proximity of the two countries' stances on the<br>
whole range of international issues. "We are glad to acknowledge the fact<br>
that our relations are developing in a positive direction," Primakov<br>
emphasized. <br>
<p>
There should be no foreign military presence in the Persian Gulf and the<br>
region should become a zone of peace and stability. This is in the interests<br>
of both Russia and Iran, Primakov said. The Russian Federation fully supports<br>
the aspirations of the Islamic Republic of Iran to normalize relations with<br>
the United Arab Emirates and other Persian Gulf states, Primakov emphasized. <br>
<p>
Ali Akbar Velayati described the atmosphere of the talks as one of<br>
friendliness and mutual trust. "Our relations are at the highest point for<br>
the last two centuries," Velayati believes. The coordination of policy and<br>
the establishment of mutual understanding between Moscow and Tehran are<br>
important stabilizing factors not only for the Central Asian region, but for<br>
the world as whole, the Iranian foreign minister said. <br>
<p>
At the same time he expressed his belief that it is first of all up to the<br>
countries of the region to ensure security in the Persian Gulf zone... <br>
<p>
Primakov says Russia and Iran will never plot against anyone <br>
<p>
Excerpt from report by Interfax news agency <br>
<p>
Both Russia and Iran are interested in preventing a greater military presence<br>
in the Persian Gulf and ensuring stability and peace there, Russian Foreign<br>
Minister Yevgeniy Primakov told a news conference in Tehran on Sunday [22nd<br>
December], following talks with the Iranian foreign minister. <br>
<p>
"The Russian side gladly met Iran's expressed willingness to improve<br>
relations both with the United Arab Emirates and other states in the Gulf<br>
area," Primakov said. "We believe that Iran should be a full-fledged member<br>
of the world community, and in this respect we welcome its contacts with<br>
other countries," he said. <br>
<p>
Primakov said Moscow and Tehran were united in their goal of stabilizing the<br>
region. Russian-Iranian cooperation in normalizing the situation and bringing<br>
about stability in Afghanistan, Tajikistan and Nagornyy Karabakh is very<br>
important from this point of view, he said. <br>
<p>
In comment on the situation in the Middle East, Primakov hoped that all the<br>
countries will observe all Oslo agreements. Russia also backs observance of<br>
all verbal accords with respect to Syria and Israel, he said. "We oppose any<br>
actions and plans which may hamper the peace process in the Middle East,"<br>
Primakov stated. <br>
<p>
Speaking about Russian-Iranian relations, he said they "are developing<br>
satisfactorily".  He was satisfied with "the degree of confidence which<br>
exists" between Moscow and Tehran. The development of Russian-Iranian<br>
relations is not directed against the United States, Primakov had told<br>
reporters upon his arrival in Baghdad [as received]. "We will never<br>
mastermind a plot against anyone," he said. <br>
<p>
For his part, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati told the news<br>
conference that security in the Gulf area should be secured by the Gulf<br>
states themselves. Velayati called on the Gulf states for closer cooperation<br>
and elimination of all differences on a peaceful basis. This is the best<br>
means to prevent giving other states a pretext to interfere in the Gulf<br>
states' affairs, he said... <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Government source defends possible arms sales to Iran <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1559 gmt 20 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Russia does not rule out possible conclusion of new military contracts with<br>
Iran, a source in the Russian government told Interfax on Friday [20th<br>
December]. "This will depend on how the post-COCOM [Coordinating Committee<br>
for Multilateral Export Controls] order develops and what place Russia will<br>
have in it," the source said. <br>
<p>
"We believe that in this case there should be no discrimination against us or<br>
against Iran. If there are some agreements limiting military supplies, they<br>
should apply to everyone," the source vc said. Russia is currently<br>
"implementing the previous contracts for arms supplies to Iran concluded as<br>
early as in former Soviet times" , the source said. <br>
<p>
"Our stand on this matter is clear. Russian arms supplies to Tehran are not<br>
in any way changing the balance of power in the region, and in particular in<br>
the Persian Gulf, where the advantage is not Iran's either in terms of arms<br>
quantity or in the rate of its increase," the source said. <br>
<p>
The source declined to indicate the volume of military-technological<br>
cooperation between Russia and Iran, saying only that it was below<br>
Russian-Iranian "civil trade turnover" which totalled 370m dollars last year.<br>
<p>
<p>
Russia is not satisfied with the level of trade-economic links with Iran, the<br>
source said. The development of bilateral economic links is impaired by<br>
regional conflicts in Tajikistan, Afghanistan and Nagornyy Karabakh, and the<br>
unsettled issue of the Caspian Sea's status, the source said. "We consider<br>
Iran a very important partner. We see it as our task to put in joint efforts<br>
in order to make the region calm, from both the political and military points<br>
of view, for unhindered development of economic links," the source said... <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenian nuclear power plant to have another power unit <br>
SOURCE: Itar-Tass news agency (World Service), Moscow, in English 1806 gmt 20<br>
Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Preparations are under way to provide Armenia's nuclear power station with a<br>
new generating unit, Itar-Tass news agency reported from Yerevan. <br>
<p>
The project, which will cost 1.5-2bn dollars, has still to be approved by the<br>
Armenian government, the agency quoted the plant's director, Suren Azatyan,<br>
as telling journalists in Yerevan on 20th December. <br>
<p>
The plant, which produces 40 per cent of the republic's energy, was<br>
decommissioned following the huge earthquake which hit Armenia vc in December<br>
1988. It went back into operation in late 1995 in response to the acute<br>
energy crisis in the republic. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: New criminal links to police unveiled in Turkish mafia scandal <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France Presse, December 23, 1996 (Umit Enginsoy)<br>
<p>
The Turkish intelligence service has uncovered new links between drug<br>
smugglers and corrupt police, press reports said Monday, in a fresh twist to<br>
a massive scandal over mafia infiltration of the state security apparatus. <br>
<p>
A woman, who was caught with heroin worth 250,000 dollars at Istanbul airport<br>
earlier this month, is understood to have links with the personal guard of<br>
the special operations chief at the police directorate, according to an<br>
intelligence report. <br>
<p>
Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan revealed the report at a Sunday meeting with<br>
President Suleyman Demirel and leaders of political parties vc , the liberal<br>
Istanbul-based daily Milliyet said. <br>
<p>
Demirel called the meeting in an effort to reach a political consensus over<br>
how to tackle the controversy, which has rocked Turkey for nearly two months.<br>
<p>
<p>
The scandal broke on November 3 when wanted mafia boss Abdullah Catli, a<br>
former ultra-nationalist militant, and a senior police chief were killed in a<br>
car crash in western Turkey. <br>
<p>
Sedat Bucak, a Kurdish parliamentary deputy from Foreign Minister Tansu<br>
Ciller's conservative True Path Party, was seriously injured while travelling<br>
in the same car. <br>
<p>
The incident, which exposed links between police, politicians and organised<br>
crime, created uproar in Turkey and led to the resignation of interior<br>
minister Mehmet Agar, who has been accused by the press of personal<br>
involvement. <br>
<p>
"Those gangs operating within the state are understood to have been active<br>
since the early 1980s," the main conservative opposition leader Mesut Yilmaz<br>
said on television late Sunday. <br>
<p>
"Turkey must get rid of this embarrassing situation and all those involved in<br>
this. No matter who they are, they must be punished," said Yilmaz, who is<br>
also a former prime minister. <br>
<p>
According to press reports, Catli had been employed by the Turkish state for<br>
operations outside the country, notably against leaders of the anti-Turkish<br>
Armenian Secret Army for the Liberation of Armenia (ASALA) in the 1980s. <br>
<p>
The ASALA claimed responsibility for assassinating nearly 40 Turkish<br>
diplomats and officials abroad in the 1970s. <br>
<p>
Catli and three policemen, who later became personal guards of Bucak, were<br>
also allegedly involved in the killing of a Kurdish tycoon who owned a chain<br>
of casinos. <br>
<p>
Media reports have said several high-ranking government officials were<br>
probably linked with Catli's affairs. <br>
<p>
Milliyet said the intelligence service report revealed at Sunday's crisis<br>
meeting cited the names of 58 people who might be involved in the scandal.<br>
Their identities were not made public. <br>
<p>
"It seems these gangs were originally formed to carry out tasks for the<br>
state, but in the early 1990s they began to pursue their own purposes,"<br>
Yilmaz said. "In both cases the existence of such entities are totally<br>
unacceptable in a democratic society," he said. <br>
<p>
Yilmaz, Ciller and leaders of two left-wing parties and a small<br>
ultra-rightist party also took part in the president's meeting. <br>
<p>
In a statement he released later, Demirel urged parliament and all state<br>
institutions to facilitate an investigation launched into the scandal. <br>
<p>
Political analysts said the parliamentary immunity of some deputies,<br>
including Agar and Bucak, might be lifted soon. <br>
<p>
Yilmaz said he would present Demirel and judicial officials with additional<br>
information and documents he had regarding the scandal. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Russian Defence Minister Visits Azerbaijan <br>
SOURCE: Itar-Tass, December 23, 1996<br>
<p>
A meeting between Azeri leaders and Russian defence minister Igor Rodionov<br>
will be held in Baku today to discuss a number of problems pertaining to<br>
further cooperation between Russia and Azerbaijan, said the Russian defence<br>
minister who had arrived in Baku on a one-day working visit at the invitation<br>
of Azeri President Heidar aliyev.  <br>
<p>
Rodionov told journalists at Baku airport that "it is necessary to do<br>
everything possible so that friendship, good-neighborly relations and mutual<br>
assistance strengthen and develop in the interests of the people of the two<br>
countries."  <br>
<p>
Rodionov pointed out that many definite agreements in military and technical<br>
field had been reached vc by the two countries,stressing that some details of<br>
the mutually advantageous cooperation would be specified at today's talks in<br>
Baku.  <br>
<p>
Rodionov said that at forthcoming meetings with Azeri President Heidar Aliyev<br>
and Defence Minister Safar Abiyev he would discuss issues connected with<br>
further exploitation of the Gabelinskaya radar which has been operating in<br>
the centre of Azerbaijan for ten years by now.  This is one of the biggest<br>
radars in the post-Soviet space serviced by Russian military experts and<br>
whose status has not yet been determined since the disintegration of the<br>
former Soviet Union.  <br>
<p>
According to Azeri military sources, a protocol on military and technical<br>
cooperation between the two countries would be signed upon completion of the<br>
meeting in Baku.  <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Cooperation with Vatican Does Not Erase Identity-Catholicos <br>
SOURCE: Itar-Tass, December 23, 1996 (Dicran Liloian)<br>
 <br>
The head of the Armenian Apostolic Church said on Monday that contacts with<br>
the Vatican did not mean a refusal from its underlying principles. <br>
<p>
Catholicos Karekin I told reporters in his residence at Echmiadzin that the<br>
Armenian Apostolic Church still reject the Council of Chalcedon of 451, which<br>
remains its main characteristic feature. <br>
<p>
However, time for dialogue has come, and differences in belief should not be<br>
regarded as obstacles to cooperation among all Christians, Karekin I said. <br>
<p>
With time, relations with other denominations should be purged of<br>
misunderstanding and centuries-old differences, in an attempt to reach a vc<br>
union of churches, he noted. <br>
<p>
He said all denominations, preserving their specific features, belong to one<br>
Christ and one church.  However, unity is not uniformity, he stressed. <br>
<p>
He said his forthcoming visit to the Vatican should be viewed as a new stage<br>
of Armenia's participation in the ecumenical movement and in the development<br>
of inter-denominational ties. <br>
<p>
He said he had made his first visit after accession to the throne of<br>
Catholicos to the head of the Russian Orthodox Church, Patriarch Alexy II. <br>
<p>
The Catholicos said a permanent body should be established to promote<br>
relations with the Roman Catholic Church.  It is important that the headsof<br>
the two churches do not met only  once in 25 years, he noted. <br>
<p>
According to him, the Armenian Apostolic Church recognises the Armenian<br>
Catholic Church as a historically established one and regularly cooperates<br>
with its exarchs. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Accord on Russian-Azeri Military Cooperation Not Signed <br>
SOURCE: Itar-Tass, December 23, 1996 <br>
<p>
Russia and Azerbaijan on Monday failed to sign an agreement on military and<br>
technical cooperation, Colonel-General Leonid Ivashov, head of the Russian<br>
Defence Ministry's Department of International Military Cooperation, said<br>
after the end of the meeting between Russian Defence Minister Igor Rodionov<br>
and President of Azerbaijan Geidar Aliyev.  <br>
<p>
According to the Russian general, the ceremony of the signing Of this<br>
agreement was put off at Aliyev's proposal, who considered that such<br>
bilateral documents should be more specific and comprehensive. <br>
<p>
At the same time, Ivashov expressed the hope that this agreement, as well as<br>
an interstate protocol vc on military cooperation, would be signed in the<br>
near future.  <br>
<p>
During the meeting, the sides exchanged on a broad range of issues,including<br>
the military and political situation in the region, in particular, the<br>
settlement of the Karabakh conflict, the general said.  <br>
<p>
The two sides also discussed the extension of cooperation between Russia and<br>
Azerbaijan, especially military and technical one, Ivashov said.  <br>
<p>
He said the sides had reached an agreement on the development of bilateral<br>
military relations and are expected to work out measures to continue a<br>
dialogue.  <br>
<p>
The general said that the parties had separately discussed the question of<br>
the Gabelin radar, located on the territory of Azerbaijan and operated by<br>
Russian military specialists.   <br>
<p>
In this connection, Ivashov said that there was a special assignmentby the<br>
Azerbaijani President to the Defence Ministry to begin work out an agreement<br>
on the issue.  <br>
<p>
On the whole, Aliyev described Rodionov's visit to Baku as a step forward of<br>
the development of military cooperation between the two countries.  <br>
<p>
On Monday night, the Russian military delegation left Baku for Moscow.  <br>
 <br>
HEADLINE: Azerbaijan Upgrades Air Navigation System with EBRD Loan <br>
SOURCE: Universal News Services, December 23, 1996<br>
<p>
The Civil Aviation Authority in Azerbaijan (AZAL) is to improve<br>
aviationsafety and expand  traffic-handling capacity with the help of a US@<br>
13.7 million (ECU 11 million) loan provided  by the European Bank for<br>
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD).  <br>
<p>
Stijn Albregts, Director of the EBRD's Azerbaijan team, said:"The EBRD's loan<br>
should help  AZAL achieve greater reliability and a higher standard of<br>
services and maintenance.   The  revamped air navigation system will vc meet<br>
international aviation standards set by the  international Civil Aviation<br>
Organisation. The improvements should also enable AZAL to  eet  future<br>
traffic demand and accommodate new routes, thereby increasing its foreign<br>
 exchange  arnings." <br>
<p>
The loan will help to finance an urgently needed capital investmentprogramme<br>
to modernise Azerbaijan's air navigation system. This includes air traffic<br>
control services throughout Azeri airspace as well as terminal and airport<br>
control services in the capital city of Baku. Rehabilitation of the control<br>
tower complex to house the air traffic control equipment and to provide<br>
operation rooms will also be financed by the loan. <br>
<p>
After achieving independence in 1991, Azerbaijan gained full and exclusive<br>
control of its airspace. This covers most of the national airspace as well as<br>
an important area over the international waters of the Caspian Sea and a<br>
portion of airspace in the north, over the territory of the Russian<br>
Federation. AZAL, established in April 1992 as a fully state-owned autonomous<br>
commercial entity, is curently the sole authority and provider for civil<br>
aviation activities in Azerbaijan. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
