<title>Groong Network: More from Moskovskiy Komsomolets</title>
<h1>More from Moskovskiy Komsomolets</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 24 Dec 1996 10:39:51 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#212">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#212">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#212">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#212">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/24/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Chechnya: elections, security, oil transit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1. Chechnya: "'A Third Force' with Russian Shoulder-Boards?" <br>
2.  "What Lebed's Mother-in-Law Is Going to Be Now?<br>
If His Brother Has Become a Premier"<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Moskovskiy Komsomolets 24 December 1996 page 4<br>
<p>
   Report by Aleksandr Belonovskiy under the "Chechnya" rubric:  "'A Third<br>
Force' with Russian Shoulder-Boards?"<br>
<p>
  Something inexplicable is going on in Chechnya.  It seems that the rebels<br>
have gotten what they asked for.  Russian troops are being pulled out of the<br>
republic on schedule, the field commanders of yesterday are pasting up<br>
leaflets calling on people to vote for them in the upcoming elections.  Yet<br>
emergencies occur in the republic every day and people continue to get<br>
killed.  Over over the past 10 days several murders have been committed.<br>
   The Chechen leadership was swift to state through Movladi Udugov that<br>
children were blown up on a radio-controlled land-mine.  According to the<br>
Russian Internal Affairs Ministry's theory, this accident was caused by<br>
carelessness in the handling of a projectile.  Allegedly the kids were<br>
trying to look at what was inside the "iron toy"...<br>
   Clearly, the Chechens are no longer content with simply blaming all their<br>
woes on a mythical third force, of which everyone has heard, but which no<br>
one has ever seen.  The nation is beginning to split into small clans, which<br>
are pursuing only their own interests and on which Groznyy has very little<br>
influence.  An outside enemy that could rally everyone together has<br>
disappeared.  Where can a new one be gotten?  And there you go, a series of<br>
heinous terrorist acts take place as if they were ordered.  Who is to blame?<br>
The conclusion that readily suggests itself is as follows:  Of course, this<br>
is the third force in the shape of Russian special services.  This is the<br>
enemy plotting wicked designs: To thwart elections, to destabilize the<br>
situation, to unleash another war.<br>
   Most important, there is no need to search for the actual perpetrators.<br>
In a tiny republic everything that happens in the morning becomes common<br>
knowledge by noon.  For this reason finding the killers will hardly present<br>
any difficulty.  But who will dare touch them?  No one has abolished the<br>
laws of blood revenge.  So any attempt to bring all armed men to one common<br>
lawful denominator is bound to trigger local strife or even civil war.<br>
Strange as it might be, our special services acted in the most dignified<br>
manner in this situation.  They simply ignored the Chechen allegations.<br>
(end)<br>
<p>
Moskovskiy Komsomolets 24 December 1996 page 1<br>
<p>
   Politics Desk analysis:  "What Lebed's Mother-in-Law Is Going to Be Now?<br>
If His Brother Has Become a Premier"<br>
<p>
  It turns out that Aleksandr Lebed has a plane of his own.  It has been<br>
rumored that it is on it that Lebed went to Kemerovo for a powerful<br>
financial support, and also for the creation of a regional organization<br>
called "third force" (Yavlinskiy, Fedorov, Lebed).<br>
   The mysterious trip was explained at the general's press service<br>
approximately like this:  There is no point for Aleksandr Ivanovich [Lebed]<br>
to take trips to Kuzbass and other poverty regions "for financial backing."<br>
Sponsors call on him in his Moscow office of their own accord, and offer him<br>
money of their own accord and thus there is no point for Lebed to chase<br>
money all over the boundless vastness of Russia.  Lebed's trips pursue<br>
different objectives.  First, he has to see for himself the situation in the<br>
region and compare "government "information with the reports he is getting<br>
from his regional representatives.  Second, Lebed's supporters are urging to<br>
come over and talks with them because they, too, would like to compare<br>
"government" information on Lebed with what he says about himself, his<br>
future and the future of Russia.<br>
   The "third force" variant was clarified at "Yabloko" [headquarters]:  it<br>
is true that the regional leaders of the Honor and the Motherland], Yabloko<br>
and Svyatoslav Fedorov's party  signed a month ago an agreement on a<br>
simultaneous nomination of seven candidates in the elections for a local<br>
legislative assembly to be held next Sunday -- 29 December.<br>
   Thus it becomes clear that Lebed's trip to Kemerovo and to his brother in<br>
Khakassia, is more connected with day-today election affairs rather than<br>
with trying to procure money and create blocs.  More attention, perhaps,<br>
deserves the victory of the younger Lebed (Colonel Aleksey Lebed) in the<br>
elections for head of the executive power (premier of the government) of<br>
Khakassia.  The little brother rather haughtily spoke (in an NTV interview)<br>
about help from his elder brother:  Can two meetings with the voters by some<br>
sort of general count in comparison with seventy meetings with the colonel?<br>
   It appears that there are grounds to conclude that Lebed said everything<br>
in sufficiently precise terms in Kemerovo:  I need no "third force," I have<br>
my own....  Most likely, the formation of "Lebed's force" will consist<br>
precisely in illuminating by his name of those somewhat weak politically but<br>
devoted to their "patron" for various reasons.  What such a party of<br>
professionals is capable of pull off is another matter.  And why should not<br>
it pull off something given backing from "Moscow banks"?<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
