<title>Groong Network: Chechnya: elections, security, oil transit</title>
<h1>Chechnya: elections, security, oil transit</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 24 Dec 1996 10:29:29 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#211">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#211">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#211">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#211">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0212.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "More from Moskovskiy Komsomolets"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0210.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/24/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Kommersant-Daily 24 December 1996 pages 1, 3<br>
<p>
   Report by Andrey Smirnov:  "Only Dudayev's State Is Stable"<br>
<p>
  The presidential elections in Chechnya are slightly more than a month<br>
away.  Yesterday four candidates -- Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, Aslan Maskhadov,<br>
Shamil Basayev, and Movladi Udugov -- submitted to the Central Electoral<br>
Commission the 10,000 signatures required for registration.  With the<br>
election campaign in full swing, the Chechen authorities are doing their<br>
utmost so as to convince the outside world of their ability to ensure<br>
stability.  In the meantime, the past several days have seen yet more signs<br>
of the brouhaha reigning in Chechnya, ranging from new hostage takings to<br>
yesterday's decision by the Chechen parliament to award the rank of<br>
generalissimo to Dzhokhar Dudayev posthumously.<br>
   Yesterday the Chechen deputies made yet another decision that has little<br>
to do with the logic of Chechen realities.  The parliament requested the<br>
local electoral commission to oblige presidential candidates to submit<br>
without delay requests for suspending them from office during the election<br>
campaign.  Clearly no one will be upset if terrorist Basayev suspends his<br>
infamous activity.  But if Yandarbiyev, Maskhadov, and Udugov relinquish the<br>
authority that is already slipping through their fingers, the development of<br>
events in the republic will become absolutely unpredictable.  The killing of<br>
the Red Cross workers, the abduction of militiamen, the disappearance of<br>
delegations arriving in Chechnya, continuing skirmishes and "accidental"<br>
killings are only a part of the picture.  Another part of it, which visibly<br>
contrasts with the first one, is the Chechen authorities' desire, first, to<br>
convince Moscow of the need to support them materially and, second, to<br>
"stake out" their considerable oil interests.<br>
   This was the thrust of the appeal to the Russian authorities by<br>
Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov, president of the Southern Oil Company of Chechnya<br>
(YUNKO).  Currently the former chief of the Chechen delegation in talks with<br>
the federal side is dealing with matters of restoring the Chechen fuel and<br>
energy sector.  Speaking at a news conference in Moscow he denied, in<br>
particular, that the oil factor had played any role in unleashing or ending<br>
the Chechen war.  In his view, the latter could only be achieved thanks to<br>
the victory of the "party of peace" in the Russian leadership.  At the same<br>
time Yarikhanov cautioned that the war was far from over; it was only<br>
suspended.  The definitive peace will only be possible after the<br>
cancellation of the pieces of legislation that gave the pretext for starting<br>
combat operations.<br>
   The absence of "formal peace" does not prevent Chechen leaders at all<br>
from demanding assistance in restoring their war-ravaged economy from their<br>
erstwhile enemies.  The issue is first of all the Chechen sector of a main<br>
pipeline connecting Caspian shelf deposits with the oil terminals of<br>
Novorossiysk.  Groznyy appears to see the pipeline not only as the<br>
foundation of the republic's future economic prosperity -- the Caspian<br>
international consortium is ready to pay $15.67 for the transit of one tonne<br>
of oil -- but also as an economic basis to shore up Chechen independence.<br>
At the same time the Groznyy authorities count on Russian assistance for the<br>
restoration of the fuel and energy sector.  According to Yarikhanov, at the<br>
initial stage alone it will require 302 billion rubles -- the Chechens<br>
estimate the total damage done to the industry by war at 8 trillion.  So<br>
officials in Groznyy express their astonishment at seeing corresponding<br>
Russian agencies display no particular enthusiasm about cooperation with the<br>
republic.  In particular, the YUNKO head expressed his displeasure with the<br>
stance of the Fuel and Energy Ministry, which, as he put it, "shows no<br>
interest" in the plans for restoring the Chechen fuel and energy sector,<br>
although they were "included as a separate item" on the November agreement<br>
between Viktor Chernomyrdin and Aslan Maskhadov.<br>
   The Fuel and Energy Ministry disagreed with this assessment, however.  A<br>
spokesman for the ministry told your Kommersant-Daily correspondent that the<br>
agreement was being drawn up and that this work was slowed down only by<br>
uncertainty with regard to sources of financing.  To all appearances, no<br>
clarity in this matter should be expected in the near future.  Plans for an<br>
inflow of private investment in Chechnya will remain wishful thinking as<br>
long as terrorist acts, hostage takings, and similar occurrences continue in<br>
the republic.  Be it a matter of transporting oil, restoring the economy, or<br>
conducting elections in accordance with democratic standards -- it will also<br>
require guarantees to ensure at least the security of those who can help the<br>
Chechens carry out these undertakings.<br>
   The restoration of an oil pipeline and an oil refinery will require not<br>
only money, but also involvement of Russian specialists.  Chechnya has no<br>
qualified specialists of its own -- even at the best of times, when the<br>
republic's oil sector processed over 20 million tonnes of oil, the share of<br>
local specialists in the industry did not exceed 1 percent.  There can<br>
hardly be any doubt as to the fact that in current conditions no Russian<br>
specialists will go to Chechnya -- nor will foreign observers, without whose<br>
participation presidential elections are unlikely to be deemed free and<br>
democratic.<br>
   Yarikhanov devoted a major part of his news conference to attempts to<br>
assure that the current Chechen authorities can give security guarantees to<br>
the people who could help it restore its devastated economy.  Yet he could<br>
never give coherent answers to the perplexed questions of journalists --<br>
mainly Western correspondents, because for their Russian counterparts the<br>
criminal situation in Chechnya has already become commonplace -- as to what<br>
guarantees can one talk about after the killing of the Red Cross workers.<br>
Just as clumsy were attempts by Chechen Deputy Prime Minister Movladi Udugov<br>
to deny the obvious.  Yesterday he claimed that the ID's of Chechen Army<br>
servicemen found on those killed in the Monday skirmish with Internal<br>
Affairs Ministry officers in the Prigorodnyy Rayon of North Ossetia had been<br>
planted by some "enemies from the party of war."<br>
   As the elections draw closer such incidents will become increasingly<br>
frequent, there is no doubt about it.  And this is attributable not so much<br>
to the sinister designs by the enemies of Chechen independence than to the<br>
internal struggle among separatists themselves.  The fact that Yandarbiyev,<br>
Maskhadov, Udugov, and Basayev, who are formally members of the same team,<br>
had their candidacies nominated at the same time proves the absence of unity<br>
in the Chechen leadership.  Moreover, the presence of people similar to<br>
Salman Raduyev on the Chechen political scene -- the degree of his sanity<br>
can be judged if only by his resolution to continue carrying out "Dzhokhar<br>
Dudayev's orders" -- does not arouse any optimism as to the prospects for<br>
achieving stability in Chechnya any time soon.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
