<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/23/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/23/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 23 Dec 1996 19:56:23 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#208">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#208">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#208">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#208">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0209.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 23)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0207.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Family Life Is an Important Part of the Turkish Culture"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  A Tale of Two Elections<br>
2.  Turkish president meets party leaders to discuss mafia scandal  <br>
3.  Primakov: Russia to integrate Iran into international society <br>
4.  Chechen official holds "fruitless" talks in Moscow on oil transit via<br>
Chechnya <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  A Tale of Two Elections<br>
SOURCE:  The Wall Street Journal Europe, December 23, 1996 (Ms. Pilon is the<br>
director of programs for Europe and Asia at th e Washington- based<br>
International Foundation for Election Systems. She is the author of "The<br>
Bloody Flag: Post-Communist Nationalism in Eastern Europe -- Spot light on<br>
Romania" (Rutgers University Press, 1992). <br>
<p>
This was a good season for democracy in some parts of Eastern Europe. A few<br>
post-Communist governments, notably in Bulgaria, Lithuania and Romania, were<br>
pushed from office. Two elections in particular this season -- in Romania and<br>
Armenia -- showed vc what a fine line there is for many of these countries<br>
between moving toward democracy and bogging down.<br>
<p>
In November, Romanians danced in the streets chanting that "Iliescu is no<br>
more." For the first time in nearly four decades, their head of state had<br>
been removed by peaceful ballot. Free and fair elections, however, were by no<br>
means assured until the very last moment: Only a few days before the election<br>
there was some evidence that the government may have been planning to rig the<br>
election, but with a bit of ingenuity on the part of U.S. and Romanian<br>
experts the tables were turned on the Central Election Bureau and the<br>
elections proceeded in a surprisingly orderly and legal manner.  <br>
<p>
By contrast, a nation further east did not fare as well: The Armenian<br>
presidential elections on Sept. 22 were contested in the Constitutional<br>
Court. Serious electoral violations were committed in full view of the<br>
international community. Yet the court decided, on Nov. 22, to validate those<br>
results; it is unlikely, however, that the court decision can salvage the<br>
reputation of the current administration.  <br>
<p>
Romania may well have overtaken Armenia on the road to democracy and<br>
prosperity. Armenia had been in the vanguard, the first Soviet republic to<br>
declare independence in 1991 and blessed with a reformist president. Romania<br>
hardly changed course when, after the death of its dictator Nicolae<br>
Ceausescu, the Communist Party's former ideology secretary Ion Iliescu<br>
immediately took over. Five years later much has changed.  <br>
<p>
In Romania in mid-October, the recently formed electoral body ( the CEB)<br>
announced its intention to include some newly formed nongovernmental<br>
organizations to observe the elections, as it had done in 1992.   In effect,<br>
these "phantom" NGOs would have squeezed out nearly two-thirds of  the 14,000<br>
bona fide observers necessary to ensure a fair result by using an  old<br>
lottery system that would have limited the number of observers assigned per<br>
polling station. When the CEB, however, was presented with an alternative<br>
 system -- devised by an American election expert and Romanian computer<br>
specialists working with the International Foundation for Election Systems --<br>
 the commission could find no arguments against its use. The system involved<br>
a software package that allocated all available observers equitably  to every<br>
district (judet). CEB members watched, amazed, as the entire exercise was<br>
completed in less than an hour.  <br>
<p>
They still had another trump card. Only four days before the election, it<br>
appeared that domestic observers were going to be banned from watching the<br>
counting of the ballots, the most crucial part of the process. Again local<br>
democratic activists and IFES acted together, producing a detailed memorandum<br>
to the CEB explaining that the intent of the existing electoral law allows<br>
for domestic observers to be part of the counting process. The next day, the<br>
CEB reversed its decision. The elections proceded and were deemed free and<br>
fair by the international organizations such as the Organization for Security<br>
and Cooperation in Europe present. <br>
 <br>
Armenia, on the other hand, was almost an electoral mirror image  of Romania.<br>
Most importantly, the Central Election Commission did not retreat  in the<br>
face of international  pressure and allow domestic polling observers.  While<br>
the CEC argued that its law does not permit them, IFES and others pointed<br>
 out that no law forbids them either. Indeed, in the 1995 elections domestic<br>
observers had been allowed.    Also, on election day, official tallies were<br>
not uniformly posted according to Armenia's election law. Worse, there was a<br>
large discrepancy,  mainly in Yerevan, among the ballots counted and the<br>
number of coupons indicating how many people had picked up ballots. Since the<br>
margin of votes needed by President Ter-Petrossian to win was about 20,000,<br>
that discrepancy alone would be enough to bring the whole process into<br>
question since it exceeded that number. In fact there were several other<br>
incidents of electoral fraud. They were all brought to the attention of the<br>
CEC by the international agencies present and the losing candidates. But no<br>
credible response was forthcoming. <br>
<p>
The hope is that Armenia will soon be back on the road to democracy.<br>
President Ter-Petrossian, considered a friend of the U.S. has been perceived<br>
as a man of progress and peace, with every intention to take his nation into<br>
the post-Communist era. He is also trying to walk a fine line between  Russia<br>
and Iran while being subjected to blockades from Turkey and neighboring<br>
Azerbaijan. But, as much of Eastern Europe is now proving, there is little<br>
that can substitute for a free and fair election.   <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Turkish president meets party leaders to discuss mafia scandal  <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France Presse, December 22, 1996<br>
<p>
President Suleyman Demirel met Sunday with Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan<br>
and five other party leaders to discuss allegations of mafia infiltration<br>
into the state's security apparatus. <br>
<p>
"The president and the government should do everything necessary to unveil<br>
what is still in the dark and those responsible should be punished,"<br>
conservative main opposition leader Mesut Yilmaz said Saturday. <br>
<p>
Yilmaz, Erbakan's coalition partner, and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller as<br>
well vc as leaders of two left-wing parties and a small ultra-rightist party<br>
took part in the meeting at the presidential palace. <br>
<p>
The nation has been rocked by the scandal which erupted on November 3 when<br>
wanted mafia boss Abdullah Catli, a former ultra-nationalist militant, and a<br>
senior police chief were killed in a car crash in western Turkey. <br>
<p>
Also in the same car was Sedat Bucak, a Kurdish parliamentary deputy from<br>
Ciller's conservative True Path Party. He survived the accident but suffered<br>
serious injuries. <br>
<p>
The incident, which exposed links among police, some politicians and<br>
organised crime, created a furor in Turkey leading to the resignation of<br>
Interior Minister Mehmet Agar and the sacking of Istanbul's security<br>
director. <br>
<p>
According to press reports, Catli had been employed by Turkey for operations<br>
outside the country, notably against leaders of the anti-Turkish Armenian<br>
Secret Army for the Liberation of Armenia (ASALA) in the 1980s. The ASALA<br>
claimed responsibility for assassinating nearly 40 Turkish diplomats and<br>
officials abroad in the 1970s. <br>
<p>
Catli and three policemen, who were personal guards of Bucak, were also<br>
allegedly involved in the killing of a Kurdish tycoon who owned a chain of<br>
casinos. <br>
<p>
Media reports have said several high-ranking government officials are likely<br>
to have been involved in Catli's affairs. <br>
<p>
Yilmaz has accused Erbakan of failing to launch a comprehensive and<br>
high-level inquiry into the allegations, leaving police to investigate the<br>
events. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Primakov: Russia to integrate Iran into international society <br>
SOURCE:  Deutsche Presse-Agentur, December 22, 1996<br>
<p>
Russia will help to integrate Iran into the international community, Russian<br>
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Sunday in Teheran. <br>
<p>
"Iran is an important country and given the high level of mutual trust,<br>
Russia will try to integrate Iran into the international society as a fully<br>
authorised member with equal rights," Primakov told newsmen at the Iranian<br>
foreign ministry. <br>
<p>
Primakov arrived in Teheran earlier Sunday and vc was greeted at the airport<br>
by his Iranian counterpart, Ali Akbar Velayati. <br>
<p>
He said that political and economic ties between Teheran and Moscow have an<br>
upward trend and termed future prospect of bilateral ties as "quite<br>
promising". <br>
<p>
Primakov and Velayati termed the first round of their talks as "sincere and<br>
frank". The talks covered issues ranging from Tajikistan, Nagorno Karabakh<br>
and Afghanistan to the Gulf and the Middle East. <br>
<p>
"Russia is in favour of a peaceful Persian Gulf region and welcomes any<br>
understanding between Iran and the littoral states," Primakov said. Regarding<br>
the Middle East, he said that Russia wants previous agreements, such as the<br>
Oslo agreement, to be realised. <br>
<p>
Velayati in turn said ties between Teheran and Moscow were at "their best<br>
level in the last two decades" and said that two states are determined to<br>
continue this suitable trend based upon mutual respect and non-interference<br>
in the internal affairs of the other country. <br>
<p>
Primakov is on his first visit as Russian Foreign Minister to Teheran but<br>
according to Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister, Mahmud Vaezi, he has been in<br>
Teheran five times before under other positions. <br>
<p>
Upon arrival in Teheran with a 15-man delegation, Primakov said that<br>
relations between Teheran and Moscow were very good and constantly expanding,<br>
and both sides had many common topics to talk about during this "important<br>
visit". <br>
<p>
He added that his talks with Iranian officials will focus more on the peace<br>
talks in Tajikistan, which are currently being held between the Tajik<br>
government and the Islamic opposition groups in Moscow where Vaezi<br>
represented Iran. <br>
<p>
Velayati said due to the Iranian influence among the Islamic opposition group<br>
in Tajikistan and Russia's influence in the Tajik government, the two sides<br>
could have an effective co-operation in settling the crisis in Tajikistan. <br>
<p>
Primakov rejected the assumption that his visit would be a move against U.S.<br>
interests. "Russia will never make any plot against anybody," Primakov said,<br>
laughing with Velayati. <br>
<p>
During the Russian foreign minister's three-day-stay in Teheran, the two<br>
sides are supposed to sign three protocols in connection with Tajikistan,<br>
Afghanistan and the Caspian Sea. <br>
<p>
Primakov will also meet with President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, who has just<br>
returned from a state visit to Turkey, Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq<br>
Nuri and Vice-Speaker Hassan Rowhani.  dpa fm ba <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Chechen official holds "fruitless" talks in Moscow on oil transit<br>
via Chechnya <br>
SOURCE: RIA news agency, Moscow, in English 1757 gmt 20 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Russia is not ready to sign an agreement on terms for the forthcoming<br>
delivery of so-called "early" Azeri oil across Chechnya, RIA was told today<br>
by Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov, the president of the Chechen oil company Yunco<br>
[Southern Oil Company], now in Moscow to conduct talks with Russia's Fuel and<br>
Energy Ministry . <br>
<p>
According to Yarikhanov, his meeting today with the deputy minister, Viktor<br>
Kudryavyy, turned out to be "fruitless" because "the ministry was totally<br>
unprepared for joint work on the document".  He also said that Kudryavyy had<br>
informed the Chechen side that vc a special working group under the auspices<br>
of the Fuel and Energy Ministry had been set up to "seriously consider their<br>
proposals" . The stance of the ministry and possibly documents drawn up by<br>
the Russian side will be discussed at a meeting in Groznyy which, according<br>
to Yarikhanov, will take place early next year. <br>
<p>
The Yunco president's response to reports by some mass media that Groznyy<br>
wants to join the Azeri consortium was that "it was all the invention of the<br>
biased Russian press" . Meanwhile, according to Baku, Chechen emissaries who<br>
visited the Azeri capital earlier for talks with the management of the<br>
Azerbaijan International Operating Company made it clear that the issue of<br>
safe transportation of early Azeri oil to Novorossiysk across Chechnya<br>
heavily depends on Chechnya' s admission to the consortium. In addition to<br>
that, Groznyy's delegate Ruslan Abdurzakov [as received] said in Baku that no<br>
oil will go from Azerbaijan to Russia if Chechnya remains outside this "<br>
contract of the century" ... <br>
