<title>Groong Network: Family Life Is an Important Part of the Turkish Culture</title>
<h1>Family Life Is an Important Part of the Turkish Culture</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 23 Dec 1996 19:56:52 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#207">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#207">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#207">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#207">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/23/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0206.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-23-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
HEADLINE:  Family Life Is an Important Part of the Turkish Culture<br>
SOURCE:  Market Europe, December 1, 1996<br>
<p>
History, culture, and geography have all made Turkey a country where<br>
turbulence is a natural state of affairs. <br>
<p>
The past two years have been no exception to this pattern, and current events<br>
make it unlikely that there will be any substantial change in the next two<br>
years.<br>
<p>
The people of the country and those doing business vc with them are<br>
weathering stormy times.<br>
<p>
Turkey's economy in the 1990s has lurched from peak to trough and back again.<br>
The breakaway growth that made the country a hot property in the 1980s is a<br>
thing of the past. Gross domestic product (GDP)contracted in 1991, rebounded<br>
mildly in 1992 and 1993, then dipped 5  percent in 1994 as the country was<br>
plunged into the worst economic crisis in its modern history. There was a<br>
recovery in 1995, and modest growth of 2.8 percent is forecast for 1996. <br>
<p>
The economic crisis, set off by rapid deterioration of public accounts, led<br>
to triple-digit inflation that has been trimmed only marginally since.<br>
Inflation for the first six months of 1996 was 44.8 percent. The inflation<br>
rate has forced successive devaluations of the Turkish lira. Turkish<br>
wage-earners are stretched to maintain living standards.  <br>
<p>
Political problems compound Turkey's instability. The long-running war<br>
against the Kurdish terrorist groups (PKK) forces diversion of vast resources<br>
to the military and damages the country's democratic image abroad.  <br>
<p>
Relations with Iran, Syria, and Iraq are perennially difficult, and the<br>
international trade boycott of the latter has cost Turkey an estimated US$27<br>
billion in lost commerce. Tensions have flared sporadically with the old<br>
enemy, Greece, most recently over a disputed island territory and the thorny<br>
issue of Cyprus.  <br>
<p>
Internally, a series of ineffective coalition governments have eroded public<br>
trust and ceded ground to the Islamic cause of the Welfare Party (RP). This<br>
year the RP entered government for the first time in a coalition with the<br>
True Path Party (DYP). Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan has moderated his<br>
Islamic rhetoric since taking power, and at the city level the RP's municipal<br>
administration is the most honest in years. <br>
<p>
Yet Erbakan's cultivation of ties with Iran has not helped to placate fears<br>
at home and abroad that Turkey's cherished tradition of secular democracy is<br>
under threat.    <br>
<p>
Hopes of Turkey joining the European Union remain alive, and there are those<br>
within the country who view this as a panacea for the country's economic<br>
ills. Turkey has entered into a customs union with the EU, which has removed<br>
tariffs on manufactured goods, a step arguably more important for its<br>
symbolic cementing of European ties than for any impact on trade. The Kurdish<br>
question is likely to have a negative impact on Turkey's attempt to move<br>
closer to Europe while encouraging further cooperation with its Middle<br>
Eastern neighbors.  <br>
<p>
Strangers to turmoil they are not, yet Turkish people have seen the optimism<br>
of the 1980s shredded in the 1990s. Confidence is lacking at both the<br>
business and individual levels. After the crisis of 1994, investors and<br>
workers are only now finding encouragement to participate and take risks.<br>
There is still a tendency for consumers to abstain from major purchases and<br>
to measure present spending against the cost of inflation.  <br>
<p>
What keeps Turkey ticking is the strength of its family system and a strong<br>
sense of nationalism. Like people in other Southern European countries, Turks<br>
measure their well-being in terms less individual than collective.    <br>
<p>
When doubts arise over employment or earnings, the family is there to help.<br>
In a wider sense, this collective identity makes Turks ready to weather<br>
change in the interests of the nation.    <br>
<p>
Land and people - Nationality is important to the people of Turkey.<br>
Regardless of religion and lifestyle, they are proud to identify themselves<br>
as Turks before all else. This is despite the fact that theirs is a large<br>
nation of diverse ethnic groups and lifestyles.    <br>
<p>
Turkey straddles the Sea of Marmara, which divides Europe and Asia. The small<br>
European part of Turkey, called Thrace, measures 24,000 square kilometers.<br>
The remaining 757,000 square kilometers are called Anatolla and are part of<br>
the Asian continent. Turkey shares land borders with Greece, Bulgaria, Syria,<br>
Iraq, Iran, Georgia, and Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
Administratively, Turkey is divided into 79 provinces and 84 districts. The<br>
political capital is Ankara, but Istanbul is the commercial capital and<br>
largest city. It is the base for the largest companies and banks, and the<br>
main entry point by sea, air, and land. Domestic transport depends on roads<br>
along with the extensive air links and coastal shipping. Railways are not<br>
well developed.  <br>
<p>
Only 30 years ago, the population stood at 31.4 million.  In 1996, according<br>
to an estimate from the Population Reference<br>
Bureau based on data from Turkey's National Statistics Office,<br>
that figure had more than doubled to reach 63.9 million. About 63 percent of<br>
the population lives in urban areas. The populations of the largest cities<br>
are shown in the sidebar table on page 14.   <br>
Istanbul is growing quickly due to internal migration; the net inflow of<br>
people to the city averages 120,000 per year. Izmir, the manufacturing and<br>
transport center on the Aegean Sea coast, is growing faster than is Ankara.  <br>
<p>
The top three cities are far from being the only concentrations of<br>
population. There is a large number of second-tier cities of considerable<br>
size which are centers of regional economic activity and attract provincial<br>
migration. The southeastern city of Adana and the northeastern city of Bursa<br>
each have more than one million people. Antalya, Balikesir, Diyarbakir,<br>
Gaziantep, Hatay, Icel, Manisa, Samsun, and Sanli Urfa are districts of more<br>
than one million, and a further 25 cities are home to more than 500,000<br>
people each.    <br>
<p>
Each of these areas derives a strong identity from its region. On the<br>
northwestern coast of the Black Sea, for example, the Laz ethnic group<br>
dominates the cities of Trabzon and Rize. The Southeast is the domain of<br>
Kurds, more and more of whom are migrating to escape the poverty and conflict<br>
of their homeland. The outlying districts of Thrace show influence from<br>
Greece and Bulgaria.  <br>
<p>
The vast and frequently arid center of the country, locked into a traditional<br>
lifestyle based on small agricultural holdings, is losing population to the<br>
cities. In the modern environment of the coastal cities, the contrast between<br>
Westernized natives and conservative immigrants is sharp. Young women in<br>
tight jeans and T-shirts share space with contemporaries in ankle-length<br>
dresses and head scarves.  <br>
<p>
Turkey is an Islamic country, inasmuch as most of the population are Muslim<br>
in name. This should not be taken to mean that all Turks are practicing<br>
Muslims. A widely accepted analysis of religion in the country is that about<br>
one-sixth of the population are devout Muslims who follow the daily<br>
observances laid down in the Koran.  <br>
<p>
Perhaps 40 percent of the population attend mosques on the holy day, Friday.<br>
Religious practice is strongest in rural areas and the Southeast.  <br>
<p>
More potent a figure than Mohammed for modern Turks is Mustafa Kemal Ataturk,<br>
the leader who founded Turkey from the wreckage of the Ottoman Empire.<br>
Ataturk bequeathed a secular state to the Turks, and the vast majority of the<br>
population still separate Islam from business and education. Ataturk is<br>
revered with an almost religious intensity. Busts and profiles of the Father<br>
of the Turks are found in most homes and public places.  <br>
<p>
Necmettin Erbakan's Welfare Party drew about 25 percent of the vote in the<br>
1996 general elections, yet more than one-third of that support is said to<br>
have come from voters dissatisfied by corruption and inefficiency in the two<br>
major parties (both of which polled about the same as Welfare). Those who<br>
voted for Erbakan are nevertheless going to have to live with some Islamic<br>
policies.  <br>
<p>
A Shift in Attitude Toward Population Growth - One of these policies is less<br>
concern about population growth. Previous governments, both military and<br>
democratically elected ones, supported programs to restrict population<br>
growth. Welfare is inclined to ease off on these programs. The Islamic view<br>
of life as something given by God and above human interference is already<br>
evident in the high birth rates in the more religious Southeast and rural<br>
interior. Surveys by the State Institute of Statistics have found that<br>
couples in Mediterranean coast provinces desire an average of 2.28 children,<br>
compared with 3.47 in the Southeast. The national fertility rate was 2.65 in<br>
1990, compared with 6.1 in rural areas of the South East.  <br>
<p>
Turkey thus appears likely to continue the precipitous natural increase in<br>
its population until the end of this century. Infant and child mortality<br>
rates have fallen drastically over the past decade. At the same time the<br>
total fertility rate (the average number of children born to women in their<br>
child-bearing years) has stabilized at around 2.7, and the mean age at<br>
childbearing has dropped to 27.7 years.  <br>
<p>
External migration in the past has helped limit the impact on labor markets<br>
and social services of the average 2.17 percent annual growth in population.<br>
 <br>
<p>
Turkish guest workers and emigrants form significant communities in parts of<br>
Western Europe, especially Germany, and North America. The tightening of<br>
immigration laws in Europe now threatens this safety valve.  <br>
<p>
Immigration to Turkey, meanwhile, is small-scale. Aside from a period in the<br>
late 1980s and early 1990s marked by the forced exodus of the Turkish<br>
minority in Bulgaria, Turkey has generally counted its immigrants by the<br>
hundreds. There were 72,800 foreigners resident in the country in 1994, of<br>
whom 21,700 were from Bulgaria, 6,600 from Greece, 4,400 from Iran, 2,900<br>
from the U.S., and 2,400 from the former Soviet Union. <br>
<p>
Marriage as an institution remains strong. Surveying the population aged 12<br>
and over in 1990, the State Institute of Statistics found that 60.3 percent<br>
were married, 34.6 percent were single, 4.3 percent were widowed, and a mere<br>
0.8 percent were divorced. Each year sees an average of 450,000 marriages and<br>
27,000 divorces.  <br>
<p>
Most divorces occur in marriages of less than five years where there are no<br>
children, a sign of the importance of the nuclear family in this still<br>
traditional society. It is unusual for couples to live together before<br>
marriage.  <br>
<p>
So long as family earnings permit, women normally become home-makers after<br>
marriage.    <br>
<p>
Uninterrupted natural increase makes this a young society. Some 33 percent of<br>
the total population is younger than 15 years; only 5 percent is over age 65.<br>
<p>
<p>
Male life expectancy is 65 years, while women enjoy an extra five years of<br>
life on average.  <br>
<p>
Turkey is facing a rising demand for primary education and housing. Adult<br>
literacy is at about 82 percent.    <br>
<p>
Social welfare takes a back seat to defense spending, which accounts for 40<br>
to 50 percent of the government's annual budget. The military has a high<br>
profile in civil life. All men must complete military service of 16 to 18<br>
months.  <br>
<p>
In conversation, Turks will often express regret that the country's location<br>
compels such a high level of military spending, but there is little dissent.<br>
A pervasive sense of nationalism holds the country together. This is evident<br>
in the distinctive crescent- moon-and-star flag, which is flown proudly at<br>
every opportunity. Turks are passionate about their flag.  <br>
<p>
Earning, Spending, and Saving - Monetary conditions have been far from ideal<br>
in Turkey this decade. Most people have seen their nominal incomes rise with<br>
inflation while their real incomes have fallen. Uncertainty over the future<br>
has made it harder for businesses to attract investment or for retailers to<br>
draw buyers.  <br>
Using 1987 prices as a base rate of 100, the consumer price index was at<br>
754.5 in 1991, at 2,131.2 in 1993, and at 4,395.9 in 1994. Inflation in 1994<br>
was a record 125.3 percent as food prices doubled, property prices rose 85<br>
percent, and general household expenses rose 110 percent. To attract savings,<br>
banks today must offer 100 percent interest rates.  <br>
<p>
Fluctuations in exchange rates and GDP show up in dollar-based calculations<br>
of per capita income. GDP per head stood at US$2,724 in 1992, $3,033 in 1993,<br>
and $2,152 in 1994. Export-import and travel businesses now denominate many<br>
prices in U.S. dollars to protect against the regular devaluation of the<br>
Turkish lira.  <br>
<p>
Surprisingly, official statistics show little change in unemployment during<br>
the period of economic crisis. The unemployed have made up an average of 8<br>
percent of the labor force this decade. Urban unemployment stands at 11.5<br>
percent of those available to work in the cities.  <br>
<p>
What the statistics don't reflect is the extent of youth unemployment and<br>
underemployment. The low salaries offered starting workers have been rendered<br>
even more unattractive by inflation, and there still is a reluctance among<br>
employers to hire inexperienced graduates.  <br>
<p>
About 51 percent of the population over age 12 is in the labor force--an<br>
estimated 22.2 million people. Nearly 34 percent of women in this age group<br>
were in the labor force in 1994, according to OECD data.  <br>
<p>
A breakdown of the economically active population from a 1993 labor force<br>
survey gives an idea of the main spheres of work in Turkey. Of the 19.3<br>
million people included in the active category, the largest group, 8.4<br>
million, were engaged in agriculture, fishing, and related industries. Social<br>
and personal service industries, manufacturing, retailing and catering<br>
industries, and construction were other major employers.   <br>
<p>
Clothing and textiles are Turkey's main export earner, followed by iron and<br>
steel. Germany is the top trading partner, ahead of the USA. More than half<br>
the country's imports are raw materials, with consumer goods making up 14<br>
percent of the total.    <br>
<p>
Tourism has been an important growth sector over the past decade, and has<br>
become the second-largest earner of foreign exchange. Last year saw 7.8<br>
million overseas visitors, boosting employment in retailing and services,<br>
principally in Istanbul and the coastal centers.    <br>
<p>
Tourism revenues are now approximately US$5 billion a year. Remittances from<br>
overseas workers contribute a further $3 billion to the national coffers.  <br>
<p>
Households and Families -Turkey had 11.2 million households at the time of<br>
the 1990 census, 52.5 percent of them in urban areas.  <br>
<p>
Istanbul had 1.7 million households, Ankara 725,000, Izmir 650,000,and Adana,<br>
Bursa, and Konya some 350,000 each. The average household size was 5.2<br>
members.    <br>
<p>
Urbanization has not yet spawned the one-person household: There were as many<br>
households with eight members as there were with one in 1990. <br>
<p>
These statistics underscore the importance of the family as an economic unit<br>
in Turkey. Grandparents, grown-up children, and even grandchildren commonly<br>
live in the same household. When a child marries, families with means will<br>
try to build or buy an apartment for their offspring. It is rare for sons or<br>
daughters to move out on their own unless they have to move to another city<br>
for work.  <br>
<p>
Entrepreneurial activity sustains income at the household level. Urban<br>
households derive 30 percent of income from wages and salaries, compared with<br>
42 percent from rents, trade, and private enterprise. Rural households derive<br>
52 percent of their income from agriculture, with only 16 percent being<br>
earned in the form of wages and salaries. Although available figures have<br>
become fast outdated due to inflation, the general pattern is for urban<br>
households to earn 50 percent more than their rural counterparts, despite<br>
higher urban unemployment.    <br>
<p>
When it comes to expenditures, though, rural households appear to be in the<br>
better position. The average rural household spends no more than two-thirds<br>
of its income; the average urban household, 86 percent. Nationwide, prior to<br>
the economic crisis, households were saving 21 percent of their income. The<br>
primary items of consumption were food, housing, clothing, furniture, and<br>
transport/communications, in that order (see table in sidebar on page 15).  <br>
<p>
Expenditure on food and drink is high in part because of the priority Turks<br>
place on eating well. Great pride is taken in cooking and hosting meals.<br>
Lunch and dinner are occasions for families to get together, relax, and talk<br>
around a table. Meals are often accompanied by a bottle of the national<br>
liquor, raki, beer, or wine. The diet relies on fresh vegetables and fruits,<br>
dairy foods, seafood, and some meats (pork is not eaten). <br>
<p>
Self-contained houses are ever more the preserve of the economically<br>
advantaged in the cities and of rural families. Elsewhere, home is an<br>
apartment. Well-off families usually have a country house to which they can<br>
retreat from summer heat.    <br>
<p>
A sense of neighborliness still prevails in Turkish cities. Many apartment<br>
blocks have a grocer or fruit store on the ground floor purveying to the<br>
inhabitants and nearby residents. Turks are used to a sense of law and order<br>
in their cities. A rise in underworld crime in Istanbul this year has caused<br>
alarm in the media and parliament.  <br>
<p>
Cars are considered an essential item in most households, even if not all<br>
have the means to maintain one. In 1994, there were 2.86 million private<br>
cars, and 789,000 motorcycles registered in the country. European models,<br>
often produced in joint ventures with Turkish holdings, are the most popular.<br>
The market leader is Murat (a Turkish joint venture with Fiat). Renault and<br>
Ford are the number 2 and 3 makers, respectively. Toyota is the only Asian<br>
manufacturer with significant market share, but South Korea's Kia has just<br>
launched a joint venture with Ihlas Holding to make and sell Kias in Turkey.<br>
 <br>
<p>
Few Turkish houses are without basic household appliances such as<br>
refrigerators, washing machines, or gas ovens. White goods and consumer<br>
electronics tend to be of either German or Italian origin, or are<br>
domestically produced. Arcelik is the leading domestic brand for household<br>
appliances. Italian and French brands have the strongest impact in fields<br>
such as fashion, jewelry, and optics, with American fashions typically<br>
popular with those under age 25. Gold jewelry is a symbol of success and<br>
cause for pride among both men and women.<br>
<p>
Retailing is another area where European companies are making inroads.<br>
Traditionally, Turkish homemakers would make major weekly purchases at local<br>
markets, where they could stock up on fruit and vegetables, meat, and plastic<br>
goods. Convenience shopping was the preserve of local grocers.    <br>
<p>
Since the late 1980s, hypermarkets and shopping malls backed by European<br>
retailers have appeared to challenge this tradition. Sometimes pushing<br>
category-killers, sometimes using club shopping advantages, chains such as<br>
Migros, Metro, Tespo, Tansas, and Kiler are drawing Turkish shoppers away<br>
from city centers. Malls now offer services such as unlimited car parking and<br>
restaurants.  <br>
Lifestyles and Culture - Television is the best way of getting a message<br>
across to the Turkish consumer. There are 239 sets per 1,000 inhabitants, or<br>
more than one per household. It is safe to say that when a Turk is at home,<br>
the TV is rarely off. Accordingly, this is the number one advertising medium.<br>
 <br>
<p>
TRT, the government broadcasting corporation based in Ankara, runs four<br>
nationwide TV channels, as well as national radio stations. A fifth<br>
government channel, GAP, broadcasts to the Southeast. From Istanbul numerous<br>
private channels go nationwide, among them the movie- and drama-oriented<br>
Canal-D, Show, and HBB, the music stations Number 1 and Kral, and two Islamic<br>
channels.   There are more than 30 local stations in different parts of<br>
Turkey. <br>
<p>
Cable TV has proliferated in the major cities. Users pay around L1 million<br>
every three months to access stations like the domestic Cine 5, which has the<br>
rights to cover soccer games, and a menu of international channels including<br>
CNN, BBC Prime, and a sampling of German, French, Italian, and Spanish TV.<br>
The expansion of movie channels on cable has had a negative impact on the<br>
market for rental videos. Sales of VCRs are reported to be slack.  <br>
<p>
Cinemas too are losing out to home entertainment. In 1987, 460 cinemas were<br>
registered in the country, but in 1994 there were only 290. The domestic<br>
movie industry has fared worse than imports. There were 11.7 million<br>
spectators for Turkish movies in 1987, but only 1.8 million in 1994. The<br>
slower decline for foreign movies from 13.1 million to 9.3 million testifies<br>
to the continued appeal of Hollywood action on the big screens of Turkey. <br>
<p>
Radio is holding its ground against TV by offering tailored programs to women<br>
at home or drivers stuck in traffic. Soldiers in Turkey's 800,000-strong army<br>
depend on radio for their contact with the civilian world. Most private<br>
channels are on FM bands and gain daytime allegiance from TV viewers because<br>
of their lower ratio of advertisement to content.  <br>
<p>
After TV, newspapers are the main source of information for Turks. The<br>
newspaper world is currently experiencing intense competition to increase<br>
sales, among both the tabloid and quality dailies such as Hurriyet, Milliyet,<br>
Cumhuriyet, and Sabah. The competition is not concerned with price; rather,<br>
the newspapers increase their value by offering extravagant prizes to readers<br>
who can collect coupons from successive editions. Stereos and even cars have<br>
been given away, prompting parliament to seek controls over the giveaway<br>
campaigns. <br>
<p>
The telephone is an important communication tool for Turks. There are 159<br>
telephones per 1,000 people. Fax machines and personal computers are common<br>
in Turkish offices, though rare in homes. Limited by the small PC market and<br>
the plain existing phone network, use of the Internet is still in its<br>
infancy, though a spate of Internet-related seminars in Istanbul and Ankara<br>
this year give notice that cyberspace is reaching the Bosporus.  <br>
<p>
Eating out in restaurants or snack bars is an integral part of life for<br>
Turkish people, and is one area where friends rather than family form the<br>
group. Older men retire to coffee shops (kahvehane) to chat while sipping<br>
drinks, playing backgammon, and puffing tobacco through large water pipes.<br>
Work-mates drop into a doner kebab shop on the way home. Students and young<br>
couples drop into discos or cafe bars, where dancing is popular. <br>
<p>
Younger Turks living in the cities have a strong appetite for Western<br>
fashions and Turkish pop music. The thriving pop market is mostly<br>
merchandised in cassette tapes, which cost an affordable US$6 per unit,<br>
one-third the price of a CD. Songs and videos purvey an image of open<br>
sexuality, often at odds with the older generation who generally enjoy the<br>
sedate tones of Turkish classical music. <br>
<p>
There is no disputing that Turkey's most important sport is soccer, which is<br>
followed with a passion that rivals that of Brazil. Top honors have eluded<br>
the national team, yet the best clubs like Galatasaray and Fenerbahce have<br>
scored notable wins in European competition.<br>
<p>
Internationally, Turkey succeeds at weightlifting and wrestling, the latter<br>
being a great tradition.  Participation in sports is mostly informal. Outside<br>
of schools, only 120,000 Turks were active members of sports clubs in 1994,<br>
reports the General Directorate of Youth and Sports. Jogging and aerobics are<br>
popular.  <br>
<p>
Women's beauty salons often incorporate gym functions.    <br>
<p>
Determined as they are to enjoy life, Turks have not developedthe health<br>
consciousness or the environmental concerns of their European neighbors. At<br>
least three- quarters of men and one-half of women smoke cigarettes, the<br>
brands of choice being Marlboro and nationally produced Tekel. Recycling is<br>
rudimentary. On the other hand, streets and beaches are generally clean.    <br>
<p>
This reflects a paradox about the Turks. While they do not seem too concerned<br>
about their own status and health, that of their family and country is<br>
paramount. <br>
<p>
Critics talk of a me-first mentality creeping into Turkish culture, yet to an<br>
outsider the group orientation of this society remains striking.  <br>
<p>
It is this orientation that is helping Turks get by in the difficult 1990s.<br>
When jobs and money seem insecure, the strong family structure comes into<br>
play to help.  <br>
<p>
Targeting the breadwinner (usually the senior man) and the decision-maker<br>
(the senior woman) within the family unit is important for business success.<br>
 <br>
<p>
The problems faced by Turks have eased a bit since 1994, but stability is<br>
still elusive. Regional tensions could flare up at any time. Population<br>
growth is adding to the difficulties caused by inflation. For the short term<br>
at least, Turkish consumers are likely to be cautious about making big<br>
commitments and to stick to the things they know.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
