!ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/23/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. ARF DELEGATION MEETS WITH RUSSIAN OFFICIALS<br>
2. KOCHARIAN SWEARS IN<br>
3. MANOUKIAN CALLS FOR A UNITED FRONT<br>
4. ARF YOUTH ATTEND EURO-COUNCIL CONFERENCE<br>
5. TER-PETROSYAN ASKED TO REPRESENT ACCUSED MINISTRY OFFICIAL<br>
6. INVESTMENT ACTIVITY DROPPED THIS YEAR<br>
7. AVETISSIAN PLEADS NOT GUILTY<br>
8. REFUGEES IN ARMENIA RELUCTANT TO ACQUIRE CITIZENSHIP<br>
9. IRAN, TURKEY PLEDGE FOR CLOSER TIES DESPITE US<br>
<p>
<p>
1. ARF DELEGATION MEETS WITH RUSSIAN OFFICIALS<br>
<p>
MOSCOW-A delegation of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation <br>
Bureau and the ARF Executive Council of Armenia was in Moscow from <br>
December 18-22 for a number of high-level meetings.<br>
	ARF Bureau chairperson Peno Tontian and members Mgrdich <br>
Mgrdichian, Apo Boghigian and Martun Matevossian were joined by <br>
ARF Executive Council members Rouben Hakobian, Hovik Aghazarian <br>
and Gagik Mkrtchian, as well as Seyran Baghdassarian, director of <br>
the ARF Bureau office in Moscow.<br>
	The ARF delegation attended the annual meeting of the <br>
Russian Communities Congress on Saturday, Dec. 21 at the Hall of <br>
Writers of the Russian Federation.<br>
	RCC chairman Dimitri Rogozin and ARF Executive Council <br>
politicial affairs director Rouben Hakobian signed a declaration <br>
of cooperation and called for continued friendly relations between <br>
the Russian and Armenian peoples.<br>
	Later that evening, the ARF delegation met with former <br>
presidential candidate and National Security Minister Alexander <br>
Lebed. The group expressed their deep gratitude to General Lebed <br>
for his unwavering and decisive support of the Armenian residents <br>
of Baku during the 1990 pogroms in the city in an attempt to rid <br>
the Azeri capital of its Armenian population. Lebed was the <br>
commander of the Russian forces in Baku at the time of the <br>
pogroms, and is credited for saving the lives of nearly 200,000 <br>
Armenians.<br>
	The two-hour meeting also foused on common geopolitical <br>
interests and stressed the importance of Russian-Armenian <br>
cooperation in that sphere.<br>
	On Friday, the ARF delegation, joined by writer Zori <br>
Balayan, met with Russian Federation Deputy Prime Minister <br>
Alexander Lobov, and thanked him for his continued support of <br>
Armenia and the Armenian people, especially for his efforts in <br>
assisting the 1988 earthquake survivors. The meeting also focused <br>
on political relations of Armenia and the Russian Federation and <br>
issues related to further development of Russian-Armenian ties.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. KOCHARIAN SWEARS IN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-President-elect Robert Kocharian was sworn <br>
in on Dec. 23 at a special session of the Karabakh National <br>
Assembly. Robert Kocharian was elected president of the Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh Republic in the Nov. 24 national election.<br>
	At the ceremony, the President swore to safeguard the <br>
Constitution and Laws of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic, security <br>
of Karabakh citizens and their rights and freedoms. <br>
	He said that it was his duty to pursue a political line <br>
aimed at ensuring the unity of the people of Nagorno-Karabakh, <br>
Armenia and the Armenian Diaspora.<br>
	Head of the Artsakh Diocese, Bishop Barkev Martirossian said <br>
a prayer and blessed the President and the people of Artsakh. The <br>
inauguration was attended by Armenias Foreign Minister, Alexander <br>
Arzoumanian and Chairman of the Central Bank of Armenia, Bagrat <br>
Assatrian.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. MANOUKIAN CALLS FOR A UNITED FRONT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-"I bear the responsibility for the events on <br>
Sept. 25, for the rally and procession to the parliament building. <br>
People followed my call, and if the authorities are looking for <br>
those responsible for the events, they must know that it is I and <br>
not the 18 young people who are still in custody. I am <br>
responsible, but not guilty," National Democratic Union Chairman <br>
Vazgen Manoukian said at the NDU party conference.<br>
	Manoukians speech was mainly devoted to the political <br>
consequences of 1996, particularly  the post-election events of <br>
Sept. 25. He noted that the authorities were interested in <br>
creating disorder, particularly by firing upon a rallying crowd. <br>
According to Manoukian, the uncontrollable situation allowed the <br>
authorities to define those events as an attempt of a coup detat.<br>
	"Entering the parliament building was not a wrong thing. The <br>
people had the right to dictate their will. However, as a man and <br>
political figure, I condemn the violence that took place that <br>
day," Manoukian said.<br>
	Manoukian said that his election campaign erased the myths <br>
claiming that there was no replacement for Levon Ter-Petrosyan and <br>
that, no matter who comes to power, he would be incapable of <br>
changing anything in the country. <br>
	Manoukian compared the high electoral activity in 1996 with <br>
the all-national movement of 1988. According to him, the events <br>
during the election campaign was a surprise to the authorities <br>
which resulted in actions that were inadequate for the situation. <br>
	Manoukian said that the falsifications of the poll returns <br>
were accompanied by secret arrests. For example, after the rally <br>
on Sept. 24, 11 cars were impounded, and their owners, who took an <br>
active part in the election campaign, were arrested. "The <br>
authorities tried to threaten the society."<br>
	"I overestimated the authorities respect for Armenias <br>
future. It turned out that their personal interests are top <br>
priority for them," Manoukian said. He pointed out that the power <br>
elected in a non-democratic way will obviously lose respect in the <br>
world.<br>
	"Under current authority, Armenia is deprived of a future, <br>
since the state is not capable of showing political, military and <br>
economic power. I think that the problem of Nagorno-Karabakh must <br>
be solved by a shift in authority as well," Manoukian said.<br>
	Manoukian said that the opposition was never against an <br>
agreement with the authorities, but any agreement must have been <br>
conducted within the guidelines of justice. Organizations of new <br>
elections and adoption of a new Constitution are the problems <br>
which the opposition will negotiate with the authorities in the <br>
future. According to Manoukian, the social and economic crises <br>
will deepen in the near future, the discords within the power <br>
structure will get worse and they will gradually lose power.<br>
	Under such conditions it is necessary to establish a single <br>
front. It is expected that in order to form such a front, <br>
representatives of the National Accord bloc will start <br>
negotiations with other political parties, as well as public <br>
organizations.<br>
	"Our main objective is to get back to a democratic way of <br>
development and running of new elections. To do this, we need to <br>
strengthen our party," he said.<br>
	The next NDU congress will take place in February of 1997.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. ARF YOUTH ATTEND EURO-COUNCIL CONFERENCE<br>
<p>
BUDAPEST-A representative of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation <br>
Youth Organization, Hagop Sarian of Cyprus, participated in the <br>
European Council-sponsored "Euro-Arab Cooperation" conference in <br>
Budapest, Hungary.<br>
	The Dec. 10-14 conference aimed at strengthening European <br>
and Arab relations and outlining future relations at the youth <br>
level.<br>
	The general meeting and the various workshops stressed the <br>
importance of peace as a pre-condition to resolving regional <br>
conflicts democratically, emphasizing the right to self-<br>
determination, while condemning the forceful seizure of <br>
territories and the perpetuation of hostilities.<br>
	The conference participants called for mutual understanding <br>
and consent in settling regional issues.<br>
	The conference adopted the following decisions: development, <br>
at the youth level, of educational programs aimed at conflict <br>
prevention and the establishment of peace, as well as educational <br>
exchange of cadres; establishment of a non-governmental youth <br>
association and a sub-committee of the European Council to <br>
facilitate the issuing of travel visas; publication of key human <br>
rights documents in Arabic and organization of a conference <br>
focusing on the rights of youth; <br>
involvement in the development of educational activities and <br>
programs of UNESCO; establishment of a youth information center; <br>
and use of modern communication technologies in English, French <br>
and Arabic language youth publications.<br>
	The conference called on the European Council to assist in <br>
the implementation of the decisions adopted in Budapest.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. TER-PETROSYAN ASKED TO REPRESENT ACCUSED MINISTRY OFFICIAL<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The former advisor to the Minister of <br>
Interior, Aram Petrossian, who was arrested on March 7 for the <br>
illegal possession of weapons and fraud, submitted a written <br>
appeal to the court inviting Levon Ter-Petrosyan to be his <br>
attorney. <br>
	Petrossian based his appeal on the provision of the <br>
Constitution that the Armenian President is a guarantor of every <br>
Armenian citizens rights. Judge Albert Hakobian turned down the <br>
appeal.<br>
	Extremely upset by the rejection, Petrossian appealed for <br>
postponement of the session. He refused to testify unless his <br>
attorney was invited.<br>
	The defendant made two statements at the session.<br>
	First, he demanded that the investigation be carried out by <br>
the Prosecutor-Generals office. According to legislation, <br>
proceedings instituted against officers of interior law <br>
enforcement agencies are conducted by the Prosecutor-Generals <br>
office. Petrossian noted that this fact was concealed by the <br>
investigator of the sixth department of the Ministry of Interior, <br>
Vanik Obossian, who introduced the defendant as a director of a <br>
limited liability society.<br>
	Secondly, Petrossian told the court that the first deputy <br>
chairman of the sixth department of the interior ministry, Hamlet <br>
Hakobian was using his "Lada" type car after he was arrested on <br>
March 8, 1996. Petrossian said that he had given his car to one of <br>
his creditors. Judge Hakobian said that if this fact is confirmed, <br>
the case would be considered as a violation of the law.<br>
	Manoukian was charged with defaulting on $600,000 in loans <br>
from the Armimpexbank, Ardshinbank, Land, and Credit-Yerevan <br>
banks.<br>
	He also denied the weapons charges against him and refused <br>
saying that two of his five bodyguards had the right to carry <br>
weapons. He insisted that the gun found in his possession was <br>
planted by the employees of the sixth department of the Interior <br>
Ministry. <br>
	Petrossian refuted the statements saying that he used the <br>
credits for his personal use. He stressed that part of the money <br>
was used for reconstruction of the Childrens Railway of Yerevan, <br>
supplies for the childrens cafe, stationing 17 sculptures in the <br>
territory of the park and reconstruction of the Zovk mineral water <br>
plant.<br>
	He said that he was physically and psychologically pressured <br>
to provide some of the statements.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. INVESTMENT ACTIVITY DROPPED THIS YEAR<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The investment activity index, "Hrant," <br>
dropped two-fold for the year of 1996. Hayk Markarian, Director of <br>
the "Hrant" investment and broker company said that in January the <br>
IAI was 15.11, whereas in December it is 7.8.<br>
	IAI estimates the investment activity on the basis of <br>
indices, like the exchange rate of the dram, market price of <br>
privatization certificates, application volumes for real estate <br>
purchase and other indicators.<br>
	According to Markarian, the causes of the IAI drop are <br>
insufficient investment offers. Despite the fact that the volume <br>
and term of privatization were corrected many times by the <br>
parliament, the government failed to ensure the privatization even <br>
in the corrected volumes and extended terms. Besides, the <br>
government could never be able to offer a large enough amount of <br>
securities and attractive conditions for their placement.<br>
	Another reason was the decision on emission of new vouchers. <br>
That decision resulted in a drop of market prices for vouchers and <br>
a real reduction of sums designed for privatization.<br>
	Lastly, political instability, indefinite prospects of <br>
resolution of the Karabakh problem, the presidential elections and <br>
questions on voting that remained disputable after the polls are <br>
among the risk factors from the point of view of both foreign and <br>
domestic investors.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. AVETISSIAN PLEADS NOT GUILTY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-At the Dec. 19 court session of the "Trial <br>
of 31," defendant Tigran Avetissian pleaded not guilty to charges <br>
of plotting a coup.<br>
	As to the murder of the policeman, Avetissian said that Gnel <br>
Hovanessian had been shot at by one of the policemen. He said he <br>
fired a shot into the ground, however, a bullet fired from the AK-<br>
47 might have ricocheted and hit the policeman. He saw the <br>
policeman squat. Avetissian said that while hiding in Sourenavan <br>
they were surprised to learn about the murder of the policeman, as <br>
both him and Gagik Karapetian had been shooting into the ground.<br>
	The defendant noted that on August 23, 1995 he surrendered <br>
to the Shengavit police department of the Ministry of Internal <br>
Affairs. Defendant Manvel Yeghiazarian, commander of the "Arapo" <br>
detachment, said that allegations from the preliminary <br>
investigation stating that only one of the three policemen had a <br>
gun was inconceivable. He said that a shot fired from an AK-47 <br>
from that range would have left a larger burn area on the body.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. REFUGEES IN ARMENIA RELUCTANT TO ACQUIRE CITIZENSHIP<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The main topics for discussion on the first <br>
day of the "Naturalization of Refugees in the Republic of Armenia" <br>
conference held in Yerevan were problems of economic, political <br>
and psychological effects on refugees and the creation of a legal <br>
basis providing for their full integration into the community.<br>
	Lilia Kalian, chief of the Social Security Ministrys <br>
Migration Department and leader of the "Refugees and Displaced <br>
Persons" working group, noted in her speech that acquiring <br>
citizenship would mean changing the refugee status. No similar <br>
procedure exists in international practice, nor does it correspond <br>
to the norms of the International Convention on Refugee Status, <br>
which calls for the promotion of refugee naturalization and the <br>
acceleration of legal procedures.<br>
	Gevork Poghossian, the president of the Armenian <br>
Sociological Association, stressed the role of non-governmental <br>
organizations that might conduct explanatory works among refugees. <br>
Refugees ought to realize that by having only social rights and no <br>
citizenship they cannot be valuable citizens of the country and <br>
take part in its political and economic life.<br>
	While R. Melik-Pashaeva, leader of a non-governmental <br>
refugee organization, said that refugees must be guaranteed <br>
housing and work first and only in that case a real naturalization <br>
was possible. Besides, in accordance with the Armenian law only a <br>
person who has a permanent registration in Armenia may acquire <br>
citizenship. At present, thousands of refugees live in communal <br>
centers, boarding-houses, hotels and houses unfit for use, and the <br>
authorities will not register them there.<br>
	The participants of the conference agreed that it was <br>
necessary to create a legal and material basis and social <br>
guarantees, elaboration of a single policy in relation to the <br>
problem of the naturalization of refugees in Armenia, and their <br>
full integration was also needed.<br>
	The conference was organized by the Armenian Social Security <br>
Ministrys Migration Department along with the International <br>
Migration Organization and United Nations High Commissioner for <br>
Refugees.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. IRAN, TURKEY PLEDGE FOR CLOSER TIES DESPITE US<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-Turkey and Iran signed several accords Saturday to <br>
boost economic relations following top level talks between the two <br>
neighbors in defiance of US efforts to isolate Tehran.<br>
	"If the agreements we have signed disturb other countries, <br>
it is their problem," Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani <br>
told a news conference after signing the accords with Turkish <br>
President Suleyman Demirel in Ankara.<br>
	"The policy of (the United States of) America is to prevent <br>
strong countries in this region from cooperating," said <br>
Rafsanjani, on the third day of a four-day visit.<br>
	"I dont think America can change our cooperation policy <br>
with Turkey. The Turkish president, prime minister and we are <br>
determined not to allow America to dictate anything to our <br>
region."<br>
	The US government on Friday expressed disapproval of <br>
Rafsanjanis visit to the NATO member Turkey and advised Ankara <br>
against improving relations with Tehran.<br>
	The United States, a close ally of NATO member Turkey, has <br>
accused Iran of sponsoring terrorism. Iran denies the charge. <br>
	Rafsanjanis visit marks a step forward in strengthening <br>
relations between the two Moslem countries since Necmettin Erbakan <br>
became Turkeys first Islamist prime minister in June. <br>
	"A turn to Islamic movement has started in Turkey. And the <br>
latest general elections is the best example of this," he said of <br>
the Welfare Party of Erbakan, which narrowly came first in the <br>
December 1995 elections.<br>
	The Islamist-led Turkish government and Iran aim to double <br>
the two-way trade volume to $2 billion from 1997, enable easier <br>
capital flow for investments and benefit from port facilities in <br>
the three agreements.<br>
	A memorandum of understanding will enable cooperation in <br>
environmental matters and a protocol envisages establishing a <br>
common chamber of commerce and industry to enable communication <br>
between the two countries industrial firms.<br>
	The sides also agreed to open credit lines worth $150 <br>
million to each other to finance bilateral trade.<br>
	Turkey said on Friday it would renew a current oil import <br>
agreement with Iran to continue to buy 4.5 million metric tons of <br>
Iranian crude from April, when the current agreement expires. <br>
	The presidential talks followed a series of joint economic <br>
meetings earlier in the week in which senior Turkish and Iranian <br>
officials agreed to launch air links on Istanbul-Tabriz and <br>
Ankara-Tehran lines and improve a rail link from Tehran to eastern <br>
Turkey.<br>
	Turkish officials have said a six-month study would be <br>
launched to investigate the feasibility of a pipeline to carry <br>
Iranian oil to Western markets through Turkey.<br>
	Iran and Turkey agreed in August in Tehran to build a <br>
pipeline to carry three billion cubic meters of Iranian gas <br>
annually to Turkey from 1998 under a 23-year, $23-billion deal. <br>
	The pipeline and gas deal was struck days after President <br>
Bill Clinton signed a law imposing sanctions on any company <br>
investing over $40 million a year in energy projects in Iran or <br>
Libya.<br>
	Ankara said the deal would not be affected by US sanctions <br>
because Turkey was only constructing the stretch of pipeline on <br>
its own territory, for which it announced a tender last week.<br>
<p>
