<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/22/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/22/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Sun, 22 Dec 1996 23:34:37 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#204">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#204">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#204">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#204">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0205.html">Dr Manook Soghomonian: "Pan-Armenian Acad. Sci. Soc. News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0203.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/23/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Minister reports "unity of views" with Russia on "significant issues" <br>
2.  Ciller comments on "very favourable" visit on return from Russia <br>
3.  Kurdish MED TV reports oppression of Alawite Kurds in Erzincan <br>
4.  Transponder Watch: 7oE: Eutelsat II F4 <br>
5.  Toddler proves the star of Stalin birthday bash <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Minister reports "unity of views" with Russia on "significant<br>
issues" <br>
SOURCE: TRT TV, Ankara, in Turkish 1300 gmt 19 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Tansu Ciller, foreign minister and deputy prime minister, has said that a<br>
unity of views has been reached between Turkey and Russia on taking joint<br>
steps on significant issues concerning regional peace. <br>
<p>
Ciller, who concluded her contacts in Moscow, held a news conference. She<br>
said that the Turkish-Russian protocol on cooperation against terror and the<br>
agreement on the vc construction of the Turkish-Russian Trade Centre in<br>
Moscow signed during her visit would give an impetus to the development of<br>
bilateral relations. Pointing out that Turkey and Russia had clearly stated<br>
that they respected one another's territorial integrity as well as that of<br>
other countries, Ciller added that the two countries would act jointly<br>
regarding the solution of the Karabakh issue. Drawing attention to the fact<br>
that Turkey was the second country on Russia's foreign trade list, Ciller<br>
said that the bilateral volume of trade would grow through the joint projects<br>
to be discussed in the near future. She added that another important issue<br>
that came up during her visit was that all the Russian officials, including<br>
Russian Prime Minister [Viktor] Chernomyrdin in particular, had promised that<br>
they would not approach the economic projects in the region with political<br>
considerations. Ciller noted that the developments achieved during her talks<br>
regarding visa exemptions between the two countries would significantly<br>
contribute to the development of bilateral trade relations. <br>
<p>
Ciller said that the 6 billion cubic meters of natural gas purchased annually<br>
from Russia would be increased to 14 billion at the joint economic committee<br>
meeting that will convene in January. She noted that significant developments<br>
had been achieved in the projects concerning the transfer of natural gas to<br>
Samsun in a bid to meet Turkey's needs. She added that 3 billion cubic meters<br>
would be transferred from Russia to Turkey via Georgia and 16 billion cubic<br>
meters via the Black Sea. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Ciller comments on "very favourable" visit on return from Russia <br>
SOURCE: TRT TV, Ankara, in Turkish 1800 gmt 19 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Tansu Ciller, foreign minister and deputy prime minister, has concluded her<br>
visit to Moscow and returned to Turkey. Some ministers and other officials<br>
received Ciller at Ankara's Esenboga airport. <br>
<p>
In a statement she issued, Ciller said that her contacts in the Russian<br>
Federation had been vc very favourable. Explaining that she had held a very<br>
long and comprehensive meeting with Russian Prime Minister Viktor<br>
Chernomyrdin, Ciller added that a significant unity of views was reached on<br>
settling differences on regional issues. In this context, Ciller stressed,<br>
Russia accepted that the Turkomans [Turkic people in northern Iraq] should<br>
secure their autonomy within the framework of Iraq's territorial security.<br>
She added that issuing an official communique on this issue was an important<br>
step for Turkey . <br>
<p>
Commenting on the Azeri-Armenian conflict, Ciller said that Russia shared<br>
Turkey's views along the lines of recognizing the Azeri territorial integrity<br>
in its entirety. Ciller said: Our mutual work will proceed. For this reason,<br>
it is very important in terms of international relations that our neighbour<br>
Russia confirmed Azerbaijan's territorial integrity. Ciller further explained<br>
that important steps were taken towards encouraging investment projects by<br>
eliminating the obstacles in the way of Turkish transporters and the issuing<br>
of visas. <br>
<p>
Recounting that an agreement in principle was reached with Russia with regard<br>
to meeting Turkey's natural gas demands in 1999 and 2000, Ciller continued:<br>
The agreement envisages the transportation of 14 billion out of the 45<br>
billion cubic metres of natural gas needed by Turkey through Bulgaria and<br>
Romania, another 16 billion cubic metres from the Black Sea to Samsun, and 3<br>
billion cubic metres through Georgia. Thus, the agreement in principle<br>
roughly envisages the transportation of 34-35 billion cubic metres of natural<br>
gas from Russia to Turkey. This is very important for Turkey. BOTAS [Pipeline<br>
and Petroleum Transport Corporation] will be an associate in this project,<br>
and in this way Turkey will have the possibility of distributing cheap<br>
energy. Also noting that all their aims were directed towards making Turkey<br>
an oil distributing country, Ciller added: Thus, in the next three to five<br>
years, Turkey will assume its position as a country which distributes oil<br>
transported from the Caspian Sea and the Iraqi oil pipelines as well as<br>
through the Mediterranean Sea. <br>
<p>
Ciller continued: In this context, we insisted that the Caspian Sea oil,<br>
which is envisaged to reach Nova [place name as heard] and Supsa in the Black<br>
Sea, cannot be transported through the straits. Transporting this oil through<br>
the straits will pose a danger for Istanbul and its 10-million population and<br>
is impossible both physically as well as for environmental reasons. We<br>
explained this very clearly to all the Russian officials. We also told them<br>
not to rely on transporting the oil through the straits when they make their<br>
calculations, and that it is essential in terms of regional peace and the<br>
interests of both countries that Russia should become a partner in this<br>
system, which will transport this oil to the Mediterranean and distribute it<br>
from there. I am pleased to say that this view was received with<br>
understanding. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Kurdish MED TV reports oppression of Alawite Kurds in Erzincan <br>
SOURCE: MED-TV, London, in Turkish 1815 gmt 18 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
The state is oppressing the Alawites in Erzincan [eastern Turkey]. The state,<br>
with the collaboration of Bunyamin Kuran, one of the commanders of the<br>
gendarmerie, and Erzincan Governor Recep Yazicioglu, is trying to evacuate<br>
the villages inhabited by the Alawite Kurds. The village evacuation policy is<br>
being implemented by the state forces with the aim of depopulating the region<br>
using the vc pretext that the regional people are abetting the PKK [Kurdistan<br>
Workers' Party]. <br>
<p>
Many have been detained and tortured in Refahiye and surrounding villages<br>
during the past 20 days. Following these developments, a news conference was<br>
held at the Pir Sultan Abdal Cultural Centre. Those who had been detained, as<br>
well as the presidents of the Tunceli, Divrigi, Imranli, and Bahadir Cultural<br>
Associations and the Haci Bektas Veli Anadolu Cultural Fund, participated in<br>
the news conference. Videotaped interviews with those who were tortured while<br>
in detention were screened at the news conference. The tapes explained that<br>
even the mentally disturbed were tortured and accused. The interviewees<br>
disclosed that the methods of torture included electric shocks and sexual<br>
assaults. <br>
<p>
Murtaza Demir, president of the Pir Sultan Abdal Cultural Association, said<br>
that the oppression was mounting and that there were attempts to expel the<br>
Alawites living in the Refahiye provincial centre and its surrounding<br>
villages from the region. He added that Kuran threatened the Alawites in<br>
order to get them to leave the region. According to Demir, Kuran says the<br>
following to the detainees: You are traitors. I will not let you live here.<br>
You are actually from Tunceli [south of Erzincan], and the residents of<br>
Tunceli are of Armenian origin. This country cannot benefit from you. Demir<br>
said that Kuran also tortured the detainees. Noting that the regional people<br>
were being forced to emigrate through such pressures, Demir said that a<br>
delegation would be sent to the region and a rally organized. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Transponder Watch: 7oE: Eutelsat II F4 <br>
SOURCE:  Cable and Satellite Europe, November 1996<br>
<p>
An unusual uplink was captioned UKI 252 Yerevan on 11080MHz vertical and a<br>
quick look at the map identified it as Armenia, east of Turkey.  The beam of<br>
these satellites extends quite well East, but is dropping fast by the time it<br>
crosses Turkeys eastern border.   Rai Pico is seen on weekday mornings vc<br>
around 0900 GMT on 11080MHz vertical.  This satellite is also used for feeds<br>
out of Israel; APTV fed ex-Jerusalem on 11178MHz horizontal, before the start<br>
of Serbian RTS TV.  (ruling) Party's conference output was partly fed on this<br>
satellite.  A speech by the UK Prime Minister appeared on 11142MHz vertical.<br>
Nagravision scrambled signals at 11163MHz horizontal are from Euro Trans Med.<br>
WorldNet, C-SPAN and the VOA piggyback radio feeds have all left 11575MHz<br>
vertical for a digital feed on another satellite.  Regular broadcasters at<br>
this neglected location are VTV Slovakia, ATV from Turkey which is<br>
re-locating to Turksat 1C, Sarajevo's BiH TV, Greek International TV and<br>
InterStar, also from Turkey.  A digital feed at 11631MHz vertical is from the<br>
Turkish Kral TV.  RTP Lisbon will leave if and when Hot Bird 2 is ready. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Toddler proves the star of Stalin birthday bash <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France Presse,  December 21, 1996<br>
<p>
Georgia's die-hard communists celebrated the 117th anniversary of Stalin's<br>
birth Saturday by christening the Soviet dictator's two-year-old namesake and<br>
great-great-grandson, Josef Dzhugashvili junior. <br>
<p>
A crowd of some 600 gathered outside Stalin's humble brick house, now a<br>
museum, in his birthplace Gori, 65 kilometres (35 miles) east of the capital<br>
Tbilisi. <br>
<p>
The town is the centre of a personality vc cult that, despite official Soviet<br>
"de-Stalinisation," never quite died in the republic of the ex-dictator's<br>
birth. <br>
<p>
The die-hard communists carried portraits of Stalin, who died in 1953, and<br>
banners reading: "Bring Back Free Medical Care and Free Education," and<br>
"Hail, the United Communist Party." <br>
<p>
"We must do all we can to show today's youth the true face of comrade Stalin,<br>
and somehow help them to form an objective opinion about the personality of<br>
the great leader," said Stalin's grandson, Yevgeny Dzhugashvili. <br>
<p>
Yevgeny is the son of Stalin's eldest son, Yakov, who died as a<br>
prisoner-of-war in German captivity during World War II. <br>
<p>
The crowd greeted Yevgeny's grandson, two-year-old Josef, with thunderous<br>
applause, and were then treated to a display of disco-dancing by a Gori<br>
childrens' group called the "21st-Century Communists." <br>
<p>
Young children recited poems written by Stalin in his youth, when he still<br>
went by the name of Josef Dzhugashvili, and had not yet risen to become<br>
dictator of the proletariat. <br>
<p>
The crowd, waving red flags and clutching bouquets, then moved on to the<br>
four-metre-high (12-foot) granite Stalin statue that dominates the town. <br>
<p>
Turkish and Armenian communists were among the Stalin fans who turned out to<br>
praise the Soviet supreme leader who fostered a monolithic personality cult<br>
and unleashed state-sponsored terror which claimed millions of lives. <br>
<p>
Later, communists accompanied Yevgeny Stalin and his family to the Sioni<br>
Monastery, for the christening of Josef Dzhugashvili junior, for once turning<br>
a blind eye to the atheist teachings of Marxism-Leninism. <br>
<p>
Three clerics struggled to hold the screaming toddler, but finally managed to<br>
wrap three little gold crosses round his neck. <br>
<p>
Georgia's communists have high expectations of the boy who bears one of the<br>
most infamous names in history. <br>
<p>
Niko Abuashvili, a member of the United Georgian Communist Party, remarked:<br>
"a person's genes are immortal, and I'm sure that this boy will fulfil our<br>
ideas no less successfully than his great-grandfather." <br>
<p>
The party's leader Panteleimon Giorgadze, who was in Moscow Saturday, sent a<br>
message of congratulations for the christening and anniversary. <br>
<p>
The old Stalinists' ignorance of religious tradition was revealed when they<br>
stood with their backs to the church icons and failed to observe any of the<br>
Christian rituals during the ceremony. <br>
<p>
The christening was rounded off with a banquet in honour of the new rising<br>
star in the Georgian communists' firmament. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
