<title>Groong Network: NeGa interview with Shamil Basayev</title>
<h1>NeGa interview with Shamil Basayev</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 21 Dec 1996 13:17:09 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#202">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#202">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#202">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#202">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0203.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/23/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0201.html">Zareh Khachatourian: "Boston Area Event"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nezavisimaya Gazeta 21 December 1996 page 3<br>
<p>
   Interview with Shamil Basayev by Maksim Shevchenko under the general<br>
headline:  "Who Is the Culprit in the War"<br>
<p>
  [Shevchenko]  First of all, what do you think about the tragic incident in<br>
Novyye Atagi.  Who do you think is behind this crime?<br>
 [Basayev]  At first I was inclined to think that this act was committed by<br>
regular criminals.  An unhealthy atmosphere has long developed around that<br>
hospital, related to financial matters, and even mere employment with very<br>
good compensation packages.  Yet, judging by the massive onslaught in the<br>
Russian mass media and their state of agitation during the past three days,<br>
I come to the conclusion that this is the work of Russian special services,<br>
timed to coincide with Raduyev's capturing of POW's.  Generally, standing<br>
behind it are the people who are strongly anti-peace.  This is an act of<br>
unprecedented vandalism.  We Chechens are saying today that we regret,<br>
sympathize, and so forth.  In fact, however, the stigma of disgrace has<br>
fallen on all Chechens and all citizens of the republic.  Our people have<br>
never offended a guest.  Meanwhile, recently guests began to be kidnapped<br>
and even killed.  The Chechen people cannot do this; the Chechens cannot act<br>
in this way.  During this war we have had plenty of opportunity to kill<br>
indiscriminately; the people were strongly embittered.  Yet nobody -- not<br>
even Russian journalists, even though they were fighting on the Russian side<br>
-- was touched here.  I think that this is a provocation aimed against<br>
elections, against ending the war, and against peace.  But we shall do our<br>
utmost to catch the criminals in the very near future and punish them severely. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  Precisely who could be behind the crime?  Maybe you have some<br>
theories?<br>
 [Basayev]  Today I am a private person.  But I have talked with President<br>
Yandarbiyev on this count, and he told me that there is some information<br>
about it.  All our power structures are at work, including the Internal<br>
Affairs Ministry, the State Security Department, and a special<br>
anti-terrorist group.  Work is in progress on all lines.  I spoke with the<br>
deputy internal affairs minister, and representatives of the State Security<br>
Department, and listened to a tape recording the discussion of economic and<br>
financial matters at the hospital.  There has been a lot of juggling with<br>
figures, and abuses.  But most importantly, today I have attended a session<br>
of the Human Rights Committee which adopted a document and expressed<br>
condolences; I was also present at a session of the International<br>
Conciliation Group which adopted an appeal to the Red Cross and other<br>
international organizations, stressing that the Chechens cannot do this with<br>
their own hands -- if only because we badly need the Red Cross.  Now they<br>
have gone, and we have over 200 mentally sick people in Zakan-Yurt without<br>
medical care, without food, without anything....  In fact, several thousand<br>
people in the republic have been left without medical assistance or food<br>
supplies.  We are not suicides to do this with our own hands.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Shamil, some political figures and media organizations link<br>
your name with the strange situation around the North Ossetian delegation.<br>
Could you clarify this issue?<br>
 [Basayev]  At the time when the delegation went missing I was at the<br>
village of Novoye Gordalo, taking part in the exchange of the Penza OMON<br>
[special purpose militia] troopers.  I learned about the incident in the<br>
evening from a TV news show, where everything was presented so finely:  They<br>
knew exactly that the people had been abducted in jeeps and taken to Vedeno.<br>
I understood at once whom they were targeting.  I go around with my<br>
bodyguards in two jeeps, and I come from Vedeno.  This is the district for<br>
which I am responsible in the military sense.  At the end of the footage<br>
about the events in Novyye Atagi they showed the entrance to my election<br>
headquarters and my bodyguards, and said that the killers have not been<br>
found, but that they must be found.  This is a dirty, unprofessional, and<br>
brazen lie on the part of the Russian mass media.  On one hand, this is<br>
insulting to me, but on the other, it pleases me.  I am pleased by the<br>
weakness of the Russian special services and the Russian state.  This will<br>
facilitate our progress down the path of independence. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  How do you react to the harsh comments against you on the<br>
part of Russian Duma Speaker Gennadiy Seleznev?  In particular, that Russia<br>
may not recognize you as president of Ichkeria owing to your past?<br>
 [Basayev]  I will say this:  The dog barks but the caravan passes on.<br>
Seleznev is not concerned either about the fate of Russia or Chechnya.  In<br>
fact he could not care less whether I indeed could become the president or<br>
not.  And I will certainly become one, if only to spite Seleznev....  Today<br>
he accuses me of being "covered in blood from foot to ears."  Seleznev<br>
himself is covered in blood from foot to the top of his head!  This is the<br>
blood of the Chechen people, the blood of our Russians, [as published] and<br>
the blood of Russian soldiers.  Today they are like small dogs who can bark<br>
at Yeltsin, Chernomyrdin, and the whole of the presidential staff.  They<br>
took a step toward peace, but then stopped and corrected their mistake.<br>
Before the Communists yelled in parliament that it was necessary to stop the<br>
war, but when it was stopped, they began to yell that it cannot be stopped.<br>
If Seleznev is so concerned about the great power, let him come here and<br>
fight, but not send here ordinary Russian soldiers:  Let him send his own<br>
sons.  We shall gladly meet them and fight them.  And we shall also find a<br>
job for Seleznev:  He will shepherd my sheep in the mountains.  Let him<br>
come.  I need a good shepherd.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Once the issue of the prisoners of war has been raised, I<br>
simply must ask about their fate.  How many Russian servicemen are in the<br>
hands of the Ichkerian government, and what are the final terms for their<br>
release or exchange?<br>
 [Basayev]  I do not know the exact figure like nobody in the republic knows<br>
it.  But this figure is high.  And it is the Russian State Duma and<br>
personally Seleznev, who could not care less about the fate of these boys,<br>
that are to blame for that they have not as yet returned to their<br>
Motherland.  Some of them were killed here, while those who stayed alive<br>
cannot return home.  I have repeatedly invited the Russian leadership,<br>
members of the Russian delegation, and personally Boris Berezovskiy -- three<br>
days ago -- to make a goodwill gesture and show at least for once that this<br>
is after all a great state and a great power.  A great state should be<br>
generous, without none of the slavish emotions that today hold sway in the<br>
Duma.  I invited them to amnesty all Chechens and Ingushes who were<br>
imprisoned on the ethnic principle in the period from 26 November 1994 until<br>
26 November 1996.  I feel awkward having to teach the Russian leadership<br>
politics.  I am telling them:  "This will be a big stick in your hands.  You<br>
will be able to dictate terms to us in front of the word community!"  And<br>
we, the republic's leadership will have to run around looking for these<br>
prisoners of war or maybe their remains, and hand them over to Russia.<br>
Today our people are holding many POW's.  But the Russian special services<br>
from the very start chose to engage in exchanging POW's on a case by case<br>
basis, buying out military servicemen.  After that the Chechens stopped<br>
selling them POW's.  Because they are not indifferent to the fate of these<br>
people.  We have a different mentality:  In combat they are our enemies, but<br>
now we feel sorry for them.  Today I have given one prisoner of war to a<br>
friend.  When we caught him, he was all lice-infested, shabby, and dirty....<br>
If you talk to our people and say that prisoners need to be released, they<br>
say:  "But where are our men?  Can you ensure the release of our relative,<br>
who is being held, for no good reason, at a particular place?"  I say that<br>
today I cannot do this.  And they go:  We shall talk when you can.  The<br>
Chechens have this law:  A prisoner of war is private property.  Many see<br>
this as barbarism, as slavery.  No, this is not slavery!  They eat what we<br>
eat.  Some caught their POW's themselves; some bought them; some received<br>
them as a gift -- like this man here.  I have already released more than 200<br>
men for free: to soldiers' mothers and Chechens from various diasporas.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Do you consider Russia a hostile country?<br>
 [Basayev]  I feel deeply sorry for the Russian people.  Because at the end<br>
of the day we grew up in the same state, in the same family.  I remember the<br>
days when I sang:  "My address is not a street or a block number...."<br>
[reference to a popular Soviet-era song that goes on as follows:  My address<br>
is the Soviet Union]  Today people are in slavery.  The Russians must free<br>
themselves from it.  When I become the president I shall help Russia --<br>
providing humanitarian assistance.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  You have said this in at least three earlier interviews.<br>
What is your definition of slavery?<br>
 [Basayev]  Slavery is the complete indifference of a whole nation.  An<br>
aspiration to suppress everybody and everything, and to destroy everything<br>
and everybody.  And, third:  Russians live in poverty and so, they believe,<br>
everybody else should live in poverty.  A free person does not act like<br>
this.  A free person supports somebody when he falls and is glad when<br>
somebody makes progress.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Do you consider Russia a Christian country?<br>
 [Basayev]  I consider Russia a country of agnostics.  When, during this<br>
war, some ignorant people on our side said that we were fighting against<br>
Christians, that this was a crusade, I responded that we were fighting not<br>
Christians but agnostics.  What does it matter if somebody wears a cross<br>
around his neck but has no faith in his heart?  I cited concrete examples.<br>
It was the agnostics who organized a crusade against us.  No, I do not<br>
consider Russia to be Christian.  The main tenet of Christianity is this:<br>
"Thou shalt not kill." <br>
 [Shevchenko]  Do you believe that military crimes have been committed in<br>
Chechnya, and will you press for punishment of those who committed them?<br>
 [Basayev]  This is the concern of nongovernmental organizations that have<br>
been recording everything from the outset of the war.  Both military crimes<br>
and crimes against the person have been committed here as well as genocide<br>
against the Chechen people.  I mean the people of the Chechen Republic and<br>
also the Russians against whom genocide was also committed.  The culprits<br>
must answer for this.  They will be called to account before an<br>
international tribunal.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  The Russian-Chechen war is often related to economic<br>
problems.  The oil pipeline, oil fields, and many other things are cited in<br>
this context.  Are these the defining moments here, or is there something<br>
else besides?<br>
 [Basayev]  The defining moment here is the backward Russian policy.<br>
Russianism [rusizm] is a terrible ideology, worse than fascism, racism, and<br>
so forth.  This definition was given by our first president Dzhokhar<br>
Dudayev.  Today everybody is shouting that this abhorrent, bandit-style war<br>
is over oil, but they make it a point never to say that this is a<br>
"national-liberation" war.  This has been a war for our independence and our<br>
freedom.  Economically, we achieved great stabilization back in 1994.  The<br>
whole North Caucasus was buying from us.  Long convoys arrived at our<br>
bazaars with two battalions committed to ensure their protection.  Inflation<br>
was falling....  In January 1995 we were planning to introduce our own<br>
currency and our own Chechen passports.  All this caused the war.  We were<br>
setting a bad example to others.  And so, instead of learning from us, they<br>
decided simply to stop us. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  But at the same time the Chechen Republic was accused of<br>
sheltering bandits.  There was that scandal over false money orders....<br>
 [Basayev]  We called them "castle-builders."  They stuck in our throats<br>
like a bone.  They were stealing in Russia but building palaces or castles<br>
in the air here.  People hated them.  But we could not do anything.  Because<br>
Russia, which should have taken the first step by at least concluding an<br>
agreement on the extradition of criminals, would not do that.  It was<br>
because of the Russian leadership that these criminals managed to flee here<br>
and launder their money.  If Russian authorities do not officially state<br>
that they want a particular crook, how can we possibly indict him then?  And<br>
after this we are called a safe haven for bandits and thieves!  If official<br>
representatives are not sent here asking that certain persons be caught and<br>
extradited, we cannot do anything on our own.  Now when those terrorist acts<br>
started in Mineralnyye Vody, in the first two incidents we cooperated with<br>
[Russian] special services. We let them into our territory.  Incidentally,<br>
the Russian special services failed to catch the bandits, but we got them:<br>
We returned both the money and the men.  They did not like it that we were<br>
better at it. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  What kind of society do you intend to build in Chechnya?<br>
 [Basayev]  I am content with the situation whereby there are super-rich<br>
people.  But they should be rich by virtue of their brains, not at the<br>
expense of the state or the brazen sucking of people's blood:  We shall not<br>
allow anybody to get rich on people's blood.  Islam presupposes the<br>
existence of both rich and poor, but it also presupposes protection of the<br>
poor.  I want to enforce Chechen laws.  Today we live by Russian laws.  I am<br>
going to introduce two codes in the republic: a civilian code and a Sharia<br>
code.  In taking a matter to court, everybody is free to choose the first or<br>
the second....  Unofficially, this has always been so just the same.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  And still, do you see the possibility of a complete<br>
settlement of the Russian-Chechen relations?  How do you envision the future<br>
for Chechnya and Russia?<br>
 [Basayev]  In his time Dzhokhar Dudayev formulated our foreign policy<br>
principles.  Back in 1993 and 1994 I proposed that we have a common defense<br>
system with Russia.  And today the Chechens can easily field two special<br>
purpose brigades to defend Russian borders.  We have a common geopolitical<br>
space and common economic interests.  We can be the conduit of Russian<br>
policy in the Islamic world, in the Middle East.  Russia can be a conduit of<br>
our interests in Europe.  Or take the UN.  Will Russia not be happy with an<br>
extra vote on its side if we are allies?  We need not faraway America or<br>
nearby Turkey.  They have never helped us.  There has been talk to the<br>
effect that we shall end up under Iran, under Turkey...  The point is that<br>
we shall never be under anybody -- if only under Russia, and if only because<br>
we would be awed by such a great power.  The Almighty created us free, and<br>
we are slaves only to Allah.  Russia can benefit from having common economic<br>
interests with us.  We also stand to gain from this.  We agree to a<br>
commonwealth within the CIS. I understand that after taking on the republic<br>
like a bag on your shoulders we shall not be able to run away anywhere.  As<br>
they say, "not in Russia, but with Russia."  We agree to live in a common<br>
building, but only in our own apartment.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
