<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/19/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/19/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Dec 96 15:49:19 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#198">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#198">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#198">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#198">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0199.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Daily 12/19/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/18/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	+&gt; Tajik talks postponed  <br>
	+&gt; Uzbekistan gets $50 million loan  <br>
	+&gt; Turkish bulker impounded at Port Said  <br>
	+&gt; European rights court condemns Turkey  <br>
	+&gt; Australia supplies ferries to Turkey  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey, Russia sign anti-terrorism pact  <br>
	+&gt; Japan and EBRD rebuild Uzbek refinery  <br>
                               ======<br>
 Tajik talks postponed<br>
	A planned meeting between the president of Tajikistan<br>
and the troubled Central Asian nation's opposition leader has<br>
been postponed for at least one day. Tajik opposition leader<br>
said Said Abdullo Nuri arrived in the Russian capital several<br>
hours after his talks with President Emomali Rakhmonov were to<br>
begin Thursday. The rivals in the former Soviet republic reached<br>
a cease-fire deal last week to end months of escalating<br>
fighting. They also pledged to sign a blueprint for peace and<br>
political reconcilitaion at the Moscow meeting. Differences<br>
remain that could make the talks rocky: The linchpin of the<br>
peace plan is a pledge to form a joint commission that would<br>
iron out disputes, but the sides disagree on how much power the<br>
group will have. The opposition wants to share real power<br>
through the commission until new elections can be held.<br>
Emomali's government does not want to release its increasingly<br>
weak hold on war-ravaged Tajikistan and its rival<br>
clans. Fighting has plagued the impoverished nation of 5.7<br>
million since a 1992 civil war that that killed tens of<br>
thousands of people and drove much of the opposition across the<br>
frontier into Afghanistan.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Uzbekistan gets $50 million loan<br>
	The Manila-based Asian Development Bank Wednesday said<br>
it has approved a $50-million loan and $830,000 technical<br>
assistance grant to rehabilitate and modernize agro-processing<br>
enterprises in the Central Asian republic of Uzbekistan. The<br>
bank said the loan to the former Soviet republic aims to enable<br>
medium non-state firms to access new export markets. "It will<br>
also provide collective and family farms with new<br>
micro-processing facilities," an ADB official said. Agriculture<br>
plays a key role in Uzbekistan's economy, accounting for nearly<br>
30 percent of the country's gross domestic product and 45<br>
percent of total employment. Prior to its independence in 1991,<br>
the country was among the largest producers of fruits and<br>
vegetables in the former Soviet Union, and was the source of<br>
fresh and processed fruit and vegetable products to other<br>
republics.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkish bulker impounded at Port Said<br>
	A Turkish bulker has been impounded at Port Said, in<br>
Egypt, after allegations that her operator failed to pay<br>
$450,000 for fuel and provisions another of its ships had taken<br>
on an earlier voyage, the Lloyd's List said Wednesday. The<br>
26,732 dwt Gokceli, operated by Istanbul-based Akmar Shipping<br>
and Trading Co., was impounded after sailing through the Suez<br>
Canal. The vessel, Hassan B, allegedly slipped away from Port<br>
said in October without paying her dues, the paper said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 European rights court condemns Turkey<br>
	The European Court of Human Rights has has ordered<br>
Turkey to pay compensation to the family of an ethnic Kurd who<br>
was allegedly tortured while in police custody. The man, Zeki<br>
Aksoy, was killed in Turkey 16 months after being released from<br>
jail and several weeks after he filed a complaint with the<br>
European court, which is based in the eastern French city of<br>
Strasbourg. Turkish authorities have denied any involvement in<br>
the killing and have charged a member of a Kurdish dissident<br>
group with his death. The court said Wednesday that Aksoy was<br>
arrested in November 1992 in Kizitepe, in southeastern Turkey,<br>
and held by police for at least 14 days. It said that while in<br>
police custody he was tortured by having live electrical wires<br>
placed on his genitals. He was also allegedly stripped naked and<br>
hung by his arms for long periods, as a result of which he<br>
suffered paralysis of the lower arms. The European court ruled<br>
the torture constituted "extremely serious violations" of the<br>
European Convention on Human Rights. It ordered Turkey to pay<br>
the equivalent of around $42,000 in compensation to Aksoy's<br>
father, plus legal costs of about $35,000.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Australia supplies ferries to Turkey<br>
	Western Australian aluminum shipbuilding specialist<br>
Austal Ships has strengthened its export market standing with<br>
the completion of two passenger catamarans for a Turkish ferry<br>
operator, the Lloyd's List said Wednesday. The London shipping<br>
daily said the deliveries involve the 450 passenger-capacity<br>
sisters Sinan Pasa and Piyale Pasa. The contract forms part of<br>
one of the largest single deals in the history of Australia's<br>
light-weight vessel construction industry. The ferries will be<br>
deployed on Bosporus crossings and between ports in the Sea of<br>
Marmara, the paper said. Meanwhile, Turkish shippers, Akdeniz<br>
Gemi Isletmeciligi, in Istanbul, has given a $2 million contract<br>
to Antwerp Shiprepairers to replace some 152 tonnes of steel on<br>
board the 124,100 dwt Turkish bulk carrier Esra 1. The vessel<br>
suffered engine problem, struck a lock and was grounded while<br>
entering Antwerp in late November.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey, Russia sign anti-terrorism pact<br>
	The foreign ministers of Turkey and Russia have sought<br>
to smooth out troubled relations by pledging to cooperate in<br>
fighting terrorism. Tansu Ciller and Yevgeny Primakov signed the<br>
anti-terrorism memorandum Wednesday. Ciller is in Moscow for<br>
talks on trade and problems that plaguing the traditionally<br>
tense relationship. The pact aims to dispel Kremlin concern<br>
about perceived Turkish support for Chechen rebels and Turkish<br>
anger over what it sees as Russian support for the separatist<br>
Kurdistan Workers' Party or PKK -- which has offices in<br>
Russia. Another prickly point came up with Primakov's defense of<br>
reported Russian plans to sell ground-to-air missile systems to<br>
the Greek Cypriots. He says such sales would not threaten peace<br>
because the weapons are "not offensive." Ciller also met with<br>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin to discuss trade, thriving<br>
despite a struggle to host the export route for Caspian Sea oil<br>
and a dispute over regulations for passage of tankers through<br>
Turkish straits. Ciller and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov agreed on<br>
the construction of a trade center to bring order to the $6<br>
billion "suitcase trade" done by Russians who buy goods in<br>
Turkey and sell them at home.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Japan and EBRD rebuild Uzbek refinery<br>
	Japan's Eximbank and the European Bank for<br>
Reconstruction and Development, EBRD, will team up to help fund<br>
the overhaul of the Fergana Oil Refinery in Uzbekistan. Japan<br>
will contribute $85.5 million to the project under an agreement<br>
signed in Tokyo by Eximbank and the Uzbek Bank for Foreign<br>
Economic Activities, the Russian Interfax news agency<br>
reported. An Uzbek government official told the agency Wednesday<br>
that the EBRD will lend the same amount, and Uzbekistan will<br>
provide about $30 million to cover the remaining costs of the<br>
project. Japan's Mitsui will carry out the upgrade, which<br>
involves installing new equipment to refine locally drilled oil<br>
with a high sulfur content. The overhaul is scheduled to take<br>
three years.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
