<!-- body="start" -->
  	  				 <br>
	+&gt; Japan in $130m Uzbekistan airport loan  <br>
	+&gt; South Korea joins Uzbek bank venture  <br>
	+&gt; Turkish leader hints Iran military ties  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Japan in $130m Uzbekistan airport loan<br>
	Japan will lend Uzbekistan $130 million to improve<br>
airports in the "silk route" cities of Samarkand, Bukhara and<br>
Khiva, the Russian news agency Itar-Tass reported Tuesday. An<br>
agreement on the loan was signed in Tokyo by Uzbek Deputy Prime<br>
Minister Bakhtier Khamidov and Akira Nishigaki, president of<br>
Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation Foundation, Itar-Tass<br>
said. Like an earlier Japanese credit for construction of a<br>
plant in Uzbekistan to repair railroad cars, the airport loan is<br>
repayable over 30 years with an annual interest of 2.7 percent<br>
after a 10-year grace period. A Japanese official said the easy-<br>
term loan was the third to be granted to Uzbekistan by the<br>
foundation under a program to speed up development in nations<br>
with gross national product per capita of $695 to $1,345. Per<br>
capita GNP in the Central Asian nation of 22 million was $950 in<br>
1994, according to Japanese figures. The total of the three<br>
loans granted over the past two years is about $300 million, the<br>
official said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 South Korea joins Uzbek bank venture<br>
	South Korea's Daewoo Securities and Koram Bank have<br>
signed a contract to join a bank project in Uzbekistan, a<br>
spokesman said Tuesday. Starting next month, the bank will<br>
provide general bank services, targeting South Korean companies<br>
in Uzbekistan, spokesman Min Kyong-bu said. Daewoo will hold 55<br>
percent equity and Koram 10 a percent stake in the $20-million<br>
UzDaewoo Bank, Min said. The European Bank for Reconstruction<br>
and Development will own a 25-percent stake, while<br>
Uzbekistan-based firms NBSEA and Turon Bank will each hold 5<br>
percent, the spokesman said. Some 20 South Korean companies,<br>
including Daewoo Group, currently operate businesses in<br>
Uzbekistan, Min said.<br>
                               ======<br>
	 <br>
 Turkish leader hints Iran military ties<br>
	Turkey's prime minister risked a crisis Tuesday with the<br>
United States by announcing that he was seeking military<br>
cooperation with Iran.  "Military cooperation would be for the<br>
benefit of both countries," Nemettin Erbakan told reporters on<br>
the eve of a visit to Ankara by Iranian President Ali Akbar<br>
Hashemi Rafsanjani. Asked whether such a move would not conflict<br>
with the U.S. call to isolate Iran, Erbakan said. "No, it means<br>
that Turkey is an independent country," he said.  Erbakan, who<br>
leads the hard-line Muslim Welfare Party, has made it a feature<br>
of his premiership to turn Turkey toward eastern, Muslim-<br>
dominated countries. He made his first foreign visit to Iran in<br>
August.  U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said<br>
last week that the United States was aware of reports that<br>
Turkey was interested in military cooperation with<br>
Iran. "Should that be true, we would be greatly concerned,"<br>
Burns said. Recalling that Turkey is a U.S. ally in the North<br>
Atlantic Treaty Organization, Burns said: "We believe the<br>
Turkish government ought to understand a fundamental fact: The<br>
Iranian government is a government that sponsors terrorism and<br>
is trying to acquire weapons of mass destruction." "Why would<br>
any NATO country want to help Iran enhance its defense<br>
production capabilities? It does not make sense, and we would be<br>
opposed to it," Burns added. But on Tuesday, Erbakan said of<br>
Turkey's NATO membership: "Trying to make a defense agreement<br>
with a non-NATO country is something else again." He did not<br>
elaborate. Erbakan said other NATO countries had already sold<br>
weapons to Iran and reminded reporters that on his August visit<br>
to Tehran, Turkey and Iran had agreed to double their volume of<br>
trade to $2 billion a year. "We will jointly lower customs<br>
tariffs, and we will not be paying in dollars," Erbakan said.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
