<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/17/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/17/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Dec 96 15:47:47 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#196">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#196">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#196">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#196">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/18/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Barlow DerMugrdechian: "Fresno State Armenian Studies WWW Page"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	+&gt; Turkey pleased by Kurd camp closure  <br>
	+&gt; Turkmenistan in agricultural crisis  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey marks first shipment of Iraq oil  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Turkey pleased by Kurd camp closure<br>
	Turkey expressed satisfaction Monday with a United<br>
Nations decision to withdraw from a Kurdish refugee camp in<br>
northern Iraq, which the government in Ankara considered a base<br>
for separatist rebels. U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees<br>
office said last week it was pulling out of the camp at Atrush<br>
because the outlawed Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, had taken<br>
effective control of the camp. ``We are pleased with the U.N.<br>
decision to close the camp, where our Kurdish people are under<br>
heavy pressure from the PKK,'' Turkish Foreign Ministry<br>
spokesman Omer Akbel said. Turkey would welcome effective<br>
implementation of the refugee panel's decision in the ``shortest<br>
time possible. We are ready to extend our help in every way for<br>
the return of the Turkish Kurd inhabitants back to Turkey.'' The<br>
camp, set up two years ago about 40 miles (65 km) from the<br>
Turkish border, shelters about 14,000 Kurds who fled the<br>
fighting between secessionist rebels and Turkish troops in<br>
southeastern Turkey. No date has been scheduled for the<br>
withdrawal, but a spokeswoman at the regugee agency's<br>
headquarters in Geneva said it was pulling out because ``we can<br>
no longer provide support. PKK sympathisers are in control of<br>
the camp committee.'' Ankara has long been seeking closure of<br>
the Atrush camp, which it said was being used as a base for the<br>
PKK, who have been fighting since 1984 to carve an independent<br>
Kurdistan out of southeastern Turkey. At least 21,000 people<br>
have been killed and many more wounded in the insurgency.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkmenistan in agricultural crisis<br>
	Turkmen President Saparmurat Niyazov says the nation<br>
must solve a worsening agricultural crisis that is seeing some<br>
of its 4 million citizens go hungry despite rich material<br>
resources. Niyazov has told a state council meeting that farmers<br>
in Turkmenistan have harvested less than half the planned amount<br>
of grain this year and said the cotton harvest is three times<br>
smaller than projected. The Russian news agency Itar-Tass quotes<br>
him as saying the situation ``demands an immediate solution''<br>
and suggesting croplands be handed over to those who work them<br>
to create incentive. He says, ``The need has arrived to give<br>
land to its real owners, who will provide the nation and the<br>
people with agricultural products they produce themselves.''<br>
Niyazov says 450,000 tons of cotton have been harvested this<br>
year instead of the planned 1.4 million tons, and 480,000 tons<br>
of grain instead of 1 million. Reports say bread is scarce in<br>
some regions. Niyazov has created a personality cult in the<br>
former Soviet republic and rules with an iron hand. He has had<br>
trouble boosting the economy despite natural gas reserves that<br>
are the fourth largest in the world.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey marks first shipment of Iraq oil<br>
	Turkey Monday held a ceremony to mark the first shipment<br>
of Iraqi oil after a six-year freeze caused by U.N. economic<br>
sanctions against the Arab country for invading its tiny Arab<br>
neighbor Kuwait in 1990.  Although the sanctions remain in<br>
place, a special U.N. approved oil-for- food deal allows Iraq to<br>
export $2 billion worth of crude every six months to pay for<br>
medicine and essential food for the Iraqi people and to pay<br>
compensation to victims of the invasion that ended with the 1991<br>
Gulf War. Pumping from Iraq's northern Kirkuk fields began last<br>
week, sending tons of oil through a joint Iraqi-Turkish pipeline<br>
to Yumurtalik terminal in southern Turkey. The Anatolian news<br>
agency said oil was loaded on the 150,000 dwt Turkish tanker<br>
Gole at Ceyhan at a ceremony attended by Turkish Prime Minister<br>
Necmettin Erbakan and his deputy Tansu Ciller. ``The<br>
celebrations are not only for the first loading of the tanker<br>
with Iraqi oil but also signal the (economic) revival of our<br>
southeast region,'' said Erbakan. He said he hoped that the<br>
economic ties with Iraq would flourish in the near<br>
future. Ciller, who is also the Foreign Minister in the<br>
Islamist-led Coalition, said Turkey's aim was to make use of the<br>
full capacity of the pipeline soon. Turkey had closed the<br>
pipeline in 1990 in line with the U.N. economic sanctions.<br>
Turkey's state-owned oil refiner Tupras was the first company to<br>
sign a contract in Baghdad last week for the daily shipment of<br>
75,000 barrels of Iraqi crude.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
