<title>Groong Network: Great scholar dies</title>
<h1>Great scholar dies</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>STONE@vms.huji.ac.il</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Dec 96 14:53:50 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#194">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#194">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#194">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#194">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Barlow DerMugrdechian: "Fresno State Armenian Studies WWW Page"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0193.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-20-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Archbishop Norayr Bogharian of the Brotherhood of St.<br>
James died last night. He will be interred tomorrow,<br>
Saturday, after services in St. James Cathedral,<br>
Jerusalem.<br>
<p>
Archbishop Bogharian was born in Aintab on 17 January,<br>
1904. After the deportations during which he was chiefly<br>
in Syria, he studied at St. James, Jerusalem, under the<br>
learned Patriarch Eghishe Turian. He was ordained as<br>
celibate priest on Transfiguration Sunday, July 22, 1928<br>
He then studied for two years in London and returned to<br>
Jerusalem, where he lived for the rest of his life,<br>
except for 1935-1940 during which he was Dean of the<br>
Seminary in Antelias.<br>
<p>
He became Keeper of Manuscripts in 1949 and held that<br>
position until he was 90 years old.<br>
<p>
He was a remarkable scholar, and wrote very numerous<br>
articles on Armenological matters in Sion for the most<br>
part, but also in Hask, Echmiadzin and other journals.<br>
<p>
His major life's work was the full catalogue of the<br>
almost 4,000 manuscripts of the Library of the Patriarchate.<br>
These eleven volumes appeared between 1966 and 1991. His<br>
other works include a critical edition of the poems of<br>
Yovhannes Tlkuranc'i, his work on Armenian Literature,<br>
Hay Groghner, on Scribes, Hay Gric`ner and Painters,<br>
Hay Nkaric`ner. He wrote up to the last days before his<br>
death and since his retirement from the Manuscript<br>
Library, had produced a new edition of Girk' Tl'toc'<br>
(The Book of Letters) and a number of other books.<br>
<p>
Norayr srpazan was without doubt the premier Armenologist<br>
of the time. He was a small man, of enormous learning,<br>
who loved learning and did not suffer fools lightly. But<br>
a human man, with a sense of humor to be appreciated. He<br>
was a faithful servant of his Church and of St. James<br>
all his life.<br>
<p>
Those who have been touched by him will carry the<br>
imprint always.<br>
<p>
He was a patron member of AIEA from its founding.<br>
<p>
His life will be a light for our feet.<br>
<p>
Michael Stone, Jerusalem<br>
<p>
(I drew biographical details from Pete Cowe's sketch in<br>
the Festschrift for him published in REArm 18.1 (1984) for<br>
his eightieth birthday).<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
