<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/20/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. REPERATION FOR GENOCIDE MUST BE SOUGHT, SAYS KOCHARIAN<br>
2. MEDZAMOR UPGRADING CONTINUES<br>
3. GAS SUPPLY TO ARMENIA AND GEORGIA SHUT OFF<br>
4. NOUNE SARKISSIAN NAMED TEMPORARY CHARGE DAFFAIRS<br>
5. ANCA-WR BOARD MEMBER MEETS WITH WILSON<br>
<p>
<p>
1. REPERATION FOR GENOCIDE MUST BE SOUGHT, SAYS KOCHARIAN<br>
<p>
PARIS (Gamk)-Reparation to the Armenian people for the Genocide <br>
must be pursued, outlined Nagorno-Karabakh Republic President <br>
Robert Kocharian during a public meeting at the Royal Monceau <br>
Hotel Wednesday, where the leader also discussed the recent <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe Lisbon summit <br>
and the role of all Armenians in the future of Karabakh.<br>
	"Armenian should have weakened Turkeys position by <br>
addressing the Genocide issue and the territorial reparations <br>
stemming from it," remarked Kocharian during discussion of <br>
Armenias policy prior to and during the OSCE Lisbon summit.<br>
	Kocharian stated that Turkey, as the perpetrator of the <br>
Armenian Genocide, should not be a part of the OSCE peace talks, <br>
since it advocates for the same interests as Azerbaijan, thus its <br>
position is one-sided on the international mediating effort.<br>
	"Karabakh has already declared its independence through a <br>
referendum, and any concession which endangers the security of the <br>
Karabakh people will not take place-not today, not ever," asserted <br>
Kocharian.<br>
	The Karabakh leader admitted that Azerbaijan was preparing <br>
itself for one year through diplomacy and Armenia, especially in <br>
the latter part of the year, was busy with the presidential <br>
elections and thus was not prepared at the summit.<br>
	Kocharian characterized the outcome of the Lisbon summit as <br>
neither a victory nor a defeat, stressing that Armenia utilized <br>
its veto privilege and halted a pro-Azeri resolution from being <br>
included in the final declaration, despite the efforts of the <br>
international community which, based on their own interests, sided <br>
with Azerbaijan where oil issue is an important one.<br>
	In addressing the military condition in Karabakh, Kocharian <br>
explained that todays Karabakh army cannot be compared to the <br>
battalions of Hadrut and Stepanakert of some years back.<br>
	"Our soldiers must constantly be trained, live in proper <br>
conditions, in order to be able to continue their devoted-and <br>
imperative-service for the future of the Republic," Kocharian <br>
stated.<br>
	The president also emphasized that during all talks, a <br>
representative of northern Karabakh, who is a native of the still <br>
occupied Shahumian Region, is always included.<br>
	Kocharian explained that recognition of independence was not <br>
a priority for Karabakh initially, adding that neutralizing Azeri <br>
firing posts and liberating Azeri-occupied territory became the <br>
vanguard for the Karabakh struggle, as did  guaranteeing the <br>
rights and will of the people of Karabakh.<br>
	The recognition issue, Kocharian stressed, is a matter which <br>
could take years to achieve.<br>
	Kocharian also emphasized the importance of the Diaspora in <br>
assisting in the enhancement of Karabakhs economy, and called on <br>
all Diaspora-Armenians to participate in the rebuilding process of <br>
Karabakh.<br>
	Stressing that people of Karabakh have paid their dues for <br>
the entire Armenian nation through their will and blood, Kocharian <br>
said  now the time has come for Armenia and the Diaspora to share <br>
in the process and assist the people of Karabakh who have <br>
experienced such horrors as the Sumgait and Kirovabad massacres.<br>
	"The most important issue for us is the youth and the task <br>
of keeping them in Karabakh. For this we need to provide them with <br>
work and education and create personal security. It is a major <br>
tragedy for us when more than 5000 youth leave Karabakh-even if <br>
they establish residence in Armenia," stressed Kocharian.<br>
	The president also spoke about Karabakhs agricultural <br>
capabilities, stating that this year, Karabakh produced more than <br>
13,000 metric tons of wheat, adding that other agricultural crops <br>
were also on the rise.<br>
	He stated that the Karabakh government planned to implement <br>
a privatization program beginning in 1997, reminding the audience <br>
that the 150,000 residents of Karabakh cannot overcome the <br>
obstacles and difficulties facing them, alone.<br>
	The gathering which was organized by the Armenian Ambassador <br>
to France Viken Chitechian and the Friends of the Armenian Embassy <br>
organization was mainly to allow a dialogue between the French-<br>
Armenian community and the Karabakh leader.<br>
	At the on set of the program, Kocharian discussed his visit <br>
to the various communities in France, as well as briefed the <br>
participants about meetings with French and Swiss government <br>
officials, stating that he has met mayors, members of parliaments <br>
and high-ranking officials at the foreign ministries of France and <br>
Switzerland.<br>
	He emphasized that the Karabakh side was lobbying for France <br>
to assume the co-chairmanship of the OSCE Minsk Group.<br>
	Kocharian stated that his visit, coupled with the active <br>
political participation of the French-Armenian community could <br>
improve Frances negative position vis-a-vis Karabakh.<br>
	Kocharian was accompanied by his wife, Karabakhs <br>
representative in Armenia Alexander Harutunian, as well as <br>
Karabakhs representative to France and the European Parliament <br>
Varoujan Grigorian.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. MEDZAMOR UPGRADING CONTINUES<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The second block of  Armenias Medzamor <br>
nuclear power plant is currently working at 92 percent of its <br>
projected capacity, generating some 370 megawatt/hour daily, <br>
director of the plant, Souren Azatian said Thursday at a news <br>
conference called on the 20th anniversary of the plant.<br>
	Since its resumption last year, Medzamor has been stopped <br>
only once which testifies to a higher degree of its safety, <br>
Azatian said. He discussed plans aimed at further increasing the <br>
plants safety.<br>
	"The Armenian nuclear power plant will be working until <br>
another block is built on the same ground. Besides, the nuclear <br>
power plant will be stopped in a year after a new block is put <br>
into operation," Azatian said.<br>
	Armenia is currently working with French Framatom company, <br>
which has pledged to assist Armenia in constructing nuclear waste <br>
depositories.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. GAS SUPPLY TO ARMENIA AND GEORGIA SHUT OFF<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Combined Sources)-Gas supplies to Armenia and Georgia <br>
were shut off Wednesday morning as a result of non-payment of <br>
debts incurred by the two countries.<br>
	Armenias debt to the joint Russia-Turkmenistan Itera <br>
enterprise has totaled $15 million for the past 11 months, <br>
Armenias Energy Minister Gagik Martirossian said Thursday during <br>
a briefing.<br>
	Martirossian said that Armenias industrial enterprises and <br>
population owe large sums to the energy sector. At present, <br>
Armenias energy sector debt totals $75 million, more than half of <br>
which was incurred by private citizens.<br>
	According to Martirossian, the debt is expected to grow, but <br>
at a slower rate until next August when the restructuring of <br>
Armenias energy sector will be completed and it will be possible <br>
to make regular payments for the consumed energy. The debt will be <br>
fully repaid in at least two years, Martirossian said.<br>
	Martirossian reported that those who regularly pay their <br>
utility bills should not expect power or natural gas to be shut <br>
down. Measures are being take to resume the gas supply.<br>
	Before Wednesdays shut down, Armenia received 5 million <br>
cubic meters of gas daily, of which 3 million was used to generate <br>
power.<br>
	Armenians have grown accustomed to difficulties with energy <br>
supplies in the years since independence. Having no natural energy <br>
sources and being subject to Azeri blockades, they are used to <br>
dealing with one fuel supply crisis after another.<br>
	With the recently announced reforms, Armenian consumers are <br>
expected to pay more to heat their homes and maintain power <br>
supplies. Under an agreement signed nearly a year ago with the <br>
World Bank, the Armenian government is scheduled to implement an <br>
increase in utility costs starting in January.<br>
	The aim is to create a rational economic basis for the <br>
functioning of the electricity industry, first by covering the <br>
cost of production, and secondly by financing rejuvenation of the <br>
antiquated system.<br>
	Prices are due to rise next month by some 30 percent to 20 <br>
dram (about 4.5 cents) per kilowatt/hour of electricity. Further <br>
price increase are expected in stages during the year.<br>
	Armenian Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian plans to hold talks <br>
with the World Bank next month in order to adjust the terms of the <br>
original agreement. Sarkissian believes a segment of the <br>
population will not be able to pay such a high price for <br>
electricity.<br>
	A Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty correspondent in Yerevan <br>
reported that Armenian industry would also be hard-hit by such <br>
steep price rises. According to the RFE/RL report, a local factory <br>
which manufactures rubber (chloroprene) already pays 14 drams per <br>
kilowatt/hour, with the energy component making up 90 percent of <br>
the production costs.<br>
	At the same time, large-scale investment, nearly $250 <br>
million, is urgently needed to reconstruct the supply system.<br>
	Some foreign credits have already been approved, such as the <br>
$57 million grant from the European Bank for Reconstruction and <br>
Development to upgrade the conventional, Soviet-styled thermal <br>
power plant in Armenia.<br>
	In addition, the World Bank has extended $13.7 million in <br>
credits for the renovation of some hydroelectric power stations, <br>
as well as Russias 60 million rubles to finance last years re-<br>
starting of the controversial nuclear power plant at Medzamor. <br>
Negotiations are underway for additional funds for the further <br>
safety upgrades of Medzamor.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. NOUNE SARKISSIAN NAMED TEMPORARY CHARGE DAFFAIRS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg)-Noune Sarkissian, the wife of newly-appointed Prime <br>
Minister Armen Sarkissian, is currently acting as Armenias <br>
temporary Charge dAffairs in London.<br>
	Prior to being named to temporarily represent Armenia in <br>
Great Britain, Sarkissian was involved in the diplomatic functions <br>
of the Armenian Embassy as well as its day-to-day operation.<br>
	Noune Sarkissian holds a degree in philology, and is a <br>
graduate of the Fine Arts Department of London University.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. ANCA-WR BOARD MEMBER MEETS WITH WILSON<br>
<p>
SACRAMENTO-During a private reception in Sacramento in honor of <br>
Governor Pete Wilson, Armenian National Committee of America-<br>
Western Region Board member Ohannes Boghossian had a chance to <br>
talk with the California governor about the Armenian-American <br>
communitys plans for 1997.<br>
	Governor Wilson spent several minutes thanking the ANCA-WR <br>
for its continued support of his efforts and briefly outlined his <br>
plans for 1997. The Governor also informed Boghossian that he <br>
hoped that the ANCA-WR would assist in making his 1997 agenda for <br>
California a reality.<br>
	"Its always nice to see Governor Wilson and renew our <br>
friendship," stated Boghossian. "I am certain that the ANCA-WR and <br>
the Governors office will continue to work together next year to <br>
better serve the California Armenian community," Boghossian <br>
concluded.<br>
<p>
<p>
Please send your comments and questions to Asbarez-on-line at the <br>
above E-mail address. We also encourage suggestions on improving <br>
our on-line services.<br>
<p>
All subscription inquiries and changes must be made through the <br>
proper carrier and not Asbarez-on-Line. AOL does not transmit <br>
address changes and subscription requests.<br>
