<title>Groong Network: Interview with Yandarbiyev</title>
<h1>Interview with Yandarbiyev</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Dec 1996 10:52:59 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#190">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#190">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#190">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#190">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0191.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 20)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0189.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/20/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nezavisimaya Gazeta 20 December 1996 page 3<br>
<p>
   Interview with Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, president of the Chechen Republic<br>
of Ichkeria, by Maksim Shevchenko under the general headline:  "Terrorist<br>
Acts in Chechnya Have Not Stopped" -- in Groznyy<br>
<p>
        Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, president of the Chechen Republic of<br>
Ichkeria, received Nezavisimaya Gazeta's correspondent in his residence, and<br>
responded to his questions.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  What will be your comment on the killing of the Red Cross<br>
workers in the village of Novyye Atagi?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  This is an extremely deplorable incident.  I cannot define<br>
it otherwise than as a major political provocation.  Such provocations have<br>
increased as we are nearing elections.  Generally speaking, this is a crime<br>
atypical of the Chechen mentality.  So I am stumped [as to who did it].  And<br>
I cannot assess it otherwise than as a barbarous and senseless murder of<br>
people who had come to do good.  The Chechen people are as one in their<br>
indignation and condemnation of this atrocity.  So I declared 19 December a<br>
day of mourning.  I have just been briefed by the chief of the state<br>
security department.  He said that although it is too early to talk about<br>
any concrete trail, there are some theories.  We have started working, and<br>
soon the crime will be solved.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Are you counting on assistance in the investigation on the<br>
part of Russian special services?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  To be frank, no.  At least not on objective assistance.  I<br>
am afraid that Russian special services themselves could be involved here.<br>
This is sad, but possible.  When they were at Severnyy airport and in<br>
Khankala, these special services committed many crimes -- both with their<br>
own hands and with the hands of various criminal scum.  I am not counting on<br>
anything.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  What can you say about the capture of the North Ossetian<br>
delegation? <br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  The military commanders of the Russian group of forces,<br>
which are being pulled out of Chechnya, told Udugov that they had received a<br>
phone call from Galazov, who told them that a certain group had set out to<br>
meet with Udugov here.  The latter said that he did not know anything about<br>
that, and so made no arrangements about the meeting.  Naturally neither I<br>
nor any of the state leaders knew anything about that.  Possibly this was<br>
yet another provocation.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  What forms of statehood are upheld by Ichkeria's leadership<br>
and its people?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  The status of the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria is that of a<br>
fully independent state as it has existed since 1991.  It was confirmed<br>
during the recent Russo-Chechen war and is based on the full observance of<br>
principles of international law.  This is a status established in full<br>
conformity with the contemporary laws of the ChIASSR, [Checheno-Ingush<br>
Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic] the RSFSR, and the USSR through the<br>
expression of the will of the people via elections.  There are 74 documents<br>
confirming the legitimacy of the power structures of the Chechen state of<br>
Ichkeria, which four years ago were sent to the UN, but to all appearances<br>
they never reached it.  So, there is only one possible status: the<br>
independent Chechen Republic of Ichkeria.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  But the Khasavyurt agreements do not provide for full<br>
independence of Chechnya....<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  The Khasavyurt agreements neither affect nor infringe this<br>
status.  In Khasavyurt, we took the safest possible path.  At least in order<br>
not to irk those ill-wishers who do not want the war to stop.  But at the<br>
same time the agreements in no way infringe the independence of our state.<br>
This is enough to enable us to say that we have upheld our status.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  How do you plan to shape your relations with Russia after<br>
process of state building has been completed?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  Both before or after it is completed we intend to build our<br>
relations with Russia as interstate relations.  But I believe that we should<br>
above all look for ways of achieving a better mutual understanding with<br>
Russia as well as interaction in all spheres: economic, political, social,<br>
cultural, and others....  Based on principles of integration.  This on<br>
condition that the Russian leaders and the Russian state are really<br>
interested in acquiring the Chechens as reliable allies.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Oftentimes Chechen resistance is associated with the notion<br>
of "Islamic revolution."  To what extent does this conform to reality?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  I do not think that Islam in Chechnya was so weak or so<br>
suppressed that it would take a revolution to revive it.  Although, indeed,<br>
Islam is reviving.  Yet it would be more appropriate to describe this<br>
process through the notion of "gazavat" or "jihad" -- the holy Muslim war in<br>
the name of Allah and for the freedom of Muslims, that is, for the<br>
independence of all Muslims and all citizens of the Chechen state.  To be<br>
sure, many representatives of other Muslim peoples, aroused by the flame of<br>
jihad, got involved in this struggle.  So, not an Islamic revolution, but jihad.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  How in this context are your relations evolving with Islamic<br>
states -- for instance, Iran and Turkey?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  In the context of these developments our relations with them<br>
are not evolving.  This especially refers to Iran and some other states that<br>
are aspiring today to being Islamic.  Their "Islamism" is confined in<br>
itself.  After addressing the specific tasks of the initial period of the<br>
Iranian revolution, they ended up involved in infighting and internal<br>
strife, which does not allow them to act just as boldly as it was at the<br>
start, after Homeini's comeback.  In this respect the incumbent leadership<br>
of Iran and other Muslim countries, which call themselves constitutionally<br>
Islamic, has not shown much solidarity with us.  As to the people at large<br>
-- in any Muslim or even non-Muslim country, they strongly sympathize with us. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  Does your jihad have a purely territorial meaning, being<br>
confined to Chechnya, or is this holy war supposed to spread in any way?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  Our jihad is above all a jihad to defend the territory,<br>
honor, and dignity of the Chechen people.  But jihad is not simply an armed<br>
struggle.  This is a struggle against everything that contradicts the order<br>
established by God; that is to say, everything that is forbidden by God to a<br>
Muslim.  In this respect, of course, jihad has no rigid forms or borders.<br>
It is prescribed to a Muslim from the moment of his birth until the his last<br>
breath.  This world was made by God for man so that he goes through jihad --<br>
in the true sense of the word that is described in the Koran.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  In his time Gen. Dudayev observed:  "Today we are liberating<br>
Chechnya; tomorrow, Russia; and the day after tomorrow, Europe."<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  I do not recall Dzhokhar Dudayev saying this in this<br>
particular form.  But he did say that "by liberating Chechnya today, we are<br>
liberating Russia."  He took a very philosophic approach toward the problem<br>
of liberating the individual, the people, and mankind, on the assumption<br>
that today mankind is enslaved by those forms of international communities<br>
and organizations at various levels that dictate to whole nations how to act<br>
-- even [preaching] submission to evil instead of helping them to get rid of<br>
that evil; instead of helping them to free themselves from injustice.  It<br>
was in this sense that he viewed the situation in Russia.  He said, with<br>
profound conviction and frankness, that the Russian people was suffering the<br>
most from the regime reigning in Russia -- as a result of the unconscious<br>
despotism that even today is dictated by Russian state practices, the<br>
interrelations between nations imposed by the state, as well as the<br>
interrelations between the ruling authority and the individual, and between<br>
the citizens of different social standing.  It was in this context that he<br>
spoke about the need to liberate Russia.  He believed that the Chechen<br>
people and the Chechen state would serve as a tool for liberating the<br>
Russians.  I share this point of view. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  Could you say precisely by which forces Russia is enslaved<br>
today?  <br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  Forces that have put first material interests -- profit and<br>
lust for profit, by any means and methods, regardless of the price.  This is<br>
the main force that has enslaved and suppressed the peoples [narody] of<br>
Russia.  This force today is concentrated in the Russian state power<br>
structures.  Many economic processes were affected by this force.  The<br>
Chechen Republic became a target of this man-hating aggression in part<br>
because we excluded our country from this pseudo-economic bacchanalia which<br>
spread across the empire, especially after the breakup of the USSR.  <br>
 [Shevchenko]  But then it is with these forces that you are concluding a<br>
treaty....<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  We are concluding a treaty with the actual forces that today<br>
act in the name of the Russian state and the people.  But we are concluding<br>
the treaty not to fall under the impact of these forces.  Especially given<br>
that we are concluding the treaty in light of the fact that the war has<br>
changed much in the Russian leadership itself.  New people came in, people<br>
who have the experience of a two-year war with Ichkeria.  This experience<br>
dictates quite a different behavior pattern to them.  The incumbent Russian<br>
leadership declares -- and partially demonstrates through its behavior --<br>
the wish to act in other ways.<br>
 [Shevchenko]  Moving over to more down to earth matters, here is this<br>
question:  What is preventing the return of the bodies of the Russian<br>
servicemen killed in action?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  This sounds strange to me.  There are no obstacles<br>
preventing the return of the bodies of a clergyman and other Russians who<br>
were killed here. <br>
 [Shevchenko]  Is the oil pipeline a key problem to formalizing Ichkeria's<br>
independence?<br>
 [Yandarbiyev]  The oil transit route today is an international and<br>
political problem.  We predicate many questions on how it is resolved.  <br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
