<title>Groong Network: A People of Hope, a Land of Challenge</title>
<h1>A People of Hope, a Land of Challenge</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 20 Dec 1996 00:11:11 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#188">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#188">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#188">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#188">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0189.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/20/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "from western wires"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
HEADLINE:  A People of Hope, a Land of Challenge // Armenia<br>
SOURCE:  The Orange County Register,November 17, 1996 (John Hughes)<br>
<p>
At the end of an unmarked alley, past gardens burdened by fruit of a rich<br>
soil that has not failed Armenia when much else has, the family of Samuel<br>
Kocharian is evidence that the world's sweetest people live where the<br>
pavement turns to dirt.<br>
<p>
My photographer companion and I were looking for a vantage point from which<br>
to photograph Mount Ararat. Without the benefit of a common language, a man<br>
whose smile makes neither English nor Armenian necessary leads us past an<br>
area with a tattered fence in which an impossibly large hog is a willing<br>
captive, past a slant-roof coop in which a dozen chickens fight for grape<br>
leaves, to his modest home on the edge of a ravine. <br>
<p>
Gesturing unmistakably, Kocharian invites us to climb a discomforting ladder<br>
onto the tin roof over his kitchen. From there another ladder takes us<br>
higher, to the top of his home, level, it feels, with the snow-covered peak<br>
of the distant mountain where Noah found landfall after the Deluge.  <br>
<p>
Noah _ the agent of a vengeful, if loving, God _ could do no more for the<br>
cause of spiritual belief than this simple man who has led us to his roof for<br>
a look at that mountain.  <br>
<p>
My partner walks uneasily across rafters from which tin has un-nailed itself<br>
and aims his lens across the backside of Yerevan, Armenia's capital, toward<br>
Turkey, where Mount Ararat is a reminder of land that, too, was once<br>
Armenian. <br>
<p>
They have a joke here: At least Armenia, they say, gets to see the pretty<br>
side of the mountain.  <br>
<p>
It is a country of challenge, Armenia. A country of great reward for the<br>
ambitious traveler. And it is a country of people who have learned to adjust.<br>
<p>
<p>
Communism brought an assured degree of relative prosperity but with it,<br>
oppression. Oppression was lifted in 1988, but so was the safety net that the<br>
socialist government offered. Also that year an earthquake took more than<br>
25,000 lives and in the six years that followed, a war with neighboring<br>
Azerbaijan for rights to Nagorno-Karabakh killed thousands more.  <br>
<p>
At the Kocharian home, Samuel, a taxi driver, no longer has a shift and<br>
recently had surgery and lost weight, making his oversize clothes hang from<br>
him. A wife, two daughters, a son and Samuel get by, though, supported partly<br>
by one daughter's work at a bakery and by the unpredictable means that seem<br>
to be the good fortune of this country where at least 70 percent are<br>
unemployed.  <br>
<p>
For some, the means come from Armenians of the diaspora who have immigrated<br>
to America and send millions a month to families and friends whom they've<br>
left but mercifully not forgotten.    <br>
<p>
At the clean home of the Kocharians, economic insufficiency is hardly noticed<br>
because wealth of the soul is so abundant. <br>
<p>
We come down from that roof to where Nellie, Samuel's wife, and Lusine, a<br>
daughter, meet us with freshly ground Armenian coffee, pastries, watermelon<br>
and English walnuts.  <br>
<p>
His other daughter, Aramine, begins making a cake with fresh eggs gathered<br>
from Samuel's chickens.  <br>
<p>
Coffee behind us, we are taken down the way to Nellie's father's house where<br>
more relatives join us for a noon meal that includes spiced bologna, two<br>
types of cheese, fresh mahatnakash bread, eggplant, tomatoes, two varieties<br>
of grilled pork kebabs, pickled peppers, juice, vodka, sweet wine and an<br>
Armenian brandy favored by Winston Churchill. <br>
<p>
An interpreter is located and Samuel's first words to me are an apology.  <br>
<p>
"We do not have much," he says through Efram, the soldier and translator,<br>
"but what we have we gladly share with you, our new friends. If we had known<br>
you were coming we could have prepared better." <br>
<p>
I start to reply but to my huge surprise and Western-influenced<br>
embarrassment, tears stop my words as I try to tell Samuel how much his<br>
graciousness has touched me. <br>
<p>
The gentle man cradles my head in his rough hands, kisses my forehead and<br>
tells me it is good when people are open to unexpected feelings. <br>
<p>
Kocharian's words are with me three days later as I light a candle in his<br>
honor inside Geghart, a monastery that dates to the fourth century, when<br>
Armenian monks carved cells and a cathedral into the side of a mountain just<br>
outside Yerevan.  <br>
<p>
Geghart was both a place of worship and a fortress for Christian monks whose<br>
beliefs were a death sentence at the hands of Turkish Muslims.  <br>
<p>
Dark as any cave, Geghart is a web of catacombs linked to two main cathedrals<br>
that are magnificent studies in ancient worship and architecture. <br>
<p>
Much of Armenia _ the first country to adopt Christianity as a national<br>
religion (in A.D. 301) _ has links to biblical times. Geghart, Armenian for<br>
"spear," is where a spear believed to be the one used by a Roman soldier to<br>
pierce Christ's side at the Crucifixion was kept until the ninth century,<br>
when it was transferred to Echmiadzin for safekeeping.  <br>
<p>
Echmiadzin, about 12 miles from Yerevan, is to the Armenian Apostolic Church<br>
as the Vatican is to Roman Catholicism.    <br>
<p>
Built on the site of a pagan temple (as was the custom for many early<br>
religious centers in Armenia), Echmiadzin's legend is that Jesus Christ<br>
descended from heaven to designate the site of the church _ built in A.D.<br>
301-303  _ where Gregory the Illuminator became the first Armenian<br>
catholicos, or church leader. Echmiadzin's seminary is a testament to more<br>
modern times in the life of Armenia's foremost religion. <br>
<p>
Here, Father Paren Avedikian and other priests teach 110 theology students,<br>
where once, during Soviet times, there were fewer than 30. And, until 1988,<br>
Echmiadzin was the only seminary in the country. Now, there are three.  <br>
<p>
"I do not think there are proper words to describe the repression by the<br>
Soviets," says Avedikian.  <br>
<p>
But to focus only on its history of struggle and suffering _ significant as<br>
it is _ is to miss the very satisfying benefits of a nation that has<br>
triumphed when others might have surrendered.  <br>
<p>
A transplanted Texan who has lived in Armenia four years, Rick Ney, sees his<br>
adopted country's past as an enhancement to its considerable cultural wealth,<br>
and as a sign of hope for glory days ahead. <br>
<p>
"In the end," Ney says, "these people push themselves up. They always push<br>
themselves up."  <br>
<p>
During Soviet times, Armenia drew more than 1 million tourists a year. Most<br>
came to Yerevan for its art, for its history and to enjoy the company of a<br>
warm and hospitable people.  <br>
<p>
Ney, who works with a program that helps schools create their own incomes,<br>
sees Armenia as a fertile bud waiting to blossom _ a country of great<br>
scholars and scientists looking for ways to use skills and knowledge left<br>
dormant with the collapse of communism.  <br>
<p>
The American has written a travel guide and, as he waits for a publisher, on<br>
Nov. 7 his first installment of "Armenia: A Practical Guide for the<br>
Adventurous Soul" appeared on the Internet at www.arminco.com, with others to<br>
follow. <br>
<p>
Still, however, the country with new Internet access has a phone system that<br>
is unreliable _ it is easier to make an international call than a local one.<br>
 <br>
<p>
And, although one of Armenia's first acts of independence was to create a<br>
national stamp, there is no effective postal service. (Osheen Keshishian,<br>
editor of the Armenian Observer in Los Angeles, once mailed himself a letter<br>
from Yerevan, which took two months to arrive in the United States.) <br>
<p>
Paper products are still something of a luxury, and, in a country known for<br>
some of the world's harshest winters, the citizens of Yerevan are expecting<br>
as few as 14 hours a day of electricity. Gasoline is sold from jugs at<br>
roadside stops, but, these people will unflinchingly say, "at least we now<br>
have gasoline."  <br>
<p>
Relics of communism remain: Socialized medicine is the norm, although<br>
privatization looms amid concerns of how the 70 percent of the citizens who<br>
are unemployed could afford to pay for their own health care.  <br>
<p>
And, a sure sign that democracy comes slowly is seen in routine and frequent<br>
traffic stops by police, who extort money from drivers.  <br>
<p>
Still, there are compelling reasons to visit Armenia, including Vernisage, a<br>
weekend market in the middle of the city that is the gathering place for the<br>
nouveau capitalists of the young republic, who sell goods ranging from Soviet<br>
flasks with hammer-and-sickle insignias to nesting dolls in the image of<br>
President Clinton.  <br>
<p>
It is here on a Sunday that I am approached by an excited artist whose<br>
stumbling English adds to the bizarre charm of the moment when he says to me:<br>
"Please. I must paint you. I am artist, understand? Do you know you look like<br>
the king of Sweden? You must come, please. I will take only moments."  <br>
<p>
Curious, I follow the man to an easel he keeps on the edge of a dry fountain.<br>
   <br>
<p>
Expecting, in the way we are taught (to our fault at times), that I am being<br>
set up for a scam, my American suspicions are shamefully displaced. The<br>
gracious artist wants nothing but a chance to draw a portrait of features he<br>
rarely sees: that is, those of a blond, blue-eyed drifter. <br>
<p>
"You look like Jesus," the artist says.  <br>
<p>
The Christ of history, of course, most likely resembled the artist himself<br>
more than this American of Irish descent. But why argue?  <br>
<p>
So, I sit while he works in a fury, surrounded by onlookers.   <br>
<p>
He finishes, apologizes that his pen is low on ink, and says that with my<br>
permission he will use the drawing as a reference for a later painting. <br>
<p>
<p>
So, if you are in Yerevan and see a painting of Jesus, the king of Sweden ...<br>
 <br>
<p>
At Vernisage, artists once commissioned to do the state's work now sell their<br>
self-expressions for the price of art supplies alongside housewives who sell<br>
crocheted tablecloths and have learned this much English: "Special price for<br>
you!"  <br>
<p>
Musicians play instruments that are also for sale. Pieces of jewelry that<br>
could have been family heirlooms are shopped at bargain prices, marking an<br>
unfortunate crossroad where struggle and capitalism meet. <br>
<p>
And, on nearly every street in Yerevan, sidewalks are crowded with vendors<br>
selling cigarettes (approximately 10 out of every 10 men smoke), penny<br>
candies, magnificent loaves of bread, mineral water and delicacies such as<br>
sujuk, a sweet candy made of walnuts, fruit and syrup wrapped in grape<br>
leaves. <br>
<p>
Nearby, Republic Square is the grandest of Yerevan's attractions _ a great<br>
boulevard highlghted by fountains and a reflecting pool with "dancing" water<br>
that throws itself into the night, in a rhythmic spray to classical music. <br>
<p>
Oddly vacant and occupying nearly a full block is a platform where a<br>
prominent statue once stood. Some years ago that likeness of Lenin was<br>
toppled, replaced by nothing _ signifying, it would seem, that these newly<br>
freed Armenians would rather see empty space than a reminder of communist<br>
authority. <br>
<p>
It is hard for a first-time visitor to comprehend a people of such passion<br>
being suppressed, especially by influences that would stifle their resilient<br>
spirit. <br>
<p>
Hope is a great sustenance. That is Samuel Kocharian's message, delivered as<br>
I  stop by his home for one last moment before leaving Yerevan. <br>
<p>
I have gone to the market and purchased the most expensive and largest bottle<br>
of Armenian brandy I can find (for about $15) and am standing at Kocharian's<br>
door with a translator. <br>
<p>
"Enjoy this with your family," I have the translator tell him. "And when you<br>
drink, lift a glass toward America and think of someone whose life you've<br>
made richer."  <br>
<p>
"No," he replies. "We will not open it until you return."  <br>
<p>
SIDEBAR - Survival brings hope<br>
<p>
Armenia, a country of about 3 million, is a little smaller than Maryland, and<br>
is landlocked, bordered by Turkey, Iran, Azerbaijan and Georgia. <br>
<p>
During Soviet rule (which ended in 1988), scientists in Armenia were<br>
responsible for much of the engineering and development in computer<br>
technology for the entire Soviet Union. Today, those scientists and other<br>
professionals whose livelihoods were dependent on the Soviet Union are among<br>
the millions trying to adjust to life in a new republic. <br>
<p>
Armenia's conversion to democracy has not been easy. Although its people have<br>
embraced their independence emphatically, forces beyond their control have<br>
made life a remarkable struggle.  <br>
<p>
In 1992, an earthquake that killed more than 25,000 and crippled thousands<br>
more came when the country already was suffering the effects of a fierce war<br>
with Azerbaijan over Nagorno-Karabakh, an enclave of 250,000 that is about 90<br>
percent Armenian within Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
Because of the war with Azerbaijan and bad relations with Turkey that have<br>
existed since the early 1900s, when Turkish Muslims killed 1.5 million<br>
Armenians in a religious genocide, Armenia's geography has contributed to its<br>
struggle. <br>
<p>
With the collapse of the Soviet Union, Armenia lost its source of crucial<br>
supplies such as petroleum. Blockades by surrounding countries forced Armenia<br>
into the impractical position of having to fly gasoline into the country,<br>
which created heating shortages during some of the country's worst winters.  <br>
<p>
In 1991-92 the national income of Armenia fell 60 percent, and it dipped an<br>
additional 15 percent in 1993.  <br>
<p>
Today, at least 70 percent of Armenia is unemployed, surviving economically<br>
only with outside help, largely from the United States. America's per capita<br>
aid to Armenia is second only to the amount it sends to Israel. <br>
<p>
Still, there are signs of hope for Armenia's recovery and its eventual<br>
self-reliance. Relations with Turkey are improving, and trade between the<br>
countries is expected soon. And, because internal strife in Georgia has<br>
abated, Armenia now has access to two crucial Black Sea ports that previously<br>
were not at its service.    <br>
<p>
Forty American companies now do business in Armenia, and, slowly,<br>
privatization of businesses is contributing to hopes for a stable economic<br>
infrastructure. <br>
<p>
The effects of struggle are subtle in Yerevan, the country's capital, where<br>
life moves with European flavor on streets crowded with smartly dressed men<br>
and women offering little hint of such fresh suffering. <br>
<p>
During a recent speech at the University of California, Irvine, the consul<br>
general of Armenia, Armen Baibourtian,  acknowledged what any casual student<br>
of Armenian history knows: "The faith of Armenians," he said, "has been<br>
stretched beyond the limitations of imagination." <br>
<p>
But he added, "We believe (living conditions) will improve in one to two<br>
years. This is only the beginning."  <br>
<p>
IS THIS FOR YOU?<br>
<p>
YES if you want to meet the indomitably spirited people of an<br>
ancient land.<br>
<p>
NO if you want room service.<br>
<p>
GETTING THERE: Armenian Airlines has weekly flight connections from Paris,<br>
Amsterdam and Athens to Yerevan. Aeroflot has daily connections between<br>
Moscow and Yerevan. <br>
<p>
DON'T FORGET: All foreign visitors must have a visa, which can be requested<br>
through the Armenian Embassy, (202) 319-1976, or the Consulate General, (310)<br>
657-6102. <br>
<p>
HANG YOUR HAT: Hotel Armenia, 011-3742-52-53-93; Hotel Ani,<br>
011-3742-52-07-75; Hotel Divin, 011-3742-53-63-43. <br>
<p>
THE BOTTOM LINE: The current exchange rate is approximately 405 Armenian<br>
drams to the dollar. Small bills are recommended for easy exchange. Credit<br>
cards and traveler's checks generally are not accepted. <br>
<p>
TIPS: Paper products, including toilet paper and paper towels, are not easy<br>
to obtain in Armenia. While the natives are proud of their drinking water,<br>
foreigners could find it troublesome. Bottled mineral water is available. <br>
<p>
TIPS II: As Armenia has no effective postal service, good relations with the<br>
locals can be established by offering to bring back mail to the United<br>
States. With one-third as many Armenians in this country as in Armenia, many<br>
natives have connections here.<br>
 <br>
