Subject: Russian spacecraft returns to Earth over S.Pacific<br>
Date: Mon, 18 Nov 1996 0:10:27 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 WASHINGTON (Reuter) - Russia's crippled Mars probe, carrying  <br>
four canisters of radioactive plutonium, fell to Earth Sunday <br>
over the South Pacific west of Chile, U.S. and Australian <br>
officials said. <br>
	 U.S. Space Command in Colorado Springs, Colorado, which had  <br>
been monitoring the stricken spacecraft's orbit, said it <br>
re-entered Earth's atmosphere above ``a broad ocean area <br>
somewhere west of Chile'' at about 8:30 p.m. EST. <br>
	 Australian officials said the probe landed between Easter  <br>
Island and the Chilean coast and located the impact site at 31 <br>
degrees South, 96.3 degrees West. <br>
	 The Chilean Navy had received no official word of the crash,  <br>
but recovery of any debris from the spacecraft would be <br>
difficult if not impossible, a Chilean naval officer said. <br>
	 ``This area has one of the deepest ocean floors in the  <br>
world. Any kind of recovery, if it were possible, would be very, <br>
very tough,'' the officer told Reuters. <br>
	 The area where the spacecraft fell is up to 6,000 yards  <br>
deep, according to maps of the area. <br>
	 U.S. Space command spokesman Dave Knox said his agency  <br>
tracked objects in space, not in the atmosphere, therefore it <br>
was impossible to know whether the six-ton craft exploded upon <br>
re-entry and where exactly the debris landed. <br>
	 ``We have confirmed that the spacecraft has re-entered.  <br>
There's no way for us to tell if something survived re-entry,'' <br>
Knox told Reuters. <br>
	 If the probe survived re-entry, it may have crashed into the  <br>
Southern Pacific several hundred miles from the calculated <br>
re-entry location, the command's Space Control Center said. <br>
	 Most of the craft likely burned up upon entering the Earth's  <br>
atmosphere, although NASA officials said two landing vehicles <br>
weighing 110 pounds each were built to survive a landing on Mars <br>
and likely crashed into the ocean as debris. <br>
	 The vehicles each carried two tiny plutonium batteries about  <br>
the size of 35mm film canisters containing a total of 200 grams <br>
(seven ounces) of the radioactive material, but Russian <br>
officials said they were designed to survive the intense heat of <br>
re-entry and the impact of a crash. <br>
	 U.S. officials said they were confident the batteries had  <br>
survived intact and were now at the bottom of the ocean. <br>
	 ``Our operating assumption is that the plutonium ...  <br>
withstood re-entry and fell into the water fully encapsulated,'' <br>
said Department of Energy spokeswoman Carmen MacDougall. ``In <br>
the unlikely event that a release (of radioactivity) occurred, <br>
the weather is currently blowing away from Chile.'' <br>
	 The spacecraft lifted off from Kazakhstan's Baikonur space  <br>
center on Saturday, but failed to break out of the Earth's orbit <br>
after a booster rocket misfired. <br>
	 Initially the probe looked likely to hit Earth over  <br>
Australia, causing Australian defense officials to jump into <br>
frenzied preparations for a possible emergency. <br>
	 Two 6.5-foot penetrators designed to ram into the surface of  <br>
Mars and weighing 143 pounds each, were also expected to survive <br>
re-entry. <br>
	 The Russian probe had been due to reach Mars on Sept. 12  <br>
next year. The failed mission was the second of three planned <br>
trips from Earth to Mars in just over a month. <br>
	 The United States launched a robot voyage to Mars two weeks  <br>
ago and a second mission will blast off on Dec. 2. All were <br>
tasked to check for signs of water on the distant planet -- a <br>
key clue to whether there was once life on Mars. <br>
	 National Security Council official Robert Bell told  <br>
reporters a misfiring of a fourth stage of the probe's booster <br>
rocket had doomed the Russian Mars probe. <br>
	 Before it landed, Bell, a special assistant to President  <br>
 Clinton and a senior director of the NSC for defense policy,  <br>
outlined what would happen if the plutonium batteries did not <br>
survive. <br>
	 One possibility was that the canisters would break up. If  <br>
this happened at high altitude, Bell said a small radioactive <br>
cloud that would result would dissipate harmlessly. <br>
	 Plutonium 238 causes lung or bone cancer if inhaled.  <br>
	 Bell said dispersal at a lower altitude or breakage upon  <br>
impact could have been lethal to humans. <br>
	 The Russian space mishap was the fourth in recent years. A  <br>
U.S. space vehicle, Skylab, plunged to Earth over Western <br>
Australia in 1979 without causing damage and a Russian Cosmos <br>
satellite fell in an unhabited region of Canada in 1987. <br>
	 In 1991 the Soviet space station Salyut 7 re-entered the  <br>
Earth's atmosphere and the debris was believed to have landed in <br>
the Atlantic Oceon, though some pieces were reportedly found in <br>
Argentina. <br>
