Subject: Kazakh oil pipeline problems settled<br>
Date: Mon, 18 Nov 1996 7:15:02 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	LONDON, Nov. 18 (UPI) -- Ten oil companies and the governments of  <br>
Russia, Kazakhstan and Oman have settled their remaining differences <br>
over construction of an export pipeline for at least $18 billion worth <br>
of western oil ventures in Kazakhstan, a London business daily reported <br>
Monday. <br>
	The Financial Times quoted Ed Smith, general director of the Caspian  <br>
Pipeline Consortium, as saying all issues had been settled in principal <br>
at a meeting of the parties in Moscow last week. <br>
	They were now wording the shareholder agreement and hoped to sign it  <br>
in early December, enabling the 10 companies the following month to buy <br>
50 percent of the consortium from its current members, the governments <br>
of Russia, Kazakhstan and Oman, the daily said. <br>
	The $1.5 billion pipeline, due on line in 1999, would pump 28 million  <br>
tons a year from the west of the country to the Russian Black Sea port <br>
of Norosossiysk. Later expansion to 68 million tons would be financed <br>
partly from early revenues. <br>
	Chevron and Mobil, among others, have held back production in  <br>
Kazakhstan because Russia, claiming capacity limitations, would not <br>
grant sufficient access to its export pipelines. <br>
	Kazakh officials accused Russia of using its stanglehold on the  <br>
project to press for political concessions, the Financial Times said. <br>
