Subject: Armenia court upholds presidential election result<br>
Date: Fri, 22 Nov 1996 11:51:45 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 YEREVAN, Armenia (Reuter) - Armenia's Constitutional Court  <br>
Friday rejected an opposition plea for the results of a <br>
presidential election in September to be annulled. <br>
	 The decision was likely to fuel tensions in the Armenian  <br>
capital Yerevan, where opposition supporters have staged big <br>
demonstrations against the vote. <br>
	 The Central Electoral Commission (CEC) declared that  <br>
President Levon Ter-Petrosyan had won a second five-year term in <br>
the Sept. 22 poll, but his election challenger, former prime <br>
minister Vazgen Manukyan, accused the president of vote-rigging. <br>
	 Ter-Petrosyan, a Soviet-era dissident and former close ally  <br>
of Manukyan in the independence cause, denied the charge. <br>
	 Foreign observers noted major irregularities in the election  <br>
by Ter-Petrosyan forces, and the Organization for Security and <br>
Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) said they could have been serious <br>
enough to call his victory into question. <br>
	 The CEC says Ter-Petrosyan, officially sworn in on Nov. 11,  <br>
won with 51.8 percent of the votes, just clearing the 50-percent <br>
hurdle needed to win without a run-off. It said Manukyan won <br>
41.3 percent. <br>
	 The leader of the opposition Party of National  <br>
Self-Determination condemned the court's ruling and said he <br>
would appeal to the European Court of Human Rights. <br>
	 ``Today it was proven that we do not have a constitutional  <br>
court and that the authorities in Armenia are lacking in all <br>
reason,'' Paruyr Airikyan told reporters. <br>
	 In the immediate aftermath of the election, Ter-Petrosyan  <br>
sent tanks into the streets, rounded up dozens of opponents, and <br>
closed several political parties after demonstrations by <br>
Manukyan's backers turned violent. <br>
