Subject: Presidential vote held in Karabakh<br>
Date: Sun, 24 Nov 1996 13:40:50 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	MOSCOW, Nov. 24 (UPI) -- Presidential elections were held Sunday in  <br>
the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh enclave in Azerbaijan, despite opposition <br>
from Baku, which does not recognize the enclave's independence. <br>
	The election sparked protests in cities and towns throughout  <br>
Azerbaijan, some of which included thousands of demonstrators, Russian <br>
news agencies reported. <br>
	State-run Azerbaijani television also commented that the presence of  <br>
Russian electoral observers at voting sites represented a lack of <br>
respect for the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the nation. <br>
	The mostly Armenian population in Nagorno-Karabakh chose between  <br>
three candidates -- incumbent President Robert Kocharyan, former Deputy <br>
Parliament Speaker Boris Arushayan and Communist leader Grant Melkumyan <br>
-- all of whom support independence for the enclave and the continuation <br>
of economic reform. <br>
	Nearly 50 percent of an eligible electorate of 130,000 had voted by  <br>
Sunday afternoon, well in excess of the 25 percent turnout needed to <br>
validate the election, the Nagorno-Karabakh electoral commission <br>
reported. <br>
	If no candidate wins 50 percent of the vote a runoff will be held  <br>
between the two top finishers in two weeks. The election is to a five- <br>
year term. <br>
	``The main goal of the so-called election is to pressure Azerbaijan.  <br>
It is not to legitimize the self-declared separatist regime,'' <br>
Azerbaijani presidential adviser Vafa Gulizade told the Russian Interfax <br>
news agency. <br>
	``Those who are seeking to regain their foothold in the region''  <br>
believe it benefits their cause to increase tensions in the region, <br>
Gulizade said, accusing neighboring Armenia of organizing the vote. <br>
	The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe together with  <br>
a number of foreign countries expressed concern for the effect the vote <br>
might have on regional stability, the Russian Itar-Tass news agency <br>
reported. <br>
	Russia and Turkey have also objected to the election on the grounds  <br>
that it is being held before talks on the region's political status are <br>
completed. <br>
	A bloody conflict over the disputed enclave broke out in 1992 between  <br>
mostly Muslim Azerbaijan and mostly Christian Armenia. The fighting cost <br>
25,000 lives and created more than 1 million refugees. <br>
	After two years of war a 1994 cease-fire agreement brought peace to  <br>
the enclave, but attempts at a political settlement between the former <br>
Soviet republics have been unsuccessful. <br>
	As talks have dragged on, the self-declared independent republic has  <br>
sought to turn its military victory against Azerbaijan into a permanent <br>
union with Armenia. <br>
	Relations between Armenia and Azerbaijan remain tense despite two  <br>
years of relative calm. <br>
	In September, Azerbaijani President Heydar Aliev threatened, ``If our  <br>
lands are not freed, we will have to free them ourselves.'' <br>
	The Karabakh Armenians have said they will not give up territory  <br>
without international guarantees of peace. <br>
	Western nations have been particularly concerned to see fighting does  <br>
not re-ignite in the region as a pipeline slated to carry oil from the <br>
Caspian Sea to the Black Sea port of Batumi runs through the enclave. <br>
