Subject: Incumbent wins Karabakh vote<br>
Date: Mon, 25 Nov 1996 2:10:31 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	YEREVAN, Nov. 25 (UPI) -- Incumbent Robert Kocharyan has easily won a  <br>
second term as president of the self-proclaimed republic of Nagorno- <br>
Karabakh, election officials in the ethnic Armenian enclave said Monday. <br>
	Kocharyan, 42, polled 86.1 percent of the vote held Sunday despite  <br>
fierce oppsosition from Azerbaijan, which does not recognize the <br>
sovereignty of the region. He will be inaugurated to a five-year term. <br>
	Karabakh parliament member Boris Arushunyan was a distant second with  <br>
under 7 percent of the vote in the region of 190,000 people, and <br>
regional Communist Party leader Grant Melkumyan got 3.7 percent. <br>
	The vote was a slap in the face to Azerbaijan, which fought a drawn-  <br>
out war with Armenia over Nagorno-Karabakh. The conflict ended in 1994, <br>
when the sides signed a cease-fire that cemented Armenian gains in the <br>
fighting. <br>
	The election sparked protests Sunday throughout Azerbaijan, and  <br>
state-run television said the presence of Russian observers at polling <br>
places showed a lack of respect for the territorial integrity of <br>
Azerbaijan. <br>
	A former Communist Party official and advocate of uniting Nagorno-  <br>
Karabakh with Armenia, Kocharyan was elected president of Nagorno- <br>
Karabakh by the regional parliament in a December, 1994 vote that also <br>
defied Azerbaijan. <br>
	No foreign country recognizes the sovereignty of Nagorno-Karabakh,  <br>
but it is run as an independent nation and gets strong support from <br>
Armenia, which seized the strip of land between Armenia and Nagorno- <br>
Karabakh in the war. <br>
	Since the 1994 cease-fire, international efforts to broker a lasting  <br>
political settlement of the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute have met with <br>
little success. <br>
