Subject: Turkish opposition sees gangster scandal cover up<br>
Date: Wed, 27 Nov 1996 14:42:00 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 ANKARA, Turkey (Reuter) - Main opposition leader Mesut  <br>
Yilmaz Wednesday accused the Islamist-led government of <br>
attempting to cover up a scandal over Turkey's alleged use of <br>
far-right gangsters to carry out political dirty work. <br>
	 ``It's no coincidence that their attempts to control the  <br>
judiciary and silence the press come at a time when political <br>
dirt has reached such an extreme dimension,'' Yilmaz said. <br>
	 The ruling coalition is preparing a bill that is expected to  <br>
restrict criticism of the government and bureaucrats by Turkey's <br>
media on the trail of an unpleasant scent in the corridors of <br>
power. <br>
	 ``Those who want to silence the press are trying to cover  <br>
their own dirty business, they are afraid of the truth coming <br>
out,'' Motherland Party (ANAP) leader Yilmaz told reporters. <br>
	 A series of media revelations uncovered a close relationship  <br>
between late mobster Abdullah Catli and government member of <br>
parliament Sedat Bucak, who heads an anti-guerrilla Kurdish <br>
militia. <br>
	 Catli, once a leading light in the extreme nationalist  <br>
``Grey Wolf'' movement, is alleged to have helped the pope's <br>
would-be assassin Mehmet Ali Agca escape imprisonment in Turkey <br>
before the 1981 attack on the pontiff. <br>
	 The media has also said that Turkey may have ordered Catli  <br>
or other rightist mobsters to carry out death squad killings of <br>
suspected Kurdish rebel sympathizers and an Armenian guerrilla. <br>
	 Far from trying to hide the scandal, Deputy Prime Minister  <br>
Tansu Ciller Tuesday defended the gangster. <br>
	 ``I do not know whether he is guilty or not ... but those  <br>
who fire bullets or suffer their wounds in the name of this <br>
country, this nation and this state will always be respectfully <br>
remembered by us,'' she said in a reference to Catli. <br>
	 ``I don't know Abdullah Catli, but I have investigated. He  <br>
has no confirmed conviction in Turkey,'' Ciller, also the <br>
foreign minister, told a meeting of her conservative True Path <br>
Party. <br>
	 Convicted drug smuggler Catli and a senior policeman died in  <br>
the same car in a crash Nov. 3. MP Bucak, from Ciller's True <br>
Path Party, was also in the vehicle. <br>
	 State officials are alleged to have encouraged criminal  <br>
gangs to take over the lucrative heroin trade from Kurdish drug <br>
barons sympathetic to Kurdistan Workers Party rebels. <br>
	 ``Our people's money is being used as a vehicle for dirty  <br>
dealings. Dirty money is the foundation of the mafia and these <br>
gangs,'' Yilmaz said. <br>
	 Former prime minister Yilmaz was punched in a hotel lobby  <br>
last weekend during a visit to Budapest. His aides have blamed <br>
Grey Wolves resident in Hungary for the attack. <br>
	 President Suleyman Demirel has only half-heartedly called  <br>
for the scandal to be probed and commentators see the government <br>
as unwilling to cooperate. <br>
	 ``It is obvious that the True Path wing of the government  <br>
will pull out all the stops to cover up the scandal,'' political <br>
analyst Bilal Cetin told Reuters. <br>
	 ``Welfare may try to cover up for the sake of continuing the  <br>
coalition. They may try to drag it out forever,'' he said. <br>
	 The interior minister, who stayed at the same hotel as the  <br>
gangster on the weekend of Catli's death, resigned earlier this <br>
month. <br>
