Subject: Summit torn by disputes over European security<br>
Date: Mon, 2 Dec 1996 15:01:22 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 LISBON, Portugal (Reuter) - Russia attacked NATO's plans for  <br>
enlargement and Belarus came under fire at a security summit <br>
Monday, sounding a jarring note as some 50 nations promised to <br>
build a lasting peace in Europe. <br>
	 The first day of the summit was also marked by a fierce  <br>
dispute between Armenia and Azerbaijan which threatened to block <br>
the entire summit declaration, and by growing concern over <br>
Serbia's handling of mass protests on the streets of Belgrade. <br>
	 Leaders from the Organization for Security and Cooperation  <br>
in Europe (OSCE) did manage to agree on a new round of arms <br>
control talks that would adapt and extend a Cold War-era <br>
agreement cutting conventional force in Europe. <br>
	 They also agreed on a security blueprint for the 21st  <br>
century, a set of concepts designed to make all nations feel <br>
secure on the continent where two world wars have started. <br>
	 But the veneer of diplomatic harmony was shattered almost  <br>
from the start, when Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin <br>
told assembled leaders that NATO would create new fault lines in <br>
Europe if it went ahead with plans to take in countries from <br>
Eastern Europe as new members. <br>
	 ``Is it not clear that the appearance of new dividing lines  <br>
would lead to a worsening of the whole geopolitical situation in <br>
the world?'' Chernomyrdin asked the opening session of the <br>
two-day meeting. <br>
	 The last summit of the 54-nation Organization for Security  <br>
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), two years ago in Budapest, was <br>
wrecked by a row on the NATO issue and differences over Bosnia. <br>
	 The United States and NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana  <br>
insisted that the alliance posed no threat to anyone and that it <br>
wanted to cooperate with Russia. <br>
	 ``NATO has been and remains a defensive alliance...it poses  <br>
no threat to any other state,'' U.S. Vice President Al Gore told <br>
the summit. ``The stability that NATO can help extend to Central <br>
Europe can help ensure the security of all nations.'' <br>
	 Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus told reporters his country  <br>
still expected to be among the first to join the alliance, and <br>
Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski said: <br>
	 ``Moscow has trouble accepting that NATO's enlargement is a  <br>
foregone conclusion.'' <br>
	 However, the Lisbon meeting did reach agreement on an issue  <br>
of concern to Russia -- adapting and extending a 1990 arms <br>
treaty which Moscow says no longer reflects reality. A new round <br>
of negotiations is now expected to start in Vienna in January. <br>
	 Western nations told Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko,  <br>
accused of trying to acquire dictatorial powers, to put the <br>
former Soviet republic back on the track to democracy. <br>
	 A defiant Lukashenko responded by supporting Russia's  <br>
opposition to NATO expansion, denying there was any problem at <br>
home and telling leaders to mind their own business. <br>
	 ``It would be counterproductive to try to exert pressure on  <br>
us or try to interfere in our internal affairs,'' he said. <br>
	 The summit is expected to endorse a continued OSCE role in  <br>
Bosnia, one year after the war ended there, although most eyes <br>
were on Serbia and the unprecedented challenge from <br>
demonstrators to President Slobodan Milosevic's autocratic rule. <br>
	 International peace coordinator Carl Bildt called for  <br>
Milosevic to start radical democratic reforms and to drop a <br>
threat to crush the protests. <br>
	 A senior U.S. official, who asked not to be identified, said  <br>
there could not be a ``decent peace in the Balkans'' unless <br>
Serbia became an open society, while British Foreign Secretary <br>
Malcolm Rifkind also called for greater democracy there. <br>
	 Russia has won little support at the summit for its  <br>
proposals to give the OSCE a more powerful role in European <br>
security and have it act as a counterbalance to NATO. <br>
	 France and Germany showed some sympathy for Russian  <br>
concerns, but many other countries fear Moscow wants to gain an <br>
effective veto on important European security issues by changing <br>
the way the OSCE works. <br>
	 German Chancellor Helmut Kohl told the meeting Europe must  <br>
not miss the chance to build real cooperation. <br>
	 ``There can only be security in Europe with, not against,  <br>
Russia,'' the German leader said. <br>
	 The security blueprint adopted by the summit reflects such  <br>
differences, balancing Russian concerns with the desires of NATO <br>
allies and Eastern European nations to press on with expansion. <br>
	 It said countries would consider developing a charter on  <br>
European security, something Moscow wants, but reaffirmed the <br>
rights of all nations to join alliances. <br>
	 Diplomats said the dispute between Armenia and Azerbaijan  <br>
over the disputed enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh could torpedo the <br>
final summit communique, which was due to be issued Tuesday. <br>
Every country in the OSCE has a veto. <br>
