Subject: Russia, Iran in Caspian oil agreement<br>
Date: Tue, 3 Dec 1996 7:41:17 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	MOSCOW, Dec. 3 (UPI) -- Russia and Iran have signed an agreement  <br>
pledging to create a joint Caspian Sea oil exploration and drilling <br>
company, reports said Tuesday. <br>
	The deal came late Monday, on the first day of a four-day session of  <br>
a bilateral commission on economic cooperation that is meeting for the <br>
first time since the collapse of the Soviet Union five years ago. <br>
	The Caspian agreement was signed by Russian Energy Minister Pyotr  <br>
Rodionov and the Iranian Economics and Foreign Trade Minister Mohammad <br>
Khan, the independent NTV television network reported. <br>
	Russian and Iranian officials declined to comment on the deal. They  <br>
did not say whether it would drill for oil in the Iran or the Russian <br>
sectors of the Caspian, or seek to work in the sectors of the other <br>
three littoral states. <br>
	Russia and Iran have sought to enforce Soviet-era treaties under  <br>
which all decisions on development of the oil-rich inland sea are <br>
subject to a consensus of all five shoreline states, but they have been <br>
rebuffed by Azerbaijan. <br>
	Pressure from the United States pushed Iran out of a $7.4 billion  <br>
Western-led consortium to drill three oil fields in the Azerbaijani <br>
sector of the Caspian, although Russia's Lukoil received a 10 percent <br>
stake in the contract. <br>
	The aim of the revived joint commission is to boost trade between the  <br>
former partners. Soviet trade with Iran in 1991 stood at more than $1.3 <br>
billion, while Russian-Iranian trade was just $250 million last year. <br>
	According to the Russian Ministry of Foreign Economic Relations, the  <br>
two nations have raised that to $350 million this year and have signed <br>
an additional $700 million worth of bilateral deals. <br>
	Those figures do not include a controversial $800 million contract  <br>
signed in January 1995, under which Russia is helping build a nuclear <br>
power plant near the Iranian city of Bushehr. <br>
	Russian Foreign Trade Minister Oleg Davydov, who heads the Russian  <br>
side in the joint commission, told the Itar-Tass news agency bilateral <br>
trade with Iran ``could reach several billion dollars within a few <br>
years.'' <br>
	Davydov told the Itar-Tass news agency 70 percent of the existing  <br>
trade comprises Russian delivery of machinery for the Iranian oil and <br>
energy sectors, and stressed energy should remain the focus of trade in <br>
the future. <br>
	Despite the sunny forecast of skyrocketing cooperation, Davydov  <br>
lamented that the development of trade is hindered by the lack of a <br>
legal basis and financial institutions to support it. <br>
	He said a treaty eliminating double taxation and investment  <br>
protection was being drawn up but would probably not be ready for <br>
signing until the next meeting of the bilateral commission. <br>
