Subject: Iran, Turkey cash on California's woes<br>
Date: Thu, 5 Dec 1996 9:01:49 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	LONDON, Dec. 5 (UPI) -- California's weather woes have benefitted nut  <br>
traders of Iran and Turkey, with British consumers having to pay more <br>
for the Christmas crunchies. <br>
	A looming shortage has pushed up prices of almonds and pistachios,  <br>
while the cost of hazlenuts has jumped by 35 percent after the Turkish <br>
government intervened to bolster prices, a London business daily <br>
reported Thursday. <br>
	Good quality almonds are almost sold out and prices are up 20 percent  <br>
in the past six weeks following a poor Californian crop for the second <br>
year running, the Financial Times said. <br>
	Pistachio prices are also 20 percent higher after bad weather  <br>
affected almost half of this year's Iranian crop. <br>
	Californian almond prices have more than doubled over the past two  <br>
years as cold and windy weather during the important growing periods <br>
caused a decline in the harvest and poor-quality nuts. After a <br>
disastrous crop in 1995 there were no stocks to carry over to this <br>
season, the daily said. <br>
	Pistachio prices have risen from $3,200 a ton in July to $4,000 and  <br>
nuts and dried-fruit trader expect a further rise of $50 to $100 before <br>
next summer when supplies will run out. <br>
	The new season's crop comes to market in November.  <br>
	The daily said the Turkish government's farm cooperative has so far  <br>
bought 25 percent of this year's hazelnut harevest at almost $1,000 a <br>
ton higher than the free market price in an effort to push up prices <br>
from their low base of recent years. <br>
	Free market prices have risen to $3,800 a ton, but remain below the  <br>
$4,100 which the Turkish cooperative is believed to be paying farmers, <br>
the daily said. <br>
