their trade volume by $2.5 billion. <br>
	The visit was announced the day after Iranian Foreign Minister Ali  <br>
Akbar Velayati concluded his visit to Syria with fresh criticism of a <br>
renewed military accord between Israel and Turkey. <br>
	``We strongly oppose any accord concluded between Muslim countries  <br>
and the Zionist entity,'' Velayati told the government-run Ath-Thawra <br>
newspaper before leaving Damascus after a two-day visit. <br>
	He was referring to a renewal, signed last week, of a military  <br>
training accord that had sparked protests from Turkey's Muslim <br>
neighbors, particularly Syria, Iraq and Iran. <br>
	``It is clear that such an accord is not in the interest of the  <br>
Muslim world,'' Velayati said. ``We have announced our protest and <br>
rejection of such an accord.'' <br>
	Velayati met President Hafez Assad, Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa  <br>
and other high officials during his visit. <br>
