Subject: Activists say West encourages rights abuses in former USSR<br>
Date: Tue, 10 Dec 1996 13:30:55 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 MOSCOW (Reuter) - The United States and its Western allies  <br>
put political and economic interests ahead of the protection of <br>
human rights in the former Soviet Union, a watchdog group <br>
charged Tuesday. <br>
	 ``In 1996 human rights principles were subordinated to  <br>
current political and economic interests,'' said Alexander <br>
Petrov, Moscow representative of the U.S.-based Human Rights <br>
Watch/Helsinki group. <br>
	 ``This particularly concerned the United States and the  <br>
countries of the European Union,'' he told a news conference to <br>
mark International Human Rights Day. <br>
	 ``An example of this kind of policy was provided by Russia's  <br>
accession to the Council of Europe despite the renewal and <br>
continuation of intense military activity in Chechnya involving <br>
colossal violations of humanitarian law,'' he said. <br>
	 The Council of Europe, which sees itself as an arbiter of  <br>
human rights, accepted Russia in February after months of delay <br>
due to concerns over Moscow's campaign in the breakaway region. <br>
	 Council members said at the time that having Russia on board  <br>
would help it to push forward human rights, but critics charged <br>
that it did nothing to stop the Chechnya fighting, which killed <br>
tens of thousands before a peace deal was signed in August. <br>
	 ``Things were no better in other republics,'' Petrov said,  <br>
citing aid given to Armenia and Georgia despite government <br>
crackdowns on opposition groups. <br>
	 Azerbaijan had also conducted a campaign to crush dissent,  <br>
he said, but nevertheless won observer status in the Council of <br>
Europe. Kazakhstan and Kirgizia also got Western support. <br>
	 As far as the rights situation itself was concerned, Petrov  <br>
said autocratic and arbitrary rule in Uzbekistan and <br>
Turkmenistan made them the biggest causes for alarm. <br>
	 In Russia, Petrov said the only significant improvement was  <br>
the end to the conflict against separatist rebels in Chechnya, <br>
begun when President Boris Yeltsin sent in troops two years ago. <br>
	 ``If you set this aside human rights stayed on the same  <br>
level and in some cases worsened,'' he said. <br>
	 He said the situation in Russia's regions was worse than in  <br>
Moscow and other big cities, citing direct threats and financial <br>
sanctions which he said were used to gag the media. ``There is <br>
no progress, but a regression here.'' <br>
	 Petrov also pinpointed a growth in xenophobia in Russia,  <br>
particularly against people of Caucasian origin beaten up and <br>
deported from big cities by the authorities. <br>
<p>
