Subject: Death sentence for 3 in Armenia<br>
Date: Tue, 10 Dec 1996 11:02:12 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	YEREVAN, Dec. 10 (UPI) -- Armenia's Supreme Court, culminating a 17-  <br>
month trial widely viewed as politically motivated, handed down death <br>
sentences Tuesday to three men convicted of murdering three members of <br>
their own political party. <br>
	The court found Arsen Artsumi, Armen Daryan and Armenak Grigoryan  <br>
guilty in the murder of three former members of their outlawed <br>
Dashnaktsutyun party who had left the group and allegedly had <br>
compromising information on its activities. <br>
	Another eight defendants in the case were pronounced guilty on  <br>
charges of drug trafficking and spying on government officials, and <br>
received prison terms of three to 13 years. <br>
	The court said the defendants were memers of DRO, a secret branch of  <br>
Dashnaktsutyun that allegedly engaged in illegal operations aimed at <br>
enriching the party and improving its political standing. <br>
	Ruben Akopyan, a lawmaker and member of Dashnaktsutyun, which was  <br>
declared illegal two years ago to exclude it from 1995 parliamentary <br>
elections, denounced the trial as an effort to ``oulawed our party <br>
forever.'' <br>
	``I am certain that this trial had political aims, and the  <br>
accusations of anti-government action essentially have removed the basic <br>
political rival of the current leadership,'' Akopyan said. <br>
	Akopyan reiterated claims the defendants were ``violently abused and  <br>
practically beaten to death'' in prison. One of the orginal 12 <br>
defendants died in solitary confinement in a pre-trial holding center. <br>
	Grant Markaryan, an Iranian citizen and a chief ideologue of  <br>
Dashnaktsutyun, received a surprisingly short five-year sentence. One of <br>
the defendants sentenced to death, Artsumi, is a citizen of Lebanon. <br>
	Political observers in Armenia said it was likely the death sentence  <br>
would be commuted, as President Levon Ter-Petrosyan has repeatedly said <br>
there will be no capital punishment while he is in office. <br>
	Ter-Petrosyan has led the country since 1990. He won a second term as  <br>
president in an election last September, winning 51 percent of a vote <br>
marred by claims of fraud and riots to protest the official result. <br>
	Dashnaktsutyun, formed early in the century and revived amid the  <br>
drive for independence from Moscow, was banned before campaigning got <br>
under way for 1995 parliamentary elections foreign observers called <br>
``free but not fair.'' <br>
	Its leader, Vahan Hogannesyan, and 30 other members are being tried  <br>
in a separate case on charges of conspiring to seize power during the <br>
disputed 1995 vote. <br>
