	 Turkey's Islamist Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan has  <br>
turned down an invitation to dine with EU ministers during the <br>
summit, saying he did so to warn Europe about its coolness <br>
towards Turkey. <br>
	 Europe has put Turkey's application for EU membership on  <br>
hold because of Ankara's economic troubles, human rights record <br>
and disputes with member Greece. <br>
	 Turkish officials bemoan the fact that former communist  <br>
nations of eastern Europe have streaked ahead of it in the queue <br>
for full membership. <br>
<p>
<p>
***************************************************************************<br>
Subject: Azeri parliament approves 1997 budget<br>
Date: Fri, 13 Dec 1996 11:11:02 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 BAKU, Dec 13 (Reuter) - Azerbaijan's parliament on Friday  <br>
approved a $758 million budget for 1997 which includes a $163 <br>
million deficit, a significant increase over 1996. <br>
	 The Milli Mejlis, or parliament, approved spending of 3.18  <br>
trillion manats and revenues of 2.5 trillion manats. The 680 <br>
billion manat deficit is significantly more than in 1996 which <br>
it was 516 billion manats ($117 million at the then exchange <br>
rate). <br>
	 The deficit is to be covered mainly by issuing treasury  <br>
bills and ``bonuses'' paid into state coffers by western oil <br>
companies signing new offshore Caspian Sea drilling contracts <br>
with the government. <br>
	 The government expects gross domestic product to rise two  <br>
percent over 1996 levels to 17.2 trillion manats. <br>
	 Education accounts for 648 billion manats, the biggest slice  <br>
of government spending, while 357 billion go to defence, 278 <br>
billion for social security and 250 billion for health care. <br>
	 Servicing the government debt will take 413 billion manats.  <br>
	 Some Milli Mejlis deputies complained about what they see as  <br>
the relatively low level of military spending at a time when the <br>
country is still in conflict with neighbouring Armenia over the <br>
disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
	 Finance Minister Fikret Usifov said the government had  <br>
collected nearly 100 percent of expected tax revenues for 1996. <br>
	 ($1 US &lt; 4250 manat)  <br>
 -- Lawrence Sheets, Tbilisi bureau (995-32) 99-93-70  <br>
<p>
<p>
***************************************************************************<br>
Subject: Azeris, oil firms sign $2 bln Caspian Sea deal<br>
Date: Sat, 14 Dec 1996 8:00:26 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 BAKU, Dec 14 (Reuter) - Azerbaijan and a consortium of  <br>
foreign oil companies led by Amoco Corp's Amoco Eurasian <br>
Petroleum Company signed a $2 billion deal on Saturday in Baku <br>
to develop the Ashrafi and Dan Ulduzu oil fields. <br>
	 The 25-year contract is Azerbaijan's fourth major deal with  <br>
a consortium of Western companies, in the Caucasus republic's <br>
Caspian Sea reserves. <br>
	 Amoco said it hopes to sign another exploration agreement  <br>
with the former Soviet republic soon. <br>
	 The Western consortium in Saturday's deal includes Amoco  <br>
Eurasian, with a 30 percent stake, Unocal with 25.5 percent, <br>
Japan's Itochu with 20 percent and Saudi Arabia's Delta Nimir <br>
with 4.5 percent. <br>
	 The Azerbaijan state oil company SOCAR will have a 20  <br>
percent stake in the deal and Azeri oil officials say 65 to 80 <br>
percent of profits from the development of the fields will go to <br>
the Azeri government. <br>
	 The Ashrafi and Dan Ulduzu fields lie appoximately 30 miles  <br>
off the Apsheron peninsula. They are spread over 453 square km <br>
(175 sq miles) at depths of 75 to 200 metres (246 to 656 feet) <br>
and are estimated to contain 150 million tonnes of crude. <br>
	 First production is expected to come on line in 2003 and  <br>
will reach seven million tonnes per year by 2007. <br>
	 The deal requires an up-front bonus payment to the Azeri  <br>
government of $75 million from consortium members and must be <br>
ratified by the Azeri parliament. <br>
	 The deal brings total western investment in Azerbaijan's  <br>
promising oil sector to over $12 billion. <br>
	 Azeri President Haydar Aliyev said the agreement was  <br>
evidence of the growing importance of the former Soviet republic <br>
for American companies. <br>
	 ``I am happy that the Clinton administration is finding  <br>
cooperation with Azerbaijan,'' Aliyev said, adding that he had <br>
received a telephone call from U.S. Vice President Al Gore on <br>
Friday. <br>
	 ``I consider that the U.S. and Azerbaijan are strategic  <br>
partners... The Vice President said the administration supports <br>
cooperation with the Azeri oil sector and regards the contract <br>
as of the utmost importance,'' he said. <br>
	 Azerbaijan, with its vast Capsian oil potential, has been  <br>
the centre of a tug-of-war between Russia, Iran, Trukey and <br>
Western countries since independence in 1991. <br>
	 Tom Stacy, Chairman of Amoco Eurasian Petroleum Company,  <br>
said the oil giant hoped to sign another Caspian contract with <br>
the Azeri government soon. <br>
	 ``We are happy to work in Azerbaijan and hope to sign another  <br>
contract soon on exploration of the southern part of the Azeri <br>
sector of the Caspian basin,'' he told a news conference. <br>
<p>
<p>
***************************************************************************<br>
Subject: Chechen oil head assures pipeline safe, wants cut<br>
Date: Thu, 19 Dec 1996 15:02:31 PST<br>
<p>
  	  				 <br>
	 MOSCOW, Dec 19 (Reuter) - The head of war-torn Chechnya's  <br>
oil company said on Thursday that Russia's rebellious region <br>
would guarantee the safety of a major oil pipeline across its <br>
land but demanded a cut in foreign deals that will use the link. <br>
	 Khozhakhmed Yarikhanov, president of the Southern Oil  <br>
Company, which is based in the devastated capital Grozny, told a <br>
news conference that an $8 billion multinational consortium that <br>
will use the link to export oil in 1997 should not worry because <br>
the pipeline was safe and sound. <br>
	 ``We guarantee the link's safety,'' he said. ``But remember  <br>
that with pipelines all over the world, things sometimes happen <br>
-- sabotage, technical errors, human errors.'' <br>
	 He said Chechnya should get a cut from transit fees via the  <br>
so-called northern link, which can carry 17 million tonnes of <br>
oil a year. <br>
	 ``The Chechen part is approximately in the same condition as  <br>
the rest of the link,'' he said, referring to the stretch running <br>
through Grozny and linking the Azeri capital Baku to Russia's <br>
Black Sea oil export outlet of Novorossiisk. <br>
	 The 13 international oil companies in the Azerbaijan  <br>
International Operating Company plan to reverse the flow of the <br>
pipeline to ship up to 100,000 barrels per day (bpd) of early <br>
oil from their Caspian offshore projects near Baku from August <br>
1997. <br>
	 The consortium is led by an alliance of British Petroleum  <br>
Plc and Norway's Statoil. <br>
	 Protracted bloodshed and instability in the 21-month Chechen  <br>
conflict have given the consortium the jitters ever since Moscow <br>
sent troops into Grozny in December 1994 in a bloody bid to rein <br>
in the breakaway region. <br>
	 The oil firms, worried that exports from their big ticket  <br>
investments could fall prey to a separatist war, have access to <br>
a second export route via the former Soviet republic of Georgia. <br>
	 Underscoring the fragility of the region for oil investors,  <br>
six foreigners working with the International Committee of the <br>
Red Cross were shot dead at a Chechen hospital on Wednesday and <br>
six ethnic Russians were killed on Thursday. <br>
	 Yarikhanov, who said he had faced a cool reception at  <br>
Russia's Transneft oil pipeline monopoly, which owns and <br>
operates the pipeline, and at the Fuel and Energy Ministry, said <br>
Moscow was not doing enough to resurrect the region's <br>
once-glorious oil sector. <br>
	 While he said the pipeline was no worse for the war,  <br>
Chechnya's production and refining facilities had been laid <br>
waste. <br>
	 At least eight trillion roubles ($1.44 billion) were needed  <br>
to bring the facilities back on line. Yarikhanov said financing <br>
could come from a Chechen cut in the transport fees that the <br>
Azeri oil consortium will pay to ship oil via Chechnya. <br>
	 ``We want our share of profits from the transport of oil  <br>
across our country,'' he said, adding the Azeri group would pay <br>
$16.57 per tonne to send oil from its Caspian Sea platforms near <br>
Baku to Novorossiisk. <br>
	 The Azeri oil consortium also includes Azeri state firm  <br>
SOCAR, Amoco Corp, Pennzoil Co, Unocal Corp, Exxon Corp, Ramco <br>
Energy Plc, Russia's LUKoil, Turkish TRAO, McDermott <br>
International Inc, Itochu Corp and Saudi Arabia's Delta Nimir. <br>
	 The Southern Oil Company, also called the Chechen Oil  <br>
Company, had hoped to stabilise output at three to four million <br>
tonnes a year before the breakaway region descended into <br>
bloodshed. <br>
	 Chechnya accounted for one-third of Soviet oil production in  <br>
the 1970s, or around 22 million tonnes a year, before Moscow <br>
began tapping its massive Siberian reserves. <br>
	 Refining capacity in the south Caucasian region is 20-22  <br>
million tonnes a year, but operations have ceased. <br>
 ($1&lt;5549 Rouble)  <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
