<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-19-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-19-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>19 Dec 96 19:46:37 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#185">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#185">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#185">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#185">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 12/19/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0184.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Daily 12/19/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/19/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. CONSENSUS APPARENT IN GOVERNMENT PROGRAM, SARKISSIAN SAYS<br>
2. ARF MARKS 106TH ANNIVERSARY IN YEREVAN<br>
3. DEFENDANT REJECTS PRELIMINARY TESTIMONY<br>
4. BARONESS COX RECEIVES KARABAKH MEDAL<br>
5. PROSECUTOR-GENERAL ASKS COURT TO REVISE "DRO" TRIAL VERDICT<br>
6. YEREVAN MAYOR MEETS WITH  CHINESE AMBASSADOR<br>
7. ARMENTEL TO UPGRADE TELEPHONE SERVICE<br>
8. GERMAN EXPERTS STUDY CONDITION OF ARMENIAN RAILWAY<br>
9. ARMENIA CALLS FOR JOINT PROTECTION OF ANI WITH TURKEY<br>
10. TACIS IMPLEMENTS ENERGY PROGRAM IN ARMENIA<br>
11. UN ENVOY NOMINEE SUPPORTS ARMENIAN ISSUES<br>
<p>
<p>
1. CONSENSUS APPARENT IN GOVERNMENT PROGRAM, SARKISSIAN SAYS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN-At a press conference Thursday, Armenian Prime Minister <br>
Armen Sarkissian stated that he would introduce reforms in the <br>
countrys tax system, adding that there was a domestic consensus <br>
in the governments overall proposed agenda, reported the Noyan <br>
Tapan news agency.<br>
	The prime minister also announced that he planned to make <br>
changes in the 1997 fiscal year budget, increasing earning by two-<br>
thirds percent, for which he planned to initiate reforms in the <br>
taxation and customs areas.<br>
	Stressing that the governments programs are in concert with <br>
that of the opposition platform, Sarkissian stated that there <br>
existed a domestic consensus in Armenia.<br>
	Sarkissian added that during last weeks meeting with <br>
representatives of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation Executive <br>
Council, he "only presented all facets of his governments <br>
program."<br>
	According to Noyan Tapan, Sarkissian conveyed that the ARFs <br>
reinstatement issue in Armenia was not discussed during that <br>
meeting.<br>
	A report by the Yerevan news agency noted last week that the <br>
ARF representatives discussed the prime ministers government <br>
program during the meeting with Sarkissian, and "addressed <br>
domestic political issues, emphasizing the importance of political <br>
parties in the resolution of those concerns."<br>
	During the press conference, Sarkissian also discussed the <br>
possibility of more meetings with the opposition.<br>
	Finally, Sarkissian added, that the government had decided <br>
to establish a new structure for privatizing state businesses and <br>
unfinished construction projects, as well as a time-table for the <br>
implementing the project.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. ARF MARKS 106TH ANNIVERSARY IN YEREVAN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The 106th anniversary celebrations of the <br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation were held on December 17 in <br>
Yerevans "Hagop Baronian" theater.<br>
	Master of Ceremonies and ARF Executive Council member Vartan <br>
Petrossian drew parallels between the ARFs activities a century <br>
ago with those of today.<br>
	"One hundred years ago, the ARF came to the forefront with <br>
the famous [Sarkis] Gougounian expedition of 1896 and in 1990, the <br>
ARF took an active part in Karabakhs self-defense struggle," he <br>
said.<br>
	ARF Executive Council and National Assembly member Rouben <br>
Hakobian delivered the keynote address. "In 1890, Armenian <br>
political thought opened a new page with the founding of the <br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation, and the realization that <br>
Armenias future lies in its own strength."<br>
	Hakobian synthesized the 106-year life of the ARF with a <br>
overview of the three-stages in its development-the founding of <br>
the ARF to the Sovietization of the Republic of Armenia in 1921; <br>
the ARFs role in the Armenian Diaspora; and the ARFs return to <br>
Armenia and Artsakh as a result of the Gorbachev-era reforms and   <br>
national reawakening begining with the 1988 Karabakh movement.<br>
	Hakobian concluded his remarks by focusing on the suspension <br>
of the ARF in Armenia. "Any plans to halt the ARFs activities is <br>
doomed to failure. The ARF will continue its activity for the good <br>
of the nation and the establishment of statehood, and no force can <br>
hinder us," he said, adding "the announcement during the <br>
sentencing phase of the so-called "Dro" trial showed that justice <br>
will prevail." The court found no direct links between co-<br>
defendant and ARF leader Hrand Markarian and the "Dro" group, thus <br>
absolving any alleged ties between the ARF and the purported <br>
clandestine group.<br>
	National Democratic Union chairman Vazgen Manoukian praised <br>
the ARF on the anniversary of its establishment, saying "the ARF <br>
is a national asset and it has a mission. There is still more to <br>
be done in the future than has been done in the past."<br>
	Aram Sargssian of the Armenian Democratic Party joined <br>
Manoukian in congratulating the ARF, which he characterized as an <br>
honor.<br>
	The final speaker for the evening was former Communist Party <br>
member, Prof. Karnig Ananian, who praised the ARFs "glorious <br>
history."<br>
	The evenings celebrations concluded with a cultural <br>
program.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. DEFENDANT REJECTS PRELIMINARY TESTIMONY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-"Trial of 31" co-defendant Martin <br>
Karapetian, who is charged with high treason, conspiracy to commit <br>
a terrorist act and illegal possession of weapons, started his <br>
testimony, rejecting statements made during the preliminary <br>
investigation.<br>
	Karapetian said he gave false testimony to help his father <br>
and brother Vladik, who had been arrested. He is convinced that <br>
his father and brother were taken hostage to make his elder <br>
brother Gagik surrender.<br>
	Karapetian was convinced that co-defendant Vachagan Kossian, <br>
a fellow veteran of the Afghan war, was arrested as a warning in <br>
case of non-compliance. He said that twenty of his friends have <br>
been interrogated.<br>
	He denied preliminary investigation claims that his brother <br>
Gagik had told him about the alleged coup attempt and instructed <br>
him to recruit people. Karapetian also rejected claims alleging <br>
that he was going to learn the presidents and other top <br>
officials whereabouts via his friends working at the National <br>
Security Council in order to carry out alleged acts of terrorism.<br>
	Karapetian stated that he, his two brothers, father and even <br>
his pregnant sister-in-law were subjected to violence by <br>
investigating bodies, as a result of which his sister-in-law went <br>
into premature labor. The condition of the newborn twins is still <br>
critical, he said.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. BARONESS COX RECEIVES KARABAKH MEDAL<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (Noyan Tapan)-The Prime Minister of Karabakh, Leonard <br>
Petrossian, presented Baroness Caroline Cox, deputy speaker of the <br>
British House of Lords, with a commemorative medal dedicated to <br>
the fifth anniversary of Karabakhs independence.<br>
	Petrossian met with a delegation of the Geneva-based <br>
Christian Solidarity International, a charity group that Cox is <br>
involved with, and discussed the recent presidential election in <br>
Karabakh. Cox asked Petrossian to convey her congratulations and <br>
best wishes to Robert Kocharian on his election.<br>
	Petrossian briefed his guests on economic reforms, the <br>
development of infrastructures and tourism in Karabakh.<br>
	Deputy Prime Minister Jirayr Poghossian and writer Zori <br>
Balayan also attended the meeting.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. PROSECUTOR-GENERAL ASKS COURT TO REVISE "DRO" TRIAL VERDICT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg)-The Prosecutor-General of the Republic of Armenia, <br>
Artavazd Gevorkian, called on the Supreme Court to revise the <br>
"Dro" trial verdicts, and consequently the sentences, handed down <br>
on December 10.<br>
	By law, only Gevorkian may provide additional information, <br>
since he signed the final document. The prosecutors office <br>
believes that in certain cases the court mistakenly accepted <br>
evidence provided by the preliminary investigations, sources close <br>
to the case said.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. YEREVAN MAYOR MEETS WITH  CHINESE AMBASSADOR<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Yerevan Mayor Vano Siradeghian welcomed <br>
Chinas Ambassador to Armenia Xian Kezhun  Tuesday.<br>
	The two discussed the importance of establishing friendly <br>
relations between the two countries and possibly having China <br>
invest in Yerevans small businesses.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. ARMENTEL TO UPGRADE TELEPHONE SERVICE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The Armentel telephone company has already <br>
used $37 million to upgrade Armenias telephone service, director <br>
Vahram Soghomonian said.<br>
	The German firm, Siemens, allocated $75 million in loans to <br>
help fund the modernization of Yerevans telephone network. <br>
Soghomonian also said that Armentel received new investment <br>
proposals, however, they are not ready to utilize them yet.<br>
	"Armentel does not have financial problems. The problem is <br>
staff training, quick installation and operation of the <br>
equipment," Soghomonian said at a press conference.<br>
	Armentel is a joint-venture of which 49 percent of is <br>
controlled American Trans-World Telecom Company.<br>
	Soghomonian denied reports published in "Golos Armenii" <br>
newspaper of protest against privatization by Armentels <br>
employees. He characterized the article as "a provocation" <br>
instigated by the chairman of the Armenias Communication <br>
Employees Trade Union, Victor Adamian.<br>
	Soghomonian said that abusing the freedom of speech can <br>
hinder the investment flow into Armenia. "We manage to earn money, <br>
do not interfere with our work," he said and added that Armentel <br>
received new investment proposals from Siemens ($150,000,000), <br>
Alkatel ($20,000,000) and Daewoo ($30,000,000).<br>
	Chairman of the Yerevan Stock Exchange Sedrak Sedrakian <br>
expressed regret that Adamian and the editor of "Golos Armenii," <br>
Flora Nakhshkarian, did not take part in the news conference.<br>
	Soghomonian said that presently Armentels shares are being <br>
prepared for public sale. Conditions of the privatization must be <br>
specified by the government, he added.<br>
	According to Soghomonian, modernization of the enterprise <br>
will lead to downsizing and loss of some jobs, but at the same <br>
time, it will create a number of new ones.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. GERMAN EXPERTS STUDY CONDITION OF ARMENIAN RAILWAY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The German economic and consulting firm, <br>
Tewet, is currently preparing a package of technical and economic <br>
documents to determine the amount of money needed for the <br>
restoration of Armenian's railway.<br>
	All work is being implemented within the guidelines of the <br>
European Communitys Traceka program, which calls for an extension <br>
of the Europe-Caucasus-Asia corridor.<br>
	The 16-part program includes a joint Transcaucasus railway <br>
enterprise to be set up between Armenia, Georgia and Azerbaijan. <br>
The program is being implemented in association with GTZ and De-<br>
Consult companies of Germany and is due to be completed within the <br>
next 10 months.<br>
	A representative from the De-Consult firm, Erica Muller, who <br>
is also responsible for the implementation of the program in <br>
Armenia, reported that since September, six experts from these <br>
firms have confirmed that Armenias railway is in extremely poor <br>
shape and its restoration will require a sizable investment.<br>
	Another group of German experts who will determine the size <br>
of investments needed for the restoration of locomotives, railway <br>
stations, and communications is expected to visit Armenia in <br>
January 1997.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. ARMENIA CALLS FOR JOINT PROTECTION OF ANI WITH TURKEY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenias National Academy of Sciences, in <br>
association with the International Center for the Protection and <br>
Study of the City of Ani, the ancient capital of Armenia, it will <br>
hold talks with Turkey to discuss problems regarding preservation <br>
and study of the Ani ruins.<br>
	Historians and archeologists have tried on many occasion to <br>
draw attention to the plight of the ancient city, but to no avail, <br>
and the governments have repeatedly pledged to sign a number of <br>
international agreements in order to ensure the protection of <br>
memorials that are of international value, the academy said.<br>
	The latest call to action by the National Academy of <br>
Sciences pays special attention to the famous Ani Cathedral, which <br>
is faced with destruction as a result of the 1988 earthquake in <br>
Armenia.<br>
	The Cathedrals 1000th anniversary will be marked in 2001. <br>
It was also noted that Armenia is ready to carry out the <br>
restoration and construction of the city.<br>
	The Turkish side has offered to proclaim the Ani zone an <br>
international museum under the protection of Turkey and Armenia.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. TACIS IMPLEMENTS ENERGY PROGRAM IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Chief specialist of the Energy Ministrys <br>
Department for Reconstruction and Development, Alexander <br>
Kocharian, said that TACIS started implementing a program to <br>
develop Armenias energy sector.<br>
	The first two stages of the program are devoted to problems <br>
of project and office management, Kocharian said.<br>
	TACIS has set up guidelines for the training of office <br>
staff. Seminars are conducted by foreign specialists.<br>
	According to Kocharian, Armenia is presently getting foreign <br>
aid and loans under various projects, and it is very important <br>
that these funds are spent efficiently.<br>
<p>
<p>
11. UN ENVOY NOMINEE SUPPORTS ARMENIAN ISSUES<br>
<p>
*New Mexico Congressman Bill Richardson has backed aid to Armenia, <br>
peace in Nagorno-Karabah, the Azeri aid ban, and commemoration of <br>
the Genocide<br>
<p>
WASHINGTON-President Clintons nominee to serve as US Ambassador <br>
to the United Nations, New Mexico Congressman Bill Richardson, has <br>
a record of supporting a range of issues of concern to Armenian-<br>
Americans, including aid to Armenia, the equitable resolution of <br>
the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict, sanctions on Turkey due to its <br>
blockade of Armenia and the commemoration of the  Armenian <br>
Genocide, reported the Armenian National Committee of America. <br>
	In June of this year, Richardson voted in favor of the <br>
Visclosky Amendment, which stregthened the Humanitarian Aid <br>
Corridor Act sanction on Turkey for obstructing US humanitarian <br>
supplies to Armenia.  The Amendment, which limited the Presidents <br>
authority to waive the Corridor Act, was designed to cut off all <br>
US economic assistance to Turkey until it had ceased to block the <br>
delivery of relief assistance to Armenia.  In June 1995,  Rep. <br>
Richardson voted in favor of the Porter Amendment to the FY 1996 <br>
foreign aid bill, sharply reducing US aid levels to Turkey  <br>
because of that nations continued blockade of Armenia, occupation  <br>
of Cyprus, mistreatment of the Kurds and worsening human rights  <br>
record. He has also supported a number of other issues of concern  <br>
to Greek and Kurdish-Americans.<br>
	During the 103rd Congress, Richardson co-sponsored H.Res. <br>
86, introduced by House Democratic Whip David Bonior, which <br>
presented a six-point guideline for US involvement in the <br>
NagornoKarabakh Peace process.  The resolution called for <br>
continued humanitarian aid for Armenia; promoted a "lasting and <br>
equitable resolution to the conflict within the UN and CSCE"; <br>
called for the "full participation of the representatives of <br>
Nagorno Karabagh in all negotiations"; encouraged "Turkey, which <br>
has provided military, economic and diplomatic support for <br>
Azerbaijan, to play a neutral role"; condemned the "blockades of <br>
Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh; and demanded "the immediate lifting" <br>
of the blockades and the opening of humanitarian corridors to <br>
facilitate the delivery of humanitarian goods to Armenia; and <br>
supported the continuation of the ban on US aid to Azerbaijan <br>
until its ceases its aggression against and blockades of Armenia <br>
and Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
	Richardson voted for the Armenian Genocide resolution both <br>
times that it came before the House during his term of office, in <br>
1987 (H.J.Res.132), and 1985 (H.J.Res.192). He did not,  however, <br>
support the Radanovich-Bonior Amendment to the FY 1997 foreign aid <br>
bill.<br>
<p>
<p>
