<title>Groong Network: Kommersant on Ciller's visit to Moscow</title>
<h1>Kommersant on Ciller's visit to Moscow</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 1996 16:02:14 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#181">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#181">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#181">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#181">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0182.html">mrw@arminco.com: "The 'Rome Declaration' et cetera"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "VOA/96/Caspian Oil"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Kommersant =FF-DAILY         =20<br>
<p>
Thursday, 19 December 1996=20<br>
<p>
Summary of results of Tansu Ciller=92s visit to Moscow<br>
<p>
Tansu Ciller=92s =93shuttle=94* diplomacy<br>
<p>
By Andrei Smirnov and Marina Sergeeva<br>
<p>
<p>
The visit of Turkish Foreign Affairs Minister, Tansu Ciller to Moscow<br>
confirmed once again that economic cooperation of two countries can develop<br>
successfully despite serious political contradictions. =20<br>
<p>
Political problems aggravating bilateral relations are well-known. Primarily<br>
they are Turkey=92s =93veto=94 on oil transit through Bosporus, attempts to<br>
establish =93special relations=94 with Turkic peoples of Russia and Ankara=<br>
=92s<br>
tacit support of Chechen separatists. Ankara is concerned with Russian<br>
military equipment supplies to Greek Cypriots.=20<br>
<p>
Tansu Ciller=92s conversation with Victor Chernomyrdin and Evgenii Primakov=<br>
 on<br>
political topics left the sides with their opinions. Primakov and Ciller did<br>
not even try to conceal political contradictions.  Moscow did not soften<br>
even by Ciller=92s =93promising=94 statement that Ankara will do everything=<br>
 in its<br>
power so that NATO expansion does not pose threats to Russia. Primakov only<br>
noted that Russia did not need mediators in the dialogue with NATO. However,<br>
the exchange of =93niceties=94 ended with assurances of the sides to adhere=<br>
 to<br>
the principle of territorial integrity of each other.  By the way, the fact<br>
that Ciller would offer Moscow assistance in dealing with NATO expansion<br>
your =FF correspondent was told by one of the leaders of PKK long before the<br>
visit. In his opinion Ciller would want Moscow to give assurances to stop<br>
the support of Kurds who are engaged in a guerrilla warfare with Turkish<br>
army.  In Moscow the sides signed a Memorandum on cooperation with<br>
terrorism. But that is only a non-binding declaration. Answering a question<br>
whether the Memorandum meant a ban on the activities of PKK in Russia,<br>
Primakov said, =93 I am not responsible for activities of that party.=94 One=<br>
 can<br>
only conclude that numerous Kurdish organizations in Russia (they even held<br>
a session of their parliament in exile in Moscow not long ago) have nothing<br>
to worry about.  Military equipment supplies to Greek Cypriots will, too,<br>
continue. In response to Ankara=92s grudge Russian Foreign Affairs Minister<br>
said that=20<br>
anti-aircraft means (Russia signed a contract with the Republic of Cyprus<br>
recently) are not offensive weapon types. =20<br>
<p>
Negotiations at Moscow mayor=92s office, Yurii Luzhkov were free from<br>
contradictions on Kurds and straits. The sides agreed to implement three<br>
large business projects: construction of a wholesale trading center, a hotel<br>
and business center in Novinskii Boulevard, and a wholesale food market. A<br>
memorandum on understanding of principles of trade-economic cooperation was<br>
signed by the government of Turkey and Moscow mayor=92s office.  The<br>
construction of a wholesale trade-center is virtually an attempt to take<br>
under control =93shuttle trade=94 without decreasing the volume of trade<br>
turnover with Turkey. In 1995 in Moscow alone Turkish goods worth $226<br>
million (the official turnover standing at $3.5 billion). But statistics<br>
does not take into consideration the real turnover: thanks to =93shuttle<br>
traders=94 the real turnover is estimated at $5-6 billion in Russia and the<br>
bulk of it is concentrated in Moscow.   Last summer Luzhkov did raise =93the<br>
shuttle=94 question after Russian government had adopted new taxes for these<br>
traders. The mayor did not like these taxes. Neither did the Turkish<br>
government. Luzhkov argued then that new taxes would result in a sharp<br>
increase of prices -- by 42% -- on goods from Turkey brought in by =93shuttl=<br>
e<br>
traders=94 from Russia and consequently would be a serious blow to Russians<br>
from less wealthy walks of life. This, however, did not happen.  =20<br>
<p>
By the way, the mayor who had broken his leg after a visit to circus greeted<br>
the Turkish lady without crutches and looked fresh. In appreciation of<br>
developing cooperation Luzhkov gave his Turkish guest a swan from Khokhloma<br>
and invited her to visit Moscow as often as she could. (end)=20<br>
<p>
(Translated by AM, *play on words, Russians use the word =93shuttle traders=<br>
=94<br>
to designate tourists who travel to Turkey to purchase goods there and to<br>
sell them in Russia and other CIS countries.)=20<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
