<title>Groong Network: VOA/96/Caspian Oil</title>
<h1>VOA/96/Caspian Oil</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 1996 15:35:27 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#180">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#180">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#180">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#180">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Kommersant on Ciller's visit to Moscow"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0179.html">H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk: "From Armenpress homepage"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DATE=12/18/96<br>
TYPE=YEAREND REPORT<br>
NUMBER=5-35263<br>
TITLE=96:  CASPIAN OIL<br>
BYLINE=HASAN JAVADI<br>
DATELINE=WASHINGTON<br>
CONTENT=<br>
VOICED AT: <br>
<p>
INTRO:  THE CASPIAN SEA WITH ITS VAST OIL AND NATURAL GAS <br>
RESOURCES HAS BECOME MORE AND MORE A CONTESTING GROUND FOR <br>
WESTERN OIL COMPANIES.  IN WASHINGTON VOA'S HASAN JAVADI SURVEYS <br>
THE OIL DEALS AND DEVELOPMENTS BY THE CASPIAN LITTORAL STATES IN <br>
1996.<br>
<p>
TEXT:  SEVERAL DIPLOMATIC EFFORTS IN 1996 TO RESOLVE THE <br>
CONTESTED STATUS OF THE CASPIAN SEA WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  IRAN, <br>
RUSSIA AND TURKMENISTAN CONSIDER THE CASPIAN SEA AS A LAKE AND <br>
WANT TO SHARE ITS RESOURCES.  AZERBAIJAN AND KAZAKHSTAN REMAIN <br>
ADAMANT IN REGARDING IT AS A SEA WITH EACH STATE HAVING EXCLUSIVE<br>
COASTAL ZONES.<br>
<p>
PENDING A FINAL DEFINITION OF THE BODY OF WATER INVOLVED, THE  <br>
DEVELOPMENT OF CASPIAN OIL RESOURCES CONTINUED ON TWO FRONTS -- <br>
PIPELINE ROUTES AND OIL EXPLORATIONS. <br>
<p>
ONE NEWCOMER TO THE REGION IS JAPAN, SEEKING TO INVEST IN THE <br>
CASPIAN OIL AND GAS RESOURCES FOR EXPORT THROUGH THE BLACK SEA.  <br>
THIS HAS BEEN CALLED "THE CASPIAN DIRECTION" AND HUGE SUM OF  <br>
CAPITAL IS BEING INVESTED IN AZERBAIJAN, GEORGIA, KAZAKHSTAN AND <br>
TURKMENISTAN.  JAPANESE ITOCHU COMPANY IS INTERESTED IN BUILDING <br>
TRANSPORTATION NETWORKS IN THE REGION.  <br>
<p>
DAVID NISSMAN, A WASHINGTON-BASED OIL EXPERT, WATCHES THE AREA'S <br>
DEVELOPMENT.<br>
<p>
                        // NISSMAN ACT //<br>
<p>
         THIS POLICY WILL AFFECT  NOT  ONLY AZERBAIJAN, BUT <br>
         GEORGIA AS WELL.  AND (IT) HAS AFFECTED THE KAZAKH <br>
         DECISION TO TRY TO SHIP SOME OF THE TENGIZ (KAZAKHSTAN) <br>
         OIL OUT FROM BAKU (AZERBAIJAN) TO SUPSA (GEORGIA).  BUT,<br>
         NONETHELESS, IT MEANS THAT THE ENTIRE CAUCASUS HAS BEGUN<br>
         TO GAIN VISIBLE IMPORTANCE AS FAR AS THE GLOBAL ECONOMY <br>
         IS CONCERNED.<br>
<p>
                          // END ACT //<br>
<p>
ANOTHER DEAL WAS SIGNED BETWEEN AZERBAIJAN AND GEORGIA IN <br>
NOVEMBER AFTER MONTHS OF NEGOTIATIONS.  THE ACCORD CLEARED THE <br>
WAY FOR AN INTERNATIONAL CONSORTIUM TO TRANSPORT OIL FROM THE <br>
CASPIAN SEA VIA A GEORGIAN PIPELINE TO THE PORT OF SUPSA AT THE <br>
BLACK SEA.  THE EXISTING PIPELINE NEEDS NEARLY 240 MILLION <br>
DOLLARS OF REPAIRS.<br>
<p>
STILL, THE BULK OF THE CASPIAN OIL WILL HAVE TO BE TRANSPORTED <br>
THROUGH GROZNY, IN CHECHNYA, TO THE RUSSIAN PORT OF  NOVOROSSYISK<br>
ON THE BLACK SEA, THE NEWLY SIGNED AGREEMENT BETWEEN THE CHECHENS<br>
AND RUSSIA IS VERY IMPORTANT SINCE THE FLOW OF OIL WILL DEPEND ON<br>
PEACE IN CHECHNYA. <br>
<p>
ON DECEMBER 6 AN INTERNATIONAL CONSORTIUM SIGNED AN AGREEMENT IN <br>
MOSCOW CLEARING THE WAY FOR CONSTRUCTION OF A PIPELINE LINKING <br>
KAZAKHSTAN TO THE BLACK SEA.  UNDER THIS TWO-BILLION DOLLAR <br>
ACCORD, RUSSIA, KAZAKHSTAN AND OMAN WILL SHARE A 50 PERCENT STAKE<br>
IN THE DEAL.  EIGHT INTERNATIONAL COMPANIES WILL SPLIT THE <br>
REMAINING 50 PERCENT.  THE CHIEF BENEFICIARY IS EXPECTED TO BE <br>
CHEVRON (U.S. OIL COMPANY).<br>
<p>
THE PIPELINE IS EXPECTED TO TAKE THREE YEARS TO BUILD.  <br>
MEANWHILE, CHEVRON IS INCREASING PRODUCTION IN TENGIZ.  KAZAKSTAN<br>
ALSO SEEKS OTHER OIL EXPORT ROUTES.  LAST MAY, KAZAKHSTAN AND <br>
IRAN SIGNED AN AGREEMENT TO EXCHANGE OIL CREDITS.  KAZAKHSTAN <br>
WILL DELIVER TWO MILLION TONS OF OIL TO IRAN ANNUALLY AT THE <br>
CASPIAN SEA, AND IRAN WILL DELIVER AN EQUAL AMOUNT TO BUYERS AT <br>
THE PERSIAN GULF.  <br>
<p>
BULENT ALIREZA OF THE STRATEGIC INSTITUTE OF WASHINGTON HAS <br>
WATCHED THE CENTRAL ASIAN OIL EXCHANGE ARRANGEMENTS.<br>
<p>
                      // OPT ALIREZA ACT //<br>
<p>
         ALTHOUGH THEORETICALLY IT HAD ALWAYS THE POSSIBILITY OF <br>
         PUTTING ITS OIL THROUGH IRAN, THERE IS A DISPENSATION <br>
         THAT IS GRANTED TO THAT END BY THE TREASURY.  CLEARLY, <br>
         CHEVRON HAS DECIDED  NOT  TO TAKE THIS UP, AND HAS <br>
         PREFERRED TO PUT IT THROUGH TRANS-CAUCASUS.<br>
<p>
                     // END ACT., END OPT //<br>
<p>
MR. ALIREZA SAYS KAZAKHSTAN IS ALSO TRYING TO EXPORT OIL THROUGH <br>
AZERBAIJAN.  EARLIER THIS YEAR ONE MILLION TONS OF CHEVRON OIL <br>
WAS SHIPPED FROM AKTAU, IN KAZAKHSTAN, TO BAKU, AND FROM THERE IT<br>
WAS SENT BY RAIL TO BATUMI.  <br>
<p>
BULENT ALIREZA SAYS HE EXPECTS THAT TO CONTINUE TO THE BENEFIT OF<br>
AZERBAIJAN.<br>
<p>
                        // ALIREZA ACT //<br>
<p>
         THAT IS THE HARBINGER OF MORE TO COME. THE MOST <br>
         SIGNIFICANT THING THAT I WOULD STRESS IS THAT AZERBAIJAN<br>
         NOT  ONLY IS GOING TO BE PUTTING ITS OIL INTO MARKETS, <br>
         BUT IN ADDITION IT IS ALSO GOING TO BE PLAYING A ROLE AS<br>
         A CONDUIT FOR KAZAKH OIL.  IT IS A VERY SIGNIFICANT <br>
         DEVELOPMENT, BECAUSE WE ARE NOW TALKING OF KAZAKH OIL <br>
         REACHING MARKETS THROUGH NON-RUSSIAN ROUTES, IN WHICH <br>
         AZERBAIJAN IS PLAYING A ROLE.<br>
<p>
                          // END ACT//<br>
<p>
ONE MORE SIGNIFICANT STEP IN DISPOSITION OF THE OIL INTO MARKET  <br>
WAS THE COMPLETION OF THE FIRST FLOATING DRILLING PLATFORM,  <br>
WHICH WAS TUGGED FROM BAKU INTO THE ACTUAL OILFIELD IN THE <br>
CASPIAN IN AUGUST, 1996.  THE THREE-STORY HIGH STRUCTURE WAS <br>
COMPLETED BY AZERBAIJAN INTERNATIONAL OPERATING COMPANY ( <br>
A-I-O-C). <br>
<p>
// OPT //  AT THE MOMENT THERE ARE FOUR CONSORTIA ON THE AZERI <br>
OIL.  THE MEGA PROJECT OF THREE OIL FIELDS OF CHIRAG, GUNESHLI <br>
AND AZERI, WHICH IS WITH A-I-O-C WITH EIGHT-POINT-TWO BILLION <br>
DOLLAR INVESTMENT.  IN THIS VENTURE THE AZERI STATE OIL CO <br>
(S-O-C-A-R) IS WORKING WITH BRITISH PETROLEUM (BP), STAT OIL, <br>
AMOCO, PENZOIL, UNOCAL, EXXON, AND THIS IS DUE TO PRODUCE OIL IN <br>
OCTOBER 1997.<br>
<p>
// OPT // THE OTHER TWO CONSORTIA WHOSE AGREEMENTS WERE <br>
FORMALIZED THIS YEAR ARE SHAH DENIZ WITH PARTICIPATION OF B-P, <br>
IRAN, TURKISH PETROLEUM AND S-O-C-A-R AND KARABAKH WHICH INVOLVES<br>
LUKOIL AND PENZOIL.  THESE CONSORTIA ARE FAR FROM PRODUCTION <br>
STAGE.  IN EARLY DECEMBER A FOURTH CONSORTIUM AGREEMENT (ASHRAFI <br>
AND DAN ULDUZU) WAS SIGNED BETWEEN AZERBAIJAN, AMOCO, UNOCAL AND <br>
ITOCHU COMPANY FOR TWO BILLION DOLLARS.<br>
<p>
// OPT // TOTAL INVESTMENT IN THE FOUR CONSORTIA AMOUNTS TO <br>
12-AND-ONE-HALF BILLION DOLLARS.  AZERBAIJAN HAS SIGNED OTHER <br>
CONTRACTS WITH WESTERN COMPANIES TO ATTRACT ANOTHER 14 BILLION <br>
DOLLARS IN INVESTMENTS DURING THE NEXT 15 YEARS. // END OPTIONAL <br>
//<br>
<p>
LOOKING AHEAD, IT SEEMS THAT CASPIAN OIL WILL BE TRANSPORTED  <br>
PARTLY THROUGH GROZNY AND PARTLY BY RAIL THROUGH GEORGIA.  THE <br>
OIL COMPANIES ARE COUNTING ON PEACE IN THE CAUCASUS -- THROUGH <br>
WHICH PIPELINES PASS.  (SIGNED) <br>
<p>
CENA/HJ/CF<br>
<p>
18-Dec-96 4:37 PM EST (2137 UTC)<br>
NNNN<br>
<p>
Source: Voice of America<br>
.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
