<!-- received="Thu Dec 19 15:07:22 1996 EST" -->
<!-- sent="Thu, 19 Dec 96 11:38:56 PST" -->
<!-- name="H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk" -->
<!-- email="H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk" -->
<!-- subject="From Armenpress homepage" -->
<!-- id="CMM.0.90.4.851024336.asbed@sol.usc.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Groong Network: From Armenpress homepage</title>
<h1>From Armenpress homepage</h1>
<i>H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk</i><br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 96 11:38:56 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#179">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#179">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#179">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#179">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "VOA/96/Caspian Oil"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0178.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Armenpress homepage"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 "OUR NATIONAL-ECCLESIASTICAL TRADITIONS REMAIN UNCHANGED"<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 An interview with Archbishop Mesrob Mutafyan on the recent meeting <br>
 between Catholicos Karekin I and Pope John Paul II in the Vatican<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 ISTANBUL ("Lraper" 18 December 1996) -- Archbishop Mesrob Mutafyan, <br>
 Chairman of the Religious Council of the Armenian Patriarchate of <br>
 Constantinople, gave an interview to the Istanbul Armenian daily <br>
 newspaper "Jamanag" in which he elucidated the main points and <br>
 significance of the formal declaration issued recently in the Vatican <br>
 on the occasion of the meeting between Catholicos Karekin I of All <br>
 Armenians and Pope John Paul II. The interview, conducted by editor <br>
 Ara Kochunian, was first published in the 17 December issue of <br>
 "Jamanag".<br>
 <br>
 Q.  Your Eminence, you were part of the delegation of the Armenian<br>
 Apostolic Church, led by His Holiness Karekin I, that paid an <br>
 official visit to the Vatican where historic documents were signed. <br>
 Almost all the European news agencies reported that the signing of <br>
 these documents signaled the end of 1500 years of controversies <br>
 between the Chalcedonian churches and the Armenian Apostolic Church.  <br>
 It was even said that, from now on, we would celebrate Christmas on <br>
 the 25th of December. Could you please explain these things to us?<br>
 <br>
 A. Indeed, I witnessed a historic and a solemn peak [in the <br>
 relationship between our two Churches]. In recent years, I have met <br>
 His Holiness Pope John Paul II on six occasions (once for a private <br>
 visit and five times during ecumenical and inter-religious meetings). <br>
 However, this seventh meeting was different from all previous <br>
 encounters for several reasons.<br>
 <br>
 It is an historic and significant event when the successors of the<br>
 Apostles St. Peter and Sts. Bartholomew and Thaddeus embrace each <br>
 other. This is an important event for Christ's Apostolic Holy  <br>
 Church. This does not happen too often.  The last time the Pope of <br>
 the Roman Catholic Church and the Catholicos of All Armenians met was <br>
 26 years ago.<br>
 <br>
 It is significant that, at the threshold of the third millennium,  <br>
 the two pontiffs, through their own example, were providing a light <br>
 of inspiration to their followers and to all Christians, and were <br>
 affirming the fact that without the one the other would not be <br>
 complete.<br>
 <br>
 It was the first time in history that the Catholicos of All  <br>
 Armenians visited the Vatican in his capacity as the chief pastor of <br>
 an ancient people, who, at long last, have a free and independent <br>
 state. The Catholicos had come [to the Vatican] this time not to ask <br>
 for help, or to play diplomacy under the pressure of some hostile <br>
 state, but, inspired by the new age of independence, he had come to <br>
 his brother in Rome in an expression of fellowship and spiritual <br>
 togetherness.<br>
 <br>
 Q.  Your Eminence, is it true that the Armenian Church, putting  <br>
 aside the christological controversies, ended the 1500-year old <br>
 dispute, in order words, have the Armenian Apostolics become  <br>
 "Chalcedonian"?<br>
 <br>
 A.  No. The Catholicos of All Armenians, our two Patriarchs and the <br>
 nine archbishops [of whom the delegation consisted] are not able [to <br>
 decide] such an issue. In order to make such a historic decision, <br>
 certain commissions would have to be established to study the <br>
 dogmatic and theological aspects of the issue. The reports of the <br>
 commissions would then have to be studied by a series of episcopal  <br>
 conclaves and then they would be presented to the National <br>
 Ecclesiastical Assembly for final approval.<br>
 <br>
 Therefore, the Catholicos of All Armenians and the members of the<br>
 delegation have not accepted the decisions of the Council of  <br>
 Chalcedon  [A.D. 451].  Such a decision is beyond our power and <br>
 authority. We continue to follow the teachings of our Church Fathers, <br>
 that is, the living Orthodox Faith of our Church.<br>
 <br>
 Q.  What has changed then?<br>
 <br>
 A.  From a dogmatic point of view, nothing.  The two sides--without <br>
 making any changes in their theological terminologies or their modes <br>
 of explaining Christ's nature--formally accepted that, although they <br>
 use different formulae, each is as orthodox as the other, they <br>
 believe in the same Lord Jesus Christ. Christ is One, but at the same <br>
 time he is both perfect God and perfect Man. The two sides explain <br>
 this truth by using different formulae. Henceforth, the sides will no <br>
 longer criticize each other for being "diophysite" or "monophysite" <br>
 as it has been the case since 451 A.D.<br>
 <br>
 In this connection, we should remember Patriarch Malachia Ormanian of <br>
 Constantinople who always defended the view that all other churches <br>
 are obligated to accept the orthodoxy of the Armenian Apostolic <br>
 Orthodox Church, because, if we accept a Church as orthodox before <br>
 451 A.D., we cannot consider it heretical after 451 A.D. Our Church's <br>
 faith was formulated long before 451 A.D. This is what the Church of <br>
 Rome, through the signature of Pope John Paul II, formally <br>
 recognized.<br>
 <br>
 It is very clear in the joint statement--clearer than the statement <br>
 that was signed by Catholicos Vazken I and Pope Paul VI in 1970 -- <br>
 that both the Roman and the Armenian Churches have numerous common <br>
 teachings of faith.<br>
 <br>
 For example, they both believe in "Apostolic succession", that is,  <br>
 the episcopal form of Church government where the bishops in the  <br>
 Church are understood as the successors of the apostolic college of <br>
 Christ. Therefore, the two Churches formally recognize each other's <br>
 episcopal authority. For an Armenian, a Roman Catholic bishop is to <br>
 be respected as much as a bishop of the Armenian Church, and vice <br>
 versa.<br>
 <br>
 The pontiffs formally agreed that linguistic, cultural and  political<br>
 dynamics in the past caused serious misunderstandings, confrontations <br>
 and tragic divisions between the two Churches.  The two pontiffs, <br>
 humbly before God, expressed regrets for those confrontations and <br>
 promised to try to eradicate the ill feelings of the past, mutual <br>
 accusations, even hatred -- which have cast a shadow on true <br>
 brotherly relations between the faithful and religious leaders of the <br>
 two Churches -- from the thoughts and memories of their respective <br>
 followers.  Therefore, the signed document is not only a formal <br>
 communique about last week's summit, but has the appeal of an <br>
 Apostolic Letter, through which all members of the Church, both laity <br>
 and clergy, are called to a fuller reconciliation.<br>
 <br>
 Q.  Would the faithful be able to take Communion in sister Churches?<br>
 <br>
 A. Unfortunately not yet.  The declaration of the pontiffs clearly<br>
 affirms that there is unity between the two Churches, but it is not <br>
 full unity. In other words, Holy Communion is a sign of full unity or <br>
 agreement. Our Catholic brethren allow their faithful to take <br>
 Communion in the Armenian Church only when a Catholic Church does  <br>
 not exist in a given city or neighborhood.<br>
 <br>
 Reciprocally, the faithful of the Armenian Church could take <br>
 Communion in a Catholic Church only when there is no Armenian Church <br>
 in a given region. Of course, one could go to any Christian church <br>
 for prayers or pilgrimage, but on festive days or for regular Sunday <br>
 worship each faithful should attend the Divine Liturgy in the Church <br>
 of their rebirth by baptism.<br>
 <br>
 Q.  How about the date of Christmas?<br>
 <br>
 Not only the date of Christmas, but all our national-ecclesiastical<br>
 traditions remain unchanged.<br>
 <br>
 A.  How would you evaluate our relationship  with the Armenian <br>
 Catholic Church after the recent visit of the Catholicos to the <br>
 Vatican?<br>
 <br>
 During the consultations, our relationship with the Armenian  <br>
 Catholic Church was not on the agenda. However, His Holiness the <br>
 Pope, in his address, in one sentence, mentioned the Armenian <br>
 Catholic Church and the fact that it exists--that there is an <br>
 Armenian Catholic hierarchy in existence. In the future, when we <br>
 enter into fuller communion with the Church of Rome and when there<br>
 is fuller union between the Churches, we do not know where the <br>
 Armenian Catholic Church would fit. For now, there is such a Church, <br>
 which  is ethnically Armenian, but instead of the Catholicos of All <br>
 Armenians, its members have chosen the Bishop of Rome [as the Head of <br>
 their Church].  This is a choice based on their freedom of <br>
 conscience.  This is not a problem for us.  We have equal love and <br>
 respect for them, bearing in mind that we are two separate and <br>
 independent Churches.  This is a fact that remains true.  On the <br>
 other hand, one has to confess that if the Armenian Catholic Church <br>
 did not exist, as a development of a historical reality, it would be <br>
 much easier and faster to establish full communion and unity between <br>
 the Armenian and the Roman Catholic Churches.<br>
 <br>
 A.  Your Eminence, besides being the Chairman of the Religious <br>
 Council, you are also Patriarchal Vicar for Ecumenical Affairs. As <br>
 such, what are your concluding remarks?<br>
 <br>
 Since the late 1970s, I have found myself involved in ecumenical  <br>
 affairs. I believe not only in Christian unity, but also in the <br>
 brotherhood  of all humankind. Ever since my years in school, I have <br>
 had many opportunities to be closely associated with Catholics, <br>
 Orthodox, Anglicans, Protestants, Jews and Moslems. I have come to be <br>
 fond of them and have learned something from each one of them.<br>
 <br>
 I am extremely content with the visit of the Catholicos to the <br>
 Vatican and his meeting with the  Pope. May the Lord bless their <br>
 mutual proposals, and may He lead us all in  the path of peace and <br>
 brotherhood.<br>
          <br>
 [end]<br>
 [translated by ht]<br>
