<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
        GOVERNMENT CONTINUES DISCUSSIONS OF THE 1997 BUDGET<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The Government of the Republic of Armenia continues the discussions<br>
 of the 1997 State Budget. According to Mr. Khosrov Harutyunian,<br>
 Advisor of the Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia, member of<br>
 the parliament, the Government discusses both the revenue and<br>
 expenses part of the budget. At this time, the Government carefully<br>
 examines the dynamics of the 1996 budget in order to make the numbers<br>
 in the 1997 budget more accurate.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIA TO HAVE BETTER TELEPHONE COMMUNICATION<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 In the summer of 1996, Armenia and Greece signed an agreement,<br>
 according to which the Greek side will provide a loan for financing<br>
 the construction of 450 km long Yerevan-Megri optical cable, which<br>
 will join in Iran the telephone cable connecting Europe and Asia. The<br>
 investment of $7 mln is expected to be recovered in 6 years. Most of<br>
 the investment will be in a form of equipment. The first shipment of<br>
 equipment is expected to arrive in Armenia next week. $2.2 mln will<br>
 be given in cash for the earth works.<br>
 Recently, a representative of the Greek Helleskom telephone company<br>
 visited Armenia to get acquainted with the process of implementation<br>
 of the project. He emphasized the importance of this project, which<br>
 will give Armenia reliable and cheap (compared to satellites)<br>
 telephone communication with the world.<br>
<p>
        THE VERDICT IN THE "DRO" CASE MAY STILL BE APPEALED<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Today, it is seven days since the verdict in the "Dro" case was<br>
 published. However, the accused side has a right to appeal the<br>
 verdict within  seven days after receiving the verdict, not after<br>
 publishing it. Since they only received the verdict yesterday, they<br>
 still have some time. According to the preliminary data, the lawyers<br>
 of the accused Arsen Artsruni, Hrant Margarian, Gegham Manukian, and<br>
 Hovhannes Mkrtchian have an intention to appeal the verdict.<br>
 The accusing side's deadline for the appeal is 7 days after the<br>
 publication of the verdict (i.e. the deadline is today). However,<br>
 nothing is still reported about the intentions of the prosecutor.<br>
<p>
        DEMOGRAPHIC SITUATION IN SPITAK<br>
<p>
 SPITAK, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 In 1996 the child birth was the highest compared with the other 8 years<br>
 following Spitak earthquake. During the 11 months of this year there<br>
 has been 554 newly born. The number of children under the age of 8<br>
 has reached 3344, in Spitak.<br>
<p>
            CHARITY TO ARTSAKH<br>
<p>
 STEPANAKERT, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 16, Mrs. Caroline Cox, Deputy Speaker of the House of<br>
 Lords of the British Parliament, Honorable Citizen of Stepanakert,<br>
 arrived in the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic with another charitable<br>
 mission. According to the Head of the Social Development Department<br>
 of the NKR Government Mels Hakopjanian, this time Mrs. Cox has<br>
 brought Christmas gifts to children of Artsakh. Mrs. Cox is expected<br>
 to meet with the authorities and the people of the republic.<br>
<p>
        TALISH VILLAGE BEING RECONSTRUCTED<br>
<p>
 STEPANAKERT, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The village of Talish of Martuni region (Nagorno-Karabagh Republic)<br>
 has the most damage as a result of military activities. The<br>
 reconstruction of the village continues already two years. It is<br>
 financed by the donations gathered by the Eastern USA Diocese of the<br>
 Armenian Apostolic Church.<br>
 57 houses have already been completely renovated, including 26<br>
houses<br>
 in 1996. The renovation of 35 more houses is almost completed. The<br>
 village already has drinking water, electricity and telephone<br>
 communication. Out of the 600 families who were deported from the<br>
 village, 140 have already come back and settled (470 people). It is<br>
 expected that the full recovery of the village will take about 4-5<br>
 years.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIAN-SYRIAN RELATIONS DISCUSSED<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Today, the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon Ter-Petrossian<br>
 received the Charge d'affaires of the Republic of Armenia in Syria<br>
 David Hovhannisian.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed issues related to the<br>
 activities of the Armenian Embassy in Syria and the present state of<br>
 Armenian-Syrian relations.<br>
<p>
        FIRST VICE PRESIDENT OF IRAN TO VISIT ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 18, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Today, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Armenia<br>
 Alexander Arzumanian received the Ambassador Extraordinary and<br>
 Plenipotentiary of the Islamic Republic of Iran in Armenia Hamid Reza<br>
 Nikkar Esfahani.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed issues related to the upcoming<br>
 visit of the First Vice President of Iran to Armenia Hasan Habib.<br>
<p>
<p>
        WORLD BANK CONTINUES FINANCING PROJECTS IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 19, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia Armen<br>
Sargsian<br>
 received Basil Kavalsky, the Director of the World Bank's Department of<br>
 Eastern Europe and Central Asia. The discussion was mainly around the<br>
 economic situation in Armenia, the social-economic projects of the<br>
 Government. Both sides agreed that World Bank must continue and<br>
 expand the financing of the projects in different fields.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIAN RELIEF FUND'S PROGRAMS<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 19, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the Armenian branch of the Armenian Relief Fund of the<br>
 Eastern USA Diocese of the Armenian Apostolic Church held a press<br>
 conference. The Deputy Director of the Armenian branch Armenak<br>
 Mikaelian mentioned that the Fund has implemented $1.5 mln worth of<br>
 development programs in the areas of social development, medicine,<br>
 agriculture, and construction.<br>
 Among the social programs, Mr. Mikaelian mentioned the installation<br>
 of 2 stationary electric power generation in the Chekhov school in<br>
 Yerevan, renovation of the heating system of the Khnko Aper Library<br>
 in Yerevan, and similar projects throughout Armenia.<br>
 The important construction projects are: the construction of an<br>
 orphanage in Hermon village of Yeghegnadzor region (southern<br>
 Armenia), renovation of some old people's houses, reconstruction of<br>
 some schools and construction of water systems.<br>
 In the area of agriculture the Armenian Relief Fund projects deal<br>
 with the wheat sowing campaign, the modern technologies in potato<br>
 production, the construction of a mobile mill, and the construction<br>
 of fruit dryers.<br>
<p>
        BORDER INCIDENTS<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 19, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 According to the Ministry of Defense of the Republic of Armenia, the<br>
 Azeri military units have broken the ceasefire again on the<br>
 north-eastern section of the Armenian-Azeri border. One incident took<br>
 place in the evening of December 17, the other one - on December 18,<br>
 both near the Parabakar village of Tavush provice.<br>
 No casualties are reported.<br>
<p>
        GAZ SUPPLY TO GEORGIA AND ARMENIA CUT OFF<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 19, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The pressure in the gaz pipes of the Republic of Armenia has dropped<br>
 significantly, yesterday morning. According to the Head of the<br>
 Armenian state concern "Haygazard" Roland Adonts, the gaz supply<br>
was<br>
 cut off by Turkmenistan near the Ossia-Georgia border. The reason is<br>
 the fact that Georgia has not paid its debts for gaz.<br>
 According to Mr. Adonts, Armenia has already paid its debt in money<br>
 for more than 1 blm cubic meters of gaz, which have entered the<br>
 country withing the last 11 months. There are some problems with<br>
 paying the commodity part of the debt, which will most likely be<br>
 settled by the end of this year.<br>
 Mr. Adonts said that today, in Moscow, representatives of Armenia and<br>
 Georgia will meet with the representatives of the Turkmen-Russian<br>
 joint-stock company to examine the situation and to restore the gaz<br>
 supply.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIAN-GEORGIAN BORDER INCIDENT DISCUSSED<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 19, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 17, the Armenian and Georgian delegations met near the<br>
 Armenian-Georgian-Azeri border in the Tavush province of Armenia.<br>
 The main issue discussed in the meeting was the Armenian-Georgian<br>
 border incident on December 14, where one Georgian was killed. Diring<br>
 the meeting the Georgian side tried to place the entire<br>
 responsibility fot the incident on the Armenian side.<br>
 The Armenian side carefully examined the situation and stated that<br>
 the responsible for the issue were the Georgian citizens, who<br>
 illegally crossed the border and found themselves within 35-40 meters<br>
 from the Armenian defense positions. These people did not obey any<br>
 warning orders of the Armenian border guards. Moreover, they were<br>
 armed.<br>
 As a result of the meeting, the sides came to a conclusion that the<br>
 Armenian soldiers were acting in accordance with the established<br>
 procedures.<br>
<p>
        NAGORNO-KARABAGH REPUBLIC TO HAVE ITS OWN SEISMIC<br>
SAFETY SERVICE<br>
<p>
 STEPANAKERT, DECEMBER 19, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 During a meeting of the Stepanakert City Administration, it was<br>
 announced that from 1997 Stepanakert will have its own seismic safety<br>
 service, which will have the status of a branch of the National<br>
 Seismic Safety Service of the Republic of Armenia.<br>
 To settle some issues related to the creation of such service, a<br>
 delegation of the National Seismic Safety Service of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia, headed by its Director Sergey Balasanian, visited<br>
 Stepanakert. The delegation was received by the Prime Minister of the<br>
 Nagorno-Karabagh Republic Leonard Petrossian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
