<title>Groong Network: Dadrian's Lecture in Boston</title>
<h1>Dadrian's Lecture in Boston</h1>
vahe ghahraman (<i>vghahram@lynx.dac.neu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 96 11:40:03 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#176">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#176">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#176">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#176">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0177.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 19)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0175.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/19/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
 <br>
 NAASR   (617) 489-1610<br>
 Blue Crane Books (617) 926-8585<br>
 <br>
 <br>
                 PROF. DADRIAN DETAILS GERMANY'S<br>
                 COMPLICITY IN THE ARMENIAN GENOCIDE<br>
 <br>
 <br>
         Before a standing-room-only audience of nearly 300 at the First<br>
 Armenian Church in Belmont, Mass., Prof. Vahakn N. Dadrian, foremost<br>
 authority on the Armenian Genocide, delivered on the evening of December 5<br>
 a lecture on Germany's complicity in the Armenian Genocide-~the subject of<br>
 his latest book published by Blue Crane Books of Cambridge, Mass. This was<br>
 the first public lecture he has given on this aspect of his ongoing<br>
 research on the Armenian Genocide.<br>
         In a tightly woven discourse on the set of conditions which were<br>
 responsible for the involvement of a host of high-ranking German military<br>
 and civilian functionaries in the World War I tragedy of the Armenian<br>
 population of Turkey, Dr. Dadrian presented his case against the German<br>
 leadership of the time.<br>
         With his unique and captivating style of delivery, Dadrian first<br>
 dealt with the Turko-German relationship in its historical perspective,<br>
 followed by the ramifications of the World War I Turko-German political and<br>
 military alliance. He then focused on the actions and the actors of the<br>
 complicity at issue, the German alibis and cover-ups, and, finally, the<br>
 legal implications for amends and reparations from the standpoint of<br>
 national and international law.<br>
 <br>
         Multitude of Documents Cited<br>
 <br>
         He cited a multitude of German and Turkish documents, including<br>
 official reports, memoirs, signed deportation orders, and Turkish Military<br>
 Tribunal findings as collaborating evidence to complete the final picture<br>
 of Germany's direct and indirect involvement in the planning and execution<br>
 of the mass deportations and annihilation of the Armenian population of<br>
 Ottoman Turkey.<br>
         In detail after detail, Dr. Dadrian revealed the characters,<br>
 doctrines, and actions of major German military and civilian officials,<br>
 exposing the complicity of such figures as the two Chiefs of the Ottoman<br>
 General Staff at the Ottoman General Headquarters, Generals Fritz Bronsart<br>
 von Schellendorf and Hans Friedrich von Seekt, as well as Ambassador Hans<br>
 von Wangenheim, Chief of Railroad Services Lt. Colonel Boettrich, Marshal<br>
 Colmar von der Goltz, and even the Kaiser himself.<br>
 <br>
         Damning Indictment of the Germans<br>
 <br>
         Dr. Dadrian in his research into the German archives uncovered the<br>
 very close relations between German and Turkish officials and the cases<br>
 where German officers actually signed deportation orders for the Armenians.<br>
 One highly placed German, Max von Oppenheim, developed a plan for the<br>
 annihilation of the Armenians. Germans were even involved in the<br>
 establishment of the Special Organization units which actually carried out<br>
 the Genocide.<br>
         While his research leaves no doubt about a high level of German<br>
 complicity in the Genocide, Dadrian at the same time stressed that by no<br>
 means should a blanket denunciation be made of the Germans in the Ottoman<br>
 Empire. Many Germans vociferously condemned the atrocities they had<br>
 witnessed, risking their positions, their health, and even their lives, in<br>
 the process. These included one ambassador, Count Paul von Metternich,<br>
 several generals, and the longtime consul in Aleppo, Dr. Walter Rossler.<br>
 <br>
         Co-perpetrators and Accessories<br>
 <br>
         A central feature of German complicity is "the willingness of a<br>
 number of German officials, civilian and military, to aid and abet the<br>
 Turks in their drive to liquidate the Armenians," Dadrian stated. "They<br>
 qualify to be regarded as co-perpetrators and accessories to the crime."<br>
         Prof. Dadrian predicted that open-minded Germans would accept his<br>
 conclusions and demand justice "despite great pressure from politicians,"<br>
 who would argue that Germans have enough on their hands as a result of the<br>
 Nazi Holocaust without becoming concerned now about their responsibility in<br>
 the Armenian Genocide as well.<br>
         Dadrian, however, expressed confidence that Germany would<br>
 eventually accept the truth preserved in its own archives; and once Germany<br>
 officially recognizes its complicity in the Genocide, then Turkey will<br>
 remain totally isolated.<br>
         If Germany, Turkey's ally in World War I, accepts responsibility,<br>
 "this will then close all avenues of escape for Turkey" in that nation's<br>
 persistent and continued efforts to deny the Armenian Genocide, Dadrian<br>
 concluded.<br>
         Dadrian delivered his over-an-hour-long lecture without notes, as<br>
 has become his hallmark. He received a prolonged standing ovation from the<br>
 audience, who continued the evening with numerous questions and a long<br>
 queue to meet the author in person and have their books auto graphed.<br>
 <br>
         Unique and Varied Background<br>
 <br>
         Having studied mathematics, philosophy, international law, and<br>
 sociology in European and American universities, his varied background has<br>
 prepared him uniquely to undertake his research and writing about the<br>
 Armenian Genocide. After serving as Professor of Sociology at the State<br>
 University of New York for over 20 years, Dr. Dadrian is now devoting his<br>
 efforts full-time to his research on the Armenian Genocide and has been<br>
 director of a major Genocide Study Program sponsored by the H.F. Guggenheim<br>
 Foundation.<br>
         The evening was co-sponsored by Blue Crane Books, publisher of<br>
 Dadrian's most recent title, German Responsibility in the Armenian<br>
 Genocide: A Review of the Historical Evidence of German Complicity, and the<br>
 National Association for Armenian Studies and Research (NAASR).<br>
         The evenings program began with a brief commentary by Board<br>
 Chairman Manoog S. Young of NAASR on the implications and impact of<br>
 genocide in today's world and on the singular accomplishments by the guest<br>
 lecturer. Prof. Dadrian received special accolades from Rev. Vartan<br>
 Hartunian, pastor of First Armenian Church, who coupled his praise of<br>
 Dadrian's work with an appropriate quotation from Shakespeare's Hamlet. His<br>
 remarks were from a pastoral letter on the occasion of the publication of<br>
 Dadrian's book on Germany's complicity.<br>
 <br>
         Book Now in Second Printing<br>
 <br>
         Introducing the speaker, the publisher of Blue Crane Books, Ms.<br>
 Alvart Badalian, outlined the many academic achievements of Prof. Dadrian<br>
 in the U.S. and abroad, announcing that while German Responsibility has<br>
 gone to a second printing in less than six months of publication, Blue<br>
 Crane books has embarked on a forthcoming publication in 1997 of a new work<br>
 by the distinguished scholar, titled Warrant for Genocide: The Key Elements<br>
 of Turko-Armenian Conflict. She ended her presentation with an excerpt from<br>
 a moving letter to Prof. Dadrian by Father Sahag Jemjemian, Abbot of the<br>
 Mkhitarist Congregation in Venice, written in August 1996, only five weeks<br>
 before his unexpected passing. It reads:<br>
         "I wish to convey to you the thanks of the entire Armenian nation<br>
 for the singular and unprecedented work you are doing- -a work that<br>
 transcends the national boundaries and reaches to the international. The<br>
 Armenian nation today has but one and only one Vahakn Dadrian and everyone<br>
 is filled with gratitude toward you for the gigantic work you are<br>
 performing. It is the nation that is grateful to you and I join my<br>
 compatriots in intoning to you THOUSAND THANKS, dear Vahakn."<br>
 <br>
         Lectures in Europe and Canada<br>
<p>
         Prof. Dadrian has just returned from a five-week multi-language<br>
 lecture tour of Europe---his second tour in 1996---during which he was<br>
 invited to address the Italian Parliament on the subject of the recognition<br>
 of the Armenian Genocide. In 1995 he had lectured in the British House of<br>
 Commons on the occasion of the 80th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide.<br>
 Recently he also visited Toronto, Canada, where he lectured at the<br>
 University of Toronto and at the Armenian Community Center.<br>
 <br>
         Copies of "German Responsibility in the Armenian Genocide" may be<br>
 ordered from the publisher: Blue Crane Books, P. O. Box 291, Cambridge, MA<br>
 02238 (Tel: 617/926-8585, Fax: 617/926-0982, email:<br>
 arrow@us1.channel1.com).  Copies of complete works by Dr. Dadrian are<br>
 available from NAASR's Armenian Book Clearing House, 395 Concord Ave.,<br>
 Belmont, MA 02178 (Tel.: 617-489-1610; Fax: 617-484-1759).<br>
 <br>
